<HTML>
<HEAD>
	<TITLE>SPACEZONE &#149; WALT CUNNINGHAM</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!--Copyrigh© 1996 Warner International Communications Group, Inc. All Rights Reserved.-->
<P><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#1113AB" VLINK="#B40FB"
ALINK="#F0051" >
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2>GENESIS VENTURE PARTNERS</H2><BR>
<I>Houston's Technology Gateway</I>
</CENTER>
<P>
Genesis Venture Partners (Genesis) is a private, Houston based venture investing firm. Our goal is to provide our Limited Partners with superior levels of return on their investment, by making long-term investments in rapidly growing smaller companies. Genesis' primary investment area is the under-served, but technology rich Gulf Coast region. Our usual investment commitment is between &#36;500,000 and &#36;4,000,000 and we expect to hold an investment for a period of three to seven years.
<P>
<A HREF="walt.htm">Walter Cunningham</A>, the Managing General Partner, is a physicist with 35 years of diversified management experience in private industry, as a Marine Corps fighter pilot, as a NASA Astronaut and, for the past 13 years, as a <A HREF="vencap.htm">venture capitalist</A>. The second General Partner, Dr. Richard Johnson, is an entrepreneur and physician with broad management experience in marketing, new product development and clinical research at a fortune 100 healthcare company.
<P>
<B>THE GENESIS FUND</B>
<P>
The Genesis Fund is a &#36;15.7 million early stage fund with a portfolio of technology investments. This Fund is the sole owner of  UNCO Ventures, an SBIC capitalized at &#36;3 million. As of 1994, four portfolio companies had completed successful public offerings. The Genesis Fund placed major emphasis on early stage investing, including nine start-ups. The Fund is currently in the liquidation phase of its life cycle.
<P>
<B>THE GENESIS FUND II</B>
<P>
The Genesis Fund II, a planned &#36;30 million, venture capital Small Business Investment Company, is the second venture fund organized by Walter Cunningham. The &#36;30 million in private capital will be leveraged up to an additional &#36;60 million through the sale of non-recourse Participating Securities to the U.S. Small Business Administration. This Fund will create a portfolio of early stage and selected later stage investments in technology and healthcare related companies.
<P>
<B>INVESTMENT CRITERIA</B>
<P>
Genesis prefers to make investments in companies that have the potential to become significant forces in their respective markets.  Other characteristics of companies sought are:
<OL>
<LI>	Innovative, proprietary products or services with maximum pricing flexibility;
<P>
<LI>	Competing in a large and growing marketplace with the opportunity for superior profits;
<P>
<LI>	A well developed strategy to exploit the company's market niche;
<P>
<LI>	A high growth rate, requiring funds for expansion and further market penetration;
<P>
<LI>	A clearly defined exit strategy; i.e. a clear desire and potential to become publicly traded or an attractive acquisition candidate in 3-7 years;
<P>
<LI>	An experienced and dedicated management team with a significant ownership position;
<P>
<LI>	A return on investment opportunity commensurate with risk; and
<P>
<LI>	A business activity and management team compatible with the people and skills of the Genesis Principals.
</OL>
<P>
The most important investment criterion is the caliber of management, with a preference for companies where exceptional capability has been demonstrated by previous performance.
<P>
<B>PREFERRED INDUSTRIES</B>
<P>
Based on their location and the Principals' technical backgrounds and experience, Genesis focuses on companies in the following disciplines:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Life Sciences and Medical Technology
<LI>Managed Health Care and Health Care Delivery Systems
<LI>Computer Software and Hardware 
<LI>NASA Developed Technology and Telecommunications.
</UL>
<P>
<B>OPERATING PHILOSOPHY</B>
<P>
Genesis Venture Partners is among the small group of venture capitalists still willing and able to contribute more than money during the start-up and rapid growth phases of an emerging business.  We believe in company building and goal sharing with the entrepreneur. "Hands-on" operating experience leaves us better prepared to make meaningful contributions to management to keep an investment on track.
<P>
We are long term equity investors, investing as owners of businesses rather than investors in shares.  We conduct detailed analyses before investing and are then prepared to assist management for several years in preparation for a successful exit. Usually, we own from 5 to 30 percent of the companies in which we invest.
<P>
We take an active role in the evolution of our investments.  In new, small companies, if the planning and financial skills or the experience required to manage an enterprise are missing, we introduce them.  In more mature companies, we establish an active dialogue with management and play a policy-making role.
<P>
We view ourselves as partners with management. We do not want to manage companies but to be a resource to management teams as board members and advisors. We tend not to be threatening to existing management but, rather, to support them. We perform in the complex and changing roles of advocate, adviser and adversary, as required. In most cases, we are represented on the Boards of Directors of the companies in which we are involved.



We employ our professional skills to enhance investment results.  We are able to orchestrate financings and assist in long-term planning.  If equity markets do not fully recognize values, we seek other ways to liquify our investments, such as divestiture and merger programs. At various times we function as investment adviser, investment banker, management consultant, psychiatrist, minister and a variety of other functions that are part of the creative venture capital process.
<P>
In summary, our investments are both personal and directive in nature, are made in partnership with management and they usually mature in four to seven years. 
<P>
<B>PRINCIPALS</B>
<P>
<B>Walter Cunningham</B>, for the past 15 years, has worked exclusively with entrepreneurs, including the startup and development of more than 30 venture financed companies. He is the Managing General Partner of The Genesis Fund, UNCO Ventures SBIC and The Genesis Fund II.
<P>
Mr. Cunningham is perhaps best known as America's second civilian Astronaut and Pilot of the first manned Apollo mission (Apollo VII, October, 1968). He has been CEO of two engineering companies, each with extensive operations in the international marketplace.
<P>
Mr. Cunningham received B.S. and M.S. degrees in Physics from UCLA and is a graduate of the Advanced Management Program at the Harvard Graduate School of Business. He is a former Marine Corps fighter pilot, with the present rank of Colonel, USMCR - Retired.
<P>
<B>Richard Johnson</B>, M.D. is a General Partner with The Genesis Fund II and a Senior Associate with the first fund. While at Lederle Laboratories, he created and directed strategic clinical Research and Development plans; evaluated new products for licensing and acquisition and was the chief strategist and marketing director of the new product marketing group. Dr. Johnson is one of the few individuals in the industry to be a trained clinician and researcher as well as a line operating manager with marketing responsibility for launching new products into highly competitive multi-billion dollar markets.
<P>
His clinical medical experience includes the practice of Critical Care and Internal Medicine and Cardiology. His entrepreneurial experience includes founding several biomedical start-up companies and creating strategic partnerships in the health care industry.
<P>
Dr. Johnson received his Bachelor's Degree from New York University and his Doctor of Medicine from Mount Sinai School of Medicine in New York.
<P>
<B>Mr. Stuart Schube</B>, a General Partner with the first Genesis Fund and Venture Partner in the second, brings 25 years of venture industry experience to Genesis Venture Partners. Mr. Schube received his B.S. in Industrial Engineering from Pratt Institute and his M.S. in Industrial Administration from Purdue University.
<P>
Genesis Venture Partners<BR>
520 Post Oak Blvd.  Suite 130<BR>
Houston    TX   77027<BR>
Tele: 713/622-9595<BR>
Fax:  713/622-9007<BR>
