<HTML>
<HEAD>
	<TITLE>SPACEZONE &#149; WALT CUNNINGHAM</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!--Copyrigh© 1996 Warner International Communications Group, Inc. All Rights Reserved.-->
<P><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#1113AB" VLINK="#B40FB"
ALINK="#F0051" >
<BODY>
<CENTER>

<H2>PROFESSIONAL VENTURE CAPITAL</H2>
</CENTER>
<P>
VENTURE CAPITAL: a combination of both human and capital resources committed to investments of a diverse nature in order to achieve a better risk/reward ratio than might otherwise have been available to a passive investor. Investment capital is called equity, which includes the cash invested by founders and retained earnings generated by the company.
<P>
PROFESSIONAL VENTURE CAPITAL: capital provided by firms of full time professionals who invest alongside management in young, rapidly growing or rapidly changing companies that have the potential to develop into significant competitors in regional, national and global markets.
<P>
The most visible venture funding comes from professionally managed venture capital firms. Generally, these are private partnerships or closely held corporations funded by an informal network of investors that include:  pension funds, insurance companies, endowment funds, foundations, bank holding companies and their affiliates, corporations, wealthy individuals, foreign investors and the venture capitalists themselves.
<P>
Venture capitalists also contribute their experience and industry knowledge to help companies avoid growing pains and move them toward becoming tomorrow's leading industrial and service companies.  Venture capitalists generally are characterized by the following common features:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>They finance new and rapidly growing companies;
<LI>They develop an innovative business idea for a product or service;
<LI>They add value to the company by active participation;
<LI>They take higher risks with expectation of higher rewards;
<LI>They have a long term orientation; and
<LI>They purchase equity securities.
</UL>
<P>
Professional venture capitalists assist young companies by carefully screening both the technical and business merits of proposals and by investing risk capital -- usually with no cash repayment schedule.  They work actively with the management of their portfolio companies, contributing the experience they and their firms have developed helping other companies with similar growth challenges.
<P>
The risks and returns of venture investing are rendered less volatile by including investments in a number of companies in a single venture capital portfolio and by co-investing in those companies with other professional venture firms.  The stability and the returns achieved by professional venture firms have attracted funds from institutions and foreign investors, thereby significantly increasing the flow of capital into young American companies.
<P>
