<!--Volume 3-->
<P>
<IMG ALIGN="left" WIDTH="172" HEIGHT="131" SRC="art/blank.jpg" ALT="World Was There">

<A NAME="v3"><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>World Was There</B></FONT></A>
<P>
<B>Awards</B><BR>
<I>First Prize, Aeronautique Festival, Washington D.C., 1965
<P>

First Prize, Television Documentary, Vichy, 1965
<P>

In Exhibition, National Gallery of Art, 1965</I>
<P>
35 minutes<BR>
Introduced by Astronaut Wally Schirra
<P>
This exciting video takes you back to a time second only to America's independence: the Mercury era. Seven astronauts that would become heroes to a nation, became ideals to a generation. It was the height of patriotism in our country, and the news knew no boundaries.
<P>
Worldwide media coverage didn't miss a word as NASA and the United States shared all the information they gathered from space. The Mercury program was an icon of the American way. Teamwork was what everyone saw in America and the astronauts of the first six Mercury missions, because through the media, the world was there.
<P>
