<!--Volume 6-->
<P>
<IMG ALIGN="left" WIDTH="172" HEIGHT="131" SRC="art/blank.jpg" ALT="Legacy of Gemini">

<A NAME="v6"><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Legacy of Gemini</B></FONT></A>
<P>

<B>Awards</B><BR>
<I>Golden Eagle, Council on International Nontheatrical Events (CINE), 1968
<P>

Silver Medal, Atlanta International Film Festival, 1968
<P>

Chris Award, Columbus Film Festival, 1968
<P>

Award of Merit, American Film Festival, 1968
<P>

Diploma, 6th International Film Festival, Trieste, 1968
</I>
<P>
35 minutes<BR>
Introduced by Astronaut Charlie Duke
<P>
This video overviews the entire Gemini project. Several major scientific accomplishments paved the way for Apollo including extended EVA, or extra vehicular activity; docking of spacecraft, to be ultimately used when space stations were in place; and carrying out more scientific experiments during spacewalks.
<P>
The accuracy of splashdowns was also improved, and the 10 Gemini missions were completed in just 18 months. This was the next step after Mercury's successes. And soon, man would walk with greater confidence, on the surface of the moon.

<P>
<IMG BORDER="0" ALIGN="middle" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="38" SRC="art/film.gif">Legacy of Gemini, QuickTime sample available soon.
<BR>
<IMG BORDER="0" ALIGN="middle" WIDTH="46" HEIGHT="25" SRC="art/ra.gif">
