<HTML>
<HEAD>
	<TITLE>SPACEZONE &#149; STS-80</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!--Copyrigh© 1996 Warner International Communications Group, Inc. All Rights Reserved.-->
<P><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#1113AB" VLINK="#B40FB"
ALINK="#F0051" >
<BODY>

<IMG ALIGN="left" WIDTH="395" HEIGHT="119" SRC="art/szlogo.gif" ALT="SpaceZone">
<BR CLEAR="all">
<IMG ALIGN="left" WIDTH="189" HEIGHT="190" SRC="art/80patch.gif"ALT="STS-80 Patch">
<BR>
<P>

<H1>Shuttle Mission STS-80</H1><BR>

<P>
<A HREF="80time.htm">Back to Mission Timeline</A>
<BR CLEAR="all">

<b>November 22, 1996</b><dl>
<dt>10:53 am
<dd>
Crew wakeup


<dt>12:24 pm
<dd>
Cockrell and Rominger conduct another rendezvous burn to maintain the proper distance from the ORFEUS-SPAS satellite


<dt>01:08 pm
<dd>
Jones powers up the robot arm and grapples the Wake Shield Facility as Cockrell deactivates the Regenerative Carbon Dioxide scrubbing system on board to maintain a pristine environment for WSF deployment


<dt>01:23 pm
<dd>
Jernigan powers up the Orbiter Space Vision System


<dt>01:48 pm
<dd>
Cockrell maneuvers Columbia to a gravity gradient attitude (tail to Earth) to minimize attitude disturbances during WSF deploy preparations and the FES is shut off


<dt>02:58 pm
<dd>
Jones uses the robot arm to unberth the WSF


<dt>03:16 pm
<dd>
Jones positions the WSF into the R am cleaning position to allow atomic oxygen molecules to "cleanse" the underside of the saucer-shaped satellite ( 2 1/2 hour procedure )


<dt>06:02 pm
<dd>
Jones repositions the WSF to an orientation for the checkout of the satellite's Automatic Data Acquisition and Control System ( ADACS )


<dt>06:58 pm
<dd>
Jones maneuvers the robot arm to the WSF release orientation


<dt>07:08 pm
<dd>
JONES DEPLOYS THE WAKE SHIELD FACILITY FOR THREE DAYS OF FREE-FLYING THIN FILM GROWTH OPERATION


<dt>08:38 pm
<dd>
A second WSF release window opens, if required, for a backup deployment opportunity


<dt>08:53 pm
<dd>
Jones powers down the robot arm and Jernigan powers down the Orbiter Space Vision System hardware


<dt>09:53 pm
<dd>
Cockrell exercises


<dt>10:08 pm
<dd>
A third and final WSF release window opens, if required, for a backup deployment opportunity


<dt>10:23 pm
<dd>
Rominger exercises


<dt>10:53 pm
<dd>
Jernigan exercises


<dt>11:23 pm
<dd>
Musgrave exercises


<dt>11:53 pm
<dd>
Jones exercises</dl>

<p><b>November 23, 1996</b><dl>
<dt>12:38 am
<dd>
Musgrave checks on the rodents which are part of the PARE-NIH experiment


<dt>12:45 am
<dd>
Cockrell and Rominger conduct another rendezvous burn to seperate from the WSF and maintain a seperation distance from ORFEUS-SPAS


<dt>12:53 am
<dd>
Jones reactivates the Regenerative Carbon Dioxide Removal System


<dt>02:13 am
<dd>
Private medical conference


<dt>03:53 am
<dd>
Crew sleep begins</dl>





