<HEAD>
	<TITLE>SPACEZONE &#149; STS-80</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!--Copyrigh© 1996 Warner International Communications Group, Inc. All Rights Reserved.-->
<P><BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#1113AB" VLINK="#B40FB"
ALINK="#F0051" >
<BODY>

<IMG ALIGN="left" WIDTH="395" HEIGHT="119" SRC="art/szlogo.gif" ALT="SpaceZone">
<BR CLEAR="all">
<IMG ALIGN="left" WIDTH="189" HEIGHT="190" SRC="art/80patch.gif"ALT="STS-80 Patch">
<BR>
<P>

<H1>Shuttle Mission STS-80</H1><BR>

<P>
<A HREF="80time.htm">Back to Mission Timeline</A>
<BR CLEAR="all">
<b>December 2, 1996</b><dl>
<dt>03:53 pm
<dd>
Crew wakeup


<dt>06:23 pm
<dd>
The astronauts begin their rendezvous procedures for the retrieval of ORFEUS-SPAS


<dt>06:53 pm
<dd>
Jones exercises


<dt>07:17 pm
<dd>
Cockrell and Rominger conduct a course correction maneuver to edge closer to the ORFEUS-SPAS satellite


<dt>07:23 pm
<dd>
Jernigan exercises


<dt>08:02 pm
<dd>
Cockrell and Rominger conduct a height correction maneuver as part of the ORFEUS-SPAS rendezvous


<dt>08:23 pm
<dd>
Jernigan powers up the robot arm


<dt>09:22 pm
<dd>
Cockrell and Rominger conduct another course correction maneuver as Columbia bears down on ORFEUS-SPAS


<dt>10:19 pm
<dd>
Cockrell and Rominger conduct the Terminal Initiation (TI) burn to place Columbia on an intercepting path to the ORFEUS-SPAS</dl>

<p><b>December 3, 1996</b><dl>
<dt>12:28 am
<dd>
JERNIGAN AND JONES USE THE ROBOT ARM TO GRAPPLE THE ORFEUS-SPAS SATELLITE AT THE COMPLETION OF ITS TWO-WEEK FREE FLYING ASTRONOMY MISSION


<dt>12:38 am
<dd>
Jernigan and Jones use the robot arm to maneuver the ORFEUS-SPAS into an orientation to gather experimental navigation data from orbiting GPS satellites


<dt>01:08 am
<dd>
The ORFEUS-SPAS systems are deactivated; Jones joins her to begin Orbiter Space Vision System tests with the grappled satellite at the end of the robot arm; Musgrave begins to stow rendezvous tools


<dt>01:53 am
<dd>
Cockrell checks the rodents in the PARE-NIH experiment


<dt>02:53 am
<dd>
Cockrell exercises; Rominger practices landings with the PILOT laptop computer trainer


<dt>03:23 am
<dd>
Rominger exercises


<dt>03:53 am
<dd>
Cockrell practices landings with the PILOT laptop computer trainer; Musgrave exercises


<dt>04:38 am
<dd>
Jernigan and Jones berth the ORFEUS-SPAS satellite back onto its platform in the cargo bay


<dt>04:43 am
<dd>
Jernigan powers down the robot arm for the final time


<dt>06:33 am
<dd>
Private medical conference


<dt>06:53 am
<dd>
Private family conferences for Jones and Musgrave


<dt>07:53 am
<dd>
Crew sleep begins ( 9 hours )</dl>






