<h2 align=center><font size=3>South Florida Regional Planning Council</font><font size=5> <br>
</font><font size=4><strong>Services and Responsibilities</strong></font></h2>
<hr>
<p><a href="#b"><b>LOOKING TO THE FUTURE</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#c"><b>REGIONAL PLANNING</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#d"><b>EASTWARD HO!</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#e"><b>TRANSPORTATION PLANNING</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#f"><b>REGIONAL DISPUTE RESOLUTION</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#g"><b>VISIONING AND FACILITATION SERVICES</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#h"><b>SOUTHEAST FLORIDA 2025</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#i"><b>CLEAN CITIES</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#j"><b>COASTAL ZONE MANAGEMENT</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#k"><b>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#l"><b>HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PLANNING</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#m"><b>LOCAL GOVERNMENT COMPREHENSIVE PLAN REVIEW</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#n"><b>DEVELOPMENTS OF REGIONAL IMPACT</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#o"><b>INTERGOVERNMENTAL COORDINATION AND REVIEW</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#p"><b>WORLD WIDE WEB</b></a> </p>
<p><a href="#q"><b>STATE DATA CENTER</b></a> </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="b"><b>LOOKING TO THE FUTURE</b></a></p>
<p>Looking to the future is at the heart of the Regional Planning Council's activities. Anticipating South Florida's future 
challenges and responding proactively is a primary mission of the Council. Many of our partners in preparing for the future 
operate in environments that are focused on a single issue, such as water use, transportation or education. The value added 
to the system by the Council is in innovation and cross-issue identification. Understanding the relationship between and 
among programs and activities is critical. The true strength of the Regional Council lies in the ability to reach consensus on 
our desired future and the blueprint for achieving that future.</p>
<p><a name="c"><b>REGIONAL PLANNING</b></a></p>
<p>The Council, with input from other governmental entities and the private sector, prepares, adopts, and implements the goals 
and policies of the <a href="../current/menu521.htm">Strategic Regional Policy Plan for South Florida (SRPP)</a>. Implemented in August 1995, the SRPP 
provides guidance to the decisions made by the Council. It guides Council activities such as the review of local government 
comprehensive plans and developments of regional impact pursuant to Chapters 163 and 380, F.S., respectively. No part of 
the SRPP is applied in isolation; rather the goals and policies are used to balance the needs of the Region.</p>
<p><a href="../current/menu531.htm"><b>EASTWARD HO! REVITALIZING SOUTHEAST FLORIDA'S URBAN CORE</b></a></p>
<p>In February 1996, Council staff began work on Phase 1 of Eastward Ho! Revitalizing Southeast Florida's Urban Core. To 
develop the Phase 1 report, staff worked closely with the Department of Community Affairs, 50 affected local governments, 
the Treasure Coast Regional Planning Council, and interested parties from the public and private sectors.</p>
<p>A recommendation of the Governor's Commission for a Sustainable South Florida, the Eastward Ho! initiative is intended 
to assist public and private sectors in revitalizing Southeast Florida's historic eastern urban core. The study area runs 
nearly the length of Dade, Broward, and Palm Beach Counties and encompasses lands between and around the CSX and 
FEC railroad tracks. The report for this project was delivered in July 1996. Extensive follow-up efforts are anticipated.</p>
<p><a name="e"><b>TRANSPORTATION PLANNING</b></a></p>
<p>The Council's Multi-modal Regional Transportation Systems Committee provides an active forum for discussion of 
regional transportation issues, such as regional transit planning, and the MPO process. Council staff coordinates among 
Monroe, Dade, Broward, and Palm Beach Counties, the Florida Department of Transportation, the Treasure Coast Regional 
Planning Council, Tri-Rail, and other parties involved in these matters. Over the past year, the Committee convened a 
series of meetings to prepare a regional assessment of the proposed high speed rail system linking South Florida, Orlando, 
and Tampa. Council staff are currently participating in the feasibility study of a tri-county regional transportation authority, 
partnering the Dade, Broward, and Palm Beach county transit systems with Tri-Rail to create a regionally coordinated 
public transit system.</p>
<p><a name="f"><b>REGIONAL DISPUTE RESOLUTION PROCESS</b></a></p>
<p>The Council's Regional Dispute Resolution Process (RDRP) was adopted two years ago in response to the requirements of 
Chapter 186.509, F.S. The RDRP is designed to reconcile differences in planning, growth management, and other matters 
among local governments, regional agencies, and private interests. The RDRP endeavors to be a flexible process that will 
clearly identify and resolve problems as early as possible; utilize procedures in a low-to-high cost sequence, allow 
flexibility, provide for the appropriate involvement of affected parties, and provide as much process certainty as possible.</p>
<p><br>
</p>
<p align=center><a href="../council/services.htm#a">Return to Top of Page</a> <br>
</p>
<p><a href="../whatsnew/whatnew3.htm"><b>VISIONING AND FACILITATION SERVICES</b></a></p>
<p>The number of visioning retreats coordinated and staffed by the Council grew during FY 1995-1996. In October 1995, 
Council staff provided facilitation services for the City of Pompano Beach's &quot;Pompano Beach Vision 2000+&quot; workshop. 
Attended by more than 120 citizens and interested parties, the workshop was designed to assist the City in creating a 
comprehensive vision for its future.</p>
<p>In November, staff provided facilitation services for the City of Deerfield Beach in two four-hour strategic planning 
workshops regarding the City's Community Redevelopment Area. Staff also provided facilitation assistance to the Broward 
County Community Development Corporation in a half-day strategic planning session with health care providers seeking 
better ways to deliver care to the special needs population.</p>
<p>In March 1996, Council staff facilitated a visioning retreat for the Downtown Fort Lauderdale Transportation Management 
Association (TMA). The purpose was to examine the TMA's role in the downtown community and its transportation future. 
Participants discussed long-term goals, objectives, and funding requirements.</p>
<p><a href="../current/menu524.htm"><b>SOUTH FLORIDA 2025: AN INVESTMENT STRATEGY FOR THE FUTURE</b></a></p>
<p>The Council serves as staff to the Southeast Florida 2025 Steering Committee. Created through special legislation in 1994, 
Southeast Florida 2025 established a visioning process for Southeast Florida. The Steering Committee, under the 
leadership of Senator Kenneth C. Jenne, II , has developed a comprehensive vision of the Region's future, covering areas 
including but not limited to, education, law enforcement, health, and transportation. The process considered the human, 
physical and natural systems of Palm Beach, Broward, Dade, and Monroe Counties using a variety of means including focus 
groups, discussions, presentations, and an American Assembly in May 1995.</p>
<p>On February 29, 1996, the Southeast Florida 2025 Steering Committee met to review the Final Report and approve 
initiatives that will move the project from vision to action. Action Teams in the issue areas of Economic Development; 
Education; Transportation, Land Use and Infrastructure; Natural Resources; and Public Health were formed to undertake 
specific initiatives to move Southeast Florida into the 21st century. Southeast Florida community leaders serve as 
facilitators and team members.</p>
<p><a href="../current/menu523.htm"><b>FLORIDA GOLD COAST CLEAN CITIES COALITION</b></a></p>
<p>In 1992, the U.S. Department of Energy initiated the national Clean Cities program to encourage cooperation between the 
private and public sectors in developing a sustainable market for alternative fuel vehicles. In September 1993, Governor 
Chiles signed State of Florida Executive Order 93-278 establishing the Florida Gold Coast Clean Cities Coalition.</p>
<p>The Florida Gold Coast Clean Cities Coalition is an advisory council composed of state legislators, local government 
representatives, federal and state agency representatives, and private sector representatives concerned with alternative fuel 
vehicles. The role of the Coalition is to provide fuel-neutral policy direction to maximize the use of vehicles operating on 
alternative fuels throughout the three-county area, composed of Palm Beach, Broward and Dade Counties. Council staff 
provides support to the coalition through a contract with the Florida Department of Community Affairs.</p>
<p>In December 1994, staff prepared the final draft of a report entitled Obstacles and Incentives to Alternative Fuel Vehicle 
Use in the Florida Gold Coast. This report analyzes several types of obstacles and incentives affecting alternative fuel 
vehicle use currently in place throughout the country. The report also examines a number of strategies that can help 
overcome the existing obstacles. In February 1995, the Coalition developed a comprehensive alternative fuels plan for the 
Florida Gold Coast entitled the Market Development and Legislative Initiatives Plan. This plan outlines a strategy to 
convert vehicles and develop infrastructure along I-95 and at the three international airports of the region including Fort 
Lauderdale, Miami, and Palm Beach. The United States Department of Energy has distributed the report to other designated 
Clean Cities around the nation as an example of how staff can take a major step in focusing Coalition activities. These 
reports will be revised and updated in FY 1996-97.</p>
<p>The Florida Department of Community Affairs committed four million dollars to the Council to implement the Alternative 
Fuel Vehicle Grant and Alternative Fuel Vehicle Revolving Loan programs to assist local governments and private 
businesses in converting or purchasing alternatively fueled vehicles. The goal of these programs is to help decrease the 
region's dependence on foreign fuels, improve air quality and promote economic development within the region; all while 
positively impacting the natural environment.</p>
<p>In June 1996, four grants totaling $520,928 were awarded to the City of Miami Beach/Miami Beach Transportation 
Management Association; Broward County; City of Hollywood; and the City of North Bay Village. The second phase of the 
Alternative Fuel Vehicle Grant Program is expected to begin in fall 1996. The first phase of the Alternative Fuel Vehicle 
Revolving Loan Program will also begin in fall 1996.</p>
<p><a name="j"><b>COASTAL ZONE MANAGEMENT ACTIVITIES</b></a></p>
<p>As part of the Council's Coastal Zone Management program, staff continues to work in a number of issue areas. The <a href="../current/fmrissum.htm">Florida 
Marine Resource Information System</a>, a geographic information system linking computer-based maps of South Florida 
coastal resources with information databases, was completed this year. Staff continue to improve and update information on 
the system and work with others throughout the state to expand the system to other regions. </p>
<p>The Hurricane Survival Guide for Small Businesses provides small business owners with information on mitigating risk 
before a hurricane and recovering in the aftermath. The Guide was nominated for an award at the 1996 National Hurricane 
Conference. </p>
<p>Also in the past year, Council staff completed work on a model Regional Strategic Coastal Management Element for local 
government comprehensive plans. The model element is designed to help build regional consensus on coastal issues and 
provide resources for local governments. The Southeast Florida Hurricane Evacuation Study was updated to reflect 
post-Hurricane Andrew conditions.</p>
<p>This year, Council staff are working to identify and secure additional <a href="../current/mciess.htm">hurricane shelter space </a>on the mainland for Monroe 
County residents and to create a database of Broward County's critical facility characteristics and locations for use by both 
public and private interests in post-storm damage assessment. </p>
<p><br>
</p>
<p align=center><a href="../council/services.htm#a">Return to Top of Page</a> <br>
</p>
<p><a name="k"><b>ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT ACTIVITIES</b></a></p>
<p>The South Florida Regional Planning Council was awarded a grant from the U.S. Economic Development Administration 
(EDA) in support of the Council's efforts to promote and facilitate a strategic approach to regional economic development 
in South Florida, inclusive of Broward, Dade and Monroe Counties. To advise and assist in implementation, the Council 
created a Regional Economic Development Committee (REDC) made up of Council members and a diverse representation 
of persons and organizations throughout the South Florida region involved with economic development. The Committee 
assists staff in the development of plans and programs, research, identification and development of funding sources for 
various programs and projects; and serve as an advisory board on various programs in the Region.</p>
<p>Under the direction of the REDC, projects have been designed to promote and implement activities based on regional 
collaboration among elected officials, government agencies, community groups, businesses, economic development 
organizations, universities, school systems and other planning and policy-making groups. Staff developed an economic 
development work plan which facilitates the exchange of information and ideas that provided forums to assist local 
governments in providing economic opportunities and the ability to better serve their diverse multi-national and ethnic 
constituencies.</p>
<p>The <a href="../current/srppgoal.htm">Strategic Regional Policy Plan </a>includes an effective and efficient economic development component designed to 
contribute to the diversification of the regional economy, encourage stability and build community commitments. The 
Council's economic development advocacy component assists local governments, city officials, businesses, neighborhood 
communities, visitors, etc., in providing an environment that support economic development throughout the Region. The 
Council continues to assist in promoting international trade and tourism, small and minority business development, tourism, 
environmental issues, employment, community development and the injection of new capital into the South Florida 
economy.</p>
<p>The future prosperity and well-being of South Florida are dependent upon our capacity to build beneficial partnerships to 
create healthy and expanding economies and social environments throughout the Region. Partnerships are critical to 
effectively address issues such as regional growth, quality employment, quality education, affordable housing, affordable 
health care, public transportation, environmental quality, racial and ethnic compatibility, etc. Similarly, addressing the new 
realities of global competition and the changed priorities of economic development are fundamental to the Region's success 
in the world economy and the social and economic well-being of South Florida.</p>
<p><a name="l"><b>HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PLANNING</b></a></p>
<p>In 1986, Congress passed the Emergency Planning and Community Right-To-Know Act (EPCRA) as Title III of the 
Superfund Amendments and Reauthorization Act (SARA). Congress enacted this law to achieve two principal goals. First, 
in an effort to help local communities protect public health and safety and the environment from chemical hazards, the Act 
requires certain facilities to report their chemical inventories. These inventories are used to complete hazards, risk and 
vulnerability analyses designed to improve response time and effectiveness in the event of an accidental release at a 
facility. Second, the Act requires public access to the chemical inventories, thereby allowing residents to know exactly 
what potential hazards exist in their community.</p>
<p>EPCRA requires that each state maintain a <a href="../current/menu522.htm">Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC)</a> structure. Membership of the 
Committee is guided by federal law and includes representatives of government, industry, first aid, emergency management, 
and community groups, among others. Members are confirmed by the State Emergency Response Commission (SERC). The 
SERC sets statewide policy for the implementation of EPCRA.</p>
<p>Since 1988, the Council has served as staff to the District XI LEPC, which encompasses Broward, Dade and Monroe 
Counties. Staff coordinates regularly scheduled LEPC meetings, conducts How-to-Comply seminars, and answers public 
inquiries regarding EPCRA compliance. Staff also maintains the chemical inventories for public inspection consistent with 
the Community Right-to-Know provisions of EPCRA. Staff and the LEPC are also tasked with preparing and updating a 
comprehensive emergency response plan for the Region. The LEPC recently completed and submitted a major revision of 
the District XI hazardous material plan; To promote hazardous materials awareness, staff has prepared the following 
material: a video entitled Hidden Dangers in Paradise, a hospital preparedness guide entitled A Guide to HazMat 
Preparedness for Hospitals and a children's information and activity book entitled Let's Learn About Hazardous Materials. 
The LEPC uses these items and others their ongoing effort to enhance the public's awareness of hazardous materials.</p>
<p>On June 28, 1996, the District XI LEPC and staff conducted the first full-scale multiple county hazardous material exercise 
involving Dade and Broward county emergency response agencies. The exercise scenario was a leaking pressurized liquid 
rail tank car containing 33,000 gallons of liquefied gas. The objective of the exercise was to practice a multi-county 
response to a major hazardous material incident; and to test cross-county communication capabilities. More than 140 
responders, 15 hospitals and 30 emergency response agencies participated. </p>
<p><br>
</p>
<p align=center><a href="../council/services.htm">Return to Top of Page</a> <br>
</p>
<p><a href="../current/menu526.htm"><b>LOCAL GOVERNMENT COMPREHENSIVE PLAN REVIEW</b></a></p>
<p>The Council regularly reviews local government comprehensive plans and plan amendments for consistency with the SRPP. 
There are presently 63 local governments in the South Florida region, and many amend their plans regularly to adjust to 
changing conditions. Plan and plan amendments are reviewed to determine compatibility with the SRPP and for 
extra-jurisdictional impacts. </p>
<p>During FY 1995-1996, the Council received regional delegation of the sufficiency review of local government 
comprehensive plan Evaluation and Appraisal Reports (EARs) from the Department of Community Affairs. Council staff 
have now reviewed a dozen EARS for sufficiency and are now beginning to review EAR-based amendments. Council staff 
works closely with the local government, Florida Department of Community Affairs, Florida Department of Transportation, 
South Florida Water Management District and neighboring local governments in the EAR review process. The renewed 
interest in incorporation in the urban areas of the Region has continued and the potential for new local governments in Dade 
and Broward Counties remains. These recently incorporated Cities of Aventura and Pinecrest will prepare and submit 
comprehensive plans for review in the coming year. </p>
<p><a name="n"><b>DEVELOPMENT OF REGIONAL IMPACT PROGRAM</b></a></p>
<p>The Council is the coordinating agency for the Development of Regional Impact (DRI) program for the South Florida 
region. FY 1995-96 saw a significant increase in DRI program activities. Council staff coordinated the review of nine new 
or substantial deviation DRIs, including Amoco Oil Company, Dadeland Mall, Beacon TradePort, Fort 
Lauderdale-Hollywood International Airport, Miami International Airport, Portofino, Weston, Spectrum, and the Broward 
County Civic Arena. Of these, one completed the review process and eight are undergoing review. During this time period, 
Council staff also participated in the review of 22 substantial deviation determinations (Notice of Proposed Change to 
previously approved DRIs) and Binding Letters, issued by the Florida Department of Community Affairs (DCA). During the 
year, Council staff has worked to facilitate coordination and consensus building among the various DRI review agencies, 
local governments, applicants other interested parties. The Council produces and distributes the Guide for Developments of 
Regional Impact, a compilation of the various DRI related statutes, rules, and forms, including a layperson's description of 
the DRI process.</p>
<p><a name="o"><b>INTERGOVERNMENTAL COORDINATION AND REVIEW PROGRAM</b></a></p>
<p>The South Florida Regional Planning Council is responsible for the review of applications for state and federal permits and 
requests for funding from state and federal agencies for projects within the South Florida region. Council staff reviews each 
application for consistency with the Strategic Regional Policy Plan for South Florida. The review frequently involves 
consultation with various regional, state, and federal agencies as well as local governments within the region. The 
Council's recommendation is transmitted to the appropriate state or federal permitting agency and the applicant. 
Applications cover issues ranging from bridge replacement or wetlands alterations to programs for bilingual education or 
AIDS prevention. Council staff reviewed 261 applications in FY 1995-1996.</p>
<p><a name="p"><b>COUNCIL WORLD WIDE WEB HOME PAGE</b></a></p>
<p>During FY 1995-1996, the Council began development and construction of a SFRPC home page on the World Wide Web. 
As part of this project, the Council will now be linked electronically and able to send and receive e-mail over the Internet. 
The Council home page should be complete and posted on numerous search engines by the Fall of 1996.</p>
<p><a href="../region/menu4.htm"><b>STATE DATA CENTER PROGRAM</b></a></p>
<p>As an affiliate of the Florida State Data Center, the Council receives and distributes data from the U.S. Bureau of the 
Census and other sources. The Council library contains a comprehensive set of publications for the State of Florida, as well 
as an extensive collection of CD-ROMs containing detailed data. Staff can provide selected data on diskette.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p align=center><a href="../council/services.htm#a">Return to Top of Page</a> </p>
