<html>

<head>
<title>Highlights of Council Activities</title>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../images/glogoppr.jpg">
<p align=center><img src="../images/sfrpcgp.gif" align=bottom width=288 height=144></p>
<p align=center><font size=5><b>Highlights of Council Activities</b></font> </p>
<p align=center>December 1996 </p>
<hr>
<p><b>Regional Transit Organization Feasibility Study Final Report Issued</b> </p>
<p>The Regional Transit Organization Feasibility Study for Palm Beach, Broward and Dade Counties, initiated earlier this 
year, is jointly sponsored by the Metropolitan Planning Organizations (MPOs) from the three counties. Council staff has 
been serving on the Study Advisory Committee. A Final Report prepared by the consultant was issued on December 20, 
1996. The Final Report finds that the current pathway for the transit entities in the region will not be financially 
sustainable. The Report recommends the creation of a regional transit authority (RTA) in the three county area through 
state legislation. The RTA will serve as a super-regional transit planning and funding organization and have taxing 
authority. The Study Advisory Committee is scheduled to meet during January 1997 to formulate its own 
recommendations. For additional information, please contact <a href="mailto:pchang@sfrpc.com">Ping Chang</a> of Council staff. </p>
<hr>
<p><b>Council Staff Facilitates the Workshop on Human Service Delivery Systems</b> </p>
<p>Council staff facilitated a workshop to develop a model for the human service delivery system in Broward County at the 
request of the Coordinating Council of Broward (CCB). Prior to the workshop, which was held on December 9, 1996, 
staff conducted interviews with each member of the CCB. Also prior to the workshop, staff prepared and distributed 
<i>Human Services Delivery Models: An Issues and Options Paper</i>, which establishes a framework for the discussion of 
alternative service delivery models. After the workshop, a final report was prepared with a summary of the findings. For 
additional information, please contact <a href="mailto:rogburn@sfrpc.com">Dick Ogburn</a> or <a href="mailto:pchang@sfrpc.com">Ping Chang</a> of Council staff. </p>
<hr>
<p><b>Technical Assistance in the EAR based Amendment Process</b> </p>
<p>As local governments move toward the adoption of comprehensive plan amendments which respond to their Evaluation 
and Appraisal Reports (EARs), staff is providing technical assistance. Pertinent information relating to the review 
process and a list of appropriate staff persons to call has been posted on the Council's web site (www.sfrpc.com). 
Information on statute and rule changes has been made available, and staff has fielded a number of routine telephone calls 
relating to the EAR based review process. In addition staff has participated in two planning sessions with City of North 
Miami Beach department heads to assist in that city's comprehensive plan update. For additional information, please 
contact <a href="mailto:bobd@sfrpc.com">Bob Daniels</a> or <a href="mailto:hulseyj@sfrpc.com">John Hulsey</a> of Council staff. </p>
<hr>
<p><b><i>www.sfrpc.com</i></b> </p>
<p>The Council's World Wide Web site (http://www.sfrpc.com) continues to grow with additional information about the 
Council and its activities. Recently-added pages of note include the monthly <i>Highlights of Council Activities</i> (this 
document), a description of the DRI Review Process, an overview of the review process for local government 
comprehensive plans, the entire text of the Eastward Ho! report, Regional Directory listings for Broward, Dade and 
Monroe Counties, related web site links for South Florida municipalities. More is being added and updated on a daily 
basis. Check it out! For comments or additional information, please contact <a href="mailto:rogburn@sfrpc.com">Dick Ogburn</a> or <a href="mailto:esilva@sfrpc.com">Eric Silva</a> of Council staff.</p>
<hr>
<p><b>Southeast Florida 2025 Natural Resources Action Team</b> </p>
<p>Council staff hosted the fourth meeting of the Natural Resources Action Team of Southeast Florida 2025 on December 16, 
1996. The team discussed an action plan for implementation of the goals, objectives and strategies developed by the team 
since last spring. For additional information about the Natural Resources Action Team, please contact <a href="mailto:hulseyj@sfrpc.com">John Hulsey</a> or 
<a href="mailto:esilva@sfrpc.com">Eric Silva</a> of Council staff. </p>
<hr>
<p><b>Sustainable Communities Demonstration Project</b> </p>
<p>Continued interest is being shown by local governments in the Region in the Sustainable Communities Demonstration 
Project. A number of queries have been received on the status of the program. Staff discussion with Florida Department of 
Community Affairs (DCA) confirms that designations should be made by year's end. Staff anticipates involvement in the 
formulation of designation agreements for any local governments in the Region that are designated in order to ensure that 
the potential for adverse extrajurisdictional impacts is minimized. For additional information, please contact <a href="mailto:bobd@sfrpc.com">Bob Daniels</a> 
of Council staff. </p>
<hr>
<p><b>Regional Impacts and Federal Consistency Annual Workshop</b> </p>
<p>Council staff participated in the third annual workshop on the review of Regional Impacts and Federal Consistency of 
grant proposals and development permits as part of a grant funded by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric 
Administration through Florida's Coastal Management Program, Department of Community Affairs. The workshop, held in 
Tallahassee on December 17, 1996, provided the Council with input regarding how the responsibilities of the review 
process are carried out. For additional information about the grant program, please contact <a href="mailto:hulseyj@sfrpc.com">John Hulsey</a> of Council staff. </p>
<hr>
<p><b>Eastward Ho! Phase 2 Activities Begin</b> </p>
<p>Recent Eastward Ho! activities include meetings with Department of Community Affairs representatives and the mayors 
of the City of Homestead and Florida City to discuss expanding the study area boundaries to include all or part of these 
communities. Council staff continues its efforts to broaden the number of both public and private partners involved in the 
Eastward Ho! initiative. Other activities include discussions and site visits to redevelopment efforts in the City of West 
Palm Beach; continued discussions concerning the financial impediments to infill development and redevelopment; the 
first Phase 2 DCA grantee roundtable; and participation in the meetings of the Dade County Brownfield Task Force. For 
additional information, please contact <a href="mailto:isabelc@sfrpc.com">Isabel Cosio Carballo</a> or <a href="mailto:davidd@sfrpc.com">David Dahlstrom</a> of Council staff. </p>
<hr>
<p><b>Small &amp; Minority Resource Providers Forum</b> </p>
<p>The South Florida Small &amp; Minority Resources Forum held its third meeting in December. Member organizations 
discussed issues regarding the effective delivery of services to small and minority businesses in the region. Four 
committees were formed to develop strategies in four specific areas: 1) duplication of services; 2) ways to develop better 
regional communication to small and minority businesses; 3) development of a system for effective follow up; and 4) 
ways to obtain commitment from corporations to do business with small and minority businesses. For additional 
information, please contact <a href="mailto:gadson@sfrpc.com">George Gadson</a> of Council staff. </p>
<hr>
<p><b>SFRPC to Conduct Vision Exercise for Lower Matecumbe Key in 1997</b> </p>
<p>On February 26, 1997, the SFRPC will conduct a vision retreat for the community of Lower Matecumbe Key. The retreat 
will provide the citizens of Lower Matecumbe Key an opportunity to engage in dialogue and develop implementation 
strategies regarding issues impacting the community. The purpose of the retreat is to create a comprehensive vision for 
Lower Matecumbe Key's future. For additional information, please contact <a href="mailto:esuarez@sfrpc.com">Evangeline Suarez</a> of Council staff. </p>
<hr>
