<head>
<title>POTENTIAL INFORMATION TO BE INCLUDED ON THE SFRPC HOME PAGE</title>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../images/plogoppr.jpg">
<p align=center><a name="z">South Florida Regional Planning Council</a></p>
<p align=center><font size=4><b>Council Programs</b></font></p>
<p align=center><font size=4><b>Visioning and Group Facilitation</b></font></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/visionsm.gif" align=bottom width=193 height=65></p>
<hr>
<p><a href="#a"><font size=4>Visioning: The First Step in Planning for the Future</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#b"><font size=4>Are you satisfied with your city's or organization's direction?</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#c"><font size=4>Do you have a vision for the future?</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#d"><font size=4>What is visioning?</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#e"><font size=4>Who can help your city or organization conduct a visioning assembly?</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#f"><font size=4>What are the benefits of conducting a visioning assembly?</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#g"><font size=4>When should you conduct a Visioning exercise and where?</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#h"><font size=4>How many meetings will it take to conduct a Visioning workshop?</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#i"><font size=4>What should your city or organization do to begin the Visioning process?</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#j"><font size=4>Recent Workshop(s) Coordinated or Facilitated by the Council</font></a> </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="a"><font size=4>VISIONING: THE FIRST STEP IN PLANNING FOR THE FUTURE</font></a></p>
<p><a name="b"><font size=4>Are you satisfied with your city's or organization's direction?</font></a> </p>
<p><font size=3>Do you have a vision for the future?</font></p>
<p><font size=3>If you do not and have been grappling with the notion look no further.</font></p>
<p><font size=3>Many cities and organizations are not satisfied with their direction. Many lack a cohesive vision or a plan of action for the future. To create a plan of action that 
is realistic yet challenging, and moves a city or organization in a positive direction for the future, requires careful and strategic planning. </font></p>
<p><a name="c"><font size=4>What is visioning?</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>Visioning is the foundation for developing a realistic mission statement and a workable strategic plan. Visioning is a series of free-wheeling meetings involving a 
broad cross-section of residents and business owners in a particular municipality or key individuals in an organization. Participants talk conceptually about the 
long term direction they would like to see their city or organization take in the future and the issues that have a critical impact on their city or organization. The 
idea is to get your city's visioning committee or organizational team to toss out ideas and dreams for group consideration, without restrictions and inhibitions.</font></p>
<p><a name="d"><font size=4>Who can help your city or organization conduct a visioning assembly?</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>The South Florida Regional Planning Council (SFRPC), in cooperation with the appointed visioning process steering committee, can coordinate an 
Assembly/Charrette/Focus Group or Workshop for any city or organization. The SFRPC can assist in determining the most critical and growing issues of 
concern in your city or organization--with possible strategic solutions. The visioning process will be planned and implemented in conjunction with the appointed 
steering committee. Invited citizens and participants along with the visioning committee will be responsible for creating a comprehensive vision for their city or 
organization.</font></p>
<p><a name="e"><font size=4>What are the benefits of conducting a visioning assembly?</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>A visioning process can assist a city or organization in establishing a more meaningful and integrated planning process by establishing a framework to identify 
critical linkages. Taking the time to explore your city's or organization's vision for the future will enable you to see the wonderful possibilities that exist for your 
city or organization to grow to its fullest potential. </font></p>
<p><a name="f"><font size=4>When should you conduct a Visioning exercise and where?</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>A visioning exercise is often conducted as a first step in starting a new venture; nonetheless, visioning can be valuable in revitalizing or refocusing an existing 
city's or organization's mission, objectives and goals.</font></p>
<p><font size=3>Visioning assemblies are usually held in a neutral place away from city hall or your organization's offices. This allows participants to become totally involved in 
the vision process without any distractions. Typically, a hotel or meeting center offers the best accommodations, where refreshments can be served. </font></p>
<p><a name="g"><font size=4>How many meetings will it take to conduct a Visioning workshop?</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>This depends on the number of issues to be addressed and the particular organization or municipality. The normal time commitment for a full visioning assembly 
process is about two and a half days; however, some programs can be completed in a single day or half day.</font></p>
<p align=center><a href="#z"><font size=4>Return to Top of the Page</font></a></p>
<p><a name="h"><font size=4>What should your city or organization do to begin the Visioning process?</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>Contact the South Florida Regional Planning Council to discuss the services it can provide to assist your city or organization in planning and preparing for a 
Visioning assembly. Some of the services the SFRPC can provide are:</font></p>
<ul>
<li><font size=3>Facilitation/Recording Services </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Visioning Committee Assistance </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Reproduction/Mailing Capabilities </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Professional Organization/Preparation </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Assistance in Preparing a Vision Statement </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Preparation of a Final Report </font></li>
</ul>
<p><font size=3>Remember, a visioning assembly can be tailored to meet your city's or organization's specific needs. For additional information, please contact </font><a href="mailto:esuarez@sfrpc.com"><font size=3>Evangeline 
Suarez</font></a><font size=3>.</font></p>
<p><a name="OLE_LINK1"><font size=4>Recent Workshop(s) Coordinated or Facilitated by the South Florida Regional Planning Council </font></a><font size=4>(SFRPC)</font></p>
<p><font size=3>Downtown Fort Lauderdale Transportation Management Association - March 1996 </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Broward Community Development Corporation Workshop - December 1995 </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Deerfield Beach Community Redevelopment Area Vision Workshops - November 1995 </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Pompano Beach Vision 2000+ Assembly - October 1995 </font></p>
<p><a href="../current/menu524.htm"><font size=3>Southeast Florida Vision 2025: An Investment Strategy for the Future Assembly - May 1995</font></a><font size=3> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Integrating Education Issues Into The Long Range Planning Process - March 1995 </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Broward Education Foundation Forum - February 1995 </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Downtown Fort Lauderdale Transportation Management Association - January 1995 </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Blockbuster Park Community Forums - May and October 1994 </font></p>
<p><font size=3>U S Department of Commerce Economic Development Administration Workshops - February 1994 </font></p>
<p><a href="../current/menu521.htm"><font size=3>SFRPC Strategic Regional Policy Plan Workshops - May 1994</font></a></p>
<p><a href="../whatsnew/whatnew3.htm"><font size=3>Visoning in Lower Matecumbe Key - Winter 1997</font></a></p>
<p align=center><a href="#z"><font size=4>Return to Top of the Page</font></a></p>
