</DOCHDR>

<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>FMRIS</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/plogoppr.jpg">
<CENTER>South Florida Regional Planning Council</CENTER><br>


<center><b>Special Projects and Studies</b></center></font>
<center><b>
<font size=+1>Florida's Marine Resource Information System (FMRIS)
</FONT></b></center>
<hr><br>

The South Florida Regional Planning Council (SFRPC) is pleased to 
announce the availability of Florida's Marine Resource Information 
System, a geographic information system specifically designed to provide 

graphic and textual data about the ocean and coastal resources of Dade, 
Broward, and Monroe Counties.  Developed as a prototype for a statewide
 marine resource information system, FMRIS provides non-technical users 
the ability to easily access a broad range of detailed environmental 
data 
so they may better manage the region's marine resources.  The project 
was
 partially funded by a grant from the Florida Coastal Management 
Program,
 with support from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.
<br><br>
The information system created through this project includes the 
following features:
<ul>

<li> FMRIS brings together existing digital data on coastal and marine 
resources for South Florida, gathered from a variety of sources, 
enabling it to be graphically displayed in map-overlay format.  In 
addition, the system provides text cites and bibliographic data for 
regulatory programs and studies.  A listing of the categories of 
information contained in the system is included below.

<li> By selecting a geographic area and a regulatory program, a system 
user can show all objects or sub-areas falling within the scope of the 
regulatory program.  Similarly, it is possible to select geographic 
resources within the area of interest and immediately identify the 
regulatory information pertinent to those resources.

<li> A system user can locate and analyze the overlap of buffer zones 
associated with existing or proposed uses and their effect on objects or 
geographic areas.  For example, the system can identify where 
recreational uses overlap with environmentally sensitive areas.

<li> The system user can define an area of interest and conduct analyses 
within the area, depicting data in a multitude of scales ranging from 
region-wide to specific individual sites.
</ul>
<br><br>
One of the most distinctive features of FMRIS is its ability to link
 geographic data to related regulatory and bibliographic information. 
 Through these data linking capabilities, the system is able to produce
 a comprehensive report on all resources of a specific kind found within
 an area selected by the user.  Although the volume may be very large, 
it is possible to request a print-out of all of the system information
 implicated by resources contained within an area selected by the user,
 independent of having selected some subset of the geographic data.
<br><br>
FMRIS is potentially valuable to a broad range of groups such as the 
federal government, state and regional agencies, local government, 
developers and environmental groups.  It is available for user access 
initially at two locations, the SFRPC headquarters in Hollywood and the
 Florida Coastal Management Program at the Department of Community
 Affairs in Tallahassee.  These systems provide user access and print
 color maps.  Anyone desiring to operate the system at a different 
location can do so by acquiring the data and program files at cost from
 the Council and installing them on an appropriate AT-class computer
 running Microsoft Windows and ESRI's ArcView 2.  The computer, Windows,
 and ArcView must be purchased separately for each additional system.
<br><br>
Central to the success of FMRIS is the ability to periodically update 
and
 enhance the data and data structures.  Council staff will work with
 users to maintain the South Florida marine resource information 
databases current as part of our continued effort to develop a
 user-friendly regional information system to support regional 
decision-making.  FMRIS has been designed to enable a wide variety of 
data maintenance activities for each of the three component types of 
information in the system.  These range from adding objects or related 
items (records) to existing databases, to including new bibliographic 
references and updating regulatory statutes.  The routines for 
incorporating geographic data into FMRIS are automated.  Password
 protection is available for all data maintenance activities to ensure
 that changes to the data sets are made by authorized personnel.
<br><br>
The data contained in FMRIS has been drawn from the following 
categories:
<ul>
<li> Submerged Lands and Jurisdiction
<li> Marine Salvage, Finds, and Historic Preservation
<li> Management of Marine Habitat and Protected Species
<li> Benthic Resources
<li> Artificial Reefs
<li> Marine Mineral Mining
<li> Ports, Marine Terminals and Marinas
<li> Marine Recreation
<li> South Florida Base Map
<li> Water Quality
<li> Land Use
<li> Wetlands and Mangroves
<li> Miscellaneous
</ul><br><br>
At this time, the preferred method for distribution of the program and 
data files is QIC-80 compatible tape or 8mm UNIX TAR tape.  Special 
arrangements can be made to provide this information on CD-ROM.  The 
Final Report and a User Manual are available for distribution to those 
who acquire the system.  Also, an Executive Summary, with samples of 
system output, is available upon request.  Inquiries should be directed 
to <a href="mailto:rogburn@sfrpc.com">
Richard Ogburn</a>, <a href="mailto:celam@sfrpc.com"> Manuel Cela</a>, or <a href="mailto:esilva@sfrpc.com"> Eric Silva</a>.



