<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>MONROE COUNTY INLAND EVACUATION AND SHELTER STUDY</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/plogoppr.jpg">
<P>
<CENTER>South Florida Regional Planning Council<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>Special Projects and Studies<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>MONROE COUNTY INLAND EVACUATION AND SHELTER STUDY
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
The Florida Keys form an arc over one hundred miles in length
with two two-lane roads providing egress to the mainland. Due
to their low elevations, the Keys have no shelters designated
to serve in a hurricane of category 3 or greater intensity. The
resulting clearance time to evacuate the county is greater than
a twenty-four hour hurricane warning will permit. Their designated
shelter on the mainland is capable of holding less than five percent
of the resident population, without including the tourist population.
If one measures the ability to find public shelter inside or outside
the area studied, Monroe County residents are left in an untenable
position: 
<OL>
<LI>not enough shelter spaces exist inside the region; 
<LI>it takes too long to escape the region. 
</OL>
<P>
The objective of this study is to locate additional shelter space
as near to the Keys as is physically feasible. Numerous land uses,
such as private schools, places of worship, service organization
meeting halls, country clubs, community centers, and corporate
offices, typically contain structures which are conducive to use
as a hurricane shelter. The South Florida Regional Planning Council
will:
<OL>
<LI>review TRW-Redi property information for Dade, Broward, and
Palm Beach counties to generate a list of potential shelter candidates;
<LI>contact the property owners to discuss with them the need
for public/private sheltering and the possibility of the use of
their facilities;
<LI>study each facility for vulnerability to hurricane hazards
such as surge inundation, rainfall flooding, high winds, or the
presence of hazardous materials;
<LI>facilitate the design and execution of an agreement by which
each facility may be used as an emergency evacuation shelter dedicated
for the primary use of Monroe County residents; and
<LI>develop and publish an instruction pamphlet for Monroe County
residents to use to reach the new shelters before hurricane season
begins in 1997. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
For additional information on the Monroe County Inland Evacuation
and Shelter Study, please contact <A href ="hulseyj@sfrpc.com">John Hulsey</A>.
<BR>
<BR>
</OL>
<P>
