<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT08-B35-109</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA090-000961-B029-218</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.sfrpc.com:80/current/ehotools.htm 199.227.154.96 19970110051110 text/html 13913
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 10 Jan 1997 05:16:45 GMT
Server: Stronghold/1.3.2 Ben-SSL/1.3 Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 13712
Last-modified: Mon, 25 Nov 1996 22:24:55 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>Tools and Incentives</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 
2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY background="../images/plogoppr.jpg">
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">PLANNING TOOLS AND
INCENTIVES: A BRIEF DEFINITION<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">AREAS OUTSIDE (PRIMARILY WEST)
OF THE EASTWARD HO! CORRIDOR<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1. Urban Development Boundary: </FONT></B>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a
boundary to distinguish the area where urban development may occur
during a specified planning horizon.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2. Transfer of Development Rights:
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a system which takes some
of the content of the bundle of rights for one piece of property
and transfers it to another piece of property.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">3. Purchase of Development Rights:
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a technique which allows
control of the land without retaining all the responsibilities
of full management and ownership.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">4. Tiered Impact Fee System (potential):
a </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">system to reflect the full
cost of western development compared with that of the eastern
development. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">AREAS WITHIN THE EASTWARD
HO! CORRIDOR <BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<U><B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Planning Tools<BR>
</FONT></B></U>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1. Visioning/Charette: </FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">a
planning process to create a shared and desired future for a community.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2. Consistency of State/Regional/local
Plans and Land Development Regulations <BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<U><B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Public Sector Development Initiatives
<BR>
</FONT></B></U>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1. Public Entrepreneurship: </FONT></B>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">involves
public sector's activities in assembly and conveyance of land
along with possible fiscal incentives for private investment.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2. Land Banking: </FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">the
purchase of land by a governmental entity with the intent of controlling
its future use.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">3. Joint Development: </FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">real
estate development that is closely linked to public transportation
services and stations and relies to a considerable extent on the
market and locational advantages provided by the transit facility.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">4. Capital Improvement Program: </FONT></B>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a
program for the multi-year budgeting of capital improvement 
expenditures,
typically for a five year period.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">5. Commuter Rail Service on FEC Corridor
(potential): </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">the FEC corridor
is closer to many downtown areas but without commuter service.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<U><B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Regulatory Tools/Incentives<BR>
</FONT></B></U>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1. Streamlining Development Review
and Permit Processes<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2. Intensified Code Enforcement:
a tool</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua"> to help prevent the
further deterioration of an area.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">3. Overlay Zoning: zoning</FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">
which<B> </B>applies a common set of regulations and standards
to a designated area that may cut across several different preexisting
conventional zoning districts.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">4. Performance Zoning:</FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">
a zone defined by a list of permitted impacts as opposed to a
list of permitted uses.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">5. Incentive Zoning: under incentive
zoning, </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a developer may be
encouraged to erect a building in a way that is not usually permitted
in that district under the community's zoning ordinance in exchange
for providing certain amenities.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">6. Inclusionary Zoning: </FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">designed
to ensure the inclusion of very low, low, and moderate income
housing within a given political jurisdiction.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">7. Mixed-use Zoning: </FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">combination
of different land uses on the same or adjacent lots or within
the same building or complex.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">8. Planned Unit Development: </FONT></B>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a
device that allows a development to be planned and built as a
unit.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">9. Form District (potential): </FONT></B>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">determine
the &quot;form&quot; or &quot;pattern&quot; of development within
a community and to design districts which conform to those patterns
or to create new forms within a community. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">10. Transit Oriented Development:
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">an approach that emphasizes
securing a high density level, combining a mix of uses, utilizing
a hierarchy of streets and designing at a human scale to maximize
the potential for transit use within a community.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>

 <B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">11.Traditional Neighborhood Development</B>

:
similar to TOD and gives additional emphases on integrating civic
uses (e.g. community center, church) and open space into the 
development.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">12. Unified Development Code (potential):
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">
a land use ordinance that combines the provisions of ordinarily
separate zoning and subdivision ordinances.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">13. Chapter 380 Regional Activity
Center:: </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a compact, high
density multi-use area designated as appropriate for intensive
growth by the local government of jurisdiction.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">14. Regional Development District:
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a geographic area specifically
designated as highly suitable for increased threshold intensity
in the approved local comprehensive plan and the applicable strategic
regional policy plan.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">15. Transportation Concurrency Exception
Area: </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">an area within which
local government grants an exception from the concurrency requirement
for transportation facilities.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">16. Areawide or Downtown Development
of Regional Impacts: </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">two
alternative forms to the standard DRI process in addressing generally
large areas or the downtown areas. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<U><B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Financial Tools/Incentives<BR>
</FONT></B></U>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1. Incentives to Lending Institutions:
t</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">he need for incentives to
lending institutions have been mentioned throughout the Eastward
Ho! discussions. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2. Enterprise Zone: </FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">a
specific geographical area with a set of policies designed to
encourage local businesses to take advantage of tax incentives
and other public assistance with the hope of generating investment
that leads to employment growth.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">3.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">
<B>Enterprise Communities and Empowerment Zones: </B>encourage
investment in designated distressed areas by providing a combination
of direct grants, tax incentives and priority consideration for
flexibility in the use of funds. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">4. Tax Increment Financing: </FONT></B>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a
method of funding public investment in an area slated for redevelopment
by recapturing, for a set time, all or a portion of the increased
tax revenue that may result if the redevelopment stimulates private
investment.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">5. Below-market-rate Financing: </FONT></B>






<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">offering
construction or permanent financing at below-market-interest rates
can be effective in attracting developers and home purchasers.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">6. Tax Base Sharing (potential):
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a mechanism through which
fiscal benefits of growth within a metropolitan area can be shared
by all residents regardless of where the actual development occurs.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">7. Preferential Taxation: </FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">the
use of tax credits or deductions as incentives for preserving
or creating socially desired land uses.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">8. Fee Reduction or Waivers: </FONT></B>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">reductions
of permit or impact fees for infill/redevelopment projects.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">9. Funding for School Improvements
<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">10.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">
<B>Community Development Block Program (CDBG)</B>: financing programs
for both commercial and residential rehabilitation, construction
of infill-housing and infrastructure improvements in areas predominantly
with low and moderate income residents. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">11. State Housing Initiative Program
(SHIP):</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua"> provision of financial
and technical assistance for the creation and preservation of
affordable housing.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">12. HOME Investment Partnership Program
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">:
offers similar types of assistance as SHIP to both for-profit
and nonprofit developers, as well as individual homeowners.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<U><B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Institutional Tools<BR>
</FONT></B></U>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1. Community Redevelopment Agency:
an entity created by a </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">county
or municipality to carry out redevelopment function (Sec 163.356,
F.S.).<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2. Land Assembly Entities (potential):
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">entities which can acquire
land through foreclosure or donation, purchase sites needed to
aggregate larger tracts, and dispose of land to developers and
community groups.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">3. Community Financing Consortium:
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">an entity which is<B> </B>made
up of a number of financing institutions working together.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">4. Neighborhood Improvement District:
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">an area defined in Sec 163.503,
F.S. where there is a plan to reduce crime through the implementation
of environmental design, environmental security, or defensible
space techniques for crime prevention. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">5. Special Assessment District: </FONT></B>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">a
geographical area within which the special levy against property
to finance specific capital improvements is spread.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">6. Transportation Management Association:
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">an entity which is formed
by organizations within a specific area to address primarily 
transportation
issues for their employees.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">7. Regional Transit Authority (potential):
</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">an<B> </B>authority which
could have any combination of the authority regarding funding,
planning, or operation of the regional transit systems.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<U><B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Community Development Tools<BR>
</FONT></B></U>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1. Expanded University Small Business
Assistance Programs: </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">providing
expanded university small business assistance programs will help
to nurture and retain small business within the Corridor.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2. Community Policing: </FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">includes
community activities to assist the delivery of policing programs.
<BR><br>
</FONT>

<B>3. Community Leadership Training: </B>an important part
of the overall community capacity building effort.<BR>
<BR>
<HR>

