<META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<TITLE>Our People</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 
2.03z">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/ylogoppr.jpg">
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/rppsmall.gif"> <BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="a"><I><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Strategic Regional
Policy Plan for South Florida<BR>
</FONT></B></I><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Regional Profile
and Identity</FONT></B></A></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Our People</FONT></B>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="profpeop.htm#b">Rate and Sources of Growth
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profpeop.htm#c">Age Profile and the 
Elderly Population</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profpeop.htm#d">In-Migration and 
Population Diversity</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profpeop.htm#e">Population Shifts Within 
the Region</A>
<BR>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Perhaps the single most powerful force
shaping South Florida's character is its explosive growth. The
Florida of 1900 had only 12 cities with more than 2,500 people.
Most of these cities were located in the northern and central
areas of the state. Florida's largest city at that time was 
Jacksonville,
which had 28,429 residents. Miami had a population of 1,681. 
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="b"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Rate and Sources
of Growth<BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">South Florida's population began to
grow rapidly with the land boom of the 1920s. By 1930, the area
had 176,600 residents and was on its way to becoming a major force
in the state. The population of South Florida grew to 1.3 million
in 1960 and to 3.3 million in 1990. Official projections indicate
it will increase to 3.7 million by the turn of the century, and
to 4.3 million by the year 2015, the end of this plan's 20-year
planning horizon (Table 1). The region's share of statewide population,
which rose to 28.6 percent in 1970, fell to 25.3 percent in 1990,
and is projected to fall to 22.3 percent in 2015.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Table 1<BR>
South Florida Population and Projections, 1980-2015 </FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">(thousands)</FONT>
<P>
<TABLE BORDER="1">
<TR><TD WIDTH=77><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Period</FONT></CENTER>


</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Broward</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Dade</FONT></CENTER>


