</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">15,449</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=77><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2005*</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1,553</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2,231</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">96</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">3,880</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">16,742</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=77><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2010*</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1,647</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2,344</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">102</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">4,092</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">18,008</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=77><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2015*</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1,741</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2,455</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">107</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">4,304</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=120><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">19,277</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Book Antiqua">(*) Projections<BR>
Source: Bureau of Economic and Business Research, <I>Projections
of Florida Population by County, 1993-2020</I>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">As shown in Table 2, growth in each
of the three counties of the Region has been very different during
the second half of the century. The limited availability of land
in the Florida Keys has translated into population growth rates
which were substantially lower in Monroe County than in the rest
of the Region and in the state as a whole, through the 1970s.
The official projections above do not reflect Monroe County's
rate of growth ordinance, which is expected to limit future population
growth compared to historical trends. Dade County population growth
was slightly more rapid than in the state as a whole in the 1950s,
but slowed in the 1960s, as limits were placed on western expansion.
Today, even with a significant inflow of international migration,
Dade County's population is projected to increase at only about
two thirds of the annual population growth rate in the state.
By contrast, Broward County's extraordinary population growth,
beginning in the 1950s, firmly outpaced statewide and regional
growth through the 1970s, as the occupation of the western part
of the county took place, and will continue to lead the region
as the County moves toward build-out.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Table 2<BR>
Average Annual Rates of Population Growth (%)</FONT></B>
<P>
<TABLE BORDER="1">
<TR><TD WIDTH=144><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Period</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Broward</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Dade</FONT></CENTER>


</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Monroe</FONT>
