</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=144><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2000/2005*</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.3</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.1</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.3</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.2</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=96><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.6</FONT></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=144><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2005/2010*</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.2</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.0</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.2</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.1</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=96><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.5</FONT></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=144><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">2010/2015*</FONT>
</CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.1</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">0.9</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.1</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=102><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.0</FONT></CENTER>
</TD><TD WIDTH=96><CENTER><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">1.4</FONT></CENTER>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Book Antiqua">(*) Projections<BR>
Source: Bureau of Economic and Business Research, <I>Projections
of Florida Population by County, 1993-2020</I>.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">As we near the end of the century, and
Florida's population growth winds down from the more dynamic past
decades, growth poles have shifted to other regions in the state.
Even so, official projections indicate an average of 39,000 people
are being added to the South Florida population each year over
this decade, and the first fifteen years of the next century will
see approximately 43,000 new residents per year being added to
the regional population.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The impact on South Florida of migration,
both national and international, can be seen clearly by looking
at the sources of demographic changes between 1950 and 1990. <B>Nearly
85 percent of the 2.7 million new residents in the region during
those years migrated here.</B> A similar proportion of overall
growth in the state of Florida resulted from in-migration in the
same period.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="c"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Age Profile and
the Elderly Population <BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The population of South Florida today
reflects trends which are expected to emerge in the remainder
of the United States over the next decade. Migration of a significant
number of retirees to the region in past decades has given an
age profile to our population which is expected to become more
widespread as the overall population ages. The median age of the
Region's population has risen to reflect this change. The most
dramatic increases took place in Monroe County where median age
rose from 26 in 1950 to 39 in 1990. Broward County's median age
also rose, from 33 to 38. Dade County, which in 1950 had the highest
median age of the three counties, now has the lowest, holding
constant around 34 throughout the period.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">In 1990, the region had approximately
544,000 residents who were 65 years old or over.</FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">
This corresponds to 17 percent of the total, and compares to a
national average of only 13 percent of the population in this
age range. Almost half of South Florida residents within this
age group (256,000) were 75 years old or over, and 56,000 were
85 years old or over. There are distinct differences within the
region. The proportion of elderly in Broward County in 1990 was
almost 21 percent, whereas in Dade County it was only 14 percent,
and in Monroe County 16 percent.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Due in part to the increasing density
and congestion of urban South Florida, the region now attracts
a declining proportion of the elderly who migrate to Florida.
In 1990, the region's proportion of elderly was already lower
than the state's. Projections for the year 2015 indicate that
the population 65 years or over in the region will pass the 700,000
mark, remaining constant at 17 percent of the overall population,
while rising to almost 20 percent for the state. <B>For the region
as a whole, previous generations of elderly immigrants are not
being replaced by new ones.<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Within South Florida, the elderly are
most heavily concentrated in coastal communities, where it is
not uncommon to find a third or more of the population is 65 years
old or over. These communities must be prepared for the special
evacuation needs of the elderly population in the event of a hurricane.
This will be exacerbated as an increasing number of elderly are
concentrated in the upper ranges of these age categories. The
relative concentration of the elderly presents opportunities to
provide more efficiently part of the special services they require,
such as day care, transportation, and special care facilities.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="d"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">In-Migration and
Population Diversity <BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">While South Florida's growth through
the end of the 1950s was largely the result of migration from
northern states, international migration has played an increasingly
prominent role since then. Immigration from Latin America has
been a constant throughout the state's history, but the increased
flows from there beginning in the 1960s signaled an important
shift in the demographic profile of the Region. Hundreds of thousands
of Cuban refugees migrated to South Florida between the early
1960s and the 1980s. These Cubans were joined in the 1970s and
1980s by large numbers of other immigrants from Central and South
America and the Caribbean. As a diverse population has settled
in the Region, they have brought with them their culture and customs.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">A third of the region's 1990 population
was foreign-born.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua"> The rich
ethnic and cultural diversity which these residents bring will
be a strength for the region, helping to mold South Florida into
a world class cultural center with a world class work force. A
critical component of this is the increased linguistic diversity.
<B>Spanish is the predominant foreign language spoken in the region,
with over a million speakers, but in 1990,</B> <B>247,000 residents
spoke foreign languages other than Spanish. However, one out of
every five South Florida residents was not fluent in English,
more than three times the national average.</B> This means that
the region will have to face the challenge of providing easily
accessible opportunities to learn English to a broad segment of
the population.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">In the last decade, the region's population
became increasingly diversified, with significant growth of minority
racial and ethnic groups. For example, Dade County's Hispanic
community became much more heterogeneous, with migrants from a
wide variety of Central and South American countries. There also
was a dramatic net decrease of 169,000 non-Hispanic White residents
in Dade County during the decade. Although some of these out-migrants
resettled in Broward and Monroe counties, there was a net decline
of 75,000 in the region's non-Hispanic White population. Meanwhile,
the non-Hispanic African-American population in the region grew
by 175,000 in the same period. At the end of the decade, more
than one in four non-Hispanic residents was African-American.
In turn, growth in the African-American population was enriched
by increases in the number of African descendants migrating from
the Caribbean and Central and South America. Asians and Europeans
are likewise moving into the region, attracted by expanding 
international
economic opportunities.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">If the region continues to receive net
inflows of migrants from Central and South America and the Caribbean,
and if higher natural growth rates for the African-American population
continue, it is reasonable to suggest that <B>in 2015, South Florida's
population of 4.3 million could include approximately 1.8 million
Hispanic residents (41%), while almost another million (22%) would
be African-American, and the White, non-Hispanic population would
fall to approximately a third of the total.<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="e"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Population Shifts
Within the Region <BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Over the last decade, even as the
region grew by more than 150 residents per day, some of its traditional
cities actually lost population.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">
In addition, reflecting the broader trends in the region as a
whole, some cities saw significant shifts in the racial composition
of their population. Several cities experienced significant absolute
declines in White residents together with significant increases
in African-American population between 1980 and 1990, resulting
in a much higher proportion of African-American residents.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">These shifts were accompanied by substantial
changes in the socio-economic profile of residents in the municipalities
of the region, based on income, levels of educational attainment
and type of employment. Here, as in other regions of the country,
more affluent and younger residents have often chosen the newer
suburban areas, leaving behind deteriorating center cities and
older neighborhoods. These shifts impose severe hardships on the
region's local governments as they attempt to sustain vital communities.
It often has resulted in an inefficient use of the region's scarce
infrastructure investments, as resources are redirected from renewing
aging facilities in traditional cities to building new ones in
emerging communities.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The changing composition of the region's
population has contributed to the shifting base of the economy,
which is increasingly focused on international linkages<B>.</B>
Local government authorities face a challenge in planning for
a population which is in constant flux, both in size and composition.
Social services must be responsive to the specific needs of an
increasingly heterogeneous community. The provision of services
such as schools and job training, critical to building the region's
economic future, is more difficult. An additional concern is that
most residents are not native to the state, which reduces the
sense of community and weakens the understanding of, and identity
with, the region.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Another major concern is the region's
vulnerability to demographic trends which are essentially unpredictable
and out of its control. The range of unforeseeable impacts of
international migration into South Florida is best exemplified
by considering what will happen after a change in the regime in
Cuba. The region must now position itself to fully utilize the
advantage a multi-cultural population provides in a world economy.
<BR>
</FONT>
<HR>
<P>
