</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="
../images/ylogoppr.jpg"><CENTER><IMG SRC="../images/rppsmall.gif">
</CENTER>
 
<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="a"><I><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Strategic
Regional Policy Plan for South Florida<BR>
</FONT></B></I><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Regional Profile
and Identity<BR>
</FONT></B></A></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Our Environment <BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="profenvi.htm#b">Wetland Resources and the 
Everglades</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profenvi.htm#c">Coastal Resources</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profenvi.htm#d">The Florida Keys</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profenvi.htm#e">Upland Resources</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profenvi.htm#f">Water Resources</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profenvi.htm#g">Climate</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profenvi.htm#h">Growth and the Environment
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profenvi.htm#i">Electricity Generation</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profenvi.htm#j">Solid Waste and Recycling
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profenvi.htm#k">Hazardous Wastes</A><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">South Florida possesses a natural resource
base which is unique in the world. It includes the Biscayne Aquifer,
Everglades National Park and Water Conservation Areas, Biscayne
Bay, Florida Bay, the Florida Keys, lush seagrass meadows, the
only living and expanding coral reef in the continental United
States and miles of fragile coastal area. All of these resources
represent large scale ecosystems whose condition is affected by
activity on a regional, multi-county level. As the region's population
has increased dramatically over the last several decades these
resources have been subject to varying degrees of stress.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="b"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Wetland Resources
and the Everglades <BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The term &quot;Everglades&quot; refers
to the vast system of marshes, sloughs, tree islands and cypress
forests that historically covered most of southern Florida. While
it is the predominant ecosystem in South Florida, its boundaries
extend beyond the boundaries of the South Florida Region and the
system needs to be considered as a whole. The eastern Everglades
system in Dade and Broward Counties is comprised mainly of vast
fields of sawgrass and similar species. These hardy plants thrive
in the alternate wet/dry seasons that were the historical pattern.
The western portion of the Everglades system is dominated by cypress
swamps. Large stands of cypress trees are the main habitats providing
shelter for innumerable species, including the endangered Florida
Panther. <B>The Everglades system is unique; no other like it
exists anywhere in the world.<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The 1800s saw the beginning of the
decline of the Everglades.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">
Congress passed the Swamp and Overflowed Lands Grant Act in 1850,
which allowed Florida and all other states to claim &quot;swamp
and overflowed lands&quot; for the exclusive purpose of making
them productive through drainage and the construction of levees.
Florida claimed 20.3 million acres under this Act. In 1909, the
Everglades Drainage District was formed and, by 1927, 440 miles
of drainage canals, 47 miles of levees and 16 locks and dams were
completed. In 1948, the Central and Southern Flood Control District
was formed. In 1974, the boundaries were modified and the name
changed to the South Florida Water Management District (SFWMD).
One of the main responsibilities of the district is operating
the Central and Southern Flood Control Project, established in
1948 and constructed by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers for the
purpose of flood control and water supply.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Due to the efforts of Ernest Coe, a
landscape architect who worked for nearly 20 years to turn the
Everglades into America's only tropical national park, the Everglades
National Park (ENP) was created in 1947. In 1989, Congress passed
the Everglades National Park Expansion Bill. This involves purchasing
107,000 acres of land in the East Everglades of Dade County for
addition to the park. The final purchase is awaiting funding.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">During the 1950s and 1960s, several
projects were initiated which eventually had severe environmental
impact on the ENP and the system as a whole.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book 
Antiqua">
Water Conservation Areas (WCAs) were created in western Palm Beach,
Broward, and Dade counties by diking off 1,345 square miles. These
areas, established for water management, public recreation, and
wildlife management, altered the flow of water through the vast
shallow river known as the Everglades system. In the 1960s, the
Kissimmee River, which serves as the headwaters of the Everglades
system, was channeled for flood control. However, this has caused
an increase in the amount of nutrients from agricultural land
flowing into Lake Okeechobee and subsequently the Everglades.
Recent efforts have been focused on the restoration of the Kissimmee
River into a more natural system reminiscent of the system that
existed before human intervention.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">By the early 1970s, the Everglades 
infrastructure
was complete. Now controlled by more than 1,400 miles of levees,
dikes, and canals, and a variety of water control structures,
the watershed that once fed the system was under control. And
the signs began to show. Wading birds can no longer rely on natural
changes in water levels needed for feeding and breeding. The birds
have declined from a 1920 population of over 2 million to less
than 200,000. Several species which had not been previously on
the endangered species lists were added in the 1970s. Those species
which depend on the alternation of wet and dry seasons, which
was the historical pattern, are the most affected.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">In the late 1970s, the population
of South Florida began to realize what was happening to the Everglades
system. While a few people were becoming aware of the environmental
impacts of past projects, most were realizing that something more
important to them was being affected - the fresh water supply.</FONT></B>

<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">
The Everglades replenishes the Biscayne Aquifer which provides
the drinking water for South Florida. The lowering of the water
table brought on by draining the system resulted in salt water
entering in coastal wellfields and the need to move these fields
inland closer to the Everglades.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">In August 1983, Governor Bob Graham
initiated the Save Our Everglades program. The goal of the program
is to restore the Everglades to its 1900 status by the year 2000.
In the seven years since the initiation of the Save Our Everglades
program, positive steps have been made. Hundreds of acres of wetlands
have been restored and sloughs have been reflooded. Studies have
been completed and funding sought for the restoration of the Kissimmee
River. Standards for nutrient levels for Lake Okeechobee have
been set. Efforts have begun to re-establish populations of several
of the endangered species. There is now a better awareness of
the need to save this unique system. More recently, in 1994, Governor
Lawton Chiles created the Governor's Commission for a Sustainable
South Florida, which is focused on Everglades restoration, and
later signed the Everglades Forever Act, which also will work
toward that goal.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="c"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Coastal Resources
<BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Beaches<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">South Florida is famous for its beaches.
There are over 50 miles of beach along the Atlantic Coast of the
Region. Each year, millions of tourists come to the Region to
enjoy the good weather and go to the beach. Over 80 percent of
the Region's population lives within 10 miles of the coast. Real
estate values increase with proximity to the water.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Beaches also serve a natural function
of protection from severe storms and hurricanes. Historically,
they acted as a buffer between the high energy of the ocean during
severe weather and the inland areas. In addition, regional beaches
serve as nesting habitat for sea turtles, a protected species.
As development occurs along the beaches, their natural buffering
capacity is diminished and sea turtle nesting habitat is destroyed.
The loss of the region's beaches to erosion as a result of natural
forces and development has required renourishment over the years
through cooperative efforts with federal and state authorities.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Estuaries<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Historically, estuaries in the Region
were broad and shallow, teeming with organisms. Grass beds, which
aid in sediment stabilization, serve as habitat for several hundred
species. Most marine organisms spend part, if not all, of their
life cycle in the estuary. The estuarine system throughout South
Florida is vast, with Biscayne Bay and Florida Bay as the two
most significant components.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Freshwater flows into the estuaries
of the region are tied into the Everglades system.</FONT></B><FONT 
FACE="Book Antiqua">
Sloughs, rivers, and freshwater springs historically entered the
estuaries during the wet season. This mix of fresh and salt water
creates a brackish environment suitable for a wide variety of
organisms. Runoff from the uplands was filtered by the mangroves
and coastal marshes before entering the estuary.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Both the volume and duration of freshwater
flows into estuaries have been decreased as a result of development
pressures and inappropriate uses of land.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book 
Antiqua">
This led to an increase in the amount of salt water in the system,
which resulted in negative impacts to the organisms which were
historically abundant in estuaries and near shore areas. Reductions
in water quality has also resulted in significant alterations
in the trophic structure of the region.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Mangroves were considered valueless,
mosquito-infested plants that blocked the view of the water, and
were removed with fervor. Since mangrove forests are a major part
of the food web, help stabilize the shoreline, filter runoff,
buffer against storm winds and tides, and provide wildlife habitat,
their destruction resulted in a great resource loss.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Coral Habitat<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Another natural resource unique to South
Florida is coral habitat. In this region, there are three types
of coral communities: isolated coral heads, soft corals and coral
reefs. From Palm Beach County south to Cape Florida, tropical
coral reef species can be found in increasing numbers, but the
building of three-dimensional reef structures does not occur.
In these areas, coral is restricted to isolated heads and flat
communities.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">South and west of Cape Florida is the
area of maximum coral reef development. This system, extending
from Elliott Key to Dry Tortugas, consists of a diverse pattern
of reefs from 25 meters to 13 kilometers offshore. This is the
only shallow-water (less than 10 meters), tropical coral reef
system found on the continental shelf of North America and is
referred to as the Florida Reef Tract. Soft corals and their related
habitat (non-reef building coral) occur on the landward side of
the reefs (the back reef). This area also serves as important
habitat for several thousand species of marine organisms.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Impacts from boat anchors, groundings,
human contact, and illegal harvesting are increasing due to increases
in population pressures within the region. To help relieve some
of the pressures, Dade, Broward, and Monroe Counties have developed
artificial reef programs. Old ships and other debris are bought,
cleaned and sunk off the coast in designated areas permitted by
the Florida Department of Environmental Protection and the U.S.
Army Corps of Engineers. These areas provide habitat as well as
recreational dive spots.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="d"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">The Florida
Keys</FONT><FONT SIZE=4> <BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The completion of the overseas railway
in 1912, followed by the overseas highway in 1938, started the
growth the Keys would begin to feel in the 1950s. Increased access
and abundant fresh water available from Florida City made the
area more habitable. With the new growth came many consequences.
Dredge and fill activity became commonplace, increasing the amount
and value of waterfront property. Canals were dynamited out of
the hard limestone substrate. Hotels, motels and marinas were
built to accommodate the tourists. With the advent of scuba diving,
people were attracted to the reefs which up until then had been
avoided and feared.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The resources of the Keys are very diverse.
Mining for limestone and sand occurs in designated areas. Commercial
and sport fishing and tourism are other major industries. In 1975,
the Florida Keys Area of Critical State Concern was first established
by the Legislature in order to protect its natural resources.
The Florida Keys National Marine Sanctuary was designated in 1992
in order to preserve adjacent marine resources, especially the
coral reefs. The climate, atmosphere and accessibility make it
attractive for close to 2 million visitors each year.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The future of the Florida Keys is both
challenging and exciting. Due to the fragile ecosystems in this
area, a balance between development and conservation will help
preserve the Keys. The unique characteristics of this valuable
natural resource must be respected both now and in the future.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="e"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Upland Resources
<BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">As a result of the vast water dependent
resources of the region, upland resources are often not considered
as extensively. Within the region, there are several unique upland
communities; hardwood hammocks and pinelands are the most common.
These areas are found where the land is higher and rarely inundated
with water. <B>They are unique in that both tropical and subtropical
upland plant species are able to survive in these areas.</B> They
provide habitat to a variety of plants and animals, many of which
are listed as rare or endangered. Upland areas are subject to
intense development pressure because of extensive wetland regulations.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="f"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Water Resources
<BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">In South Florida, the ground water and
surface water are connected and what impacts one may impact the
other. <B>The Biscayne Aquifer is the primary source of potable
water for South Florida.</B> It is a limestone formation which
underlies the entire Region. It acts like a big sponge in that
it readily absorbs water from rainfall and stores it underground.
If water is withdrawn from the aquifer at a greater rate than
it is replenished, salt water from the east intrudes into the
aquifer, making it unfit for human consumption.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Below the Biscayne Aquifer lies the
saline Floridan Aquifer. It is separated from the Biscayne Aquifer
by an impermeable rock formation. If the Biscayne Aquifer is 
contaminated
by salt water or other pollutants, the Region may need to turn
to desalinization of water within the Floridan Aquifer, which
would be very costly. In addition, recent studies show that drawing
water from the Floridan Aquifer in Dade County may have an adverse
impact on the water supply in Martin County, which relies on the
Floridan Aquifer as its source of potable water. This will need
to be considered as plans for the use of this aquifer are investigated.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Salt is not the only contaminant threatening
the water supply of the region. The shallow water table and highly
permeable soils make ground water contamination a special concern.
Very often, pollutants enter the ground water before detection
in the soil because of the porosity of the aquifer.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Large tracts of land have been paved
during this century. This has reduced the recharge of the aquifer
by rainfall. It has also increased the amount of stormwater runoff
and the possibility of hydrocarbon and heavy metal contamination
of surface and ground waters as well as contamination from other
sources. Better surface water management technology has helped
to alleviate many of the problems associated with runoff and,
as this technology advances, runoff should not pose a threat to
the ground water and surface water quality.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="g"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Climate<BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The climate of South Florida is characterized
as subtropical marine in Broward and Dade counties, and tropical
maritime in the Keys. The region is strongly influenced by the
adjacent marine environment. The Florida Current, Gulf of Mexico,
the Gulf Stream, and the Atlantic Ocean affect terrestrial and
marine climates during different seasons.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">South Florida experiences two general
seasons: a rainy season from May to October, and a dry season
from November to April. During the rainy season, rainfall averages
6.24 inches per month. The dry season average is 1.97 inches per
month. This fact is important to the water supply of the Region.
The wet season is when the most aquifer recharge occurs. The dry
season, which is also the time of heaviest demand on the resource
because of coincidence with the &quot;tourist season&quot;, is
the time of least aquifer recharge. This must be taken into account
when planning for future water use. The wet season also coincides
with the hurricane season. This is officially from June 1 through
November 30, with September traditionally being the time of most
storms.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The Florida Current, which becomes the
Gulf Stream, affects the climate of the Region. It is a constant
source of warm water off the coast which in turn warms the surface
air. Since the Gulf Stream runs parallel to the coast at an average
distance of 3 miles, it helps to maintain the tropical and subtropical
climate. It also affects precipitation in the Region.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="h"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Growth and the
Environment <BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Continued population growth will add
to the existing strains which pressure the region's environment.
<B>Development density along the coastal ridge has reduced the
ability of natural systems to provide protection of the coastal
area from such natural forces as hurricanes. Westward growth has
also encroached on wildlife habitat. Without proper protection,
residential communities in the western areas of the region, adjacent
to the Water Conservation Areas, threaten fresh water needed for
environmental stability of the Everglades system and urban potable
water consumption.<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Fresh water is in increasing demand
to meet the needs of the environment, agriculture, and urban consumers.
Increased demand by any of these users results in direct competition
with the others. Salt water intrusion in the eastern portion of
the region is already advanced. The degradation of the Everglades
ecosystem has become of paramount concern. Further encroachment
of development into western Broward and Dade Counties will reduce
the potential for hydrological restoration of the Everglades and
Florida Bay by 1) physically eliminating portions of the proposed
buffer strip, and 2) increasing the need for flood protection,
which lowers ground water levels and increases seepage out of
the Conservation Areas to the east. It is inevitable that the
competition for fresh water will intensify as efforts are undertaken
to counteract the damage already imposed. Careful analysis of
the long-term social costs and benefits of these various uses
will make it possible to properly assign real costs and ensure
an efficient use of this scarce resource. <B>Region-wide solutions
will be necessary to avoid what some observers have suggested
may become &quot;water wars&quot; in the future. </B>South Florida
must begin now to pursue aggressive policies in this area.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The Southeast Florida airshed (Dade,
Broward and Palm Beach Counties) was officially redesignated by
the EPA to attainment/maintenance status effective April 25, 1995.
Planning for growth must recognize that the area has a limit on
ozone precursor emissions, established in the Southeast Florida
Maintenance Plan, that cannot be exceeded. Regional development
and transportation system expansion must balance the total emissions
from all area-wide sources to ensure that this limit is not exceeded.
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="i"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Electricity Generation
<BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">South Florida is a net importer of
electricity.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua"> The region is
supplied locally by one nuclear generating site (two reactors
at Turkey Point) and four non-nuclear sites, using fuel oil and
natural gas. In addition, there are waste-to-energy facilities
in all three counties which generate part of the electricity consumed.
In the absence of significant gains in conservation, a growing
population and a growing economy will require either continued
expansion in generating capacity or the importation of electricity
from other areas of the state. In fact, conservation programs
have already helped moderate the individual use of electricity,
and goals and programs are set to increase in the future. The
combination of existing generating capacity and additional conservation
is expected to meet future customer growth through the year 2001,
according to documents filed by the area's major electric utility.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">High-voltage transmission line construction
through environmentally sensitive areas on the region's western
fringe, due to concerns for residential areas further east, add
additional stress to the regional environment. The environmental
impacts of generation facilities must be weighed not only in terms
of the potential increase in air pollution but also the hazards
associated with transporting, storing and burning the fuel required
by plants.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="j"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Solid Waste and
Recycling <BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">In 1991, Broward County inaugurated
two large waste-to-energy facilities with a total capacity of
4,500 tons per day, approximately one-fourth of the incinerator
capacity installed to date in the state. Partially as a result
of state-mandated recycling efforts, the minimum volume requirements
needed to guarantee repayment of the bonds issued to finance the
units have not been met. At present, Monroe County has a contract
to ship its unprocessed solid waste to a landfill in Broward County
through 2006. Dade County's waste-to-energy facility, with a capacity
of 3,000 tons per day, recently applied to expand that to 4,500
tons per day.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Coordination of regional waste management
strategies among the region's counties will provide a better 
understanding
of the most desirable solid waste stream reduction options and
provide a stronger voice in the definition of state-wide strategies.
A major challenge for recycling will be to increase the demand
for products with recycled content, and to reduce the solid waste
stream at its origin by establishing statewide guidelines for
reducing packaging volume and toxic content of products that must
be disposed. <B>Container deposit legislation offers a prospect
of improving the efficiency of recycling efforts.<BR>
<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="k"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Hazardous Wastes
<BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The effects of long-term use of hazardous
materials in our day-to-day lives, without proper disposal, leaves
the region exposed to more frequent cases of health hazards. <B>
Population
growth and the diversification of the economy, including transportation
and storage of a broader variety of goods as part of the growing
international trade, will expose the region to a higher incidence
of hazardous material spills that can be ecologically devastating.</B>
Because the water table is so close to the ground surface - as
close as two feet in some areas - there is an increased probability
that contaminants will drain into the water table, and eventually
the potable water supply. More transport of hazardous materials
on our increasingly congested highways may lead to more frequent
spills and releases.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">In summary, the region's growth and
change has subjected environmental resources to varying degrees
of stress. In some instances, resources have been significantly
damaged, while in others, the level of stress threatens to upset
the delicate ecological balance. <B>The regional community should
become better prepared in ways necessary to respond to significant
events of ecological upset.<BR>
<BR>
</B></FONT>
<HR>
<P>
