<BR>
<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="a"><I><B><FONT SIZE=4>Strategic Regional Policy
Plan for South Florida<BR>
</FONT></B></I><B><FONT SIZE=4>Regional Profile and Identity</FONT></B>
</A></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Our Community <BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B></CENTER>
<P>
<A HREF="profcomm.htm#b"><B>Urbanization</B></A>
<P>
<A HREF="profcomm.htm#c"><B>Basic Infrastructure</B>
</A>
<P>
<A HREF="profcomm.htm#d"><B>The Impact of 
Globalization and New Technologies</B></A><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><A NAME="b"></A><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Urbanization<BR>
</FONT></B>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Since the early 1950s the urbanization
of South Florida has occurred rapidly</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book 
Antiqua">.
In 1950, there were four cities within the Region that had a population
of 25,000 or more. As the Region entered the final decade of this
century, 25 of the 57 municipalities had populations greater than
25,000 and 10 had more than 50,000 residents. Today, both Miami
(Dade County) and Fort Lauderdale (Broward County) constitute
major metropolitan areas in the state.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The dramatic growth in city size over
the years has occurred despite a declining overall regional growth
rate. Essentially rural areas in the western extremes of Broward
and Dade Counties have given way to sprawling suburban residential
development and shopping centers. Indeed, these have been an important
component of the economic growth that has taken place in the Region.
<B>During the process, the once significant rural population has
virtually disappeared, resulting in the emergence of a distinctly
urban character to the Region.</B> Dade County was already 94
percent urban in 1950, and 77 percent of Broward County's population
lived in urban areas. By 1980, both counties were 99 percent urban.
Only in Monroe County did a significant portion of the population
still live outside of urban areas in 1990 (27 percent), consistent
with the special characteristics of that county's political geography.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">In the face of further population growth,
the region is likely to continue to urbanize. Current preferences
for low-density residential areas will give way to a higher density,
more urban-like lifestyle. There will be less available, developable
land and a greater need to protect natural resources. Agriculture
will continue to be pressured as land is developed or set aside
for environmental protection. The unique opportunities the Region's
climate offers for growing tropical fruits and vegetables on a
year-round basis will have to be balanced with the demands of
growth.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="c"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">Basic Infrastructure
<BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Transportation infrastructure has been
a primary stimulus to the occupation of available land in the
western portions of the Region. The extensive roadway network
in South Florida includes a state highway system composed of more
than 900 miles of interstate highways and other expressways and
over 800 miles of county arterials and collector roads, in addition
to the local network. This system provides the Region with a solid
basis for automobile transportation for the foreseeable future.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Roadway congestion will continue to
be a concern. Development patterns have created a dependence on
the automobile that will be difficult to change. Existing roadway
capacity will be expanded to the practical limits, and new roads
built where feasible. Roadway improvements will be limited, however,
by the lack of available land, the need to protect the environment,
and the costs of acquiring the necessary right-of-way. <B>Mass
transit will necessarily expand to share in the burden of moving
people around the Region.<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Residential development in sprawling
suburban areas has made mass transit a difficult option to implement.
The 66-mile Tri-County Rail System, linking Miami to West Palm
Beach with 15 stations, is the only region-wide mass transit system.
Its initially low ridership exemplifies some of the difficulties
faced when viable automobile routes exist and destination points
are spread out, without the necessary complement of mass transit
feeder links. The Metro-Dade rail/bus transit system, composed
of Metro-Rail, Metromover and Metro Bus, provides an example of
a more integrated approach to urban transport.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The Region is relatively well served
by other forms of transportation: three international airports,
eight smaller regional airports and two military airports, three
deepwater ports and two major railways providing passenger and
freight service to and from South Florida. <B>However, these facilities
are for the most part poorly integrated among themselves and with
the existing regional transit system.<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Another major component of the Region's
infrastructure is the network of canals and water control structures
built to provide drainage, flood control, water supply, water
quality protection and environmental enhancement. The Central
and Southern Florida (C&amp;SF) Flood Control Project was authorized
by the U.S. Congress in 1948. The major purposes of the project
were to provide flood protection and an adequate water supply,
to prevent saltwater intrusion, encourage agricultural and urban
development, and to preserve fish and wildlife. Most of the C&amp;SF
Project is in Palm Beach, Broward and Dade Counties, consisting
of three Water Conservation Areas, about 1,400 miles of canals
and levees, 181 major water control structures, over 2,000 minor
water control structures, and 18 major pump stations.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">An enormous amount of other public 
infrastructure
has been built up extensively over the years. The public school
system in the Region includes approximately 700 elementary, middle
and high schools, and provides education to almost 600,000 students.
Ten universities and community colleges provide higher education
to over 100,000 students. Government and privately operated sanitary
sewer and potable water facilities can be found throughout the
Region.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The requirements for infrastructure
have lagged behind the needs. Projections prepared in 1985 to
measure the potential costs of implementing growth management
in the state indicated that the Region would need a total of $92
billion in capital and maintenance/operation expenditures for
government services in the period from 1986 to 2000. Three out
of every four dollars would be needed just to maintain and operate
the existing services. With regional revenues projected at only
$65 billion during the same period, a deficit of $27 billion remained.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The substantial backlog of basic
infrastructure in the Region results from the patterns of urban
growth.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua"> Current growth patterns
indicate a continuing trend towards low density residential development
and scattered activity centers (i.e., developments that attract
large numbers of people and usually provide a mix of uses such
as places of employment, retail centers and recreational attractions).
Providing services such as sewers, water lines, drainage networks,
solid waste collection and disposal, electricity, police, fire
and schools to these sites, and linking them with the transportation
network, can be extremely costly. Today some areas of the region
still lack sanitary sewer and potable water facilities and services.
By concentrating this development with less scattering and higher
density of residential development, and with centrally located,
mixed-use activity centers, these problems can be somewhat mitigated.
The redevelopment of the aging downtowns of the Region will be
another priority in the coming years.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<A NAME="d"><B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Book Antiqua">The Impact
of Globalization and New Technologies<BR>
</FONT></B></A>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Urban conditions are changing. <B>The
globalization of South Florida has placed increased and changing
demands on existing infrastructure.</B> As the composition of
goods and services produced changes and employment shifts, and
as changing demographic patterns create new demands for housing,
leisure and other social needs, the infrastructure of cities in
the region must adapt. Improved systems to facilitate the present
and future economic challenges and demands are imperative. <B>The
selection and implementation of these advanced systems designed
to serve the region must regard the need to reduce the harmful
impacts of urban life on the environment and to develop environmentally
acceptable and sustainable forms of urban living.<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Rapid technological developments are
exerting profound impacts on urban systems. These impacts provide
a myriad of challenges and opportunities for the development and
redevelopment of urban areas. <B>As the trend toward the 
&quot;information
society&quot; continues and the trend towards the &quot;knowledge
society&quot; emerges, the traditional urban form and function
is challenged.</B> Urban policies regarding infrastructure, housing,
services, transportation, education, the environment and land
use are affected by the new information and communication technologies.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Today, more than 26 million Americans,
about one-fifth of the work force, work at home or in satellite
locations. Of those, 4 million work at home full-time. It is estimated
that, using existing technologies, more than 50 million Americans
could work at home or in satellite offices. These technologies
have been around for years but only recently have they become
generally available through cost-effective personal computers,
easy-to-use communications products, and reliable and inexpensive
telephone services.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Telecommuting, or using telecommunications
infrastructure to accomplish work rather than physically commuting
to the work place, conserves energy while at the same time saving
the environment. <B>It has been estimated that if only 5 percent
of the commuters in Los Angeles County telecommuted one day each
work week, they would save 205 million miles of travel each year
and keep 45,000 tons of pollutants from entering the atmosphere.</B>
In an area such as South Florida, where highway commuting is a
way of life, telecommuting has enormous potential.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The new technologies, a blend of computer
science and telecommunications, are accelerating the transfer
of information to an extraordinary extent. <B>Virtually unlimited
amounts of information can now be transmitted to any destination
at any time of the day, and at falling cost.</B> Space and time
have practically been abolished. The question that must now be
asked is what this means for our cities.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Technological progress over the past
two decades has not always had the best consequences for the economic
development of cities. Technological innovations and better 
communication
have enabled industrial enterprises to move far away from cities,
and this has drained from the economic vitality that once existed
when the city was the one and same place of skilled labor, services,
transport facilities and markets. Thus change has caused cities
to lose out, and revitalizing them is a key priority. Carefully
considered use of new and proven technologies can make a substantial
contribution to that revitalization.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">As producers of services, cities
will find that the use of new information technologies can make
them more efficient at equal or lower cost.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book 
Antiqua">
As has already been seen in the auto industry these advances allow
people and machines to produce more and better goods and, by eliminating
waste, mistakes and repetitive tasks, they boost productivity.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Regional economies are fast becoming
part of a global economy: trade is intensifying and most goods
can now be bought and sold virtually anywhere in the world. In
conjunction with this trend, economies are becoming open as the
scope of regulations and licenses shrinks. Furthermore, 
telecommunications
technologies are making it possible for regional economies to
become directly involved in the global economy.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Four areas in which the local governments
and other organizations in the Region can use information and
communication technologies as part of their economic development
strategies and to enhance their potential in global markets include:
<BR>
</FONT>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">the development of teleports and
high-tech office centers;</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">public policies to encourage private
investment in telecommunications infrastructure, <I>i.e. </I>intelligent
buildings, and value added networks;</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">public policies to use technology
in the public services that affect economic development; and</FONT>
<LI><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">public policies to attract 
information-intensive
firms and activities.</FONT>
</UL>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The widespread use of computers in office
functions and the need to have access to telecommunications systems
has generated a demand for office buildings designed to serve
the specialized needs of information-intensive firms. <B>Technology
has dramatically altered the infrastructure of office buildings.
New business activity requires buildings with sophisticated 
communications
services.<BR>
</B></FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Telecommunications infrastructure of
the future may be predominantly built by private sector firms.
However local governments can play an active role in encouraging
private investment in this infrastructure by making rights-of-way
available for the fiber optic systems, by providing incentives
so that the infrastructure serves all parts of the community,
and by identifying opportunities for public-private cooperation.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">The region's cities may not all become
urban telecommunications centers, built on these new technologies.
However, many of the technologies are suitable for helping each
urban area in the region better achieve its potential role in
the regional economy. The way we make use of such technologies
will be important in shaping the quality of life our cities offer.
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Local government can use new information
technologies to manage municipal public services: internal transmission
networks can be used for remote management of water, sewer, 
transportation
and other utilities.</FONT></B><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua"> As these
trends continue, the city could become a more attractive place
to go.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Yet, even as we look to the promise
of the future, we must also identify some of the enduring difficulties
in the region. A highly visible component of the failure of our
communities to provide adequately for the well-being of its inhabitants
is growing homelessness. Even before Hurricane Andrew, the number
of homeless in the region was on the rise. Techniques will have
to be developed to produce more affordable housing which meets
standards. The pursuit of economic stability, the generation of
employment opportunities and an aggressive retraining policy in
the region will be important parts of the long-term strategy to
combat homelessness.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">Both smaller households and the increased
proportion of elderly will encourage gradual changes in the composition
of housing stock in the region, in response to changing needs.
Smaller homes and multi-family units tailored to the elderly and
more retirement communities with elderly care facilities will
be necessary.<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="profcomm.htm#a" >Return to top of 
page</A></CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="menu41.htm">Back to Regional 
Profile and Identity</A><FONT FACE="Book Antiqua">
<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></CENTER>
