<html>

<head>
<title>REGIONAL DISPUTE RESOLUTION PROCESS</title>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../images/plogoppr.jpg">
<p align=center><a name="z">South Florida Regional Planning Council </a></p>
<p align=center><font size=4><b>Council Programs</b></font></p>
<p align=center><font size=4><b>Regional Dispute Resolution Process</b></font></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/rdrpsm.gif" align=bottom width=140 height=140> </p>
<hr>
<p><a href="#a"><font size=4>Effective and Efficient Conflict Resolution</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#b"><font size=4>Flexibility is the Word</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#c"><font size=4>Who is Involved?</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#d"><font size=4>&quot;Can we talk?&quot;</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#e"><font size=4>Seeking Solutions</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#f"><font size=4>Agreements</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#g"><font size=4>Reporting Results</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#h"><font size=4>Public Involvement</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#i"><font size=4>Costs and Confidentiality</font></a> </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="a"><font size=4>Effective and Efficient Conflict Resolution</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>The South Florida Regional Planning Council has established a Regional Dispute Resolution Process, the RDRP, as specified by 186.509, F.S. The voluntary 
process provides a range of dispute resolution options, and is designed to be both time and cost effective. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>The process, developed by the Conflict Resolution Consortium (CRC), consists of two basic components: process initiation (initiation and response letters) and 
settlement meetings.</font><font size=4> </font></p>
<p><a name="b"><font size=4>Flexibility is the Word</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>The Regional Dispute Resolution Process is designed to: </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Clearly identify and resolve problems early </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Use cost efficient procedures </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Allow flexibility </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Provide for involvement of affected and </font></p>
<p><font size=3>responsible parties </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Provide process certainty </font></p>
<p><font size=3>The RDRP is not for the resolution of disputes involving environmental permits or other regulatory matters unless all of the parties agree to initiate the use of the 
Process. </font></p>
<p><a name="c"><font size=4>Who is Involved?</font></a> </p>
<p><font size=3>Parties named in the initiation letter are automatically allowed to participate. Other jurisdictions, public or private organizations, groups, or individuals must be 
suggested by a named party and agreed to by two thirds of the named parties. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Participation in the Regional Dispute Resolution Process does not waive any party's right to judicial or administrative action; nor does it convey or limit 
intervenor status or standing in any judicial or administrative proceeding.</font></p>
<p align=center><a href="#z"><font size=4>Return to Top of the Page</font></a></p>
<p><a name="d"><font size=4>&quot;Can we talk?&quot;</font></a> </p>
<p><font size=3>Pre-initiation Meeting: Any jurisdiction, organization, group, or individual may request an informal pre-initiation meeting with the </font><a href="../council/staff.htm"><font size=3>Regional Planning Council staff.</font></a><font size=3> </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Initiation Letter: The RDRP begins with an initiation letter from the representative of a jurisdiction's governing body which is sent to all named parties and the 
RPC staff. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Response Letter: The named parties must send a response letter to the RPC staff and all other named parties. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Situation Assessment:. The situation assessment can involve examination of documents, interviews and assessment meetings, and results in a recommendation 
concerning the issues to be addressed, parties that may participate, appropriate dispute resolution procedures, and a proposed schedule. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Requests to Initiate Submitted by Others: Private interests may ask any </font><a href="../websites/wwwsfmun.htm"><font size=3>local government</font></a><font size=3> to initiate the process.</font> </p>
<p><a name="e"><font size=4>Seeking Solutions</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>Settlement Meetings: This meeting may be facilitated by a member of the RPC staff or a mutually agreed upon neutral facilitator. Mediation will be provided if 
two or more named parties submit a request for mediation to the RPC, it will assist them in selecting and retaining a mediator. Alternately, the named parties 
may request the RPC make the selection. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Advisory Decision-Making: If two or more named parties submit a request for advisory decision-making to the RPC, it will assist in selecting and retaining an 
appropriate neutral. Alternately, the named parties may request that the RPC make the selection.</font></p>
<p><font size=3>All disputes shall be handled by a neutral who understands Florida's growth management issues; has appropriate experience; and is acceptable to the named 
parties. </font></p>
<p><a name="f"><font size=4>Agreements</font></a> </p>
<p><font size=3>Agreements may include: interlocal agreements; concurrent resolutions; memoranda of understanding; plan amendments; deed restrictions, or other forms as 
appropriate. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Agreements may be reached by two or more parties even if all of the named parties don't agree or don't sign a formal agreement. </font></p>
<p><a name="g"><font size=4>Reporting Results</font></a> </p>
<p><font size=3>After settlement meetings, mediation, or advisory decision-making, the named parties must submit a joint report to the RPC staff.</font> </p>
<p><a name="h"><font size=4>Public Involvement</font></a> </p>
<p><font size=3>Appropriate opportunities for public input should be considered during the process. Applicable public notice and public records requirements must be 
observed. (Chapters 119 &amp; 120, F.S.) </font></p>
<p><a name="i"><font size=4>Costs and Confidentiality</font></a> </p>
<p><font size=3>There is no charge for processing an initiation request or facilitating the initial settlement meeting. The RPC is compensated for services based on reasonable 
actual costs. Outside professional neutrals are compensated at their standard rate or at a rate negotiated by the parties. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>To the extent possible , the confidentiality provisions of Chapter 44, F.S. will govern mediation under this process. </font></p>
<p><font size=3>For additional information on the Dispute Resolution Process, please contact </font><a href="mailto:bobd@sfrpc.com"><font size=3>Bob Daniels</font></a><font size=3>.</font></p>
<p align=center><a href="#z"><font size=4>Return to Top of the Page</font></a></p>
