<html>

<head>
<title>EAR ALMANAC</title>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../images/plogoppr.jpg">
<p align=center>South Florida Regional Planning Council </p>
<p align=center><font size=4><b>Special Projects and Studies</b></font></p>
<p align=center><font size=4><b>A Guide for HazMat Preparedness for Hospitals</b></font></p>
<hr>
<p>This document is designed to orient hospital administrators, emergency response staff and planners to the various factors 
involved in planning for and responding to a hazardous materials incident, whether internal or external. While this guide is 
not all inclusive, it does provide insight into the continuing proliferation of hazardous materials in our society, and some of 
the steps that hospitals can take to ensure they are prepared to deal with hazardous material incidents. It introduces training 
requirements and planning considerations and contains a list of resources available to hospital disaster planners to assist in 
their program development. After reviewing this guide, you should have a better idea of the challenges facing you, but you 
will also be better informed on how you can plan, prepare and train to deal with hazardous materials, from triage to 
decontamination to treatment. </p>
<p>Chapter 1 discusses potential hazards that threaten day-to-day operations of emergency departments if there is a lack of 
preparation to identify, decontaminate and treat a victim of a hazardous materials incident. The chapter also defines the 
LEPC role and discusses liability. Chapter 2 presents an opportunity for each hospital to evaluate themselves against 
criteria to understand their level of preparedness. Chapter 3 provides a model outline of issues and offers checklists for 
each hospital to consider as they strive to improve their level of preparedness through planning. Most hospitals already 
have the equipment and resources within their hospital necessary to improve their safety and response capability. Pooling 
the resources and expertise from the various areas at your hospital, planning an integrated response, and exercising this 
integrated response can increase your preparedness dramatically. Chapter 4 discusses other educational references and 
tools for hospital personnel to take advantage of to improve their structural or informational level of preparedness. </p>
<p>For a copy of <em>A Guide for</em> <em>HazMat Preparedness for Hospitals</em> or additional information, please contact <a href="mailto:dam@sfrpc.com">Doris Mitchell</a>.</p>
<hr>
<p align=center><b>[ </b><a href="../council/menu1.htm"><b>The Council</b></a> | <a href="../whatsnew/menu2.htm"><b>What's New</b></a> | <a href="../websites/menu3.htm"><b>Related Web Sites</b></a> | <a href="../region/menu4.htm"><b>Our Region</b></a> | <a href="../current/menu5.htm"><b>Current Issues</b></a> ] </p>
