<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Executive Summary</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="../images/plogoppr.jpg">
<CENTER>South Florida Regional Planning Council</CENTER><br>

<font size=+1><CENTER><b>Council Programs</b></CENTER>
</font>
<HR> 
<h3><center><b>EXECUTIVE SUMMARY</b></center></h3>
<HR>
<h3>
<u><b>South Florida Region - Potential and Challenges</b></u></h3>

South Florida, including Broward, Dade and Monroe Counties, functions as 

a region in many ways, particularly in its ecological, economic and 
social dimensions.  The Region has been experiencing a major evolution. 
 In the past three decades, the Regions population has grown from 1.3 
to 3.3 million, moving it up from the eighteenth to the eleventh most 
populous region in the nation.  
<b>Tremendous quantitative growth has been
 accompanied by qualitative changes in many aspects of the regional
 community.  Our region is now at a critical point in its development,
 facing enormous challenges as well as opportunities.</b><br><br>


<b>On the one hand, our region has the potential to become one of the
 premier regions in the nation and the world.
</b>  South Floridas inherent 
advantages include, for example: a strategic gateway location linking
 North America, South America and the Caribbean, a wonderful subtropical
 climate and natural environment unique to the world, an established 
worldwide reputation as a tourist attraction, and a multi-cultural 
workforce and community.<br><br>

<b>On the other hand, analyses of current conditions and future trends
 indicate tremendous challenges ahead for our region illustrated as 
the following.</b>
<ul>

<li> The Region is expected to add another one million residents by the 
year 2015, approximately a 30% increase, led by international migration. 
 This increase in demand may further deteriorate the quality of public 
facilities and services, which already have a significant backlog.
 

<li> Growth and change have also subjected the Regions natural 
resources to varying degrees of stress.  In some instances, resources 
have been significantly damaged, while in others, the level of stress 
threatens to upset the delicate ecological balance.
 

<li> Historical development patterns, concentrating population near the 
coast, have resulted in a significant portion of the Regions population 
being vulnerable to emergency conditions, such as hurricanes.
 

<li> All of the regions major economic sectors are participating 
increasingly in the global economy.  Nevertheless, the lack of a quality 
workforce threatens the Regions competitiveness in the 21st Century, 
when competition will be based predominantly on knowledge and 
information.
 

<li>Persistent social and economic disparities among the Regions 
residents, if not improved, will further diminish the prospect of 
becoming a world-class region.


<li>Our region has excellent infrastructure and resources in isolated 
and limited cases.  However, overall the region still lacks the 
structural and qualitative components of regional systems and approaches 
to qualify as a premier region.  For example, there is no meaningful 
regional mass transit system nor are there systematic regional economic 
development efforts.
</ul>

<b>In summary, the trend scenario as discussed above indicates
 that our potential to be a premier region will continue not to be 
realized.</b>  We may even see a decline in the quality of life and a 
deterioration of the very basis (whether environmental, economic or 
social) of the South Florida regional community.  The cost of this trend 

scenario (no planning) for the future is too high to accept.

<h3><b><u>Regional Planning and the SRPP</u></b></h3>

All of the challenges discussed above transcend jurisdictional 
boundaries and hence require a planning response at the regional 
level.  To be sure, there have been many planning efforts in the Region.
  However, many of these efforts are fragmented in nature and not 
regional in their approaches.  The consideration of regional
 interdependence and coordinated actions is essential to create 
desirable
 changes for the Region. <b> It is imperative not only that a planning 
scenario be pursued, but that a planning scenario be chosen which could
 make a strategic difference for the well-being of the Region.</b><br>
<br>


<b>Regional planning consists of processes to define our vision, 
establish 
common priorities, and work together toward a shared future for our 
Region.</b>  The development and implementation of a Regional Policy 
Plan is
 at the heart of regional planning.  State legislation passed in 1993 
recognized that the Regional Planning Council (RPC) is Florida's only
 multipurpose regional entity that is in a position to plan for and 
coordinate intergovernmental solutions to growth-related problems on 
greater-than-local issues.  In assisting the RPC to perform its role, 
the legislation requires each RPC to develop a Strategic Regional Policy
 Plan (SRPP) to replace the current Comprehensive Regional Policy Plan.
<br><br>

<b>The strategic planning scenario first establishes an overall regional 

vision for South Florida to become a livable, sustainable and 
competitive
 community.
</b>  Six strategic subject areas have been selected to guide and 
focus planning efforts to achieve the overall regional vision.  These
 strategic subject areas encompass land use and public facilities 
(including education), natural resources of regional significance,
 economic development, regional transportation, affordable housing and 
emergency preparedness.  The relationship between the regional vision
and the strategic subject areas is described in the Figure on the next
 page and further discussed in Chapter III of the SRPP.<br><br>
 

<b><u><h3>Future Directions</h3></u></b>

<b>The directions that the Region should move to realize its overall 
vision include primarily the following.</b><br><br>

<ul><b>First, the Region will:</b>


<li> <b>promote a unified regional community, which capitalizes on our 
cultural diversity and strives to provide opportunities for all 
residents
 to prosper; and</b><br><br>
 

<li>
<b>achieve long-term efficient and sustainable development patterns by 
guiding new development and redevelopment within the region to areas
 which are most intrinsically suited for development, including areas
 (1) which are least exposed to coastal storm surges; (2) where negative 

impacts on the natural environment will be least significant; and (3) 
where public facilities and services already exist, are programmed or, 
on an aggregate basis, can be provided most economically.</b><br><br>


<b>Second, within the larger framework just described, the Region will:
</b>
<br><br>

<li> 
<b>revitalize deteriorating urban areas, ensure mobility, accessibility,
 the availability of affordable housing, and the adequacy of public 
facilities and services to enhance the livability of the Region through 
policies aimed to, for example:</b><br>
 <ul>

<li> promote neighborhood revitalization strategies based on public 
facilities improvements such as schools,

<li> promote transportation alternatives to reduce the reliance on 
single occupant vehicles,

<li>improve the job/housing balance and transportation linkages for 
affordable housing, and
<li> improve the cost-effectiveness of facility and service provisions.
 
</ul><br><br>
<li> 
<b>protect and manage natural resources of regional significance and 
manage growth and development to ensure the sustainability of the Region 
through policies aimed to, for example:
 </b>
<ul>
<li> restore and protect the ecological values and functions of the 
Everglades eco-system,

<li> create incentives to direct inappropriate uses of land away from 
natural resources of regional significance,

<li> increase connectedness between the fragmented natural areas and the 
regional natural system, and

<li> encourage optimized stormwater retention, freshwater utilization 
and water conservation practices.
 </ul><br><br>

<li> 
<b>achieve a competitive and diversified regional economy through the 
development of cutting edge human and technological resources and 
infrastructure to proactively position the region in the global economy 
through policies aimed to, for example:</b>
 <ul>
<li>develop and support a skilled labor force,

<li>improve key economic development infrastructure (both physical and 
informational) and resources, and

<li>strengthen the role of small and minority business in economic 
development.
 </ul><br><br>

<li> 
<b>achieve coordinated strategies to address persistent and emerging 
issues in land use and public facilities (including education), natural 
resources, economic development, regional transportation, affordable
 housing and emergency preparedness through policies aimed to, for 
example:</b><br>
<ul>

<li>strengthen the coordination of marketing and promotion of the 
Region,
<li> create a regional emergency planning committee,

<li> strengthen coordination regarding transportation improvements of 
regional significance, and
<li>improve public facility planning coordination.
</ul><br>
</ul><br><br>
Initial implementation of the SRPP will depend strongly on local 
governments within the region.  Full implementation will require the
 efforts of the whole regional community, including the public, 
non-profit and private sectors, and the general public.  Only through
 collective efforts of the whole regional community can we translate 
our potential and dreams into a reality.
<BR>
<HR>

