<html>

<head>
<title>Southeast Florida 2025</title>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../images/wlogoppr.jpg">
<p align=center><a name="a"><font size=3>South Florida Regional Planning Council</font></a><font size=3> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>Southeast Florida 2025: Natural Resources Action Team</b></font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b><img src="../images/resourc.gif" align=bottom width=72 height=64></b></font></p>
<hr>
<p align=left><a href="#b"><font size=3><b>December Agenda</b></font></a></p>
<p align=left><a href="#c"><font size=3><b>Initiative and Strategies</b></font></a></p>
<hr>
<p align=center><a name="b"><font size=3><b>SOUTHEAST FLORIDA 2025:</b></font></a><font size=3> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>An Investment Strategy for the Future</b> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>NATURAL RESOURCES ACTION TEAM</b> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>Fourth Meeting</b> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>South Florida Regional Planning Council</b> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>3440 Hollywood Boulevard, Suite 140</b> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>Hollywood, Florida 33021</b> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>December 16, 1996</b> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3><b>10:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m.</b> </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=3>&#160;</font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>I.</b> <b>Welcome and Introductions</b> </font></p>
<blockquote>
<p><font size=3>Steve Somerville, Director, Broward County Department of Natural Resources Protection </font></p>
</blockquote>
<p><font size=3><b>II. Developing action plans for initiatives</b> </font></p>
<blockquote>
<p><font size=3>This will be your final task. We will be looking for recommendations to take to the larger committee regarding actions to implement the initiatives 
discussed last meeting, as well as recommendations for further study. </font></p>
</blockquote>
<p><font size=3><b>III. Next Meeting Date</b> </font></p>
<blockquote>
<p><font size=3>This is the last meeting of the Natural Resources Action Team. You will be informed as to the date of the Southeast Florida 2025 meeting in 
February. </font></p>
</blockquote>
<p><font size=3><b>IV. Appreciation and Adjournment</b> </font></p>
<blockquote>
<p><font size=3>SOUTHEAST FLORIDA 2025 - An Investment Strategy for the Future </font></p>
</blockquote>
<p align=center><font size=3>&#160;</font></p>
<hr>
<p align=center><a name="c"><font size=3><b>INITIATIVES AND STRATEGIES</b></font></a><font size=3> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><b>INITIATIVE I: Natural Areas Partnership Initiative:</b> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><em>Purpose: To encourage collaborative relationships between private organizations and public agencies for the purchase, enhancement and 
maintenance of natural areas.</em> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><strong>Strategies:</strong> </font></p>
<ul>
<li><font size=3>Coordinate with the tourism industry to develop and market ecotourism attractions. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Establish public/private partnerships for corporate sponsorship of natural areas for their preservation, enhancement and maintenance. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Establish a seminar program for tourism employees to learn about environmental issues. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Encourage corporate participation in an &#147;adopt-a-park&#148; program based on linkages such as proximity to business location, amenities for employees, 
improved corporate public relations, business products or services, and government incentives. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Encourage corporate employee participation in volunteer labor as part of a retreat or employee bonding program. </font></li>
</ul>
<p><font size=3><b>INITIATIVE II: Urban Natural Areas Initiative:</b> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><em>Purpose: To improve natural systems values in the urban area through the identification of parcels with natural systems features which may be 
preserved, enhanced, or restored either publicly or privately.</em> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><strong>Strategies: </strong></font></p>
<ul>
<li><font size=3>Each appropriate agency should generate a list of potential parcels from previous efforts, aerial photos, tax assessor's lists, and windshield surveys. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>A map of these parcels should be developed identifying the type of resource on the site. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Parcels should be evaluated and priorities assigned for natural resource values, function, potential market value, threat from development, incompatible 
zoning, need, proximity to other natural areas and public open spaces, and eligibility for funding criteria. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Parcels should be put in priority order for acquisition, change of zoning, or public/private development agreements (e.g. conservation easement, transfer 
of development rights). </font></li>
<li><font size=3>An implementation plan should be developed by each county (in collaboration with local governments and private partners) to fund acquisition, 
enhancement, and/or maintenance of the priority natural areas. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Encourage neighborhood associations to participate in the initiative. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Encourage local governments to establish programs such as EEL in Dade County and Green Utility in Broward County.</font></li>
</ul>
<p align=center><a href="#a"><font size=3>Return to Top of Page</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3><b>INITIATIVE III: Urban Design and Landscape Initiative:</b> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><em>Purpose: To ensure that opportunities are not missed in the site design process to restore the native plant community during redevelopment, and to 
assist owners of developed properties in the removal of invasive exotics and their replacement with native vegetation. </em></font></p>
<p><font size=3><strong>Strategies:</strong> </font></p>
<ul>
<li><font size=3>Research and/or create new urban design guidelines which utilize land in the most efficient and environmentally sensitive manner. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Develop landscape guidelines for consideration by local governments which suggest a percentage of landscaped areas to be planted with native species 
(drought-tolerant where appropriate). </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Local governments should enhance public open spaces and street rights-of-way with plantings of native vegetation and removal of invasive, exotic 
vegetation. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Encourage local governments to create incentives to developers for providing native landscaped areas beyond the requirements of ordinances. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Encourage neighborhood associations to participate in the initiative. </font></li>
</ul>
<p><font size=3><b>INITIATIVE IV: Urban Infrastructure Suitability Initiative:</b> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><em>Purpose: To ensure that areas in need of redevelopment have adequate infrastructure, and that the infrastructure is designed for minimal negative 
impact to the environment. </em></font></p>
<p><font size=3><strong>Strategies:</strong> </font></p>
<ul>
<li><font size=3>Each appropriate environmental, public works, and planning agency should cooperate to develop a map of areas with any of the following characteristics 
in the urban areas: persistent stormwater flooding, poor surface water quality due to runoff, septic systems in use, potential for reuse of water, and greater 
than one-quarter mile distance to public open space/recreation. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>These areas should be put in priority order for improvement based on need, improvement to the environment, and proximity to corridors or properties 
with the greatest redevelopment potential. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>The costs of providing the necessary infrastructure to each area should be determined. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Local governments should be encouraged to include priority infrastructure improvements in their Capital Improvements Plans. </font></li>
</ul>
<p><font size=3><b>INITIATIVE V: Brownfields Reclamation Initiative:</b> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><em>Purpose: To encourage the removal of contamination from soils and ground water under abandoned properties, and to encourage the redevelopment 
and/or natural systems restoration of those properties. </em></font></p>
<p><font size=3><strong>Strategies:</strong> </font></p>
<ul>
<li><font size=3>Each County environmental agency should list and map those parcels known or suspected of being contaminated, based on abandonment, underground 
storage tanks, or CERCLIS listing. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Each parcel should be ranked based on danger to water supply wells, estimated expense of contaminant removal, redevelopment potential, and proximity 
to natural areas. </font></li>
<li><font size=3>Priority parcels should be considered for a variety of programs including: incentives or assistance for the owner to remove the contaminants, purchase by 
local government for leasing of low-risk sites, reclamation for redevelopment or restoration to a natural state.</font></li>
</ul>
<p align=center><a href="#a"><font size=3>Return to Top of Page</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3><b>INITIATIVE VI: Urban Resource Funding Initiative:</b> </font></p>
<p><font size=3><em>Purpose: To identify funding sources to implement the goals and objectives of the Natural Resources Action Team</em>. </font></p>
<p><font size=3><strong>Strategies: </strong></font></p>
<p><font size=3>Each appropriate agency should seek funding from the following sources to implement the above initiatives: </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Community Development Block Grants </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Conservation and Recreation Lands </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Florida Communities Trust </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Increased ad velorum taxes </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Municipal bonds </font></p>
<p><font size=3>User fees </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Taxes on non-native plants, fertilizers and pesticides </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Grants from the non-profit sector </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Corporate sponsorships </font></p>
<p><font size=3>In-kind contributions </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Impact fees </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Land banking </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Each appropriate agency should seek to encourage private sector participation in the above initiatives by offering: </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Low-interest revolving loans </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Community Development Block Grant funds </font></p>
<p><font size=3>State Housing Initiatives Partnership funds </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Differential pricing </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Regulatory flexibility </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Joint development </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Permit review streamlining </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Preferential taxation </font></p>
<p align=center><a href="#a"><font size=3>Return to Top of Page</font></a></p>
<hr>
<p align=center><b>[ </b><a href="../council/menu1.htm"><b>The Council</b></a> | <a href="../whatsnew/menu2.htm"><b>What's New</b></a> | <a href="../websites/menu3.htm"><b>Related Web Sites</b></a> | <a href="../region/menu4.htm"><b>Our Region</b></a> | <a href="../current/menu5.htm"><b>Current Issues</b></a> ] </p>
