<html>

<head>
<title>Executive Summary</title>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../images/plogoppr.jpg">
<p align=center>South Florida Regional Planning Council</p>
<p align=center><font size=4>Current Issues</font></p>
<p align=center><font size=4>Florida Gold Coast Clean Cities Coalition </font></p>
<p align=center><font size=4>Revolving Loan Program</font></p>
<hr>
<p><font size=4>Funding</font></p>
<p>The Florida Gold Coast Clean Cities Coalition was created in 1993, by Executive Order 93-278of the Governor of the State of Florida to serve as an advisory 
council on alternative fuels. Sponsored by the South Florida Regional Planning Council, in conjunction with the Florida Department of Community Affairs, the 
Revolving Loan Fund Program has been established to place more Alternative Fuel Vehicles (AFV) into use. A total of 2.5 million is currently dedicated to the 
Loan Program, with $500,000 of this reserved for exclusive use of local government.</p>
<p><font size=4>Fuels of the Future</font></p>
<p>Alternative fuels can play a major role in meeting our future transportation needs and improving our air quality. Vehicles using alternative fuels emit fewer pollutants 
and can result in cleaner air for our communities. Alternative fuels can reduce fuel costs as well as vehicle maintenance costs and can extend vehicle life. The 
Florida Gold Coast Clean Cities Revolving Loan Program is an opportunity for both public and private sector fleet operators to become acquainted with the many 
advantages of using alternative fuels.</p>
<p><font size=4>Revolving Loan Program</font></p>
<p>The program provides low-interest loans to private and public sector fleet owners as an incentive to purchase OEM (original equipment manufacturer) vehicles that 
operate on alternative fuels and convert vehicles to use alternative fuels.</p>
<p>The maximum loan amount available to finance the incremental cost of an OEM vehicle or the conversion cost, depending on the vehicle&#146;s type and size, is 
between $5,000 and $30,000. The total loan amount may not exceed $200,000. The payback rate is based on the estimated savings when the vehicle is operating 
on alternative fuel rather than a petroleum-based fuel.</p>
<p><font size=4>Who is Eligible?</font></p>
<p>Private owners and public fleet operators are eligible to apply for loans. Public fleet operators include the vehicles owned and operated by any public trust 
authority, county or municipality within Dade, Broward and Palm Beach counties.</p>
<p><font size=4>Minimum Qualifications</font></p>
<p>The following minimum conditions apply:</p>
<ul>
<li>business vehicle is used solely for business</li>
<li>loan must be repaid within 5 years</li>
<li>converted vehicles must operate 50 percent of the time on alternative fuel</li>
<li>vehicles must be based and primarily operated within Dade, Broward and Palm Beach Counties</li>
<li>funding cannot be used for infrastructure.</li>
</ul>
<p><font size=4>Loan Program Benefits</font></p>
<p>Potential benefits to fleet owners through participation in this program include:</p>
<ul>
<li>decreased fuel costs</li>
<li>reduced dependence on petroleum-based fuels</li>
<li>improved air quality</li>
<li>extended vehicle life </li>
<li>reduced vehicle maintenance costs</li>
<li>increased knowledge and awareness about cleaner-burning fuels.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
