<html>

<head>
<title>POTENTIAL INFORMATION TO BE INCLUDED ON THE SFRPC HOME PAGE</title>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body background="../images/plogoppr.jpg">
<p align=center><a name="z">South Florida Regional Planning Council </a></p>
<p align=center><font size=4>Council Programs</font></p>
<p align=center><font size=4>LGCP and EAR Process</font></p>
<hr>
<p><a href="#a"><font size=4>Process: UNDER CONSTRUCTION</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#b"><font size=4>Timelines: Comprehensive Plans</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#c"><font size=4>Plan Amendments</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#d"><font size=4>Action</font></a></p>
<p><a href="#e"><font size=4>Exemptions: UNDER CONSTRUCTION --- TEXT TO BE REVISED</font></a> </p>
<p><a href="#f"><font size=4>Resources: UNDER CONSTRUCTION --- TEXT TO BE ADDED</font></a> </p>
<hr>
<p><a name="a"><font size=4><b>Process: </b>UNDER CONSTRUCTION</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>In 1985 the Florida Legislature passed the &quot;Local Government Comprehensive Planning and Land Development Regulation Act&quot;. This Act is commonly 
referred to as the &quot;Growth Management Act&quot; or &quot;Chapter 163&quot;. It is intent of the Act to empower each local government in Florida to adopt a comprehensive 
plan to guide and control future development. The Act encourages local governments to develop plans that preserve and enhance present advantages to 
overcome problems that may result from the use and development of land within their jurisdictions. The comprehensive plan is a compilation of goals, objectives 
and policies that establish the guidelines and criteria for the development of land development regulations. The Act declares minimum requirements necessary to 
protect human, environmental, social, and economic resources to maintain the character and stability of present and future land use and development. These 
minimum requirements are further detailed in Rule 9J-5, Florida Administrative Code (F.A.C.). </font></p>
<p><font size=3>Once a comprehensive plan has been prepared by a local government it must undergo a series of reviews by a series of State Agencies and the applicable 
Regional Planning Council for comment and approval. Once a comprehensive plan is approved all development must be in conformity with the adopted 
comprehensive plan.</font></p>
<p><font size=3>Chapter 163 recognizes that the planning process is ongoing and provides for periodic amendments and updates to the plan. At the discretion of the local 
governing body, the plan may be amended up to two times a year, however, exemptions from the twice per year limitation exist. At a minimum, the local 
governing body must perform a self evaluation of the effectiveness of the plan and prepare amendments that update the plan and incorporate any changes in 
state law that. This is known as the Evaluation and Appraisal Report (EAR) process .</font></p>
<p><a name="b"><font size=4><b>Timelines: Comprehensive Plans</b></font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>All local governments were required to prepared comprehensive plans according to a schedule determined by the Florida Department of Community Affairs. All 
newly incorporated local governments are required to prepare a comprehensive plan within three years of incorporation. Prior to adoption, the local government 
must transmit for review a copy of the proposed comprehensive plan to the applicable Regional Planning Council and a series of State Agencies. Within sixty 
days the Florida Department of Community Affairs (DCA) prepares an Objections, Recommendations and Comments (ORC) Report which incorporates the 
comments from all the review entities and submits the ORC to the local government for consideration prior to adoption. Within 120 days of receipt of the ORC 
Report, the local government must adopt the comprehensive plan. Upon adoption of the comprehensive plan the local government must submit a copy to the 
Regional Planning Council and the DCA. Within 60 days the Regional Planning Council must determine consistency with the </font><a href="../current/menu521.htm"><font size=3>Strategic Regional Policy Plan</font></a><font size=3> and 
submit its findings to the DCA. Within the same 60 day period, the DCA must render a compliance finding. An adopted comprehensive plan is not in effect until 
the DCA finds the adopted comprehensive plan to be in compliance. </font></p>
<p align=center><a href="#z"><font size=4>Return to Top of the Page</font></a></p>
<p><a name="c"><font size=4><b>Plan Amendments</b></font></a></p>
<p><font size=3>A comprehensive plan found to be in compliance may be amended periodically. A general rule limits the amount of amendments in any particular local 
government to two amendments per year. Exceptions to the twice per year are permissible if certain conditions or circumstances are met. To amend the plan a 
local government must transmit copies of the proposed amendment to the Regional Planning Council and a series of State Agencies. The are two paths a local 
government may take when transmitting a proposed amendment 1) Request an agency review of the proposed amendments, or 2) Request that the agency not 
review the proposed plan amendments. If alternative 1) is requested, then Department of Community Affairs (DCA) will prepare an Objections, 
Recommendations and Comments (ORC) Report within 60 days. Upon receipt of the ORC Report the local government must adopt the amendment within 60 
days. Upon adoption of the plan amendment the local government must submit the adopted amendment to the Regional Planning Council and the DCA. Within 
60 days the Regional Planning Council must determine consistency with the Strategic Regional Policy Plan and submit its finding to the DCA. Within the same 
60 day period the DCA must render a finding of compliance. The plan amendment is not in effect until the DCA finds the adopted amendment in compliance. If 
alternative 2) is requested, then the DCA will within 30 days will notify the local government of its intent to review the proposed amendment and prepare an 
ORC report or its intent not to review the amendment. If the DCA determines that the proposed amendment warrants a review then the process outlined in 1) is 
automatically started. If the DCA determines that the proposed amendment does not warrant a review then the local government may proceed to adopt the 
proposed amendment within 60 days. Upon adoption of the plan amendment the local government must submit the adopted amendment to the Regional 
Planning Council and the DCA. Within 60 days the DCA must render a finding of compliance. The amendment is not in effect until the DCA finds the adopted 
amendment in compliance.</font></p>
<p><a name="d"><font size=4><b>ACTION</b></font></a></p>
<table border=1 BORDERCOLOR="#000000">
<tr><td width=345><font color="#000000"><font size=4>Transmittal of new comprehensive plan</font></font> </td><td width=323><font color="#000000"><font size=4>60 days for DCA to prepare ORC Report </font></font></td></tr>
<tr><td width=345><font color="#000000"><font size=4>Receipt of ORC Report</font></font> </td><td width=323><font color="#000000"><font size=4>120 days to adopt and submit plan</font></font> </td></tr>
<tr><td width=345><font color="#000000"><font size=4>Submittal of new comprehensive plan</font></font> </td><td width=323><font color="#000000"><font size=4>60 days for DCA to render compliance 
determination</font></font> </td></tr>
<tr><td width=345><font color="#000000"><font size=4>Effective date of new comprehensive plan</font></font> </td><td width=323><font color="#000000"><font size=4>Upon DCA in compliance finding and 21 
day appeal period</font></font> </td></tr>
<tr><td width=345><font color="#000000"><font size=4>Not in compliance determination</font></font> </td><td width=323><font color="#000000"><font size=4>Until issues resolved with DCA</font></font> </td></tr>
<tr><td width=345><font color="#000000"><font size=4>Proposed Plan Amendment No Review 
Requested</font></font> </td><td width=323><font color="#000000"><font size=4>30 days for DCA to concur</font></font> </td></tr>
<tr><td width=345><font color="#000000"><font size=4>DCA concurs</font></font> </td><td width=323><font color="#000000"><font size=4>60 days to adopt</font></font> </td></tr>
<tr><td width=345><font color="#000000"><font size=4>DCA does not concur</font></font> </td><td width=323><font color="#000000"><font size=4>60 days for DCA to prepare ORC Report</font></font> </td></tr>
</table>
<p><font size=3><i>A process time line will be developed in bullet form or some other graphic form to illustrate the local government comprehensive plan review 
process.</i></font></p>
<p><a name="e"><font size=4><b>Exemptions: </b>UNDER CONSTRUCTION --- TEXT TO BE REVISED</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3><i>Submission of local government comprehensive plan amendments is limited to twice per year. Exemptions to this requirement include DRI 
amendments, Small Scale Development amendments, Remedial amendments and amendments related to approved Sustainable Communities 
applicants.</i></font></p>
<p><a name="f"><font size=4><b>Resources: </b>UNDER CONSTRUCTION --- TEXT TO BE ADDED</font></a></p>
<p><font size=3><i>Worksheets for plan amendments (to be developed by SFRPC), and copies of the checklists used by reviewers at DCA and other reviewing agencies 
could be included in this section. Also a regularly updated listing of data sources could be included. The Regional Information System Program 
Manual and the bibliography included in the SRPP would be a good start.</i></font></p>
<p align=center><a href="#z"><font size=4>Return to Top of the Page</font></a></p>
