<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>NERC Computer Services</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC="/images/ncslarge.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1><P>
NERC Computer Services (NCS) provides and operates computer facilities in support of the
Council's environmental research programmes. It offers an integrated range of high quality,
cost-effective information technology services, which are responsive to the needs of NERC's
scientific community.
</P><HR>
<H3>The Service</H3>
<P>
The Service is geographically distributed, with computer hardware and support staff at most
NERC laboratories. <A HREF="http://www.nkw.ac.uk/kwls">Keyworth</A> (Nottinghamshire), <A HREF = "http://www.nwl.ac.uk/ncs/">Wallingford</A> (Oxfordshire) and <A HREF = "#swindon">Swindon</A>
(Wiltshire) are the main centres. The management of staff and equipment is fully integrated
to achieve flexibility in deployment and economy of scale. User support staff at NERC sites
provide expert advice to their scientific colleagues, helping them to make the best use of the
facilities available. 
</P><P>
Specialist staff in the <a href="http://wlas3.nwl.ac.uk/sst/index.tss.html">
NCS Technical Support Services</a> group, at Keyworth and Wallingford, support the
operating systems and applications packages in two teams: the Scientific Support Team</A> and Office Integration Support Team.
Other central NCS staff provide <A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/ncs/rmc.html">resource management and consultancy services</A> in all areas
of information technology. NCS also provides digital data archiving facilities for the wide
range of environmental data held by NERC.
<P>
Whilst the principal remit of NCS is to support NERC's own scientists, computing facilities are
available to researchers in the higher education sector, if capacity is available and their work
is compatible with Council's objectives.
<P>
Services are delivered according to the Council's Information Technology Strategy, which is
based on an open-systems, distributed computing model. Over 400 systems are supported
by NCS, of which the majority are UNIX-based. All sites are equipped with industry-standard
LAN technology and support is provided for personal computing through site-based server
systems and Novell NetWare. Support is also provided for VAX and IBM systems, which were
installed under an earlier technology strategy.
<P>
Beyond its role in supporting science programmes, NCS provides and supports computerised
<A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/ncs/bsg.html">business systems</A> for the Council and operates the <A HREF = "jacs.html">Joint Administrative Computer Service</A> on
behalf of NERC, the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC) and the
Particle Physics and Astronomy Research Council (PPARC).
</P><HR>
<H3>Software</H3>
<P>
Wherever possible, services are based on commercially available software. ORACLE is used for
most database applications. There is a wide range of statistical and graphical packages with
specialist software to support particular needs including geophysics, image analysis of
remotely-sensed data, geographical information systems (GIS), library management and
textual databases.
</P><HR>
<H3>External Services</H3>
<P>
All NCS computers are connected to the Joint Academic Network (JANET)/UKERNA, allowing
access to other services in the higher education and research community, as well as to
overseas networks. Supercomputers at Manchester, London and the Rutherford-Appleton
Laboratory are used extensively by NERC projects and NCS provides administrative and
technical support for these activities. Close liaison is maintained with
<A HREF = "http://www.soc.soton.ac.uk/RVS/rvsindex.html">Research Vessel Services</A>,
which provides computing facilities aboard NERC ships.
<P><HR>
<H3>Quality</H3>
<P>
NCS is a customer-focused organisation employing Total Quality Management to achieve
continuous improvement in quality. The aim is to provide services that meet or exceed
customers' expectations at a price that represents value for money. Services are delivered
in accordance with Service Level Agreements, which are negotiated annually with institutes.
</P><P>
A formal <A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/cust_complain.html">Customer Complaints
</A> mechanism is in place.
</P><HR>
Contact
<P>
