<body bgcolor=#ffffff> <p>

<h2>FUNDING OPPORTUNITIES FROM THE NATURAL
ENVIRONMENT RESEARCH COUNCIL (NERC)</h2>
<p>

<h3>INTRODUCTION</h3>
Over the past 18 months there have been a number of new funding streams that have been added
to the Council's portfolio of opportunities.   This document sets out the aims and objectives of
each scheme and provides prospective applicants with basic information on the schemes and
opportunities currently available.   <p>

<p>

<h3>DOES NERC HAVE SCHEMES THAT ARE UNIQUE?</h3>
Yes.  However it is important to recognise some of the schemes such as Realising Our Potential
Awards(ROPA), LINK and the Teaching Company Scheme, operate across the Research
Councils.   The various schemes and opportunities have been brought together under NERC's new
funding model.   <p>

<p>

<h3>WHAT IS THE NERC FUNDING MODEL AND HOW DO THE SCHEMES
MAP ON TO IT?</h3>
The funding model recognises four broad divisions:<p>

Non-thematic funding will foster excellence by supporting curiosity-driven research, training and
technology development in areas selected by applicants. Excellence will be the main criterion for
support and funding is on a marginal cost basis. <p>

-- Schemes:  1. Small research grants ( incl. CONNECT A) <p>

                    2. Standard research grants (incl.CONNECT B and ROPA)<p>

                    3. Training Awards (MSc; MRes; PhD)<p>

                    4. Fellowships (standard, advanced, senior <p>

                        and professorial)<p>

<p>

Thematic funding will encourage scientific excellence and contribute to wealth creation and
quality of life through basic, strategic and applied science, technology development and training
within selected themes.  Council's strategic planning, including inputs from Technology Foresight,
will identify these themes.<p>

Funding is on a marginal cost basis.  Major partnerships will be supported and co-funding from
the public and private sectors will be sought. <p>

-- Schemes:  5. NERC thematic programmes<p>

                    6. Teaching Company Scheme<p>

                    7. LINK and Technology Foresight<p>

<p>

In addition NERC provides core/strategic and infrastructure funding to support long term
opportunities, training and core capability in environmental science.  <p>

<p>

Core/Strategic funding, typically long term, will maintain expertise and knowledge in key areas of
the environmental sciences, determined by Council.  It will support excellent and relevant
research, survey and monitoring; technology development, and the curation, interpretation and
supply of environmental data.  It will meet current needs and will form the basis for meeting
future priorities. Most core/strategic funding is at NERC Centres/Surveys or NERC funded Units
or Centres in universities. <p>

<p>

Infrastructure funding provides essential support, equipment, services and facilities for the NERC
community.<p>

-- Funding: 8. NERC Research Vessel Services<p>

                  9. NERC scientific services<p>

<h3></h3>
<h3>WHO IS ELIGIBLE TO APPLY?</h3>
1. The non-thematic funding mode is open to research workers ordinarily resident in the UK who
are members of staff within Higher Education Institutions (HEIs) or other NERC approved
academic analogues.  Appendix C of the 1995/96 edition of the NERC Research Grants booklet
provides a list of such organisations already identified as eligible under this category. <p>

<p>

2. The thematic funding mode is open to research workers ordinarily resident in the UK who are
members of staff<p>

within Higher Education Institutions (HEIs), NERC Centres and Surveys, the Central Laboratory
of the Research Councils, and other NERC-approved academic analogues. It is also open to
research workers in institutes of other Research Councils as well as to government research
establishments (GREs) and non-profit making organisations such as UK charities and members of
the Association of Independent Research and Technology Organisations (AIRTOs).  Eligibility of
ex-GREs will be decided on a programme by programme basis. Announcements of opportunity or
invitations to bid, will contain information on eligibility, closing dates and contact points within
NERC.<p>

<p>

Details of eligibility of individuals and institutions who can apply are set out in each of the
booklets mentioned below.  Prospective applicants are also urged to consult the NERC Awards
and Training contact points for further advice and guidance.<p>

-- Booklets:    NERC Research Grants booklet<p>

                      NERC Studentships<p>

                      NERC Fellowships<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>HOW DO I KNOW WHICH OPPORTUNITIES OR SCHEMES ARE BEST SUITED TO
MY INTERESTS AND NEEDS?</b><p>

Assuming that research ideas or interests relate to the NERC mission, the following questions are
meant to aid prospective applicants navigate the opportunities.  <p>

<p>

I have a research idea/expertise that does not have any immediate benefit other than to contribute
to basic understanding. <p>

<p>

-- non-thematic:  Small and Standard Research Grants<p>

                  Training awards<p>

                  Fellowships<p>

-- thematic:      Thematic programmes<p>

<p>

I have research interests/ideas and would like to know what opportunities there are for developing
these further or contributing to NERC programmes on specific themes.   <p>

<p>

-- thematic:      Thematic programmes<p>

<p>

<p>

I have a research idea of interest to potential users/beneficiaries and would like to develop it
further.<p>

<p>

-- non-thematic:  CONNECT A (possibly B)<p>

                  Training awards (CASE studentships)<p>

                  Fellowships<p>

-- thematic:      Thematic programmes<p>

<p>

I have a research idea and offers of joint funding from potential users/beneficiaries. <p>

<p>

-- non-thematic:  CONNECT B<p>

                  Training awards (CASE studentships)<p>

-- thematic:      Thematic programmes<p>

<p>

I have current funding from industry for particular research areas and would like to extend these
and other ideas further. <p>

<p>

-- non-thematic:  ROPA   <p>

-- thematic:      LINK<p>

<p>

<b>OBJECTIVES OF SCHEMES AND METHODS OF ASSESSMENT</b><p>

1. NERC Small research grants: An open competition (1) for curiosity-motivated  basic, strategic
or applied research.  Funds sought should not be less than 2000 and not exceed 25,000
(including indirect staff costs).  No studentships are awarded under this scheme.  All applications
are subject to external peer review with final gradings being agreed by representatives of the
appropriate Research Grant and Training Awards Committee (RGTAC).  There are 3 closing
dates:<p>

<b>             1 February; 1 June;  1 October. </b><p>

<p>

1(a)CONNECT A: The CONNECT scheme's objective is to initiate new interactions between the
science base (universities, NERC Centre/Surveys and NERC approved academic analogues) and
industry, business, commerce or public sector bodies.  CONNECT intends to provide
opportunities not covered by other schemes such as ROPA or LINK.  <p>

<p>

Of particular interest under CONNECT A are "proof of concept" proposals for research which
has potential application but may have a high degree of technical risk and perhaps lack a clearly
defined end user.  Similarly costs for workshops or seminars on a theme of joint interest to the
collaborating body and science base are welcomed.  A maximum of 5,000 can be sought on
specific applications forms available from Awards and Training. In addition to scientific
excellence, applications must satisfy the following criteria: degree of user involvement, novelty,
cost effectiveness, need/urgency and likelihood of a co-funded proposal (e.g.CONNECT B)
emerging.  There are no specific closing dates and all   completed applications must be sent to Dr
A Huntingdon of NERC's Technology Interactions Group.  <p>

<p>

2. NERC Standard research grants: An open competition (1) for curiosity-motivated basic,
strategic or applied research in excess of 25,000 and for periods normally no longer than 3 years.
The primary criterion for assessment is scientific excellence with all applications subjected to
external peer review.  Meetings of Research Grants Training Award Committees (RGTACs) in
October and March each year grade the applications and make recommendations for funding.
There are two closing dates:<p>

<b>                 1 July; 1 December </b><p>

<p>

2(a) CONNECT B: As for CONNECT A the objective is to initiate new interactions between the
science base (universities, NERC Centre/Surveys and NERC approved academic analogues) and
industry, business, commerce or public sector bodies.  It is intended to provide opportunities not
covered by other schemes such as ROPA or LINK.  <p>

<p>

A prerequisite for all applications under scheme B is agreement and commitment from the
collaborating body to fund at least 50% of the total project costs.  Applications are the subject of
external peer review prior to grading by the appropriate RGTAC who are also asked to consider
degree of user involvement, novelty, cost effectiveness and need/urgency.  Priority for funding
will be given to new partnerships in preference to those that can be supported through other
funding schemes. There are two closing dates: <p>

<b>                  1 July; 1 December </b><p>

                   <p>

2. (b) ROPA: NERC participated in this scheme for the first time in 1995.   It is operated under
the scrutiny and guidance of the Office of Science and Technology (OST) and there are strict
criteria relating to eligibility to who can apply.  ROPA aims to provide opportunity for
curiosity-motivated research to applicants who already have a record of securing funds for generic
research from "bona fide" industry, business or commerce.  Calls for proposals, criteria and notes
for guidance usually appear in January each year.  <p>

Applications are submitted in March/April to the appropriate Research Council who are
responsible for assessing the proposals against two primary criteria, novelty and technical
feasibility.  Prospective applicants are advised to contact NERC at the address below for further
details and application forms<p>

<p>

NB. Rules and regulations, terms and conditions relating to NERC small and standard research
grants, the CONNECT scheme, and ROPA are detailed in the NERC Research Grants booklet
available from Awards and Training (Tel: 01793 411657. <a
href="mailto:sf@wpo.nerc.ac.uk"> E-mail</a> s<b>f@wpo.nerc.ac.uk</b>) at the
address below.<p>

<p>

3. Training Awards:  NERC has a primary responsibility for the provision of highly qualified
manpower in the environmental sciences. Only higher education institutions within the UK are
eligible as the degree awarding institution and recipients of NERC training awards must be
registered with such recognised institutions.  The vast majority of training awards are made at an
annual allocation meeting in February each year.  However research studentships (PhDs) are also
awarded within most thematic programmes, and as tied studentships on non-thematic standard
research grants (both standard and ROPA).<p>

<p>

The outcome of annual allocation exercise is publicised in the NERC Display Notice widely
circulated in March each year, and on the NERC pages on the World Wide Web.  NERC does not
accept applications from individuals who are advised to contact the designated departmental
supervisor(s) in the first instance. <p>

<p>

There are strict criteria relating to UK residency, qualifications set out in the NERC Training
Awards booklet available on request from the Awards and Training  Recipients of NERC funded
studentships are entitled to the following:<p>

<p>

  -- a maintenance grant <p>

  -- additional allowances for family responsibilities,<p>

     employment experience, age and disability,<p>

  -- the payment of approved fees,<p>

  -- assistance with travel and subsistence expenses <p>

     under specified conditions (eg fieldwork)<p>

<p>

NB. The number and level of these entitlements vary from the type of studentship and from year
to year.  <p>

<p>

3(a) Advanced Course (MSc) studentships: NERC also recognises and supports over 80
Advanced (MSc) courses.  These are disciplinary based one year advanced courses and around
240 one year studentships are allocated to them annually. All courses, and the number of
studentships allocated to them, are advertised on the Display Notice. Some courses offer partial
(50%) awards but NERC will only agree to them if their is verification that the matching 50%
support is available from elsewhere. <p>

<p>

3 (b) Research Masters Training Programme:  Since October 1995 NERC has been supporting 5
new one year Masters Research Training programmes as part of a pilot scheme anticipated to last
at least 4 years.  Each course provides a structured one year research training programme aimed
at preparing students for both future doctoral study or for employment. Courses are research
project based but also provide specialist training in research techniques and personal and
professional transferable skills. Normal NERC rules and regulations relating to research
studentships will apply.  The courses are: <p>

<p>

* Edinburgh University: Research in the Natural   <p>

  Environment  Course Organiser: Dr John Underhill, Dept<p>

  Geology and Geophysics.  Tel:  031 650 8518<p>

 <p>

* Lancaster University: Science of the Environment<p>

  Course Organiser: Professor Nick Hewitt, Institute of <p>

  Environmental and Biological Sciences. Tel: 0524 65201  <p>

    <p>

* University College, London: Environmental Sciences<p>

  Course Organiser: Dr Clive Agnew, Dept Geography,<p>

  Tel: 071 387 7050 extn.2369<p>

  <p>

* Reading University: Earth and Atmospheric Sciences<p>

  Course Organiser: Dr Ian Fenwick, Centre for Earth<p>

  and Atmospheric Sciences  Tel: 01734 318741<p>

  <p>

* York University: Ecology and Environmental Management<p>

  Course Organiser: Dr Jeremy Searle, Dept of Biology<p>

  Tel: 01904 432814<p>

<p>

3(c) Research (PhD) studentships: Around 300 NERC research studentships are awarded
annually.  Applications received from university departments by the 1 November closing date
form the basis for an open competition.   The annual allocation exercise selects the topics that
appear on the Display Notice.  <p>

<p>

Many of the selected topics are for Co-operative Awards in the Sciences of the Environment
(CASE).  In these instances supervision and research training is shared with a co-operating body
who are also expected to make a financial contribution to the research student. Through the
Industrial CASE scheme there is a special initiative to promote partnerships with industry business
or commerce who have the opportunity to formulate the research topic. <p>

<p>

NB. For both advanced course and research studentships, NERC will not accept applications
directly from students.  <p>

4. Fellowships: A very limited number of prestigious NERC postdoctoral fellowships are available
each year. This is a highly competitive exercise which from January 1996 will be enhanced to
include four categories.  <p>

<p>

 		Postdoctoral Research Fellow (3 years plus the possibility of a 2 year extension):
Early career development award to provide further postdoctoral experience to allow outstanding
environmental scientists to become independent investigators.  Available on a full or part-time
basis. Up to 1 year can be spent within a partner institution/agency.<p>

<p>

 		Advanced Research Fellow (5 years with the possibility of a 5 year extension): To
enable outstanding early/mid career researchers with high potential to develop into team leaders
of international standing.  Available on a full or part-time basis. <p>

<p>

 		Senior Research Fellow (5 years with the possibility of a 5 year extension). To
enable proven researchers of international standing at mid/peak career level to devote themselves
to personal research.  HEI Readership level equivalent. <p>

<p>

 		Research Professor (5 years plus the possibility of a further 3 years full funding and
an additional 2 years at 50% and 25%): To provide secure support and long term continuity for
proven researchers having well established international reputations. Holders must demonstrate
the capability of winning Research Council grants in open competition.   <p>

<p>

The fellowship programme also integrates a "returners" scheme which allows individuals to secure
a fellowship after a career break for example for child rearing, or after a period of study overseas.
Full details are available in the NERC Fellowship booklet available from Awards and Training
section. <p>

<p>

For all enquiries relating to all Training Awards and Fellowships telephone: 01793 411562 or <a
href="mailto:lor@wpo.nerc.ac.uk"> E-mail</a> <a href="lor@wpo.nerc.ac.uk"></a><b>lor@wpo.nerc.ac.uk</b><p>

5. NERC thematic programmes: Each year NERC starts several new Thematic programmes in
specific areas. Most of these provide opportunities for research grants and research studentships. 
Some have an Announcement of Opportunity, others have more than one at different stages of the
programme.  These are widely advertised in the national science press and directly to university
departments.  They give closing dates for applications (these vary between programmes) and
contact details of the Programme Manager who can supply further information. The primary
criterion for assessment of applications is scientific excellence within the theme of the programme,
though secondary criteria such as programme balance are also used.  Research grant applications
are subjected to external peer review. <p>

<p>

Ideas for new programmes are always welcomed and should be submitted to one of the Science
and Technology Board Secretaries by 1 September.  <p>

<p>

6. Teaching Company Scheme: The NERC plans to participate in the Teaching Company Scheme
from 1995 by supporting a small number of Training Associates.  Industrial companies and
universities wishing to participate should contact the Teaching Company Directorate in the first
instance and/or Dr Tom Huntingdon (Tel: 01793 411684), Technology Interactions Group,
NERC at the address below. <p>

<p>

7. LINK and Technology Foresight: Details of these schemes are available from Dr Tom
Huntingdon (see above)<p>

<p>

8. NERC Research Vessel Services: NERC operates a fleet of research vessels within a
comprehensive cruise programme.  All applications for shiptime are extensively peer reviewed. 
Details of closing dates, methods of assessment etc are available in the Research Grants booklet
or alternatively contact Dr Caroline Harper in NERC Scientific Services (Tel: 01973 411662 or
<a href="mailto:ceh@wpo.nerc.ac.uk"> E-mail</a><b> </b><b>ceh@wpo.nerc.ac.uk</b><p>

<p>

9. NERC scientific services: In addition to research grants, NERC scientific Services (NSS) can
provide funds to directly support wider use of facilities.  The<p>

services and facilities are listed in the Research Grants booklet and applications for funds should
be submitted on application forms available from Dr Lin Kay (Tel 01793 411600 or  <a
href="mailto:rlfk@wpo.nerc.ac.uk"> E-mail</a><b> rlfk@wpo.nerc.ac.uk</b>). The
closing date is 1 July. <p>

<p>

Return to <a href="index.htm">A+T</a><a href="index"></a> homepage<p>

<p>

<p>

