<body>
<h3>ANNOUNCEMENTS OF OPPORTUNITY - OCTOBER 1996</h3>
<p>

<h3>NATURAL ENVIRONMENT RESEARCH COUNCIL</h3>
<p>

<h3>EARTH OBSERVATION SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY BOARD</h3>
<p>

<h3>EARTH OBSERVATION SCIENCE INITIATIVE (EOSI)</h3>
<p>

The Earth Observation Science and Technology Board (EOSTB) maintains a portfolio of Core Strategic
Programmes intended to underpin UK expertise and capabilities in EO.<p>

<p>

One of the key Core Strategic Programmes is the EOSI, the objective of which is to enhance  the capacity of
the UK scientific and industrial community to improve the quality of life, increase wealth and mitigate costs
for the UK in carrying out high quality environmental science through application of EO expertise and
technology. It is specifically directed at expansion and consolidation of the EO research and user
communities chiefly by means of enhancing the UK's ability to exploit existing and future data sources and
availability.<p>

<p>

The EOSI Programme Steering Committee has recognised the need for enhanced support for the EO
Community in a number of areas, particularly with regard to the increasing demand for cross-disciplinarity,
and the assimilation into Earth Observation of expertise from the physical and other sciences.<p>

<p>

Accordingly, in order to further the strategic objectives of the EOSTB the following AOs are now issued:<p>

<p>

<OL><LI><A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/eos/ao/academpt.htm"><B>Academic Posts in Earth
Observation</B></A> - Financial support for the appointment of academic staff with the aim of attracting to
Earth Observation high quality individuals with strong backgrounds in mathematics, physics, information
systems, computer modelling and environmental issues.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<LI><A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/eos/ao/sabfello.htm"><B>Sabbaticals and Fellowships in Earth
Observation</B></A>  - Applications are invited from individuals with proven track records currently
employed in industry,  Research Council Institutes or Higher Education Institutions for :<p>

<OL><p>

<LI>Earth Observation Sabbaticals of 1 year duration;<p>

<LI>Earth Observation Fellowships of up to 5 years duration.<p>

</OL><p>

	<LI><B><A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/eos/ao/casestud.htm">(CASE) Research Studentships in Earth
Observation</B></A>  - Proposals are invited for the training of students in the handling of Earth
Observation data and the application of these data to environmental science problems.  A total of 10 awards
are available; applications under NERC's Co-operative Awards in Science and Engineering (CASE) scheme
are encouraged but high-quality non-CASE applications will be considered.<p>

<p>

<LI><B><A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/eos/ao/spacreq.htm">Special Requirements in Earth
Observation</B></A>  - Applications are invited from Higher Education Institution departments, units or
consortia for support of specific Earth Observation-related needs which are not covered of standard NERC
funding mechanisms.</LI></OL><p>

<p>

Click <A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/eos/ao/info.htm">here</A> for
application details.<p>

<p>

The call for Academic Posts in Earth Observation is <B>rolling</B>; in all other cases the closing date
is <B>6th January 1997</B>.<p>

<p>

Further details may be obtained by contacting Dr Sarah Ruth, EO Programme, NERC, Polaris house, North
Star Avenue, Swindon, Wilts, SN2 1EU.  Tel. 01793 411665, Fax: 01793 411502, E-mail: <A
HREF="mailto:saru@wpo.nerc.ac.uk">saru@wpo.nerc.ac.uk</A>.<p>

<hr>
<p>

<p>

<p>

