<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Mailing NERC staff</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H1><IMG SRC="/images/ncs.gif" ALIGN="middle">Mailing NERC staff</H1>
<HR>
<P>Most NERC staff who use e-mail can be mailed using addresses of the form -
</P>
<CENTER>
<I>name</I>@<I>place</I>.ac.uk
</CENTER>
<P>
where <I>place</I> is given by the following table -
</P>
<P>

</P>
<TABLE BORDER="1" CELLPADDING="4">
<TR><TH COLSTART="1">Institute Name</TH><TH COLSTART="2">Mail Domain</TH></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">British Antarctic Survey</TD>	<TD COLSTART="2">bas.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">British Geological Survey</TD><TD COLSTART="2">bgs.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Dunstaffnage Marine Laboratory</TD><TD COLSTART="2">dml.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Institute of Freshwater Ecology</TD><TD COLSTART="2">ife.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Institute of Hydrology</TD><TD COLSTART="2">ioh.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Institute of Terrestrial Ecology</TD><TD COLSTART="2">ite.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Institute of Virology and Environmental Microbiology</TD><TD
COLSTART="2">ivem.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Marine Biological Association</TD><TD COLSTART="2">mba.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">NERC Computer Services</TD><TD COLSTART="2">ncs.nerc.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">NERC Isotope Geosciences Laboratory</TD><TD COLSTART="2">nigl.nerc.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">NERC Scientific Services</TD><TD COLSTART="2">nss.nerc.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Plymouth Marine Laboratory</TD><TD COLSTART="2">	pml.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory</TD><TD COLSTART="2">pol.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Sea Mammal Research Unit</TD><TD COLSTART="2">smru.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">Southampton Oceanography Centre</TD><TD COLSTART="2">soc.soton.ac.uk</TD></TR>

<TR><TH COLSTART="1" COLSPAN="2"></TH></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">All NERC
staff</TD><TD COLSTART="2">nerc.ac.uk</TD></TR>       

</TABLE>
<P>
and the left-hand side of the mail address (<I>name</I> above) may be any
reasonable combination of first-name, initials and surname provided it is
unambiguous (the surname alone is not sufficient).
</P>
<P>
For example -
</P>
<PRE>	A.Cox@ncs.nerc.ac.uk
	Alan.Cox@ncs.nerc.ac.uk
	A.G.Cox@ncs.nerc.ac.uk
	Alan.G.Cox@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</PRE>
<P>
These addresses are aliases or synonyms for the <EM>real</EM> mailboxes which
people use. The latter may be changed without affecting the above addresses. The
mapping of these mail addresses to the real mailboxes relies upon the intended
recipient having registered their preferred mailbox in the
<A HREF="/ncs/curd/">Central User
Registration Database</A> (CURD).
</P>
<P>Those at NERC sites can check their CURD entries by using
<A HREF="/ncs/curd/nercform.html">this form</A>. Others
may use this
<A HREF="pubform.html">more limited form</A> to
check names, addresses and telephone numbers.</P>
<P>
</P>
<HR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.npm.ac.uk/images.symbols/golf-b.gif"> <B>What if the
person hasn't registered a preferred mailbox in the CURD or if it is
ex-directory ?</B>
</P>
<P>
A non-delivery report will be returned to you, saying that the person has not
registered a mailbox.
</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.npm.ac.uk/images.symbols/golf-b.gif"> <B>What if the name
is ambiguous ?</B>
</P>
<P>
If you mail F.Bloggs@bgs.ac.uk and there is more than one F.Bloggs in BGS, the
mail will not be delivered and a non-delivery report will be returned to you.
</P>
<P>
The report will say that the name is ambiguous and suggest a short list of
unambiguous names which best match the ambiguous name eg - 
</P>
<PRE>	F.A.Bloggs@bgs.ac.uk
	F.B.Bloggs@bgs.ac.uk
	H.Bloggs@bgs.ac.uk
	F.Blocks@bgs.ac.uk </PRE>
<P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.npm.ac.uk/images.symbols/golf-b.gif"> <B>What if the name
is misspelt ?</B>
</P>
<P>
Usually the result will be a non-delivery report returned to you containing two
lists of the best matches to the misspelt name. The first list will be of people
in, in the example, BGS, and the second will be a list of people in the rest of
NERC, in case you got the name right but the institute wrong.
</P>
<P>
Of course, if you misspell F.Bloggs as F.Blocks and there is an F.Blocks in BGS,
the mail will be delivered to F.Blocks (provided the name is unambiguous and
he/she has registered a mailbox).
</P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.npm.ac.uk/images.symbols/golf-b.gif"> <B>Can I use a
person's username ?</B>
</P>
<P>There will be people who complain that they can't remember or spell people's
names and ask - why can't I use their username ?
</P>
<P>
Fear not, you can. You can use any username belonging to a person provided it is
unambiguous. Thus you could mail me as -
</P>
<PRE>
	agc@ncs.nerc.ac.uk
</PRE>
<P>but you could not mail oracle@ncs.nerc.ac.uk because the username oracle is
used by more than one member of NCS.
</P>
<P><IMG SRC="http://www.npm.ac.uk/images.symbols/golf-b.gif">
<B><A NAME="best">Which</A>
address to use ?</B></P>
<P>NERC staff may wonder which address to use on business stationery. Use your
full first-name and all your initials, eg -</P>
<PRE> Alan.G.Cox@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</PRE>
<P>Why? The shorter forms are more likely to be made ambiguous by someone of a
similar name joining NERC. If film director Alex Cox joined NCS,
A.Cox@ncs.nerc.ac.uk would become ambiguous but Alan.G.Cox@ncs.nerc.ac.uk would
continue to work.</P>
<FORM ACTION="/cgi-bin/nerc-only/form-lookup" METHOD="GET"><P>
If you are uncertain you can see which is the best form by using
<A HREF="/ncs/curd/nercform.html">the form</A> or enter
your name here</P>
<P><INPUT NAME="name" SIZE="16"> <INPUT TYPE="SUBMIT" VALUE="search"><INPUT
TYPE="HIDDEN" NAME="type" VALUE="zb" CHECKED="CHECKED"></P></FORM>
<P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.npm.ac.uk/images.symbols/golf-b.gif">
<A HREF="complex.html">Sending complex messages</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.npm.ac.uk/images.symbols/golf-b.gif">
<A HREF="mailsec.html">Security of mail</A></P>
<P>
<IMG SRC="http://www.npm.ac.uk/images.symbols/golf-b.gif"> <B>Long mail domain
names</B></P>
<P>
The mail addresses given above are more or less obvious to NERC staff but it is
doubtful whether someone outside NERC would recognise dml.ac.uk, for example, as
being Dunstaffnage Marine Lab. Thus, where the technical constraints on length
allow, longer, more descriptive names have been set up as well -</P>
<TABLE BORDER="1" CELLPADDING="4">
<TR><TH COLSTART="1">Institute Name</TH><TH COLSTART="2">Mail Domain</TH></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">British Antarctic Survey</TD>	<TD COLSTART="2">british-antarctic-survey.ac.uk</TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSTART="1">British Geological Survey</TD><TD COLSTART="2">british-geological-survey.ac.uk</TD></TR>
