<body>
<h1><img src="/images/nerc.gif" align="middle"> Code Of Conduct</h1>
SN 10/95 <p>

<p>

<h2>REGULATIONS GOVERNING THE USE OF
COMPUTING FACILITIES WITHIN NERC</h2>

<ul>
  <li><a href="#Introduction">Introduction</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Definition of Computing Facilities">Definition of Computing Facilities</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Access to facilities">Access to facilities</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Misuse of facilities">Misuse of facilities</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Hacking">Hacking</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Data Security">Data Security</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Data Protection Act 1984">Data Protection Act 1984</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Misuse of data">Misuse of data</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Software and Data sets">Software and Data sets</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Software & data obtained under">Software &amp; data obtained under academic terms</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Public Domain Software">Public Domain Software</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Data communications networks and JANET">Data communications networks and JANET</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Electronic Mail">Electronic Mail</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Internet">Internet</a></li>
  <li><a href="#On-line Publishing">On-line Publishing</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Offensive Material">Offensive Material</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Working at Home">Working at Home</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Private use">Private use</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Games">Games</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Hardware security">Hardware security</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Health & Safety">Health &amp; Safety</a></li>
  <li><a href="#Annex A">Annex</a></li>
</ul>
<p>

<h4>1.<a name="Introduction"></a> Introduction</h4>
<p>

1.1 The guidance contained in this notice covers the use of computing equipment by NERC staff
and by other authorised persons. The guidance defines both good practice and practices which may
constitute misuse. It draws attention to operational procedures which may help to prevent misuse,
including misuse by unauthorised users. The guidance applies to all computing facilities within
NERC sites, whether or not these are supported by NERC Computer Services (NCS).<p>

<p>

1.2 The guidance is provided on the World Wide Web (WWW) at URL
<a href="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/code.html">http://www.nerc.ac.uk/code.html</a>.<p>

<p>

1.3 Staff are also asked to make themselves familiar with any `Good Practice Guides' which may
have been produced by site NCS personnel.<p>

<p>

<h3><a name="NERC COMPUTING FACILITIES"></a>NERC COMPUTING FACILITIES</h3>
<p>

<h4>2. <a name="Definition of Computing Facilities"></a>Definition of Computing Facilities</h4>
<p>

2.1 Computing facilities are taken to include computers, peripherals, networks and all
programmable computing equipment, whether or not connected to a network. They also include all
software and data stored within computing equipment or in transit on magnetic and other media.<p>

<p>

<h4>3. <a name="Access to facilities"></a>Access to facilities</h4>
<p>

3.1 Access to computer systems under the control of NCS requires identification in the form of a
unique user identifier (ID), known to the computer system being accessed, and a password known
only to the user. Application for a user ID must be made to NCS who will ensure that the chosen
combination is unique, and who maintain a record of individual users and their authorised IDs. NCS
will allocate an initial password and explain how it may be changed.<p>

<p>

3.2 The combination of user ID and password is intended to prevent unauthorised users from
accessing NCS facilities. It is therefore important to protect the security of both IDs and passwords.
Users should only use the IDs assigned to them and where it is necessary for IDs to be shared
between groups of users, each individual user should be declared to NCS in advance, or alternative
security measures acceptable to NCS should be established. Passwords must consist of a minimum
of 6 alphanumeric characters and should avoid easily guessed combinations. They should be
changed regularly and must be changed at NCS request.<p>

<p>

3.3 It is the responsibility of the user to ensure that only authorised individuals have access to NERC
computing facilities. Users should ensure that screens and memories are cleared of all confidential
information when an item is unattended or at log-off, that terminals are not left unattended when
logged-in and that hard copy which can be used to associate IDs with passwords is properly and
securely filed.<p>

<p>

<h4>4. <a name="Misuse of facilities"></a>Misuse of facilities</h4>
<p>

4.1 Misuse of computing facilities is considered a serious disciplinary offence under the terms of
the NERC Disciplinary Procedures (Staff Notice 8/89). Annex A to this notice lists actions which
may constitute misuse of computing equipment. The list merely provides an overview of actions
which will be considered to amount to computer misuse. It is not intended to be comprehensive -
line management will have the discretion to judge each case on its merits. Any alleged misuse by
a member of staff will be investigated in accordance with the Disciplinary Procedures and may
render the individual liable to disciplinary penalty.<p>

<p>

4.2 Appropriate action will be taken against other authorised users who are believed to have misused
NERC computing facilities. This may include withdrawal of support to the individual(s) concerned.<p>

<p>

<h4>5. <a name="Hacking"></a>Hacking</h4>
<p>

5.1 "Hacking" is defined as gaining, or attempting to gain, unauthorised access to a computer
system. It also covers other acts aimed at interfering with a computer system, whether through
damage or destruction of data or programs, or through disruption of operational practices. It is the
NERC policy to investigate all attempts at hacking, whether successful or otherwise, in order to
ensure the security of NERC programs and data.<p>

<p>

5.2 As part of the academic community making use of the Joint Academic Network (JANET),
NERC is also required to assist in investigating hacking of systems which are not under NERC
control. Hacking or attempted hacking of NERC systems, or any other hacking which involves the
use of NERC equipment, of staff time or of information gained during the course of NERC
employment, will be considered a serious breach of discipline to be dealt with under NERC
Disciplinary Procedures.<p>

<p>

5.3 Hacking or attempted hacking of other organisations' systems may also render an individual
liable to prosecution and claims for damages by those organisations.<p>

<p>

<p>

<h3><a name="DATA COLLECTION, USAGE AND STORAGE"></a>DATA COLLECTION, USAGE AND STORAGE</h3>
<p>

<h4>6. <a name="Data Security"></a>Data Security</h4>
<p>

6.1 Data are a valuable asset and must be adequately protected from unauthorised access, use or
manipulation. Any user of NERC computing facilities is personally responsible for the security and
integrity of any data accessed or created and for compliance with copyright rules applicable to
NERC and commercial data.<p>

<p>

6.2 NCS are required to operate in a manner which ensures proper security for data and programs
entrusted to them, in accordance with "good practice" within the computer industry. NCS publish
and periodically review their arrangements for the storage and protection of data and offer advice
to users on the risk of accidental loss. Additional security can be provided by arrangement. Users
should assess the level of security needed to protect any given data set, taking into consideration the
cost of acquisition, the consequences of loss, and the cost-benefit of additional security such as extra
back-ups.<p>

<p>

6.3 In the case of equipment outside the control of NCS, the responsibility for developing and
carrying out operational procedures to ensure the security of data rests with the user. However, the
same principles as those outlined above will apply.<p>

<p>

<h4>7. <a name="Data Protection Act 1984"></a>Data Protection Act 1984</h4>
<p>

7.1 The storage and use of computerised records relating to individuals is governed by the Data
Protection Act 1984. All staff operating or compiling databases which contain personal data must
make themselves aware of the provisions of NERC Staff Notices 14/87, 21/87 and 31/89. These
describe the working of the Act in detail. If in doubt, staff should consult their Data Protection
Co-ordinator (local Establishments sections will know who this is) or the NERC Data Protection
Officer (SEO, Personnel Section, Swindon Office).<p>

<p>

<h4>8. <a name="Misuse of data"></a>Misuse of data</h4>
<p>

8.1 The unauthorised access of data and its manipulation, corruption or destruction - regardless of
whether or not this is for personal gain - will be treated as a serious breach of trust and action will
be taken against individuals who misuse data in this way. The fraudulent misuse of data for personal
gain will be treated as a particularly serious offence under the NERC Disciplinary Procedure and
will render the individual liable to summary dismissal.<p>

<p>

<p>

<h3><a name="INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY RIGHTS AND COPYR"></a>INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY RIGHTS AND COPYRIGHT</h3>
<p>

<h4>9. <a name="Software and Data Sets"></a>Software and Data Sets</h4>
<p>

9.1 Software is recognised by law to be Intellectual Property. It is normally obtained from suppliers
under the terms of a legally binding agreement which defines the conditions under which it may be
used. NERC requires all users to comply with the terms of licence agreements into which it has
entered and not to knowingly use unauthorised copies of software.<p>

<p>

9.2 <b>Care should be taken if using software which is not subject to licensing agreements. The
use of unlicensed software (which may contain viruses) can cause serious damage to other
systems. Unsolicited software must not be introduced to NERC systems. Such software should
be passed to NCS for examination.</b><p>

<p>

9.3 Data sets generated through professional activities within NERC are also considered to be
Intellectual Property. <b>As a result, staff should not knowingly distribute or release data sets to
non-NERC organisations in either hard copy or software formats (or through the Internet)
without prior discussion with and permission from local line management.</b> Permission will need
to be given by both NERC line management and commissioned research customers should the data
sets have been generated through CR-funded projects.<p>

<p>

<h4>10. <a name="Software & data obtained under"></a>Software &amp; data obtained under academic terms</h4>
<p>

10.1 Most of the software and data provided by NCS and much of the PC software used within
NERC is obtained under special academic terms. These may be directly negotiated with the supplier
or may be the result of negotiation by the Combined Higher Education Software Team (CHEST)
on behalf of the Joint Information Systems Committee (JISC). In order to simplify the process of
negotiation with software suppliers the JISC has agreed a Code of Conduct governing the use of
software purchased under special academic terms. Copies of this may be obtained from NCS and
should be studied by all users of such products.<p>

<p>

10.2 The business of NERC, as defined by the Charter, falls within the definition of academic use
and normal computing activities in support of Council's programmes comply with the Code. NCS
will offer advice on the interpretation of the Code with respect to particular applications and will
make appropriate arrangements in the case of non-compliance.<p>

<p>

<h4>11. <a name="Public Domain Software"></a>Public Domain Software</h4>
<p>

11.1 Many useful programs are available at no charge and can often be obtained electronically from
public bulletin boards. Unfortunately, these free services have attracted the attention of computer
vandals and can be a route by which computer viruses, trojans and other anti-social and destructive
computer programs are propagated. The JISC funds the Higher Education National Software
Archives at Universities of Lancaster and Kent. Sun Microsystems supports an archive at Imperial
College known as SunSITE Northern Europe. The operators of the HENSA and SunSITE services
take great care to ensure that the software they supply comes from a well-defined source and is
uncontaminated. <b>NERC staff are therefore strongly advised to use these services if they wish
to obtain copies of public domain or other freely available software, and to refrain from
importing such software from other sources.</b><p>

<p>

11.2 Nonetheless, no-one can guarantee that software from these sources is benign and caution
should be exercised when using it. NCS will offer advice on request.<p>

<p>

<p>

<h3><a name="ELECTRONIC COMMUNICATION SYSTEMS"></a>ELECTRONIC COMMUNICATION SYSTEMS</h3>
<p>

<h4>12. <a name="Data communications networks and JANET"></a>Data communications networks and JANET</h4>
<p>

12.1 Given that NCS is responsible for the operation of the data communications networks within
NERC, no attempt should be made to attach equipment to the network or to disconnect equipment
from the network without their approval. NCS will normally provide the staff to connect and
disconnect equipment but this may, with the agreement of NCS, be delegated to Institute staff.<p>

<p>

12.2 NERC makes use of JANET for data communication between its sites. JANET operates under
the terms of a licence granted by OFTEL to the Secretary of State for Education and is operated by
the United Kingdom Education and Research Networking Association under contract to JISC. The
<A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/janet.html">
conditions for use of the Network</A> can be obtained from NCS. All normal NERC activities fall
within these terms.<p>

<p>

12.3 Conditions of use established for any other network or specialised communication link must
also be observed. Copies of these can be obtained through local administration sections.<p>

<p>

<h4>13. <a name="Electronic Mail"></a>Electronic Mail</h4>
<p>

13.1 Electronic mail is an important means of communication within NERC and offers facilities
which are complementary to other media. However, it is no more secure than ordinary, paper mail
and is, in some respects, less secure. Like ordinary mail it may be intercepted and/or forged. It
should not be used for information of a confidential nature.<p>

<p>

13.2 Unlike ordinary mail, electronic mail may sometimes contain attachments, such as programs
which are executed when the attachment is opened. These attachments need not always be benign;
a malicious person can send an attachment which damages files when it is opened. The damage may
not always be immediately apparent. You are advised not to trust or open such program attachments
in unsolicited mail. If in doubt seek advice from NCS.<p>

<p>

13.3 The electronic mail service, which is operated by NCS, does not include automatic archiving
of messages. It is the responsibility of users to create a permanent record of any messages which
must be retained in line with the normal rules for paper records. It is strongly advised that messages
which may need to be referenced for audit purposes or which may be quoted as part of official
records should be filed in hard copy form.<p>

<p>

<h4>14. <a name="Internet"></a>Internet</h4>
<p>

14.1 The Internet has established itself as an important communication facility, providing contact
with professional and academic sources throughout the world. It is already being used by staff as
a forum for discussion and information dissemination within scientific and technical communities.
Where appropriate, staff  are encouraged to make use of the Internet as part of their official
professional activities. However, attention must be paid to ensuring that published information has
relevance to normal professional activities before material is released in NERCs name. The service
allowing use of the Internet could deteriorate if used extensively, a danger if the facility is being
used for unofficial or private activities. <p>

<p>

14.2 Intellectual Property Rights and Copyright (paras. 6-10) must not be compromised when
publishing on the Internet.<p>

<p>

14.3 The availability and variety of information on the Internet has meant that it can be used to
obtain  material reasonably considered to be offensive. The use of the Internet to access and/or
distribute any kind of offensive material will leave an individual liable to punishment through the
NERC Disciplinary Procedures (see para. 16).<p>

<p>

<h4>15. <a name="On-line Publishing"></a>On-line Publishing</h4>
<p>

15.1 World Wide Web, anonymous ftp and other services which deliver electronic documents,
publications and data over the network must be operated in accordance with Centre and Institute
policy. Such services must not be operated without the prior approval of Institute management.
Where the services are to run on systems managed by NCS, approval must be obtained from NCS
in advance.<p>

<p>

15.2 If NERC does not hold the copyright of the text, images or data to be distributed, permission
for the intended use must be obtained from the copyright holder. Where the copyright belongs to
NERC, permission must be obtained from curator of the material.<p>

<p>

15.3 Further guidance regarding on-line publishing may be obtained from NCS. Information is also
to be found in Staff Notice 11/95 (The NERC Corporate Image on the Internet).<p>

<p>

<h4>16. <a name="Offensive Material"></a>Offensive Material</h4>
<p>

16.1 NERCs computing facilities (and particularly the provision of e-mail and Internet services)
must not be used to send messages or distribute material which might reasonably cause offence or
which would be considered socially unacceptable. Direct links to such material in published
hyper-text documents is also prohibited. <b>The transmission of messages which are threatening,
offensive, obscene, or which constitute racial or sexual harassment will be considered a serious
misuse of NERC facilities. Staff found to be responsible for the generation, transmission or
distribution of such materials will be dealt with through NERC Disciplinary Procedures and,
in extreme cases, may be liable to summary dismissal.</b><p>

<b><p>

</b>16.2 The use of NERC facilities to import or export obscene or offensive material on the Internet
will be regarded as a serious disciplinary offence. Again, staff found to be involved in this activity
will be liable to the severest of penalties within the NERC Disciplinary Procedures.<p>

<p>

<p>

<h3><a name="OTHER CONSIDERATIONS"></a>OTHER CONSIDERATIONS</h3>
<p>

<h4>17. <a name="Working at Home"></a>Working at Home</h4>
<p>

17.1 Staff Notice 11/94 gives guidance on the use of NERC computing equipment at home.
Particular attention should be paid by staff to the equipment and property insurance requirements
asked of them when working at home.<p>

<p>

17.2 Where staff use computers at home in connection with their work they should ensure that the
strictures on copyright violation, protection against viruses, etc, described in other sections of this
notice, are followed, especially where files are transferred between home and work.<p>

<p>

<h4>18. <a name="Private use"></a>Private use</h4>
<p>

18.1 The private use of NERC computer facilities is dependent upon agreement being obtained from
line management and (in the case of NCS managed facilities) from NCS. NERC does not wish to
discourage private use, particularly where this can be seen as a useful form of training. However,
agreement to private use will be at management discretion and will be dependent upon a number
of factors. These will include the user's objectives, the extent to which the activity will conflict with
official business and any extra demands placed upon support facilities. Private use will be expected
to take place outside normal working hours and must not contravene other conditions of use
attached to NERC computer facilities. Private use will not normally be permitted for personal gain
and the principles outlined in Staff Notice 25/89 on "Outside Professional Activities" will be
applied.<p>

<p>

18.2 Individuals wishing to use NERC computer facilities on a repayment basis should discuss this
with line management and (in the case of NCS managed facilities) with NCS.<p>

<p>

<h4>19. <a name="Games"></a>Games</h4>
<p>

19.1 There is some benefit to be derived from using games software to gain computer familiarisation
and keyboard skills. However, much games software is now contaminated with viruses and other
hidden faults. Games software also makes use of computer facilities provided primarily for scientific
or administrative use. NERC staff and other authorised users of computer equipment are therefore
not permitted to store any games software on computer equipment or to allow that equipment to be
used for the execution of such software, unless this forms part of a recognised training package or
else provided as an element of the standard Windows software package. NCS will be able to provide
further guidance on this.<p>

<p>

<h4>20. <a name="Hardware security"></a>Hardware security</h4>
<p>

20.1 An up-to-date and readily accessible record of all computer equipment should be maintained
at every site - normal NERC inventory procedures apply to computing equipment. Equipment should
not be removed from a site without the prior agreement of line management (and NCS in the case
of NCS supported facilities). Records should be maintained of equipment loaned out or otherwise
removed from sites.<p>

<p>

<h4>21. <a name="Health & Safety"></a>Health &amp; Safety</h4>
<p>

21.1 There is an onus on computer users to make themselves aware of any health and safety
regulations and codes of practice which apply at their site. Local Safety Advisers will be pleased to
offer advice.<p>

<p>

21.2 Most personal computer systems will require a 13 amp supply to several pieces of equipment.
<b>Care must be taken not to overload the mains supply.</b> Mains leads should not obstruct walkways
and should be fitted with protective rubber pads where they cross areas of floor in regular use.<p>

<p>

21.3 <b>Particular care should be taken to ensure that interconnected computer equipment is not
powered by mains supplies from different phases. Local electrical advice must be sought if you
are in doubt.</b><p>

<p>

21.4 For advice on health and ergonomic matters refer to your local Safety Adviser or request a copy
of the document "Be comfortable at your VDU" available from the NERC Safety Adviser
(01793-411577).<p>

<p>

<h6>ESTABLISHMENTS DIVISION	August 1995</h6>
<hr>
<p>

<h2><a name="Annex A"></a>Annex A</h2>
<h3>EXAMPLES OF COMPUTER MISUSE</h3>
<p>

This list gives examples of misuse which may be subject to disciplinary or other appropriate action.
It is not intended to be comprehensive and should be read in conjunction with paragraph 3 of the
Code.<p>

<p>

1. <a href="#Access to facilities">Access (Code para 3)</a> - failure to take reasonable steps to protect the security of IDs and
passwords; the unauthorised use of another person's ID/password.<p>

<p>

2. <a href="#Hacking">Hacking (Code para 5)</a> - hacking of any NERC computer system, or hacking into any other
computing system using NERC resources.<p>

<p>

3. <a href="#Data Protection Act 1984">Data Protection Act 1984 (Code para 7)</a> - failure to comply with the provisions of the Data
Protection Act; unauthorised access to, or disclosure of, information about individuals.<p>

<p>

4. <a href="#Misuse of data">Misuse of data (Code para 8)</a> - unauthorised access to data and/or programs, and their
manipulation, corruption or destruction; failure to take reasonable steps to protect the integrity of
NERC data and/or programs.<p>

<p>

5. <a href="#INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY RIGHTS AND COPYR">Software use (Code paras 9 - 11)</a> - failure to comply with the terms of NERC software licensing
agreements; infringing NERC copyright or Intellectual Property Right arrangements on NERC-generated software and data sets; the generation or use of illegal copies of software; failure to
comply with the terms of usage of academic software; the unlawful introduction or dissemination
of rogue software.<p>

<p>

6. <a href="#ELECTRONIC COMMUNICATION SYSTEMS">Data communications networks and JANET (Code para 12</a>) - failure to comply with the
conditions of use of the JANET network or of any other specialised communication link; attaching
or disconnecting equipment from the network without the agreement of NCS.<p>

<p>

7. <a href="#Electronic Mail">Electronic Mail (Code para 13</a> and <a href="#On-line Publishing">15</a>) - the misuse of the e-mail system, particularly the
transmission of messages which are considered threatening, offensive, obscene or which constitute
racial or sexual harassment; sending chain letters. <p>

<p>

8.<a href="#Internet"> Internet (Code para 14)</a> - the use of NERC computer facilities to import or distribute obscene
or offensive material either within NERC or externally.<p>

<p>

9. <a href="#On-line Publishing">On-line publishing (Code para 15)</a> - failure to comply with recognised NERC guidance on the
use of electronic communication media.<p>

<p>

10. <a href="#Private use">Private use (Code para 18)</a> - the unauthorised use of any NERC computer facility.<p>

<p>

11. <a href="#Games">Games (Code para 19)</a> - the use of NERC equipment for the execution or storage of computer
games.<p>

<p>

12. <a href="#Hardware security">Hardware security (Code para 20)</a> - failure to ensure the security of computing equipment.<p>

<p>

13. <a href="#Health & Safety">Health and Safety (Code para 21)</a> - failure to observe Health and Safety codes.<p>

<hr>
<p>

<h6>Marked up by <a href="mailto:Alan.Cox@ncs.nerc.ac.uk">Alan.Cox@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</a>, November 1995
</body>
</html>
