<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>NERC Corporate Image on the Internet</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/images/nerc.gif"></H1>
<H2>CODE OF CONDUCT - SN 11/95</H2>
<HR>
<H3>The NERC Corporate Image on the Internet</H3>
</P><P>
<HR>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#Introduction">Introduction</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="#Electronic media">Electronic media</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="#World Wide Web">World Wide Web</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="#Publishing on WWW and newsgroups">Publishing on WWW and newsgroups</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="#Comments on and criticism of official activities">Comments on and criticism of official activities</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="#Assistance available from NERC Computer Services (NCS)">Assistance available from NERC Computer Services (NCS)</A></LI>
<LI><A HREF="#THE DO'S AND DON'T'S OF USING THE INTERNET">THE DO'S AND DON'T'S OF USING THE INTERNET</A></LI>
</UL>
</P><P>

<H4>1. <A NAME="Introduction"></A>Introduction</H4>
</P><P></P><P>

1.1  The expansion of access to electronic communication systems has 
increased markedly in recent years. Most staff are likely to be familiar 
with NERC-networked electronic mail software systems which provide links 
with colleagues using personal computers (PCs). The growth of the Internet 
- a computer network which allows the electronic exchange of information and
 data between PC users - is a high-profile feature of this growth in 
communication systems. At present, there are over three million computers 
linked to the Internet system worldwide. 
</P><P>

1.2  The use of the Internet is important to NERC in promoting both the 
organisation and NERC science within computer-using academic and commercial 
sectors. The facility is available to all members of staff as part of their 
official professional activities. The guidance given in paras. 14 and 15 of 
SN 10/95 (<A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/code.html">Regulations Governing 
the Use of Computing Facilities Within NERC</A>) 
provides further information on its use. 
</P><P>

1.3  Through its presence on the Internet, NERC has created an image which 
is identifiable to a potentially vast audience. As public awareness of the 
Internet grows, NERCs Internet image will also grow in importance. <B>This 
notice is therefore intended to provide guidance to NERC staff on how the 
Internet should be used to maintain and enhance the NERC image, and the 
consequences for staff should their use of the Internet tarnish this image.
</B>
</P><P>

<H4>2. <A NAME="Electronic media">Electronic media</A></H4>
</P><P>
2.1  NERC's presence on the Internet is identifiable in two broad classes 
of activity:
</P><P>

<B>     a.   Network fora</B>
</P><P>

     i.   Individual members of staff send electronic mail or files to other 
individuals, or contribute to public discussions in <B>network fora</B> (Usenet 
newsgroups and mail distribution lists, for example) not controlled by NERC. 
</P><P>

     ii.  Network fora support the equivalent of letters and telephone calls 
to people outside NERC, and of speaking at public or other non-NERC meetings.
 Staff are already familiar with the need to be courteous and measured in 
letters and over the telephone, as well as the need for professional 
behaviour at public meetings. The same degree of courtesy and discipline 
must be shown when using the network fora.
</P><P>

     iii. Much as it is important for an audience to be clear when an 
individual is representing NERC and when they are representing themselves, 
so it is with communication conducted over the Internet.
</P><P>

<B>  b.   Servers</B>
</P><P>

     i.   NERC staff provide information on various kinds of <B>servers</B> from 
which it can be read or retrieved by other users of the Internet. Servers 
will be less familiar to NERC staff; there will probably be many who do not 
know of their existence and do not appreciate that NERC essentially 
`publishes' on the Internet.
</P><P>

     ii.  Servers are like shelves of a library or newsagent, somewhere to 
place our electronic publications so that people may browse them using 
software such as Mosaic and Netscape. The familiar counterparts of servers 
are NERC publications, which vary in form from the polished appearance of 
the annual report, to the more simply-produced project bulletin or 
newsletter. These are generally intended to represent part or all of NERC, 
rather than individual members of staff, and are received as such by the 
readership.
</P><P>

2.2   It is important that all members of staff making use of either 
electronic facility are aware of the considerations to be borne in mind 
when publishing material on the Internet, and that they ensure that the 
image NERC projects through these facilities is not compromised. These 
considerations are detailed in Annex A.
</P><P>

<H4>3. <A NAME="World Wide Web">World Wide Web</A></H4>  
</P><P>

3.1  Electronic information availability has gained particular significance 
with the development of the World Wide Web (WWW). This mechanism allows 
anyone with relatively inexpensive computing equipment to both receive 
information and publish in graphic form on the Internet. WWW has become 
extremely popular as a means of information dissemination and currently 
represents 14% of total traffic on the Internet. Experiments in publishing 
through the WWW have been under way in NERC Institutes for some time. 
Because of its novelty, some of these experiments will have been conducted 
without the same consideration to style and content as that applied to 
printed publications. 
</P><P>

3.2  Swindon Office is preparing a set of home pages on the WWW about NERC. 
These will provide information of the type currently available in NERC 
brochures, but will also provide hypertext links with Centre and Survey 
home pages. A common format for the introductory section is also being 
discussed amongst all of the Research Councils.
</P><P>

3.3  The guidelines given in Annex A describe how WWW should be used as a 
route for publishing NERC-derived information. The guidance is concerned 
primarily with the quality of the publications; whilst focusing on the WWW, 
it applies equally to other methods of Internet publishing, such as 
nonymous ftp servers.
</P><P>

<H4>4. <A NAME="Publishing on WWW and newsgroups">
Publishing on WWW and newsgroups</A></H4>
</P><P>

4.1  WWW is likely to be of use to staff wishing to publish NERC- or 
Institute-related scientific or technical news. However, it is recognised 
that the Web can be used by groups within NERC for non-work related 
activities, such as sports and social club news, union news and society or 
hobby information. Pages containing this type of information should only by 
placed on to the servers if the following points have been satisfied:
</P><P>

a.   line management approval has been obtained.<BR>

b.   server access control is used to limit the readership to NERC/Centre/
Institute/Site staff (as appropriate).<BR>

c.   use is normally confined to outside normal working hours or during 
lunchtimes.<BR>

</P><P>
Should there be any difficulties in determining whether the substance of a 
page is appropriate for insertion on to a server, the matter should be 
referred to local Establishment Officers for consideration.
</P><P>

4.2  Recreational newsgroups are often established by users to bring 
together individuals throughout the PC-user community with interests in a 
variety of non-work-related subjects. NERC takes the view that the creation 
of such newsgroups using NERC facilities can only be sanctioned if the 
criteria listed above are satisfied. It is encumbent on line managers to 
ensure that this facility is not abused by staff in any way. Excessive use 
of the service for accessing the Internet for non-work related activities 
could result in its deterioration.
</P><P>

4.3  Any pages found to have been created without satisfying the criteria 
listed in para. 4.1 will  be removed from the server and the individuals 
responsible for their creation will be dealt with through the NERC 
Disciplinary Procedures. Equally, staff felt by their line management to be 
making inappropriate use of the service, especially during working hours, 
are likely to have disciplinary action brought against them.
</P><P>

4.4  Should any pages placed on a server be found to contain obscene or 
offensive material of any kind, those found to be responsible for the 
creation of the page will be liable to serious disciplinary action (NERC 
Disciplinary Procedures).
</P><P>

<H4>5. <A NAME="Comments on and criticism of official activities">
Comments on and criticism of official activities</A></H4>  
</P><P>

5.1  The availability of electronic media facilities - and access to the 
Internet in particular - now provide opportunities for staff to distribute 
information on NERC scientific and administrative matters to a potentially 
very wide readership. With this, however, comes a responsibility for NERC 
staff to report these matters in a fair and constructive manner. It must be 
remembered that much as staff are bound by procedures when commenting on or 
criticising official activities through written or spoken media (SN 1/93 
refers) so are they bound by the same restrictions when using electronic 
media. A failure to adhere to the details of this notice when using 
electronic media to comment on and/or criticise official activities is 
likely to be regarded as a disciplinary offence.
</P><P>

5.2  This guidance will not remove the right of recognised Trade Union 
representatives to fully represent the interests of their members.
</P><P>

<H4>6. <A NAME="Assistance available from NERC Computer Services (NCS)">
Assistance available from NERC Computer Services (NCS)</A></H4>  
</P><P>

6.1  NCS will support WWW and anonymous ftp server software operating on 
Unix platforms. Where individuals or groups are officially sanctioned to 
use this software on systems managed by NERC Computer Services, NCS can 
assist in preventing unauthorised access to the servers and publication 
via them. NCS cannot prevent unauthorised access to other servers or 
otherwise police their use.
</P><P></P><P>


<B>Establishments Division, August 1995</B>

</P><P></P><P>

<BR>
<BR>

<H4>ANNEX A. <A NAME="THE DO'S AND DON'T'S OF USING THE INTERNET">
THE DO'S AND DON'T'S OF USING THE INTERNET</A></H4> 
</P><P>

a.   Centres and Institutes should establish clear procedures for 
determining who has authority to publish documents on Internet servers, and 
how authority and responsibility can be delegated.
</P><P>

b.   It is suggested that all on-line documents contain an indication of 
the authorship of the document and of whoever is responsible, if anyone, 
for approving the contents as suitable for publication. Inclusion of 
standard Internet  e-mail addresses to do this would be appropriate.
</P><P>

c.   All on-line documents should include an indication of the timeliness 
of the document (eg. the date the document was written), or if it is known 
to have a limited lifetime, its expiry date.
</P><P>

d.   Procedures should also be established for removing or updating on-line 
publications in a timely manner.
</P><P>

e.   Consider whether a consistent style should be imposed on Internet 
publications and how the style should relate to that used for print 
publications. Different styles may be appropriate for different types of 
document.
</P><P>

f.   Consider the role of pictures and other images. Bear in mind that even 
a small picture may be several kilobytes in size and that some readers will 
have slow network connections. Authors should be sparing in their use of 
images.
</P><P>

g.   Because electronic text and images can be very easy to copy, it is 
easy to inadvertently infringe someone's copyright. Determine how you will 
prevent copyright infringement. Remember that just because NERC owns the 
copyright of something it doesn't mean that you don't need permission to 
publish it.
</P><P>

h.   Where there are both on-line and print versions of a document, be 
clear about which is the master version of the document and how changes 
made to the master are to be propagated to the other.
</P><P>
i.   Don't be libellous - ensure that any facts concerning individuals or 
organisations are accurate and verifiable. Try to refrain from expressing 
opinions. Where opinions are expressed they must not be expressed in a way 
which damages the subject's reputation.
</P><P>

j.   Remember that not everyone that uses the Internet is necessarily as 
law abiding or as well disposed toward NERC as you are. Avoid giving away 
information that will invite the attentions of thieves, animal rights 
activists and others who might wish to break into NERC sites and do damage 
to material or staff. Consider separating such sensitive information from 
non-sensitive information which might be useful to a general readership, 
and limiting access to the former to network addresses within NERC.
</P><P>

k.   Advertisements for services or products should follow the same 
guidelines as used by the advertising industry; they should be legal, 
decent, honest and truthful.
</P><P>

l.   The Internet must not be used by staff for producing, accessing or 
distributing material which is (or could be considered to be) obscene or 
offensive. To do otherwise will lead to the severest of sanctions being 
brought against perpetrators through the NERC Disciplinary Procedures, as 
well as possible criminal action.
</P><P>

<A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC="/images/logoicon.gif" ALIGN="middle">
To the NERC home page</A>
<HR>
<ADDRESS>www-support@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</ADDRESS>
