<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Publishing on the Web</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC = "/images/nerc.gif" ALT="NERC"></H1>
<HR>
<H2>Publishing on the Web</H2>
<P>
NERC staff who are considering publishing information on the World Wide Web will need to
address a numer of issues:
<UL>
<LI>Why publish on the Web?
<P>
Questions to ask yourself should include:
	<P>
	<UL>
	<LI>Will the information be useful to the potential readership?
	<LI>Is the readership I'm trying to reach on the Internet?
	<LI>Can I devote the resources to maintaining the documents I wish to publish?
	<LI>How much do I mind if my documents are copied by others?
	</UL>
	<P>
<LI>How do I mark-up text so that it is suitable for publication via a WWW server?
<P>
You use the Hyper-Text Mark-up Language. Here are a few sources of information which
should help you learn to use HTML.
<P>
<UL>
<LI>HTML is a particular application of the Standard Generalized Mark-up Language
(SGML). Here is a document which contains a Postscript
<A HREF = "ftp://curia.ucc.ie/pub/sgml/p2sg.ps">Gentle Introduction to SGML</A> (via anonymous ftp)
It might be useful to read this before reading the following items.
<LI><A HREF = "http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/General/Internet/WWW/HTMLPrimer.html">A Beginner's Guide to HTML</A>.
<LI><A HREF = "http://kuhttp.cc.ukans.edu/lynx_help/HTML_quick.html">HTML Quick Reference</A>.
<LI>For those with a serious interest in HTML there is a
<A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/WWW/MarkUp/MarkUp.html">
wealth of material</A> provided by Dan Connolly of the
<A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/WWW/TheProject.html">W3 Consortium</A>,
one of the co-authors of the draft Internet standard on HTML. Amongst the items
he provides are pointers to the (draft)
<A HREF="ftp://ds.internic.net/internet-drafts/draft-ietf-html-spec-01.txt">HTML
standard</A> and the
<A HREF="http://www.w3.org/hypertext/WWW/MarkUp/html-spec/html.dtd">HTML
Document Type Definition</A>.
</UL>
<P>
It will also be useful to use your WWW browser to down-load a variety of documents and see how they are marked up. Basing your first HTML mark-up attempts on an existing document is not a bad way to start.
<P>
You can use a standard text editor to mark-up documents but there are a number
of tools becoming available which ease the process.
See the <A HREF = "http://www.boutell.com/faq/">World Wide
Web Frequently Asked Questions</A> document for pointers to such tools.
(Reports of experiences of with any tools will be gratefully received.
Please mail them to
<A HREF="mailto:www-support@ncs.nerc.ac.uk"><i>www-support@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</i></A>.)
<P>
When you think you have finished your HTML documents it would be wise
to check that they are valid HTML using one or more of the public validation
services -
</P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.cc.gatech.edu/grads/j/Kipp.Jones/HaLidation/validation-form.html">http://www.cc.gatech.edu/grads/j/Kipp.Jones/HaLidation/validation-form.html</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.unipress.com/weblint/index.html#form">http://www.unipress.com/weblint/index.html#form</A>
</UL>
<P>
You may also wish to join the mailing list <i>www-discuss@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</i> where you
can benefit from the experience of other NERC WWW users or share with them the benefit
of your experience. To join the list, mail a request to
<A HREF="mailto:www-discuss-request@ncs.nerc.ac.uk"><i>www-discuss-request@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</i></A>.
<P>
<LI>Which WWW server to use to publish your documents?
<P>
<A HREF = "/ncs/">NERC Computer Services</A>
operate servers on behalf of NERC institutes and itself.
Whether to mount your documents on one of those (and which) or whether to operate
your own is not a straight-forward question to answer. If the information is dynamically
derived from a database, for example, it will clearly make sense for the database and server
to co-located. If, on the other-hand, the information is static and requiring little or no maintenance, it may not matter from where it is served.
<P>
Your local NCS staff will be be pleased to discuss the options with you.
You may also mail
<A HREF="mailto:www-support@ncs.nerc.ac.uk"><i>www-support@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</i>
</A>for advice.
</P>
<LI>Once you have something that you'd like the world to know about, you may ask
<A HREF="mailto:www-support@ncs.nerc.ac.uk">www-support@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</A> to
announce them on NERC's <A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/#whats-new">What's
New</A> page. If you wish to announce a significant new service outside NERC
take a look at these suggestions for places to
<A HREF="announce.html">announce</A> your service.
</LI>
</UL>
<P>
The <A HREF = "http://sunsite.unc.edu/boutell/faq/www_faq.html">World Wide Web Frequently Asked Questions</A>
document is a very useful source of answers and pointers to other sources of information.
<P>
<BR>
<A HREF = "http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC  =
"/images/logoicon.gif" ALT="NERC" align=middle>To the NERC home page</A>
<HR>
<ADDRESS><A HREF = "mailto:www-support@ncs.nerc.ac.uk">www-support@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</A>
</ADDRESS>
