</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Publishing on the Internet</TITLE>
</HEAD>                               
<BODY>
<H1>
<IMG SRC="/images/ncs.gif" ALT="NERC" ALIGN=middle>
Publishing on the Internet</H1>
<HR>
<H2>Guidance for NCS Staff</H2>
<P>
This document provides guidance to NCS staff on the publication of information via the World Wide Web. In particular it deals with authority, appropriate use, appropriate content and the style of NCS publications. Although the focus is on WWW much of what is written applies to other methods of publication, such as Gopher, WAIS and anonymous ftp.
</P>
<P>
This guidance does not address use of WWW to find information on the Internet; it is solely
concerned with publication.
</P>
<P>
The <A HREF="info_mod.html">NCS Information Moderator</A> is responsible for policing this guidance and for any future
updating of this statement.
</P>
<h2>1. Justification</h2>
<P>
Any use of the WWW needs to be justified. That is not to say that approval needs to be obtainedfor each and every new document published but each document must be of a type for whichpublication has been sanctioned. If it is not then approval must be obtained before it is published.
</P>
<P>
NCS is a service organisation. Its <i>raison d'etre</i> is to provide a service to NERC and its other
customers. Use of the WWW should be seen in that context. If publication of a document or setof documents would benefit the service or is in support of a Service Level Agreement or a
Facilities Management Agreement then it probably should be done. If there is no benefit then itshould not be done.
</P>
<h2>2. Authority</h2>
<P>
Before publishing anything on behalf of NCS you must have obtained authority to do so from
your line management. Such authority will usually cover a defined class of information. Authority should be obtained afresh for something not in that class.
</P>
<P>
The <A HREF="info_mod.html">NCS Information Moderator</A> should be apprised of your intention to publish before you
prepare the material for publication.
</P>
<P>
NCS will not habitually prepare and/or publish documents on behalf of others in NERC unless
doing so in furtherance of an SLA or FMA.
</P>
<h2>3. Content</h2>
<P>
<b>3.1</b>  Information published by NCS should be done so in furtherance of the service provided
     by NCS. It will be perceived as an official publication of NCS and the tone and style of
     the content should reflect that. The tone should not be too informal or personal but neither
     should it be too formal. Remember that you are writing for an audience which includes
     the people who pay your wages and might include the Head of NCS, the Chief Executive
     of NERC and your next employer.
</P>
<P>
<b>3.2</b>  It should be clear in the document who the author is. Contact information should be given:
     e-mail address, telephone number, postal address as appropriate. If an e-mail address is
     given, provide an HTML <i>mailto</i> anchor.
</P>
<P>    
<b>3.3</b>  If the author is not the person who publishes the document, the person responsible for
     publishing the document should also be credited in the same way.
</P>
<P>    
<b>3.4</b>  It should go without saying that permission should be obtained from a document's author
     before it is published.
</P>
<P>    
<b>3.5</b>  Remember that most pictures, graphics, maps, other images  and music are protected by
     copyright. Permission must be obtained from the copyright holder or their agent before
     such items are used. The copyright holder should be acknowledged.
</P>
<P>     
<b>3.6</b>  If the on-line version of a document is not the master version of the document it is a good
     idea to make it clear where the original can be found. The on-line version should be kept
     in line with the original.
</P>
<P>     
<b>3.7</b>  Include in documents the date of last change.
</P>
<P>     
<b>3.8</b>  Establish a schedule for regularly checking on-line documents and either updating or
     removing any that are past their <i>best before</i> date. Consider including an expiry or best
     before date in your documents.
</P>
<P>     
<b>3.9</b>  Consider using an HTML-aware editor such as HoTMetaL to prepare HTML documents.
</P>
<P>     
<b>3.10</b> Check your HTML documents using one or more of the public validation services -
</P>
<UL>     
<LI><A HREF="http://www.hensa.ac.uk/html-val-svc/">http://www.hensa.ac.uk/html-val-svc/</A> 

 This uses the HENSA Unix Archive cache and should be quicker to use than the US equivalents.
<LI><A HREF="http://www.harbinger.net/html-val-svc/">http://www.harbinger.net/html-val-svc/</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.unipress.com/weblint/index.html#form">http://www.unipress.com/weblint/index.html#form</A>
</UL>
<P>          
<b>3.11</b> Don't include anything which might be construed as incitement to contravene the Computer Misuse Act, 
<A HREF="http://www.publications.hmso.gov.uk/hmso/document/Acts/00984035/dataprot.htm">
Data Protection Act</A> or other laws.
</P>
<P>     
<b>3.12</b> Don't be libellous; ensure that any facts concerning individuals or organisations are
     accurate and verifiable. Try to refrain from expressing opinions. Where opinions are
     expressed they must not be expressed in a way which damages the subject's reputation.
</P>
<P>     
<b>3.13</b> Don't include hyper-links or other pointers to obscene or pornographic material, or
     material which is otherwise offensive or illegal.
</P>
<P>     
<b>3.14</b> NCS business-sensitive information should not be visible
     outside NERC. It is easy to use WWW access control to prevent access from network
     addresses outside NERC; use it.
</P>
<P>     
<b>3.15</b> Remember that not everyone that uses the Internet is necessarily as law abiding or as well
     disposed toward NERC as you are. Avoid giving away information that will invite the
     attentions of thieves, animal rights activists and others who might wish to break into
     NERC sites and do damage to material or staff. Consider separating such sensitive
     information from non-sensitive information, which might be useful to a general readership,
     and limiting access to the former to addresses within NERC.
</P>
<P>     
<b>3.16</b> Advertisements for services or products should follow the same guidelines as used by the
     advertising industry; they should be <i>legal, decent, honest and truthful</i>.
</P>
<h2>4. Style</h2>
<P>     
<b>4.1</b>  Include in every NCS HTML document the NCS logo and a link to the NERC home page <A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/">
     (http://www.nerc.ac.uk/)</A>.
</P>
<P>     
<b>4.2</b>  Every NCS HTML document should contain at least one of -
</P>
<UL>
<LI>a link to the NCS home page
<A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/ncs/">(http://www.nerc.ac.uk/ncs/)</A></LI>
<LI>a link to the NCS site or section's home page.</LI>
</UL>
<P>    
<b>4.3</b>  Be sparing with the use of pictures and other images in HTML documents; they can
     consume a lot of bandwidth without adding significantly to the information content. Use
     'ALT' in 'IMG' elements to supply text alternatives for images. If a large image needs to
     be displayed, don't include it with the main text of a document but provide a separate link
     to it with an indication of the size of the image so that the reader can choose either to
     view or not view the image.
</P>
<P>     
<b>4.4</b>  Logos and similar images should be given <i>transparent grey</i> backgrounds: <i>transparent</i> so
     that, where a browser supports the feature, the image background adopts the browser's
     background colour; <i>grey</i> so that, where a browser does not support transparency, the
     image background has the same colour as the most common browser background colour.
</P>
<P>
<b>4.5</b>  Where a hyper-link is to a document which is subject to access control, make the
     restriction clear, so that someone following the link is not surprised when they receive an
     <i>access</i> denied message.
</P>
<P>     
<b>4.6</b>  After preparing an HTML document for publication but before publishing it, use several
     different browsers to view the document; you cannot assume that because it looks all right
     with the browser you use, it will necessarily look all right with other browsers. Ask
     someone off-site to view the document; this often highlights problems with anchors or
     image elements that appear to work when the author views the document.
</P>
<BR>
<A HREF = "http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC  =
"/images/logoicon.gif" ALT="NERC" align=middle>To the NERC home page</A>
