<HEAD>
<TITLE>Using a Proxy Server</TITLE>
</HEAD> 
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC="/images/nerc.gif"></H1>
<HR>
<H2>Using a Proxy Server</H2>
<P>Before Monday 26th September 1994, the <A HREF="http://www.hensa.ac.uk/"
>Higher Education National Software Archive (HENSA)</A> provided a <A HREF="http://www.hensa.ac.uk/mirror/"
>public <I>caching</I> service</A>.  This service has been discontinued
and replaced by a <A HREF="http://www.hensa.ac.uk/new.cache.html">public
<I>proxy</I> service</A>. The consequences of this are twofold -</P>
<OL>
<LI>Any URLs that you have in hotlists in your browser or elsewhere
which begin with <B>http://www.hensa.ac.uk/mirror/</B> should have that
part removed. For example, <XMP>http://www.hensa.ac.uk/mirror/http://ncsa.uiuc.edu/</XMP>
should be changed to <XMP>http://ncsa.uiuc.edu/</XMP></LI>
<LI>The new service has much the same purpose as the old cache but it
is invoked differently. To make use of it you must have a WWW browser
which can make use of proxy WWW servers, such as xmosaic. See <A HREF="http://www.hensa.ac.uk/new.cache.html"
>here</A> for instructions on setting up xmosaic to use the service.<P><B>
NB</B> Some documents on NERC WWW servers are subject to controls on
access which do not permit them to be read by anyone outwith NERC. An
attempt to read such documents via the HENSA proxy service will be
refused as the request will appear to originate from outside NERC.</P>
<P>Mosaic for Windows can be made to use the proxy service by adding
these lines to mosaic.ini (usually found in c:\windows) -</P><P></P>
<CODE>[proxy information]<BR>http_proxy=http://www.hensa.ac.uk/
<BR>ftp_proxy=http://www.hensa.ac.uk/
<BR>wais_proxy=http://www.hensa.ac.uk/
<BR>gopher_proxy=http://www.hensa.ac.uk/</CODE><P><B>NB</B> This does
not work on the 2.0a1 version of Mosaic for Windows nor, presumably, on
earlier verions.</P></LI>
</OL>
<ADDRESS>www-support@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</ADDRESS>
<P><A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC="/images/logoicon.gif" ALIGN="middle"
>To the NERC home page</A>
</P>
</BODY></HTML>
