<head>
<title>DEMA</title>
<meta name="CreatedBy" content="WP Internet Publisher 1.0 Beta B">
</head>
<body>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff><p>

<h1>DEMA</h1>
DEMA - Developmental Ecology of Marine Animals<p>

<p>

The Natural Environment Research Council has made available 2.6M for a thematic programme
in this area.  The research objectives of the programme are:<p>

 	to investigate the processes and mechanisms by which environmental variables, such as
temperature, salinity, oxygen, nutrients, and pollutants influence the development, early behaviour
and hence the phenotype of marine animals;<p>

 	to determine the long-term consequences of the interactions between the environment and
development at the organismal and population levels;<p>

 	to build capacity in the UK to undertake marine science using cellular, molecular and
genetic techniques by establishing expert centres.<p>

<p>

DEMA will focus on a limited number of taxa that are of economic importance in UK coastal
seas, or that are directly relevant models.  It is expected that cellular, molecular and genetic
approaches will feature strongly in the programme, and that a number of expert centres will be
supported in the fields of marine animal rearing and of molecular biology.  While cofunding of
projects by Industry or Government Agencies is not absolutely required, such cofunding will be
viewed favourably.<p>

<p>

DEMA forms part of JMERI, the Joint Marine Environmental Research Initiative, formed
between NERC, EPSRC and Industry.  Other components of JMERI are a NERC thematic
programme focusing on the processes that occur at the Benthic Boundary Layer of the deep
ocean (BENBO), and a programme cofunded with EPSRC and Industry to examine ways to
minimise the impact of offshore oil and gas activities (MIME).<p>

<p>

Two sorts of Application are invited:<p>

 	Research grants that are intended to address the research objectives above.  These
proposals may require infrastructural support in the form of shared facilities or expertise, for
example in larval rearing or molecular biology.<p>

<p>

 	Support for expert centres in larval rearing or in the provision of libraries of genomic and
cloned DNA.  While it is intended to strengthen the UK's ability in these areas, these centres will
be justified by the research needs expressed in the applications received.  Duplication of existing
facilities will be avoided.<p>

<p>

A Community Workshop will be held on 24th September 1996 in London, at which the
establishment of collaborative proposals will be encouraged and the provision of infrastructural
support in the form of expert centres may be guided by the research plans described.  Expert
reviews of existing facilities for larval rearing and for DNA library services will be presented, and
representatives of the perceived user community for this programme of research will be present. <p>

<p>

Places at the workshop are limited; those wishing to attend should complete and return an
expression of interest (available from Chris Baker, below) by 10th September 1996.  The
completed expressions of interest will be made available to all those attending the workshop.<p>

<p>

Research Grant applications should be made on standard NERC RG1 forms available from Nicky
Stevens below, marked DEMA Thematic Programme in the top right hand corner of the front
page.  All awards are subject to standard NERC terms and conditions.  The closing date for
applications is 31st October 1996. <p>

<p>

Application forms and the current NERC Research Grants Booklet are downloadable from the
Awards and Training Web Site (<a href="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/awards/grantapp.htm">http://www.nerc.ac.uk/awards/grantapp.htm</a>) or available
from:<p>

<p>

Mrs Nicky Stevens, Awards and Training Section, NERC, Polaris House, SWINDON, SN2 1EU;
Fax 01793 411616; email: n.stevens@nerc.ac.uk<p>

<p>

Scientific and other queries should be addressed to Dr Chris Baker, MSTB Secretariat, NERC,
Polaris House, SWINDON, SN2 1 EU; Phone 01793 411520; Fax 01793411545; email:
c.baker@nerc.ac.uk
</body>
