Section A<p>

<p>

GENERAL AIMS AND CONDITIONS<p>

<p>

1.   The aim of the NERC Research Fellowship scheme is to enable a small number of <p>

outstanding research workers to devote the majority of their time to research and to develop their<p>

potential to achieve recognised international reputations.<p>

<p>

Subject of Research<p>

<p>

2.   The subject proposed for research must be within the scientific areas mentioned within the<p>

NERC Mission (see Appendix A) and should provide scope for novel research.  A project which<p>

is essentially an extension of a candidate's earlier research will not normally be considered suitable<p>

for the award of a Fellowship.  It is accepted, however, that many proposals will have developed<p>

from earlier work.  NERC will not consider applications that fall within the remit of the other<p>

Research Councils.  Applications relating to borderline subjects should be discussed with one of<p>

the Research Councils in advance: candidates should not submit duplicate applications.  Proposals<p>

deemed more appropriate to another Research Council may be transferred after consultation with<p>

the applicant.<p>

<p>

General Principles<p>

<p>

3.   The NERC Research Fellowship scheme is highly prestigious and each category of<p>

Fellowship is run on an open competition basis utilising peer review procedures.  All shortlisted<p>

candidates will be subject to interview.<p>

<p>

4.   Applications are accepted and awards made on the understanding that institutions and<p>

Fellows agree to observe the regulations set out in this booklet and any changes made thereafter.<p>

<p>

5.   Whilst NERC is concerned to ensure that the research resulting from Fellowships<p>

represents good value for money, NERC accepts no liability in respect of matters arising out of<p>

the conduct of such research, nor any liability concerning the application of research results.<p>

<p>

6.   Awards are not made to relieve a research or educational institution of any part of the<p>

expenditure which it would otherwise incur, or to cover staff shortages.  <p>

<p>

7.   All categories of Fellows funded by NERC, will have available to them a recurrent grant<p>

to support small items of equipment, consumables, as well as conference attendance and<p>

fieldwork.  This expenditure must relate directly to the Fellowship.  Equipment purchased during<p>

the Fellowship becomes the property of the host institution once the Fellowship has finished,<p>

unless otherwise stated by NERC.<p>

<p>

8.   Awards are made on the presumption that there are adequate facilities to carry out the<p>

proposed research.  Requests to upgrade laboratories to accommodate Fellowships will not be<p>

considered.<p>

<p>

<p>

General Conditions<p>

<p>

9.   Postdoctoral and Advanced Fellowships must commence between 1 June and 30<p>

September in the year the award is offered.   Senior and Professorial Fellowships may start at any<p>

time within one year of the announcement of award.<p>

<p>

10.  Holders of awards will be expected to devote their full working time to research, not<p>

taking part in routine teaching or administrative duties.  <p>

<p>

Eligibility<p>

<p>

11.  There are no fixed age limits for entry into the Fellowship scheme other than those<p>

associated with normal career stage expectations.  Full consideration will be given to applicants<p>

returning to science following a career break or where the candidate has come late to Higher<p>

Education.  However, such consideration will be subject to the requirement that there should be<p>

substantial career time ahead of the Fellow.  Applications for Postdoctoral Research Fellows and<p>

Advanced Research Fellows may be given on a full or part-time basis.    Under approved<p>

arrangements up to 2 years (or 1 year in the case of Postdoctoral Research Fellows) of any 5 year<p>

Fellowship period can be spent with a collaborative institution within any EU member state or<p>

overseas.<p>

<p>

a)   Eligibility for Postdoctoral and Advanced Research Fellows<p>

<p>

     Candidates for Postdoctoral Research Fellows and Advanced Research Fellows must hold<p>

a PhD.  Applications for Postdoctoral Research Fellows may be accepted from PhD students but,<p>

if successful, awards may not start until NERC has received written confirmation of the outcome<p>

of the applicant's PhD viva.  However, applicants are advised that some post-PhD experience will<p>

be a distinct advantage when seeking a Postdoctoral Research Fellowship. <p>

<p>

b)   Eligibility for Senior Research Fellows and Research Professors<p>

<p>

     Candidates should hold a PhD/DPhil or have equivalent and substantial research<p>

experience as well as having a proven international reputation.  They should possess a successful<p>

record of securing NERC research grant funding and/or equivalent support gained in open<p>

competition.  Candidates should also have demonstrated their capability to act as research team<p>

leaders.<p>

<p>

     Successful candidates will be expected to demonstrate their ability to win NERC or other<p>

UK Research Council grant support on a continuing basis.  Such success in open competition will<p>

be an important consideration when applying for any extension to the original award.<p>

     <p>

Residence Eligibility for Postdoctoral and Advanced Research Fellows. <p>

<p>

12.  Candidates must at the date of application for an award:<p>

<p>

     (a)  be ordinarily resident in the United Kingdom, the Channel Islands and the Isle of<p>

Man and<p>

<p>

<p>

     (b)  have a relevant connection with the United Kingdom, the Channel Islands or the<p>

Isle of Man.<p>

<p>

13.  A relevant connection under 12(b) above will be established where:<p>

<p>

     (a)  the candidate has been ordinarily resident in the United Kingdom the Channel<p>

Islands and the Isle of Man throughout the 3 year period preceding the date of application for an<p>

award, and<p>

<p>

     (b)  the candidate has not been so resident during any part of that 3 year period, wholly<p>

or mainly for the purpose of receiving full-time education.<p>

<p>

14.  For the purposes of residence eligibility, a period of ordinary residence will not be treated<p>

as being interrupted by an absence which is caused by:<p>

<p>

     (a)  the temporary absence abroad, by reasons of training or employment, of the<p>

candidate, the candidate's spouse or parents or<p>

<p>

     (b)  the temporary full-time education abroad of the candidate or spouse.  Periods of<p>

more than five years cannot be considered as being temporary.<p>

<p>

15.  A candidate who is a refugee or the spouse or child of a refugee will be eligible for an<p>

award if at the date of application the refugee:<p>

<p>

     (a)  is ordinarily resident in the United Kingdom and<p>

     <p>

     (b)  has not been ordinarily resident outside the United Kingdom since being<p>

recognised as a refugee or granted asylum.<p>

<p>

16.  A candidate shall be exempted from the requirements of paragraphs 12 to 15 above if:<p>

<p>

     (a)  he/she is eligible for an award by virtue of Article 7(2) or (3) or Article 12 of<p>

Council Regulations (EEC) No 1612/68 on freedom of movement for workers within the<p>

community, (from 1 January 1994 migrant workers who are nationals of Iceland, Norway and<p>

Liechtenstein will enjoy the same rights as migrant workers who are nationals of Member States<p>

of the EC within the European Economic area), and<p>

<p>

     (b)  he/she would have a relevant connection with the European Community, Iceland,<p>

Norway and Liechtenstein if the references to the United Kingdom in paragraphs 12 to 15 above<p>

had been references to the European Community, Iceland,  Norway and Liechtenstein.<p>

<p>

17.  Candidates are responsible for providing all relevant information that might be required in<p>

assessing their eligibility for an award.  Withholding relevant or giving misleading information may<p>

lead to the rejection of an application.<p>

<p>

18.  In cases of doubt as to eligibility, the candidate should contact NERC's Awards and<p>

Training Section.<p>

<p>

<p>

Principal Place of Research and Collaborative Research<p>

<p>

19.  Fellowships may be held at Higher Education Institutions, government-funded research<p>

institutes or other research institutes in the UK acceptable to NERC.  The term "host institution"<p>

will be used throughout the remainder of this booklet to indicate the principal place of research.<p>

<p>

20.  A Fellowship should not normally be held at an institution where the candidate received<p>

postgraduate or previous training unless the institution provides unique facilities or opportunities<p>

which are not available elsewhere in the UK.<p>

<p>

21.  Fellowships may not be held overseas but up to two years of any 5 year (or 1 year of a 3<p>

year Postdoctoral Research Fellowship) period can be spent within a collaborative  institution<p>

subject to prior agreement with NERC and with the institutions concerned.  In addition Fellows<p>

may, subject to NERC's agreement, undertake fieldwork overseas during their award, providing<p>

their base and main place of work is in the UK.<p>

<p>

22.  If any period(s) of research at either a UK or overseas collaborative institution is planned<p>

during the award, full details of the location and duration of such proposed research should be<p>

given.  Where extended periods of research are planned at collaborative institutions, a letter of<p>

support from the host institution should accompany the application.  Particular attention should be<p>

given to the benefits (research experience, training, techniques etc) to be gained and linking these<p>

to the experience to be acquired in the host institution.  The host institution's conditions of service<p>

regarding employees working abroad will apply to the collaborative component of the award.   No<p>

additional cost of living allowance will be payable but travel costs will be provided if the candidate<p>

intends to spend more than a six month continuous period abroad.<p>

<p>

Employment Status<p>

<p>

23.  The host institution is expected to act as employer of all categories of NERC Fellows and<p>

to make the appointment in accordance with local arrangements in relation to:<p>

<p>

          level of salary  (but see paragraphs 33,57,92,127)<p>

<p>

          making the necessary deductions of superannuation contributions.<p>

<p>

          deducting employees national insurance contributions.<p>

<p>

          deducting tax under Schedule E by means of the PAYE procedures.<p>

<p>

24.  The host institution's normal conditions of service will apply to Fellows, except where<p>

expressly indicated below.  Host institutions will be expected to provide Fellows with a formal<p>

statement of their terms and conditions, which will incorporate these points.<p>

<p>

a)   Maternity Leave<p>

<p>

     The host institution, as employer, will be expected to extend its normal maternity leave<p>

provisions to all Fellows.<p>

<p>

     Host institutions should note that in the event of pregnancy, NERC may place the award<p>

in abeyance for up to six months and the Fellow will receive full pay during this period. <p>

Thereafter she may return on a flexible working arrangement to suit her domestic needs. Men<p>

holding a Fellowship will be entitled to take up to four week paternity leave to support their<p>

partner.<p>

<p>

b)   Superannuation<p>

<p>

     If requested, NERC will supplement Fellows' awards, within an approved limit, to cover<p>

payments to a personal pension plan, operated by a recognised insurance company or similar<p>

organisation.<p>

<p>

c)   Health and Safety<p>

<p>

     NERC places great importance on health and safety and it will be a condition of any award<p>

that both the host institution and the Fellow fully accept their responsibilities under all relevant<p>

legislation.  NERC accepts no liability for any illness, injury or accident which occurs during the<p>

period of a Fellow's award.<p>

<p>

     Fellows should establish with the host institution what cover is provided for them in terms<p>

of medical insurance, particularly during any periods of fieldwork, including overseas fieldwork.<p>

<p>

d)   Teaching<p>

<p>

     Postdoctoral Research and Advanced Research Fellows may undertake an average of up<p>

to 6 hours teaching or demonstrating per week, without deduction from the value of their award<p>

provided their head of department considers it desirable and that it will not hinder their research. <p>

No other type of paid work may be undertaken within the Fellowship.<p>

<p>

e)   Research Grants and Studentships<p>

<p>

     All NERC Fellows may apply for research grants in accordance with the normal<p>

regulations and conditions, which require applications to be supported by the host institution.  It<p>

should be noted that Fellowships are awarded on the presumption that there are adequate<p>

resources available for the research proposed and that a Fellowship does not carry with it the<p>

assurance that a research grant will be awarded.  Eligibility of host institutions for the receipt of<p>

research grants should be discussed with NERC's  Awards and Training Section, prior to<p>

application. <p>

<p>

     Applications are accepted and awards made only when there is adequate time for the<p>

completion of the research grant during the tenure of the Fellowship, excluding the period of<p>

extension.<p>

<p>

     Postdoctoral Research Fellows and Advanced Research Fellows may also be named as<p>

joint supervisors on research studentship proposals.  NERC Senior Research Fellows and<p>

Research Professors may apply for research studentships as sole supervisors.<p>

<p>

f)   Removal Expenses<p>

<p>

     NERC is unable to provide assistance with removal expenses incurred by Research<p>

Fellows on taking up an award or during their tenure.<p>

<p>

g)   Staff Appraisal<p>

<p>

     It is expected that host institutions carry out regular appraisals of all recipients of<p>

Fellowship awards.  Such monitoring appraisals will normally be undertaken under the regulations<p>

and mechanisms of the host institution and enable the department and Fellow to form the best<p>

possible assessment of, and feedback on, the individuals's performance and future development.<p>

Such appraisal should include consideration of in-service training requirements, career guidance<p>

and personal development. <p>

<p>

     The appraisal system must be accompanied by proper reporting systems which will enable<p>

the department (and NERC if necessary) to track the progress and achievements of Fellows.  It<p>

will be incumbent on the department to notify NERC where the outcome of any appraisal is<p>

deemed to be unsatisfactory.<p>

<p>

h)   Termination of Awards<p>

<p>

     Fellows whose progress or conduct fails to satisfy NERC are liable to have their awards<p>

discontinued.  If a Fellow discontinues his research or takes up other employment before <p>

     the end of the award, NERC must be informed immediately.  Fellows are also obliged to<p>

refund any overpayments. <p>

<p>

     Should the host institution decide to terminate the employment of a Fellow they are<p>

expected to notify NERC of the reason for this.<p>

<p>

Subsequent Employment<p>

<p>

25.  Fellows are obliged to send to NERC, for statistical purposes, brief details of the posts<p>

they take up on termination of their Fellowships.<p>

<p>

Starting Dates<p>

<p>

26.  Postdoctoral and Advanced Fellowships must commence between 1 June and 30<p>

September in the year the award is offered.   Senior and Professorial Fellowships may start at any<p>

time within one year of  the announcement of award.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>Section B</b><p>

<p>

<b>P<a name="post"></a>OSTDOCTORAL RESEARCH FELLOWSHIPS</b><p>

<p>

Eligibility<p>

<p>

27.  Applicants should posses a PhD in a basic science subject and would normally be expected<p>

to have a minimum of one year's postdoctoral experience. There are no fixed age limits but it is<p>

expected that most applicants will be in the 26-35 age range and should not hold tenured posts at<p>

the time of application.<p>

<p>

Application and Closing Date<p>

<p>

28.  Applications should be made on form RF1, obtainable from NERC Awards and Training<p>

Section.   A recommendation is required, on form RF2, from the head of department where<p>

candidates obtained their PhD.  An additional form RF2 should be completed by:<p>

<p>

     a)   heads of departments where candidates carried out any postdoctoral work either in<p>

the UK or overseas, and <p>

     <p>

     b)   heads of departments in the UK where candidates last studied, if their PhD was<p>

obtained overseas.<p>

<p>

     Applicants are also required to nominate two personal referees who can provide academic<p>

support in respect of the applicant's abilities and promise as an independent researcher.  The<p>

referees should be asked to complete form RF3 and to send it directly  to NERC.<p>

<p>

29.  Applications must be accompanied by two copies of a case for support.<p>

<p>

     The supporting case must not exceed 8 sides of A4, (inclusive of figures and<p>

references), and be of single spaced typescript.  Minimum font size to be used should be 12 point<p>

although references can be presented in a smaller font size provided it is sufficiently clear to<p>

ensure good quality reproductions.  Photo-reduced type must not be used.  Ideally colour should<p>

not be used in the supporting case, if it is essential, ten copies of the supporting case must be<p>

provided.<p>

<p>

     In addition to the eight page supporting case, there must be an executive summary that<p>

does not exceed one side of A4 and can be easily understood by non-experts.  The remainder of<p>

the case should detail the candidate's past and proposed research.  It should be clear what<p>

influenced the choice of department in terms of expertise or facilities.  If candidates have been at<p>

the same institution both as an undergraduate and a postgraduate and do not intend to move now,<p>

the reason should be clearly stated.  If there is a likelihood of the need to undertake overseas<p>

fieldwork during the Fellowship, this must be stated in the case for support and a realistic estimate<p>

of costs included.  In addition, copies of any abstracts and a list of publications, but not the<p>

publications themselves, should also be submitted.<p>

<p>

     Candidates are invited to nominate two or more referees for the application.  They should<p>

not be collaborators and NERC reserves the right not to approach them.  Full postal addresses<p>

should be provided.<p>

<p>

30.  The closing date for applications is 30 September each year.  Any application which does<p>

not comply to the specifications detailed in paragraph 29 will rejected.  Applications will normally<p>

be assessed within 2-3 months of receipt, after which shortlisted candidates will be required to<p>

attend an interview. No telephone interviews will be conducted  nor can  alternative interview<p>

dates be arranged.  Reasonable travel costs will be reimbursed to candidates who attend<p>

interviews. <p>

<p>

Period of Award<p>

<p>

31.  Postdoctoral Research Fellowships are tenable, on a full-time basis, for periods of up to<p>

three years in the first instance and for equivalent periods on a part-time basis.<p>

<p>

32.  Applications to extend existing Fellowships, for up to no more than five years support in<p>

total, may be considered during the third year (see paragraph 46). <p>

<p>

Value of Award<p>

<p>

33.  The host institution will determine the appropriate salary level for the Fellow.  NERC will<p>

reimburse the host institution for salary, employer's superannuation and national insurance costs. <p>

The level of reimbursement will be based on the UK universities non-clinical academic and related<p>

research staff scale with the starting salary related to the Fellow's age when taking up<p>

appointment, up to a maximum of the Age 30 point on the scale. Increments and nationally agreed<p>

pay awards will also be reimbursed.<p>

<p>

Recurrent Grant<p>

<p>

34.  Up to 7,000 per annum is available to Postdoctoral Research Fellows for all conference<p>

attendance, UK fieldwork and the purchase of small items of equipment and consumables.   <p>

35.  Fieldwork is defined as activity undertaken away from the Fellow's normal place of<p>

research for the purpose of making observations, collecting data or specimens necessary for their<p>

research.  NERC does not guarantee reimbursement for overseas fieldwork unless the requirement<p>

was explicitly stated, and its cost realistically estimated, in the research topic for which the Fellow<p>

was accepted.<p>

<p>

36.  Small items of equipment and consumables, up to an individual cost of 1000 may be<p>

purchased as and when required without prior approval.  Reimbursement should be claimed<p>

retrospectively on form FR1, available from the administrative offices at the host institution. <p>

Copies of receipts, invoices and/or university accounting statements should be attached to the<p>

FR1 form.<p>

<p>

37.  For items with an individual value of more than 1000, prior approval should be sought. <p>

The case for purchase should explain what the item is, why it is needed and the price. <p>

Reimbursement should be requested on form FR1, as above.<p>

<p>

38.  NERC is able to send payment for equipment direct to the university departments or<p>

supplying companies if so directed by the Fellow.  Further copies of form FR1 can be obtained<p>

from the Awards and Training Section, NERC.  <p>

<p>

<p>

39.  Equipment purchased during the Fellowship becomes the property of the host institution<p>

once the Fellowship has finished, unless otherwise stated by NERC.  <p>

<p>

Administrative Costs<p>

<p>

40.  Host institutions will be paid a research training support grant of 1000 pa in order to<p>

provide some direct assistance in meeting basic departmental costs incurred by Fellows (eg,<p>

telephones, fax, photocopying and stationery).<p>

<p>

41.  Bench fees or similar costs will not be paid by NERC.<p>

<p>

Overseas Fieldwork and Collaboration<p>

<p>

42.  No claims may be made for fieldwork or collaborative research done outside the period of<p>

the award.<p>

<p>

43.  Fellows should, with the support of their head of department,  submit their estimates for<p>

overseas fieldwork and collaborative visits using form EE1.  NERC recognises that travel and<p>

subsistence costs associated with working overseas will vary over time as well as between and<p>

within countries.  Such uncertainties and variation mean that it is difficult to apply a globally<p>

applicable rate.  NERC has adopted a general rule that local travel and subsistence on all<p>

Fellowships requiring overseas fieldwork, should attract a per diem rate of 50.  This does not<p>

apply where Fellows are undertaking extended research at a collaborative institution under agreed<p>

arrangements.  Requirements above this figure, which will be reviewed regularly, need to be fully<p>

justified in the case for support.  Fellows will not be reimbursed for air or sea fares unless such<p>

travel has been agreed by NERC in advance.  Claims to cover the cost of travel, medical or<p>

vehicle insurance, visas or foreign currency exchange will not be met.<p>

<p>

44.  Claims for reimbursement should be submitted on form FW1 (available from the<p>

administration offices of host institutions) no later than three months after expenditure has been<p>

incurred.  NERC cannot make advance payments for fieldwork expenses.  However, by prior<p>

agreement NERC will accept a travel agent's invoice for an air or sea fare.<p>

<p>

45.  Any extended period of work in a collaborative institution within the UK or overseas is<p>

not expected to take place until after the first or second year of an award.  Agreed claims for<p>

reimbursement of travel costs (including local travel) should be made as identified in  paragraph<p>

43 above.<p>

<p>

Reports and Applications for Extension<p>

<p>

46.  Applications from Postdoctoral Fellows requesting an extension to their initial three year's<p>

support will be dealt with at the February Training Awards Forum meeting.  Owing to the<p>

substantial funding commitment in awarding an extension, all applications will be assessed in<p>

competition with new applications for Fellowships.  The closing date for applications for<p>

extensions for Postdoctoral awards is 30 September and announcements will be made at the end<p>

of February.  Fellows should bear in mind the timing of these events in relation to the end date of<p>

their existing award if they are to secure continuity of support.<p>

<p>

47.  The application for extension should be submitted on form RF1 (forms RF2 and RF3 need<p>

not be completed) and should include a supporting case for extension of no more than eight sides<p>

of A4, including references and figures.   The application should show what has been achieved<p>

and what work is planned for the extension. The following headings, or similar are advised;<p>

<p>

     - Original objectives of investigation and any changes.<p>

     - Development of methods and techniques.<p>

     - Summary of results, with examples of data.<p>

     - Interpretation of results, conclusions and outcomes.<p>

     - Future lines of research.<p>

<p>

     The report should be submitted together with any papers prepared for publication or<p>

published during the award, although these are regarded as a supplement rather than an alternative<p>

to the report. <p>

<p>

48.  If no extension is sought or the Fellow is unsuccessful in applying for an extension, then a<p>

final report should be submitted upon termination of the award and in any case not later than three<p>

months after the end of the award.  This report should be of similar detail and content to that<p>

requested in paragraph 47 above.<p>

<p>

49.  Both extension and final reports will be submitted to independent referees for comment. <p>

The Fellow is invited to nominated two or more referees for the reports.  The referees should not<p>

be collaborators and NERC reserves the right not to approach them.  Full postal addresses need<p>

to be provided.  Publications will only be forwarded to referees if requested by the referees<p>

themselves.  <p>

<p>

     Non-submission will result in the Fellow being made ineligible for future NERC grants or<p>

awards.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>Section C</b><p>

<p>

<a name="RF"><b>ADVANCED RESEARCH FELLOWSHIPS</b></a><p>

<p>

<b>Purpose</b><p>

<p>

50.  NERC awards a small number of Advanced Research Fellowships tenable in the UK. <p>

Their purpose is to support outstanding research workers of proven ability and having a high<p>

potential to develop into team leaders of international standing, but who do not hold tenured<p>

posts at the time of application.<p>

<p>

Eligibility<p>

<p>

51.  Candidates must hold a PhD/D.Phil and have had at least two years' research experience at<p>

postdoctoral level, not necessarily in the UK, at the time of application.  They must also have<p>

proved their ability as independent research workers.  There are no fixed age limits but it is<p>

expected that most applicants will be in the 28-40 age range and should not hold tenured posts at<p>

the time of application.  Applicants returning to science following a career break will also be<p>

considered.<p>

<p>

Application and Closing Date<p>

<p>

52.  Applications should be made on form RF1, obtainable from NERC Awards and Training<p>

Section.  A recommendation is required, on form RF2, from the candidate's current head of<p>

department plus an additional form RF2 should be completed by the candidate's previous head of<p>

department<p>

<p>

     Applicants are also required to nominate two personal referees who can provide academic<p>

support in respect of the applicant's abilities and promise as an independent researcher.  The<p>

referees should be asked to complete form RF3 and to send it directly  to NERC.<p>

<p>

53.  Applications must be accompanied by two copies of a case for support.<p>

<p>

     The supporting case must not exceed 8 sides of A4, (inclusive of figures and<p>

references), and be of single spaced typescript.  Minimum font size to be used should be 12 point<p>

although references can be presented in a smaller font size provided it is sufficiently clear to<p>

ensure good quality reproductions.  Photo-reduced type must not be used.  Ideally colour should<p>

not be used in the supporting case, if it is essential, ten copies of the supporting case must be<p>

provided.<p>

<p>

     In addition to the eight page supporting case, there must be an executive summary that<p>

does not exceed one side of A4 and can be easily understood by non-experts.  The remainder of<p>

the case should detail the candidate's past and proposed research.  It should be clear what<p>

influenced the choice of department in terms of expertise or facilities.  If candidates have been at<p>

the same institution both as an undergraduate and a postgraduate and do not intend to move now,<p>

the reason should be clearly stated.  If there is a likelihood of the need to undertake overseas<p>

fieldwork during the Fellowship, this must be stated in the case for support and a realistic estimate<p>

of costs included.  In addition, copies of any abstracts and a list of publications, but not the<p>

publications themselves, should also be submitted.<p>

<p>

     Candidates are invited to nominate two or more referees for the application.  They should<p>

not be collaborators and NERC reserves the right not to approach them.  Full postal addresses<p>

should be provided.<p>

<p>

54.  The closing date for applications is 30 September each year.  Any application which does<p>

not comply to the specifications detailed in paragraph 53 will be rejected.  Applications will<p>

normally be assessed within 2-3 months of receipt, after which shortlisted candidates will be<p>

required to attend an interview. No telephone interviews will be conducted  nor can  alternative<p>

interview dates be arranged.  Reasonable travel costs will be reimbursed to candidates who attend<p>

interviews. <p>

<p>

Period of Award<p>

<p>

55.  Advanced Research Fellowships are normally held on a full-time basis for periods of up to<p>

five years in the first instance but applications for part-time Fellowships will be considered. <p>

Extensions beyond five years to a maximum of a further five years may also be considered.  Note<p>

paragraph 75.<p>

<p>

56.  Where an applicant requests and is thought suitable for five years' support, awards will be<p>

made initially for three years on the expectation that the remaining two years will be confirmed<p>

following NERC's acceptance of a fully satisfactory third year report.  <p>

<p>

Value of Award<p>

<p>

57.  The host institution will determine the appropriate salary level for the Fellow.  NERC will<p>

reimburse the host institution for salary, employer's superannuation and national insurance costs. <p>

The level of reimbursement will be based on the UK universities non-clinical academic and related<p>

research staff scale with the starting salary related to the Fellow's age when taking up<p>

appointment.  Increments, up to the Age 35 point, and nationally agreed pay awards will also be<p>

reimbursed.<p>

<p>

Recurrent Grant    <p>

<p>

58.  Up to 8,000 per annum is available to Research Fellows for all conference attendance,<p>

UK fieldwork and the purchase of small items of equipment and consumables.   <p>

<p>

59.  Advanced Research Fellows may be allowed to spend up to 20,000 of their recurrent<p>

allocation in the first year, this allocation being proportionally reduced thereafter. This should be<p>

discussed with the Awards and Training Section.<p>

<p>

60.  Fieldwork is defined as activity undertaken away from the Fellow's normal place of<p>

research for the purpose of making observations, collecting data or specimens necessary for their<p>

research.  NERC does not guarantee reimbursement for overseas fieldwork unless the requirement<p>

was explicitly stated, and its cost realistically estimated, in the research topic for which the Fellow<p>

was accepted.<p>

<p>

61.  Small items of equipment and consumables, up to an individual cost of 1000 may be<p>

purchased as and when required without prior approval.  Reimbursement should be claimed<p>

retrospectively on form FR1, available from the administrative offices at the host institution. <p>

Copies of receipts, invoices and/or university accounting statements should be attached to the<p>

FR1 form.<p>

<p>

62.  For items with an individual value of more than 1000, prior approval should be sought. <p>

The case for purchase should explain what the item is, why it is needed and the price. <p>

Reimbursement should be requested on form FR1, as above.<p>

<p>

63.  NERC is able to send payment for equipment direct to the university departments or<p>

supplying companies if so directed by the Fellow.  Further copies of form FR1 can be obtained<p>

from the Awards and Training Section, NERC.  <p>

<p>

64.  Equipment purchased during the Fellowship becomes the property of the host institution<p>

once the Fellowship has finished, unless otherwise stated by NERC.  <p>

<p>

Administrative Costs<p>

<p>

65.  Host institutions will be paid a research training support grant of 1000 pa in order to<p>

provide some direct assistance in meeting basic departmental costs incurred by Fellows (eg,<p>

telephones, fax, photocopying and stationery).<p>

<p>

66.  Bench fees or similar costs will not be paid by NERC.<p>

<p>

Overseas Fieldwork and Collaboration<p>

<p>

67.  No claims may be made for fieldwork or collaborative research done outside the period of<p>

the award.<p>

<p>

68.  Fellows should, with the support of their head of department,  submit their estimates for<p>

overseas fieldwork and collaborative visits using form EE1.  NERC recognises that travel and<p>

subsistence costs associated with working overseas will vary over time as well as between and<p>

within countries.  Such uncertainties and variation mean that it is difficult to apply a globally<p>

applicable rate.  NERC has adopted a general rule that local travel and subsistence on all<p>

Fellowships requiring overseas fieldwork, should attract a per diem rate of 50.  This does not<p>

apply where Fellows are undertaking extended research at a collaborative institution under agreed<p>

arrangements.  Requirements above this figure, which will be reviewed regularly, need to be fully<p>

justified in the case for support.  Fellows will not be reimbursed for air or sea fares unless such<p>

travel has been agreed by NERC in advance.  Claims to cover the cost of travel, medical or<p>

vehicle insurance, visas or foreign currency exchange will not be met.<p>

<p>

69.  Claims for reimbursement should be submitted on form FW1 (available from the<p>

administration offices of host institutions) no later than three months after expenditure has been<p>

incurred.  NERC cannot make advance payments for fieldwork expenses.  However, by prior<p>

agreement NERC will accept a travel agent's invoice for an air or sea fare.<p>

<p>

70.  Any extended period of work in a collaborative institution within the UK or overseas is<p>

not expected to take place until after the first or second year of an award. Agreed claims for<p>

reimbursement of travel costs (including local travel) should be made as identified in  paragraph<p>

68 above.<p>

<p>

Reports<p>

<p>

71.  Advanced Fellows are required to submit a third year report of no more than 8 sides of<p>

A4 (inclusive of tables or figures) not later than six months from the end of their third year.  This<p>

should show what has been achieved and what work is planned during years four and five of the<p>

Fellowship.  The following headings, or similar are advised;<p>

<p>

     - Original objectives of investigation and any changes.<p>

     - Development of methods and techniques.<p>

     - Summary of results, with examples of data.<p>

     - Interpretation of results, conclusions and outcomes.<p>

     - Future lines of research.<p>

<p>

     The report should be submitted together with any papers prepared for publication or<p>

published during the award, although these are regarded as a supplement rather than an alternative<p>

to the report. <p>

<p>

72.  A final report should be submitted upon termination of the award and in any case not later<p>

than three months after the end of the award.  This report should be of similar detail and content<p>

to that requested in the above paragraph.<p>

<p>

73.  Third year and final reports will be submitted to independent referees for comment.  The<p>

Fellow is invited to nominated two or more referees for the reports.  The referees should not be<p>

collaborators and NERC reserves the right not to approach them.  Full postal addresses need to<p>

be provided.  Publications will only be forwarded to referees if requested by the referees<p>

themselves.<p>

<p>

74.  Non-submission of final reports will result in the Fellow being made ineligible for future<p>

NERC grants or awards.<p>

<p>

Applications for Extension<p>

<p>

75.  Applications from Advanced Fellows requesting an extension to their initial five years'<p>

support will be dealt with at the February Training Awards Forum meeting.  Owing to the<p>

substantial funding commitment in awarding an extension, all applications will be assessed in<p>

competition with new applications for Fellowships.  The closing date for applications for<p>

extensions for Advanced awards is 30 September and announcements will be made at the end of<p>

February.  Fellows should bear in mind the timing of these events in relation to the end date of<p>

their existing award if they are to secure continuity of support.<p>

<p>

76.  The application for extension should be submitted on form RF1 (forms RF2 and RF3 need<p>

not be completed) and should include a supporting case for extension of no more than eight sides<p>

of A4, including references and figures.  Copies of abstracts of relevant papers should be attached,<p>

but not the papers themselves.<p>

<p>

77.  An extension beyond the initial five years is dependent on an agreement that the HEI will<p>

provide a permanent appointment for the Fellow within a further five years.  It is accepted that a<p>

binding arrangement may not be possible; however, NERC needs to be convinced that such an<p>

outcome is likely before making any additional commitment to the Fellow, and the Fellow's head<p>

of department is required to provide a letter giving the HEI's view of such  future employment.<p>

<p>

<p>

78.  If no extension is sought or the Fellow is unsuccessful in applying for an extension, then a<p>

final report should be submitted upon termination of the award and in any case not later than three<p>

months after the end of the award.  This report should be of similar detail and content to that<p>

requested in paragraph 71 above.<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>Section D</b><p>

<b><p>

SENIOR RESEARCH FELLOWSHIPS</b><p>

<p>

<a name="srf"><b>Purpose</b></a><p>

<p>

79.  The intention of the Senior Research Fellowship scheme is to enable proven outstanding<p>

researchers of international standing at mid/peak career level to devote themselves to personal<p>

research.<p>

<p>

Eligibility<p>

<p>

80.  Candidates should hold a PhD/DPhil or have equivalent and substantial research<p>

experience as well as having a proven international reputation.  They should possess a successful<p>

record of securing NERC research grant funding and/or equivalent support gained in open<p>

competition.  Candidates should also have demonstrated their capability to act as research team<p>

leaders.<p>

<p>

81.  Successful candidates will be expected to demonstrate their ability to win NERC or other<p>

UK Research Council grant support on a continuing basis.  Such success in open competition will<p>

be an important consideration both in the assessment of the original applications and when<p>

applying for any extension to the original award.<p>

<p>

82.  Holders of awards will be expected to devote their full working time to research, not<p>

taking part in routine teaching or administrative duties.  Senior Research Fellowships must<p>

commence within one year of the announcement of award. <p>

<p>

83.  There are no fixed age limits for Senior Research Fellows although there should be a<p>

substantive career time ahead of the candidates.  Applications are especially welcome from<p>

candidates who are either not yet established within the Higher Education system or who are<p>

intending to use the Fellowship as a means of (re-)establishing themselves in the United Kingdom<p>

perhaps following a period overseas.    <p>

<p>

84.  Applications from tenured staff will only be considered on condition that they revert to<p>

their established post on completion of a single five year award; no renewal applications beyond<p>

this period will be considered.  Where candidates for these awards are already occupying tenured<p>

UK academic posts, the institution will be expected to appoint a replacement in the same subject<p>

area throughout the period of the award.  Should the Fellow withdraw from the award, other than<p>

to revert to the tenured post, NERC will negotiate with the institution to ensure that the fixed<p>

term appointee is not disadvantaged by the premature termination of the award.<p>

<p>

Residence Eligibility<p>

<p>

85.  There are no restrictions on the residence or nationality of candidates for Senior Research<p>

Fellowships.  Candidates must however comply with Department of Employment requirements<p>

and hold a work permit where appropriate. <p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

Application and Closing Date<p>

<p>

86.  Applications should be made on form SF1, obtainable from NERC Awards and Training<p>

Section.  An SF2  form should be completed by the candidate's current head of department who is<p>

requested to provide detail of the proposed relationship between the applicant and the host<p>

institution and also giving an indication of how the applicant and their work will fit into the<p>

department (and Faculty) research profile and future planned activities.<p>

     <p>

87.  Applicants are also asked to nominate two personal referees who can provide support in<p>

respect of the candidate's research standing and future potential. The referees should be asked to<p>

complete form SF3 and send it directly to NERC.<p>

<p>

88.  Applications must be accompanied by two copies of a case for support.<p>

<p>

     The supporting case must not exceed 8
 sides of A4, (inclusive of figures and<p>

references), and be of single spaced typescript.  Minimum font size to be used should be 12 point<p>

although references can be presented in a smaller font size provided it is sufficiently clear to<p>

ensure good quality reproductions.  Photo-reduced type must not be used.  Ideally colour should<p>

not be used in the supporting case, if it is essential, ten copies of the supporting case must be<p>

provided.<p>

<p>

     In addition to the eight page supporting case, there must be an executive summary that<p>

does not exceed one side of A4 and can be easily understood by non-experts.  The remainder of<p>

the case should detail the candidate's past and proposed research.  It should be clear what<p>

influenced the choice of department in terms of expertise or facilities.  If candidates have been at<p>

the same institution both as an undergraduate and a postgraduate and do not intend to move now,<p>

the reason should be clearly stated.  If there is a likelihood of the need to undertake overseas<p>

fieldwork during the Fellowship, this must be stated in the case for support and a realistic estimate<p>

of costs included.  In addition, copies of any abstracts and a list of publications, but not the<p>

publications themselves, should also be submitted.<p>

<p>

     Candidates are invited to nominate two or more referees for the application.  They should<p>

not be collaborators and NERC reserves the right not to approach them.  Full postal addresses<p>

should be provided.<p>

<p>

89.  All applications will be considered by a Special Selection Panel and shortlisted candidates<p>

invited for interview during February/early March.<p>

<p>

90.  The closing date for applications is 30 September each year.  Any application which does<p>

not comply to the specifications detailed in paragraph 88 will be rejected.  Applications will<p>

normally be assessed within 2-3 months of receipt, after which shortlisted candidates will be<p>

required to attend an interview. No telephone interviews will be conducted  nor can  alternative<p>

interview dates be arranged.  Reasonable travel costs will be reimbursed to candidates who attend<p>

interviews. <p>

<p>

Period of Award<p>

<p>

91.  Senior Research Fellowships will be normally held on a full-time basis for periods of up to<p>

five years in the first instance.  Extensions beyond five years to a maximum of a further five years<p>

may be considered.<p>

<p>

Value of Award<p>

<p>

92.  The host institution will determine the appropriate salary level for the Fellow.  NERC will<p>

reimburse the host institution for salary, employer's superannuation and national insurance costs. <p>

The level of reimbursement will be based on the UK Universities non-clinical academic and related<p>

research staff scale. Consideration will be given to reimbursing additional increments above the<p>

"norm" for exceptional experience and inclusion of future "merit" pay.  Increments and nationally<p>

agreed pay awards will also be reimbursed.<p>

<p>

Recurrent Grant<p>

<p>

93.  Up to 10,000 per annum is available to Research Fellows for all conference attendance,<p>

UK fieldwork and the purchase of small items of equipment and consumables.   <p>

<p>

94.  Senior Research Fellows may be allowed to spend up to 25,000 of their recurrent grant<p>

allocation in the first year, this allocation being proportionally reduced thereafter. This should be<p>

discussed with the Awards and Training Directorate.<p>

<p>

95.  Fieldwork is defined as activity undertaken away from the Fellow's normal place of<p>

research for the purpose of making observations, collecting data or specimens necessary for their<p>

research.  NERC does not guarantee reimbursement for overseas fieldwork unless the requirement<p>

was explicitly stated, and its cost realistically estimated, in the research topic for which the Fellow<p>

was accepted.<p>

<p>

96.  Small items of equipment and consumables, up to an individual cost of 1000 may be<p>

purchased as and when required without prior approval.  Reimbursement should be claimed<p>

retrospectively on form FR1, available from the administrative offices at the host institution. <p>

Copies of receipts, invoices and/or university accounting statements should be attached to the<p>

FR1 form.<p>

<p>

97.  For items with an individual value of more than 1000, prior approval should be sought. <p>

The case for purchase should explain what the item is, why it is needed and the price. <p>

Reimbursement should be requested on form FR1, as above.<p>

<p>

98.  NERC is able to send payment for equipment direct to the university departments or<p>

supplying companies if so directed by the Fellow.  Further copies of form FR1 can be obtained<p>

from the Awards and Training Section, NERC.  <p>

<p>

99.  Equipment purchased during the Fellowship becomes the property of the host institution<p>

once the Fellowship has finished, unless otherwise stated by NERC.  <p>

<p>

Administrative Costs<p>

<p>

100.      Host institutions will be paid a research training support grant of 1000 in order to<p>

provide some direct assistance in meeting basic departmental costs incurred by Fellows (eg,<p>

telephones, fax, photocopying and stationery).<p>

<p>

101. Bench fees or similar costs will not be paid by NERC.<p>

<p>

<p>

Overseas Fieldwork and Collaboration<p>

<p>

102. No claims may be made for fieldwork or collaborative research done outside the period of<p>

the award.<p>

<p>

103. Fellows should, with the support of their head of department,  submit their estimates for<p>

overseas fieldwork or collaborative visits using form EE1.  NERC recognises that travel and<p>

subsistence costs associated with working overseas will vary over time as well as between and<p>

within countries.  Such uncertainties and variation mean that it is difficult to apply a globally<p>

applicable rate.  NERC has adopted a general rule that local travel and subsistence on all<p>

Fellowships requiring overseas fieldwork, should attract a per diem rate of 50.  This does not<p>

apply where Fellows are undertaking extended research at a collaborative institution under agreed<p>

arrangements.  Requirements above this figure, which will be reviewed regularly, need to be fully<p>

justified in the case for support.  Fellows will not be reimbursed for air or sea fares unless such<p>

travel has been agreed by NERC in advance.  Claims to cover the cost of travel, medical or<p>

vehicle insurance, visas or foreign currency exchange will not be met.<p>

<p>

104. Claims for reimbursement should be submitted on form FW1 (available from the<p>

administration offices of host institutions) no later than three months after expenditure has been<p>

incurred.  NERC cannot make advance payments for fieldwork expenses.  However, by prior<p>

agreement NERC will accept a travel agent's invoice for an air or sea fare.<p>

<p>

105. Any extended period of work in a collaborative institution within the UK or overseas is<p>

not expected to take place until after the first or second year of an award. Agreed claims for<p>

reimbursement of travel costs (including local travel) should be made as identified in  paragraph<p>

103 above.<p>

<p>

Reports<p>

<p>

106. An interim report must be submitted at the end of the third year, not exceeding eight sides<p>

of A4 inclusive of tables and diagrams. This should provide a factual summary of the work<p>

completed to date, details of grants and other funding/awards secured, studentships supervised,<p>

publications as well as other outcomes achieved.  A brief outline of the programme of research<p>

planned for the remainder of the award should also be given.<p>

<p>

107. Senior Research Fellows seeking an extension of their award will be required to submit a<p>

further report of no more than 8 sides A4, exclusive of tables and figures, not later than six<p>

months before the end of their award.  This should be of the same detail as the interim report<p>

identifying achievements and outcomes, with a description of work planned for the extension<p>

period.  The report should be submitted with any papers prepared for publication or published<p>

during the award.<p>

<p>

108. If no extension is sought or the Fellow is unsuccessful in applying for an extension, then a<p>

final report should be submitted upon termination of the award and in any case no later than three<p>

months after the end of the award.  This report should be of similar detail and content to that<p>

requested in paragraph 107 above, but omitting reference to work planned for the extension stage.<p>

<p>

109. Both interim and final reports will be submitted to independent referees for comment.  The<p>

Fellow is invited to nominated two or more referees for the reports.  The referees should not be<p>

collaborators and NERC reserves the right not to approach them.  Full postal addresses need to<p>

be provided.  Publications will only be forwarded to referees if requested by the referees<p>

themselves.<p>

<p>

110. Fellows are reminded that the late submission of reports will result in delay in assessment<p>

of applications for extension.  <p>

<p>

     Non-submission of final reports will result in the Fellow being made ineligible for future<p>

NERC grants or awards.<p>

<p>

Applications for Extension<p>

<p>

111. Applications for extension should be included with the Fellow's report, not later than six<p>

months before the end of the original five year award. Applications should follow the outline<p>

given in paragraph 107 above.<p>

<p>

112. A statement from the head of department should accompany the extension application<p>

confirming the continued research potential of the applicant and the relevance of the past and<p>

proposed research directions to departmental research strategy.<p>

<p>

113. An extension beyond the initial five years is dependent on an agreement that the HEI will<p>

provide a permanent appointment for the Fellow within a further five years.  It is accepted that a<p>

binding arrangement may not be possible; however, NERC needs to be convinced that such an<p>

outcome is likely before making any additional commitment to the Fellow, and the Fellow's head<p>

of department is required to provide a letter giving the host institution's view of future<p>

employment.<p>

<p>

114. Applications will be assessed in competition with new applications for Senior Research<p>

Fellows. The closing date for such extension applications is 30 September and they will be<p>

considered by a special Selection Panel in the following January.<p>

<p>

     Fellows should bear in mind the timing of these events in relation to the end date of their<p>

existing award if they are to secure continuity of support.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

Section E<p>

<p>

<a name="rprof"><b>RESEARCH PROFESSORSHIPS</b></a><p>

<p>

Purpose<p>

<p>

115. The Research Professorship scheme is intended to provide an expectation of secure, long<p>

term support for outstanding research scientists having well established international reputations<p>

and who wish to devote themselves entirely to personal research.<p>

<p>

Eligibility<p>

<p>

116. Candidates should hold a PhD/DPhil or have equivalent and substantial research<p>

experience as well as having a proven international reputation.  They should possess a successful<p>

record of securing research grant funding and/or equivalent support gained in open competition. <p>

Candidates should also have demonstrated their capability to act as research team leaders.<p>

<p>

117. Successful candidates will be expected to demonstrate their ability to win NERC or other<p>

UK Research Council grant support on a continuing basis.  Such success in open competition will<p>

be an important consideration when applying for any extension to the original award.<p>

<p>

118. Holders of awards will be expected to devote their full working time to research, not<p>

taking part in routine teaching or administrative duties.   Research Professorships must commence<p>

within one year of the announcement of the award.<p>

<p>

119. There are no fixed age limits for Research Professors although there should be a<p>

substantive career time ahead of the candidates.  Applications are especially welcome from<p>

candidates who are either not yet established within the Higher Education system or who are<p>

intending to use the Fellowship as a means of (re-)establishing themselves in the United Kingdom<p>

perhaps following a period overseas.    <p>

<p>

120. Nominations from tenured staff will only be considered on condition that they revert to<p>

their established post on completion of a single five year award; no renewal applications beyond<p>

this period will be considered.  Where candidates for these awards are already occupying tenured<p>

UK academic posts, the institution of tenure will be expected to appoint a replacement in the same<p>

subject area throughout the period of the award.  Should the Professor withdraw  from the award,<p>

other than to revert to the tenured post at the end of the award, NERC will negotiate with the<p>

institution to ensure that the fixed term appointee is not disadvantaged by the premature<p>

termination of the award.<p>

<p>

Residence Eligibility<p>

<p>

121. There are no restrictions on the residence or nationality of candidates for Research<p>

Professorships.  Candidates must however comply with Department of Employment requirements<p>

and hold a work permit where appropriate. <p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

Application and Closing Date<p>

<p>

122. The normal route for candidates to be considered for a NERC Research Professorship will<p>

be through nomination by the Vice-Chancellor or Pro-Vice Chancellor of the host institution<p>

where the candidate is to be based.<p>

<p>

123. The nomination should be accompanied by the following:<p>

<p>

     (a)  confirmation that the nomination will command full support within the institution.<p>

<p>

     (b)  a statement of what the institution is prepared to provide in order to make the<p>

appointment a success eg in terms of research facilities, support services etc.,  as well as detail of<p>

any proposed collaborative arrangements with external institutions or laboratories.<p>

<p>

     (c)  details of the proposed relationship between the nominee and the host department<p>

with information on how the nominee and their proposed work will fit into the institution and<p>

department research portfolio and future research strategies.<p>

<p>

     (d)  a full CV and full publication listing for the nominee together with a summary of<p>

research achievements, grant and other funding support previously obtained as <p>

          well as details of past postgraduate training supervision and team research<p>

leadership experience.<p>

<p>

     (e)  detail of the proposed research activity to be undertaken by the nominee during the<p>

period of the award, including relevant information on expected team building research and<p>

external collaboration.  This detail should not exceed 8 sides of A4 (inclusive of figures and<p>

references) and be of single spaced typescript.  Minimum font size to be used should be 12 point;<p>

photo-reduced type must not be used.<p>

<p>

     (f)  three external referees should also be nominated who are able to provide an<p>

independent assessment of the nominee's research standing and future potential.<p>

<p>

124. The closing date for applications is 30 September each year.  Any application which does<p>

not comply to the specifications detailed in paragraph 123 will be rejected.  Applications will<p>

normally be assessed within 2-3 months of receipt, after which shortlisted candidates will be<p>

required to attend an interview. No telephone interviews will be conducted  nor can  alternative<p>

interview dates be arranged.  Reasonable travel costs will be reimbursed to candidates who attend<p>

interviews. <p>

<p>

Period of Award<p>

<p>

125. Research Professorships will normally be held on a full-time basis for a period of five years<p>

in the first instance with extension for a further three years subject to satisfactory progress and<p>

achievement.  Holders who originally possessed an established or tenured post prior to their initial<p>

award will not be eligible for any extension.<p>

<p>

126. Applications to extend existing Research Professorships beyond an initial eight year period<p>

will be considered for a further two years but at reduced 50% and 25% funding levels <p>

<p>

     respectively. Such extension applications will also require agreement with the host<p>

institution of the provision of a permanent appointment at the end of the extension period, see<p>

paragraph 147.<p>

<p>

Value of Award<p>

<p>

127. NERC will reimburse the host institution for salary, employer's superannuation and<p>

national insurance costs.  The level of reimbursement will be based on the local institution<p>

Professorship scale and related to age and experience when taking up appointment. Consideration<p>

will be given to reimbursing additional increments above the "norm" for exceptional experience<p>

and inclusion of future "merit" pay.  Increments and nationally agreed pay awards will also be<p>

reimbursed.<p>

<p>

Recurrent Grant<p>

<p>

128. Up to 10,000 per annum is available to Research Professors for all conference<p>

attendance, UK fieldwork and the purchase of small items of equipment and consumables.   <p>

129. Research Professors may be allowed to spend up to 35,000 of their recurrent grant<p>

allocation in the first year, this allocation being proportionally reduced thereafter. This should be<p>

discussed with the Awards and Training Directorate.<p>

<p>

130. Fieldwork is defined as activity undertaken away from the Fellow's normal place of<p>

research for the purpose of making observations, collecting data or specimens necessary for their<p>

research.  NERC does not guarantee reimbursement for overseas fieldwork unless the requirement<p>

was explicitly stated, and its cost realistically estimated, in the research topic for which the Fellow<p>

was accepted.<p>

<p>

131. Small items of equipment and consumables, up to an individual cost of 1000 may be<p>

purchased as and when required without prior approval.  Reimbursement should be claimed<p>

retrospectively on form FR1, available from the administrative offices at the host institution. <p>

Copies of receipts, invoices and/or university accounting statements should be attached to the<p>

FR1 form.<p>

<p>

132. For items with an individual value of more than 1000, prior approval should be sought. <p>

The case for purchase should explain what the item is, why it is needed and the price. <p>

Reimbursement should be requested on form FR1, as above.<p>

<p>

133. NERC is able to send payment for equipment direct to the university departments or<p>

supplying companies if so directed by the Fellow.  Further copies of form FR1 can be obtained<p>

from the Awards and Training Section, NERC.  <p>

<p>

134. Equipment purchased during the Fellowship becomes the property of the host institution<p>

once the Fellowship has finished, unless otherwise stated by NERC.  <p>

<p>

Administrative Costs<p>

<p>

135.      Host institutions  will be paid a research training support grant of 1000 pa in order to<p>

provide some direct assistance in meeting basic departmental costs incurred by Fellows (eg,<p>

telephones, fax, photocopying and stationery).<p>

<p>

136. Bench fees or similar costs will not be paid by NERC.<p>

<p>

Overseas Fieldwork and Collaboration<p>

<p>

137. No claims may be made for fieldwork or collaborative research done outside the period of<p>

the award.<p>

<p>

138. Fellows should, with the support of their head of department,  submit their estimates for<p>

overseas fieldwork or collaborative visits using form EE1.  NERC recognises that travel and<p>

subsistence costs associated with working overseas will vary over time as well as between and<p>

within countries.  Such uncertainties and variation mean that it is difficult to apply a globally<p>

applicable rate.  NERC has adopted a general rule that local travel and subsistence on all<p>

Fellowships requiring overseas fieldwork, should attract a per diem rate of 50.  This does not<p>

apply where Fellows are undertaking extended tenure at a collaborative institution under agreed<p>

arrangements.  Requirements above this figure, which will be reviewed regularly, need to be fully<p>

justified in the case for support.  Fellows will not be reimbursed for air or sea fares unless such<p>

travel has been agreed by NERC in advance.  Claims to cover the cost of travel, medical or<p>

vehicle insurance, visas or foreign currency exchange will not be met.<p>

<p>

139. Claims for reimbursement should be submitted on form FW1 (available from the<p>

administration offices of host institutions) no later than three months after expenditure has been<p>

incurred.  NERC cannot make advance payments for fieldwork expenses.  However, by prior<p>

agreement NERC will accept a travel agent's invoice for an air or sea fare.<p>

<p>

140. Any extended period of work in a collaborative institution within the UK or overseas is<p>

not expected to take place until after the first or second year of an award. Agreed claims for<p>

reimbursement of travel costs (including local travel) should be made as identified in  paragraph<p>

138 above.<p>

<p>

Reports<p>

<p>

141. An interim report must be submitted at the end of the third year, not exceeding eight sides<p>

of A4 inclusive of tables and diagrams. This should provide a factual summary of the work<p>

completed to date, details of grants and other funding/awards secured, studentships supervised,<p>

publications as well as other outcomes achieved.  A brief outline of the programme of research<p>

planned for the remainder of the award should also be given.<p>

<p>

142. Research Professors seeking a further three year extension to their original award will be<p>

required to submit a further report of not more than eight sides A4, inclusive of tables and figures,<p>

not later than three months from the end of their award.  This should be of the same detail as the<p>

interim report identifying achievements and outcomes, with a description of work planned for the<p>

extension period.  The report should be submitted with any papers prepared for publication or<p>

published during the award.<p>

<p>

143. If no extension is sought or the Fellow is unsuccessful in applying for an extension, then a<p>

final report should be submitted upon termination of the award and in any case not later than six<p>

months after the end of the award.  This report should be of similar detail and content to that<p>

requested in paragraph 142 above, but omitting reference to work planned for the extension<p>

period.<p>

<p>

144. Both interim and final reports will be submitted to independent referees for comment.  The<p>

Fellow is invited to nominated two or more referees for the reports.  The referees should not be<p>

collaborators and NERC reserves the right not to approach them.  Full postal addresses need to<p>

be provided.  Publications will only be forwarded to referees if requested by the referees<p>

themselves.<p>

<p>

145. Fellows are reminded that the late submission of reports will result in delay in assessment<p>

of applications for extension.  <p>

<p>

     Non-submission of final reports will result in the Fellow being made ineligible for future<p>

NERC grants or awards.<p>

<p>

Applications for Extension<p>

<p>

146. Applications for extension should be included with the Research Professors' report, not<p>

later than six months before the end of the original five year award. Applications should follow<p>

the outline given in paragraph 142 above and will be assessed in open competition with new<p>

applications.<p>

<p>

147. A statement from the Vice-Chancellor or Pro-Vice Chancellor of the host institution<p>

should accompany the extension application confirming the continued research potential for the<p>

applicant and the relevance of the past and proposed research directions to departmental and<p>

institutional research strategy. The statement should also give an indication of the institutions<p>

view of the future employment prospects of the applicant and the likelihood of securing an<p>

established, tenured post at the end of the extension award period.<p>

<p>

148. The closing date for such extension applications is 30 September and they will be<p>

considered by a special Selection Panel in the following January.  Research Professors should bear<p>

in mind the timing of these events in relation to the end date of their existing award if they are to<p>

secure continuity of support.<p>

<p>

149. A further two year extension period beyond the initial eight years can also be considered<p>

but at a reducing funding rate of 50% and 25% for the two year period.  Such extensions will also<p>

require a firm agreement by the host institution of a permanent tenured appointment for the<p>

Research Professor at the end of the further two year extension period.<p>

<p>

<p>

Section F <p>

<p>

<a name="rfell"><b>RETURNER FELLOWSHIPS</b></a><p>

<p>

Purpose<p>

<p>

150. Charge and dynamism is vital in science and technology; constant attention is needed to<p>

keep in touch with the latest developments.  A scientist who drops out, even briefly, can easily<p>

become a permanent loss to the national resource base.  The aim of this scheme is to enable<p>

high-level environmental scientists to return to their professions following a career break.<p>

<p>

General Principals<p>

<p>

151. The NERC Research Fellowship schemes are highly prestigious and each category of<p>

Fellowship is run on an open competition basis utilising peer review procedures.  All shortlisted<p>

candidates will be subject to interview.<p>

<p>

152. Applications are accepted and awards made on the understanding that institutions and<p>

Fellows agree to observe the regulations set out in this booklet and any changes made thereafter.<p>

<p>

153. Whilst NERC is concerned to ensure that the research resulting from Fellowships<p>

represents good value for money, NERC accepts no liability in respect of matters arising out of<p>

the conduct of such research, nor any liability concerning the application of research results.<p>

<p>

154. Awards are not made to relieve a research or educational institution of any part of the<p>

expenditure which it would otherwise incur, or to cover staff shortages.  <p>

<p>

155. All categories of Fellows funded by NERC, will have available to them a recurrent grant<p>

to support small items of equipment, consumables, as well as conference attendance and<p>

fieldwork.  This expenditure must relate directly to the Fellowship.  Equipment purchased during<p>

the Fellowship becomes the property of the host institution once the Fellowship has finished,<p>

unless otherwise stated by NERC.<p>

<p>

156. Awards are made on the presumption that there are adequate facilities to carry out the<p>

proposed research.  Requests to upgrade laboratories to accommodate Fellowships will not be<p>

considered.<p>

<p>

157. Holders of awards will be expected to devote their full working time to research, not<p>

taking part in routine teaching or administrative duties.  <p>

<p>

Eligibility<p>

<p>

158. Applicants should possess a PhD in a basic science subject and would normally be<p>

expected to have had previous research experience at postdoctoral level, not necessarily in the<p>

UK.  They should have clear evidence of their ability to function as independent research workers<p>

and of their potential to achieve long term recognised, international reputations.  There are no<p>

fixed age limits but candidates will be required to provide evidence of a substantial future<p>

potential career in environmental science.  Preference will be given to proposals having arranged<p>

 placement' periods in collaboration with industry, government departments or other external<p>

agencies. <p>

<p>

Principal Place of Research<p>

<p>

159. Fellowships may be held at Higher Education Institutions, government-funded research<p>

institutes or other research institutes in the UK acceptable to NERC.  The term "host institution"<p>

is used throughout this booklet to indicate the principal place of research.<p>

<p>

160. A Fellowship should not normally be held at an institution where the candidate received<p>

postgraduate or previous training unless the institution provides unique facilities or opportunities<p>

which are not available elsewhere in the UK.<p>

<p>

Employment Status<p>

<p>

161. The host institution is expected to act as employer of all categories of NERC Fellows and<p>

to make the appointment in accordance with local arrangements in relation to:<p>

<p>

          level of salary  (but see paragraph 168)<p>

<p>

          making the necessary deductions of superannuation contributions.<p>

<p>

          deducting employees national insurance contributions.<p>

<p>

          deducting tax under Schedule E by means of the PAYE procedures.<p>

<p>

162. The host institution's normal conditions of service will apply to Fellows, except where<p>

expressly indicated below.  Host institutions will be expected to provide Fellows with a formal<p>

statement of their terms and conditions, which will incorporate these points.<p>

<p>

a)   Maternity Leave<p>

<p>

     The host institution, as employer, will be expected to extend its normal maternity leave<p>

provisions to all Fellows.<p>

<p>

     Host institutions should note that in the event of pregnancy, NERC may place the award<p>

in abeyance for up to six months and the Fellow will receive full pay during this period. <p>

Thereafter she may return on a flexible working arrangement to suit her domestic needs. Men<p>

holding a Fellowship will be entitled to take up to four week paternity leave to support their<p>

partner.<p>

<p>

b)   Superannuation<p>

<p>

     If requested, NERC will supplement Fellows' awards, within an approved limit, to cover<p>

payments to a personal pension plan, operated by a recognised insurance company or similar<p>

organisation.<p>

<p>

<p>

c)   Health and Safety<p>

<p>

     NERC places great importance on health and safety and it will be a condition of any award<p>

that both the host institution and the Fellow fully accept their responsibilities under all relevant<p>

legislation.  NERC accepts no liability for any illness, injury or accident which occurs during the<p>

period of a Fellow's award.<p>

<p>

     Fellows should establish with the host institution what cover is provided for them in terms<p>

of medical insurance, particularly during any periods of fieldwork, including overseas fieldwork.<p>

<p>

d)   Teaching<p>

<p>

     Fellows may undertake an average of up to 6 hours teaching or demonstrating per week,<p>

without deduction from the value of their award provided their head of department considers it<p>

desirable and that it will not hinder their research.  No other type of paid work may be undertaken<p>

within the Fellowship.<p>

<p>

e)   Removal Expenses<p>

<p>

     NERC is unable to provide assistance with removal expenses incurred by Research<p>

Fellows on taking up an award or during their tenure.<p>

<p>

g)   Staff Appraisal<p>

<p>

     It is expected that host institutions carry out regular appraisals of all recipients of<p>

Fellowship awards.  Such monitoring appraisals will normally be undertaken under the regulations<p>

and mechanisms of the host institution and enable the department and Fellow to form the best<p>

possible assessment of, and feedback on, the individuals's performance and future development.<p>

Such appraisal should include consideration of in-service training requirements, career guidance<p>

and personal development. <p>

<p>

     The appraisal system must be accompanied by proper reporting systems which will enable<p>

the department (and NERC if necessary) to track the progress and achievements of Fellows.  It<p>

will be incumbent on the department to notify NERC where the outcome of any appraisal is<p>

deemed to be unsatisfactory.<p>

<p>

h)   Termination of Awards<p>

<p>

     Fellows whose progress or conduct fails to satisfy NERC are liable to have their awards<p>

discontinued with one month's notice.  Similarly, if a Fellow discontinues his research or takes up<p>

other employment before the end of the award, NERC must be given one month's written notice. <p>

Fellows are obliged to refund any overpayments. <p>

<p>

     Should the host institution decide to terminate the employment of a Fellow they are<p>

expected to notify NERC of the reason for this.<p>

<p>

Application and Closing Date<p>

<p>

163. Applications should be made on form RTF1, obtainable from NERC Awards and Training<p>

Section.   A recommendation is required, on form RTF2, from the current head of department in<p>

the host institution who is requested to comment on the career and employment prospects of the<p>

applicant, and also giving an indication of how the applicant and their work will fit into the<p>

department research activity.<p>

<p>

     Applicants are also asked to nominate two personal referees who can provide support in<p>

respect of the candidate's research standing and future potential.  The referees should be asked to<p>

complete form RTF3 and to send it directly  to NERC.<p>

<p>

164. Applications must be accompanied by two copies of a case for support.<p>

<p>

     The supporting case must not exceed 8 sides of A4, (inclusive of figures and<p>

references), and be of single spaced typescript.  Minimum font size to be used should be 12 point<p>

although references can be presented in a smaller font size provided it is sufficiently clear to<p>

ensure good quality reproductions.  Photo-reduced type must not be used.  Ideally colour should<p>

not be used in the supporting case, if it is essential, ten copies of the supporting case must be<p>

provided.<p>

<p>

     In addition to the eight page supporting case, there must be an executive summary that<p>

does not exceed one side of A4 and can be easily understood by non-experts.  The remainder of<p>

the case should detail the candidate's past research activities and proposed work schedule for the<p>

duration of the Fellowship award.  The  returner' year can be used for retraining, updating, skill<p>

enhancement, new research project initiation or other appropriate activity or mix of activities.  It<p>

is expected that the Fellow will be making key contacts within the academic world as well as<p>

among potential external employers during the period of the award.<p>

<p>

     In addition, copies of any abstracts and a list of publications, but not the publications<p>

themselves, should also be submitted.<p>

<p>

     Candidates are invited to nominate two referees for the application.  They should not be<p>

collaborators or associated with the host institution in any way and NERC reserves the right not<p>

to approach them.  Full postal addresses should be provided.<p>

<p>

165. The closing date for applications is 30 September each year.  Any application which does<p>

not comply to the specifications detailed in paragraph 164 will rejected.  Applications will<p>

normally be assessed within 2-3 months of receipt, after which shortlisted candidates will be<p>

required to attend an interview. No telephone interviews will be conducted  nor can  alternative<p>

interview dates be arranged.  Reasonable travel costs will be reimbursed to candidates who attend<p>

interviews. <p>

<p>

Period of Award<p>

<p>

166. Returner Fellowships are tenable for one year duration on a full time basis or for an<p>

equivalent period on a part time basis.  No extensions to the award will be considered.<p>

<p>

Starting Dates<p>

<p>

167. Fellowships must commence between 1 June and 30 September in the year the award is<p>

offered.  <p>

<p>

<p>

Value of Award<p>

<p>

168. The host institution will determine the appropriate salary level for the Fellow.  NERC will<p>

reimburse the host institution for salary, employer's superannuation and national insurance costs. <p>

The level of reimbursement will be based on the UK universities non-clinical academic and related<p>

research staff scale with the starting salary related to the Fellow's age when taking up<p>

appointment.   Nationally agreed pay awards will be reimbursed.<p>

<p>

Recurrent Grant<p>

<p>

169. Up to 5,000 per annum is available to Returner  Fellows for all conference attendance,<p>

UK fieldwork and the purchase of small items of equipment and consumables.   <p>

<p>

170. Fieldwork is defined as activity undertaken away from the Fellow's normal place of<p>

research for the purpose of making observations, collecting data or specimens necessary for their<p>

research.  NERC does not guarantee reimbursement for overseas fieldwork unless the requirement<p>

was explicitly stated, and its cost realistically estimated, in the research topic for which the Fellow<p>

was accepted.<p>

<p>

171. Small items of equipment and consumables, up to an individual cost of 1000 may be<p>

purchased as and when required without prior approval.  Reimbursement should be claimed<p>

retrospectively on form FR1, available from the administrative offices at the host institution. <p>

Copies of receipts, invoices and/or university accounting statements should be attached to the<p>

FR1 form.<p>

<p>

172. For items with an individual value of more than 1000, prior approval should be sought. <p>

The case for purchase should explain what the item is, why it is needed and the price. <p>

Reimbursement should be requested on form FR1, as above.<p>

<p>

173. NERC is able to send payment for equipment direct to the university departments or<p>

supplying companies if so directed by the Fellow.  Further copies of form FR1 can be obtained<p>

from the Awards and Training Section, NERC.  <p>

<p>

174. Equipment purchased during the Fellowship becomes the property of the host institution<p>

once the Fellowship has finished, unless otherwise stated by NERC.  <p>

<p>

Administrative Costs<p>

<p>

175.      Host institutions will be paid a research training support grant of 1000 pa in order to<p>

provide some direct assistance in meeting basic departmental costs incurred by Fellows (eg,<p>

telephones, fax, photocopying and stationery).<p>

<p>

176. Bench fees or similar costs will not be paid by NERC.<p>

<p>

Overseas Fieldwork<p>

<p>

177. No claims may be made for fieldwork done outside the period of the award.<p>

<p>

178. Fellows should, with the support of their head of department,  submit their estimates for<p>

overseas fieldwork and collaborative visits using form EE1.  NERC recognises that travel and<p>

subsistence costs associated with working overseas will vary over time as well as between and<p>

within countries.  Such uncertainties and variation mean that it is difficult to apply a globally<p>

applicable rate.  NERC has adopted a general rule that local travel and subsistence on all<p>

Fellowships requiring overseas fieldwork, should attract a per diem rate of 50.  Fellows will not<p>

be reimbursed for air or sea fares unless such travel has been agreed by NERC in advance.  Claims<p>

to cover the cost of travel, medical or vehicle insurance, visas or foreign currency exchange will<p>

not be met.<p>

<p>

179. Claims for reimbursement should be submitted on form FW1 (available from the<p>

administration offices of host institutions) no later than three months after expenditure has been<p>

incurred.  NERC cannot make advance payments for fieldwork expenses.  However, by prior<p>

agreement NERC will accept a travel agent's invoice for an air or sea fare.<p>

<p>

180. A final report not exceeding more than eight sides of A4 (inclusive of tables and figures),<p>

should be submitted upon termination of the award and in any case not later than three months<p>

after the end of the award.  The report should identify what has been achieved during the period<p>

of the award and what job training and likely employment opportunities have emerged as a result<p>

of the Fellowship<p>

<p>

181. The final report will be submitted to independent referees for comment.  The Fellow is<p>

invited to nominate two or more referees for the report.  The referees should not be collaborators<p>

and NERC reserves the right not to approach them.  Full postal addresses need to be provided. <p>

Publications will only be forwarded to referees if requested by the referees themselves.<p>

<p>

     Non-submission will result int he Fellow being made ineligible for future NERC grants or<p>

awards.<p>

<p>

Subsequent Employment<p>

<p>

182. Fellows are obliged to send to NERC, for statistical purposes, brief details of the posts<p>

they take up on termination of their Fellowships.<p>

<p>

<p>

Section G<p>

<p>

PUBLICITY <p>

<p>

Publication of Work<p>

<p>

183. All Fellows are expected to publish the results of their research in the appropriate journals. <p>

They are, however, invited to consult NERC if other arrangements seem desirable, eg, in a case<p>

where a project involving cooperation with industry has not previously been agreed.  All<p>

published papers should acknowledge support received from NERC by use of the Fellowship<p>

reference number.<p>

<p>

184. NERC reserves the right of access to all unpublished papers, records, or collections<p>

resulting from the work carried out under a Fellowship, some of which may be required to be<p>

deposited with NERC.  Similarly NERC reserves the right to use information on the outcome of<p>

Fellowships elsewhere to report on achievements, eg, in Annual reports, Corporate Plans etc.<p>

<p>

185. NERC reviews regularly its support, both direct and indirect, for universities and other<p>

institutions of higher education.  NERC may require detailed information on the results of the<p>

work funded by Fellowships to be used for its scientific and financial audit procedures.<p>

<p>

Public Understanding of Science<p>

<p>

186. NERC is keen to increase public understanding and public awareness of science and has an<p>

expectation that Fellows will take an active role in promoting and developing this policy.  NERC<p>

Fellows are therefore encouraged to take part in national or local initiatives focused on promoting<p>

public understanding of science. <p>

<p>

Data Availability<p>

<p>

187. It is NERC policy to increase the visibility and awareness of environmental data and to<p>

improve their management as an overall resource.  Fellows should therefore make sure that<p>

NERC Designated Data Centres are aware of significant datasets generated, or to be compiled,<p>

under the award so that their long term stewardship can be assured or planned.<p>

Section H<p>

<p>

PATENT RIGHTS<p>

<p>

188. Scientific research gives rise to inventions such as new devices, materials or processes,<p>

ideas, know-how and other results.  Such results may be classified as intellectual property - a term<p>

often used in connection with exploitation.  It is NERC's policy that any such results which are <p>

obtained in the course of research that it supports and which are potentially valuable, whether<p>

patentable or not, should be exploited, and that arrangements should be made to secure a suitable<p>

return to the host  institution and the investigators.  Fellows are expected to notify Awards and<p>

Training Section when issues of exploitability arise as a result of work carried out within a NERC<p>

Fellowship.    <p>

Section I<p>

<p>

NERC AWARDS AND TRAINING COMPLAINTS PROCEDURE<p>

<p>

Introduction<p>

<p>

189. The NERC Awards and Training (A&amp;T) Section deals with the largest constituency of<p>

recipients of NERC funds.  Within such a large community it is inevitable that individuals and<p>

institutions will have comments, complaints, grievances and ideas relating to NERC policy and<p>

procedures.  We welcome these but with so many prospective points of entry into NERC, it is<p>

important that the HEI community is aware of who to contact and how.  This is especially<p>

important in instances of formal grievance or complaint.  The following procedural outline aims to<p>

provide guidance on how such approaches to A&amp;T should be made.<p>

<p>

Rationale<p>

<p>

190. A&amp;T utilises and acts on expertise and advice from a variety of NERC Committees and<p>

Boards as well as from individual members of the scientific community, representatives of<p>

government agencies and external interest groups.  These contributions are invaluable and<p>

comprise an essential part of the way that NERC delivers funding and support. <p>

<p>

     However, ultimate responsibility for decisions, action relating to NERC Committee<p>

recommendations and subsequent administration and management rests with Council and NERC<p>

officers.  It is therefore, NERC officers who must be the first recipients for complaints and<p>

grievances and not Chairmen and members of Research Grants and Training Awards Committees<p>

(RGTACs) or members of Review Panels.  Letters, where appropriate, can be copied to such<p>

members for their information.<p>

<p>

Scope and Responsibilities<p>

<p>

191. Normal practice should be to discuss any problems beforehand with the identified officer <p>

for the particular service.  The procedure outlined below will be the recognised channel for the<p>

submission and resolution of formal complaints about any of the services and procedures within<p>

A&amp;T.<p>

<p>

Procedure<p>

<p>

192. Anyone with a complaint is advised to initially discuss the problem(s) with the appropriate<p>

A&amp;T officer.  A listing of current contacts and their areas of responsibility appears below. 
Formal<p>

complaints should be directed in writing (via post or e-mail) to the appropriate A&amp;T officer.<p>

<p>

193. The appropriate A&amp;T officer will aim to acknowledge receipt of the complaint and/or<p>

discuss any related matters of clarification within ten working days.<p>

<p>

194. The appropriate A&amp;T officer will investigate the complaint, as appropriate with RGTAC<p>

members, and endeavour to resolve problems to the complainant's satisfaction.  If problems<p>

referred to named A&amp;T officers are not resolved within a reasonable time, they should also be<p>

referred in writing to the Director A&amp;T<p>

195. In the event of continued dissatisfaction with responses received from A&amp;T officers and<p>

the A&amp;T Director, complainants have the right of written appeal to the Chief Executive.<p>

<p>

A&amp;T Contact Points and Responsibilities<p>

<p>

Director:                          Professor J Bryan Ellis<p>

Head:                                   Mr David A Brown<p>

(General policy and award decisions)<p>

<p>

