(All administration)<p>

<p>

Non-Thematic Research Grant Awards:          Ms Sue Francis<p>

(Pre-award administration)<p>

<p>

Thematic Research Grant Awards:         Mrs Nicola Stevens<p>

(Pre-award administration)<p>

<p>

Research Grant Awards:                  Mrs Sue Furness<p>

(Post-award administration, all awards)<p>

<p>

<p>

Section J<p>

<p>

NERC SERVICES AND FACILITIES<p>

<p>

196. NERC has the following services and facilities which can be made available through<p>

application to NERC Scientific Services (NSS).<p>

<p>

Research Vessels and Marine Equipment<p>

<p>

a)   A fleet of three multipurpose research ships and one polar research vessel, which are used<p>

for continental shelf and oceanic research.  A comprehensive range of marine research equipment<p>

is also available.  Seatime application forms are issued by NSS in September each year.  With<p>

effect from September 1995, the return date for seatime applications (and associated research<p>

grants) will be 1 December, for a ships programme commencing  13 months afterwards. <p>

Applications for cruises are usually restricted to researchers with several years of sea-going<p>

experience.  <p>

<p>

Supercomputing<p>

<p>

b)   NERC peer reviews and coordinates requests to use UK National-Centre<p>

"supercomputers" for research in the environmental sciences.  Facilities include the Cray YMP8 at<p>

the Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, the Fujitsu VPX at Manchester Computer Centre and the<p>

Cray T3D at Edinburgh Parallel Computing Centre.  NERC also possesses distributed computers<p>

supporting a broad range of application software and databases relevant to environmental<p>

sciences.   <p>

<p>

Remote Sensing<p>

<p>

c)   Dundee Satellite Receiving Station provides access to data from the satellite receiving<p>

station which acquires and archives data from certain American meteorological and environmental<p>

monitoring satellites.<p>

<p>

d)   The Airborne Remote Sensing Facility operates a Piper Chieftain twin-engined aircraft for<p>

support of campaigns in the UK and in Europe.  Airborne sensors available include aerial<p>

photography, multispectral scanners and imaging spectrometers.  Application forms inviting<p>

participation in a given campaign should be submitted by 1 July the previous year.<p>

<p>

e)   The Remote Sensing Data Analysis Service, located at Plymouth Marine Laboratory<p>

supplies processed satellite and airborne remotely sensed data.  Image analysis facilities are also<p>

located at Monks Wood (Institute of Terrestrial Ecology), Keyworth (British Geological Survey),<p>

Plymouth University, Wallingford (Institute of Hydrology) and Wormley (Institute of<p>

Oceanographic Sciences).  <p>

<p>

Equipment Pools1<p>

<p>

f)   Geophysical Equipment Pool, at Edinburgh University, for fieldwork in seismology,<p>

geomagnetism and ground-penetrating radar.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

1  The Automatic Weather Stations Equipment Pool, operated from the Institute of Hydrology,<p>

Wallingford, will cease operations in March 1996.<p>

<p>

g)   Equipment Pool for Field Spectroscopy, at University of Southampton, in support of<p>

remote sensing projects. <p>

<p>

h)   Ocean Surface Current Radar Facility, at University of Southampton.<p>

<p>

Dating and Isotopic Analysis<p>

<p>

i)   NERC Radiocarbon Laboratory, at East Kilbride, for environmental sciences projects.<p>

<p>

j)   Oxford University Radiocarbon Accelerator Service for archaeological sciences.<p>

<p>

k)   NERC Isotope Geosciences Laboratory (NIGL) at Keyworth (stable and radiogenic<p>

isotope analyses) and British Geological Survey/Institute of Hydrology Laboratory at Wallingford<p>

(stable isotope analyses).<p>

<p>

l)   Isotope Community Support Facility, at the Scottish Universities Research and Reactor<p>

Centre (SURRC) at East Kilbride (stable and radiogenic isotope, ICP and laser microprobe mass<p>

spectrometry, radiocarbon and thermoluminescence dating, neutron activation spectrometry,<p>

gamma-ray irradiation and radioactive isotope production).<p>

<p>

m)   Argon Isotope Facility, at SURRC, East Kilbride.<p>

<p>

n)   15N Stable Isotope Facility at the Institute of Terrestrial Ecology, Merlewood (15N and<p>

13C) for ecological applications.<p>

<p>

o)   Life Sciences Isotope Support Facility at SURRC, East Kilbride for life sciences projects<p>

(notably using doubly labelled water analyses).<p>

<p>

Chemical Analysis<p>

     <p>

p)   Ion Microprobe Facility, principally for the Earth sciences, at Edinburgh University.<p>

<p>

q)   The ICP-MS Facility, at the Centre for Analytical Research in the Environment (CARE),<p>

Imperial College at Silwood Park, London University, Ascot, provides a comprehensive chemical<p>

analysis service; CARE also provides facilities for isotope production for radiotracer studies,<p>

neutron activation spectrometry, ICP-AES, large wind tunnel, enclosed rain simulator, aerosol<p>

laboratory, lysimeters and field sites.<p>

<p>

r)   The ICPAES Facility at Royal Holloway University of London.<p>

<p>

s)   Organic Geochemistry Mass Spectrometry Facility at Bristol University.<p>

<p>

Miscellaneous Experimental Facilities<p>

<p>

t)   The Atmospheric Sciences Airborne Support Facility, based at Farnborough, coordinates<p>

with the Meteorological Research Flight (MRF) of the Meteorological Office to provide access to<p>

the C-130 Hercules aircraft for research work in the areas of cloud physics, atmospheric<p>

chemistry, satellite activities, mesoscale meteorology and boundary layer studies.  <p>

<p>

u)   Experimental Petrology Community Support Facility, at Edinburgh University.<p>

<p>

v)   National Power EnFlo Facility, at Surrey University, provides environmental flow<p>

facilities.<p>

<p>

w)   The Mesosphere Stratosphere Troposphere Radar Facility (MSTRF) is located in West<p>

Wales but is managed from Rutherford Appleton Laboratory.<p>

<p>

Data Centres<p>

<p>

x)   The NSS Data Centre provides cost-effective acquisition, secure custodianship and<p>

responsive distribution of NERC's commercially acquired satellite and airborne remote sensing<p>

data to environmental scientists, and provides information on corporate data holdings.<p>

<p>

There is strong competition for the use of these resources and applications seeking provisional<p>

allocations should be submitted well in advance.  It is also especially important, particularly in the<p>

case of facilities under b, e, i, k and n above, that contact is established and the proposed work<p>

discussed with the manager of the  facility before submitting formal applications for either the<p>

grant or for the use of the facility.  Advice on the above facilities and services should be sought<p>

from the contacts for NSS given in Appendix B of this booklet.<p>

<p>

It is important to state on fellowship forms what services and facilities are required, with whom<p>

prior contact has been made to discuss the work, and whether separate application has been made<p>

to the relevant facility.<p>

<p>

In cases requiring access to facilities of the British Antarctic Survey (BAS), Cambridge, or<p>

provision of Antarctic samples by BAS, applicants should discuss their proposals with BAS (tel.<p>

01223-61188) before submitting a formal application.<p>

<p>

<p>

     APPENDIX A<p>

<p>

REMIT OF THE NATURAL ENVIRONMENT RESEARCH COUNCIL                <p>

<p>

Council Mission:<p>

<p>

To promote and support, by any means,  high-quality basic, strategic and applied research, survey<p>

and long-term environmental monitoring and related post-graduate training in terrestrial, marine <p>

and freshwater biology and earth, atmospheric, hydrological, oceanographic and  polar sciences<p>

and earth observation. <p>

<p>

To advance knowledge and technology and to provide services and trained scientists and<p>

engineers which meet the needs of users and beneficiaries, thereby contributing to the economic<p>

competitiveness of the UK, the effectiveness of public services and policy, and the quality of life.<p>

<p>

To provide advice, disseminate knowledge and promote public understanding of the aforesaid<p>

fields.<p>

<p>

User Communities:<p>

<p>

Include Water, Construction, Process Hydrocarbons, Minerals, Forestry, Agricultural, Fishing and<p>

Remote-sensing Industries together with Nature Conservation and other Regulatory Agencies,<p>

Universities and Cognate Government Departments.<p>

<p>

Environmental and Natural Resource Issues:<p>

<p>

     Management of land, water and the coastal zone, the identification and exploitation of<p>

land, freshwater and marine based resources and their sustainability.<p>

<p>

     Understanding and protection of biodiversity.<p>

<p>

     Waste management, bioremediation and land restoration.<p>

<p>

     Pollution of air, land, sea and freshwater in relation to environmental and human health.<p>

<p>

     Environmental risks and hazards, including release of genetically modified organisms and<p>

improved prediction of extreme events.<p>

<p>

     Global change, including prediction on a range of time and space scales.<p>

