<h1><img src="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/images/nerclarg.gif"></h1>
<h2>DISPLAY NOTICE 96</h2>
<h3>RESEARCH AND ADVANCED COURSE
STUDENTSHIPS</h3>
<p>

<h2><a href="#ADVANCED COURSE STUDENTSHIPS"></a><a href="#ADVANCED COURSE STUDENTSHIPS"></a><center>AWARDS AND TRAINING SECTION</h2>
</center>
<hr>
<p>

<a href="#RESEARCH STUDENTSHIPS - NUENM"></a><a href="#RESEARCH">RESEARCH</a> STUDENTSHIPS - NON-THEMATIC<p>

ADVANCED COURSE STUDENTSHIPS LEADING TO A <a href="#MASTER">MASTER</a> OF SCIENCE (MSc)<p>

<a href="#RESEARCH STUDENTSHIPS - NUENM"></a><a href="#THEMATIC"></a>RESEARCH MASTERS <a href="#TRAINING COURSES">TRAINING</a> COURSES<p>

RESEARCH STUDENTSHIPS - <a href="#THEMATIC">THEMATIC</a><p>

<hr>
<p>

<a href="#RESEARCH MASTERS "></a><p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

This Display Notice lists the studentships approved by the NERC Awards and Training 
Section to commence later this year.  It is arranged in four sections, the first listing non-thematic

Research Studentship topics, the second and third dealing with Masters courses and

the fourth listing thematic Research Studentship topics funded by the Earth Observation

Science Initative and the Laboratory Studies in Atmospheric Chemistry Thematic Programme.

Please note that other sections of NERC may fund further studentships not listed on this

Notice.

<p>

A copy of this notice is available on the world wide web via the NERC home page using

<a href="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/awards/disply96.htm">
http://www.nerc.ac.uk/awards/disply96.htm</a> 

<p>

<b>HOW TO APPLY</b> 

<p>

Prospective students seeking further details about all awards and courses, or about how to apply, 

should contact the Head of Department or Institution holding the award, and not the NERC. 

<p>

<b>NOMINATIONS</b> 

<p>

Departments have until 31 July 1996 to nominate students for these awards.    Institutions are 

asked to use the award reference numbers given when making nominations.  In the case of split MScs 

these should be shown as A or B.  Successful candidates are entitled to:- 

<p>

-    a maintenance award (6,700 pa for London and 5,400 pa elsewhere in 1996/97)<p>

-    payment of approved tuition fees<p>

-    other allowances as appropriate.<p>

<p>

<b>NOTES</b> 

<p>

i.   CASE research studentships (Co-operative Awards in the Sciences of the Environment) 

provide an  opportunity to gain experience in an industrial or other non-academic institution in a way 

which is     likely to enhance a student's career prospects.  In view of the importance which Council 

associated      with the CASE scheme all CASE students receive a supplement to their maintenance grant of 

350     pa from NERC.  The co-operating body in CASE studentships is also required to supplement 

the     maintenance grant.  This supplement must be a minimum of 1,000 pa. 

<p>

ii.  Council believes that a student's training is likely to benefit from a move to a different 

institution     after undergraduate training and strongly encourages this form of migration. 

<p>

iii. Council wishes to attract graduates into the environmental sciences who have degrees in 

subjects   such as chemistry, engineering, mathematics, physics, etc.  Many of the topics available are 

     appropriate for graduates in such subjects.<p>

 

<a name="RESEARCH"><b>RESEARCH</a> STUDENTSHIPS - NON THEMATIC</b><a href="#MATIC"></a> 


<ul>
  <li><a href="#MATIC"></a><a href="#THEM"></a><a href="#NON"></a>Jump to NON <a href="#HEMA">THEMATIC</a><a href="#THEM"></a><a href="#THEMATIC"></a></li>
</ul>
Research studentships are awarded for postgraduate training, leading to the award of a PhD. 

Studentships 

normally start in the Autumn of 1996 and are tenable for up to three years.  It is the expectation 

of NERC that research students will submit their thesis by the end of their studentships or shortly 

thereafter. 

Applicants must have, or expect to obtain, a good honours degree, normally at least an upper 

second or the equivalent.   Institutions and Departments are arranged alphabetically.  Supervisor(s) are shown 

in brackets under the relevant topic and award reference numbers begin  GT4' and  GT19'. 

<p>

<p>

<b>ADVANCED COURSE STUDENTSHIPS LEADING TO A <a name="MASTER">MASTER</a> OF SCIENCE (MSc) 

</b>
<ul>
  <li>Jump to ADVANCED <a href="#COUR">COURSES</a></li>
</ul>
These studentships will commence in the Autumn of 1996 and are tenable for 1 year.  Students 

will be expected to hold at least a second class honours degree or equivalent.  Some of these awards 

may be made as 50% support for two students.  The Course Organiser's name is shown in brackets under the 

relevant topic, award reference numbers begin  GT3'. 

<p>

The second section of this Notice lists advanced courses recognised by NERC, with the number 

of awards being made available in the coming academic year.  The courses are listed alphabetically in 

Institution.  Those recognised by NERC but which have not been awarded any studentships in the coming year
are listed separately at the end of this section. 

<p>

<b>RESEARCH MASTERS <a name="TRAINING COURSES">TRAINING COURSES</b></a> 


<ul>
  <li>Jump to RESEARCH MASTERS TRAINING <a href="#COURSES">COURSES</a></li>
</ul>
The third section of this Notice lists the five courses NERC has recognised under a new scheme, 

together with course organiser contact details.  These courses are one year research training programmes 

aimed at providing a thorough grounding in generic research methods and transferable skills.  The 

scheme therefore provides graduates with opportunities to proceed directly into employment or to doctoral
study. 

Applicants should have, or expect to gain, at least an upper second class honours degree. 

<p>

It is important that prospective students recognise that this scheme is not a prerequisite for 

doctoral study and similarly that NERC has no intention of providing graduates of the scheme with 

preferential access to future studentship awards. 

<p>

<b>RESEARCH STUDENTSHIPS - <a name="THEMATIC">THEMATIC</b></a> 


<ul>
  <li>Jump to RESEARCH STUDENTSHIPS  - THEMATIC <a href="#PROGRAMMES">PROGRAMMES</a></li>
</ul>
The NERC Science and Technology Boards have recognised the need for additional support in 

specific areas.  As a result a number of research studentship initiatives are current: 

<p>

(i)  The Earth Observation Science and Technology Board (EOSTB), and its subsidiary Earth 

Observation Research Grants and Training Awards Committee (EORGTAC), have recognised a 

shortage of scientists who can apply information systems knowledge to environmental issues.  The Earth 

Observation Science Initiative (EOSI) includes a three year programme to support about 10 CASE 

studentships in the first instance which is intended to consolidate and expand the EO community. 

<p>

(ii) The Atmospheric Science and Technology Board is continuing its successful Thematic 

Programme in support of Laboratory Studies in Atmospheric Chemistry (LSAC) with a third round of awards 

for studentships in topics of relevance to the understanding of tropospheric, stratospheric and 

mesospheric chemistry. 

<p>

The successful awards are listed in last section of this notice.  Institutions and Departments are 

arranged alphabetically.  Supervisor(s) are shown in brackets under the relevant topic and award 

reference numbers begin  GT22'.<p>

<p>

<p>

