 <body bgcolor=ffffff><p>

<b>Director: Prof J Bryan Ellis<p>

Head:     Mr David A Brown <p>

December 1996<p>

Newsletter 10<p>

<center><i>Awards and Training Mission</i><p>

</center>
<p>

Awards and Training (A&amp;T) section is part of the Science and Technology Directorate and
provides peer and merit review service for all areas and modes of NERC supported science.
In conjunction with the Science and Technology Boards, A&amp;T has specific responsibility
for the management and allocation of resources for non-thematic research grants and
training awards and for their subsequent monitoring, evaluation and
administration.Special Edition<p>

<p>

<p>

INTRODUCTION<p>

<p>

As this Newsletter is being written, decisions are being reached on several issues which will
be of considerable significance for future research activity in the UK Higher Education
sector.  They include the size and distribution of the Science Budget for the coming year(s),
the RAE subject gradings, the unified HE Quality Agency as well as the outcomes from the
Dearing Research Sub-Committee Review.<p>

<p>

Irrespective of the actual Budgetary out-turn and forward planning figures, NERC is
committed at the very least to maintaining the rates of success in the non-thematic
(responsive) mode which currently are 28% for alpha-graded proposals (or 20% overall). 
It is our firm intention to uphold these base level success rates for non-thematic research
grants and funds are being sought from the Council to ensure future planning level
expenditure.  However the security of this funding line is partly dependent on our ability to
demonstrate clear achievements arising from NERC non-thematic award research
activities which have been completed.   Although we have tried to sharpen-up end-of-grant
responses on outcomes and achievements, it is still often difficult to sift out the 'gems' from
the enveloping 'gravel'.  In particular, we need clearer information on what new
knowledge, skills and services have been developed and why these are important with
explanations being given in language that will be understood by a non-specialist reader. 
We also need clearer detail on the end-user impacts and benefits resulting from the
research including training and career opportunities provided for staff appointed under the
grant.<p>

<p>

The outcomes of the </b><a href="jrei96.htm">Joint</a><b> Research Equipment Initiative in
respect of NERC
environmental science applications to Competitions A and B are given later in this
Newsletter.  The response to this scheme by the NERC community was somewhat
disappointing with only a total of 19 applications being received by the 17 June 1996
deadline.  A number of applications were unfortunately rendered ineligible for
infringement of the regulations relating to "matched-funding" agency status.  However,
should this scheme or some something similar reappear (early signs are that this may be the
case), I am confident we will get a much wider and better based response.<p>

<p>

Further information on the new NERC PhD studentship allocation methodology (which
implements some of the recent Harris Committee recommendations), and on the MSc
course review is also given later in the Newsletter and the full cross-Research Council
review of the MRes pilot courses is shortly to be released by OST.  1997 is very likely to be
a 'watershed' year for research in UK Higher Education and so I wish everyone a relaxing
and enjoyable Christmas prior to the fresh challenges arising in the New Year.<p>

<p>

Professor J Bryan Ellis<p>

<p>

<p>

NERC TRAINING STRATEGY REVIEW<p>

<p>

The September meeting of Council approved the introduction of the new research
studentship (PhD) allocation procedure and the timetable for the zero-based review of
advanced (MSc) courses.<p>

<p>

<p>

Allocation of research (PhD) studentships:  In October higher education Departments with
a history of support from NERC received a circular letter outlining the new NERC
research studentship (PhD) allocation procedure and were invited to check the summary of
NERC research grant income over the last three financial years 1993/94 - 1995/96.   Any
mistakes or anomalies were highlighted  before returning the information together with a
Departmental statement on postgraduate training provision, to NERC.<p>

<p>

Departments were given very little time to check the data that had been hurriedly prepared
by Awards and Training and we would like to thank everyone for their patience and 
cooperation.  Identified anomalies were examined and the necessary adjustments made to
accommodate awards that are split between universities and Departments, transfer of PIs
to different institutions, establishment of new Departments etc.    In instances where the
funds and numbers of staff could not be reconciled with Departmental returns, the default
has been to use the NERC figures.    <p>

<p>

The data to be included in the algorithm is summarised below and there will be a further 
check of individual Departmental data inputs over the next few weeks:<p>

<p>

1. Thresholds<p>

(a) No Departments with a Research Assessment Exercise (RAE) rating of less than 3 (these
will be re-examined when the outcomes of the 1996 RAE are announced)<p>

(b) No Departments with a completion rate of less than 60% after 4 years.<p>

<p>

2. Data included   <p>

(a) Non Thematic (includes standard, small ROPA and CONNECT schemes)<p>

Time period = the last full three financial years i.e 1993/94; 1994/95; 1995/96<p>

Award value = the value of grants, from the actual start dates, as recorded on the NERC
profile payments system. <p>

Person years (RAs) = the number of RAs on the grants awarded shown in person years e.g.
a 3 year grant awarded an RA for 3 years is shown as 3 person years; a 3 year grant
awarded with an RA for 18 months is shown as 1.5 person years <p>

Fellows = the number of NERC Fellows (including Taxonomy fellows) in the department
during the financial years i.e. not in person years<p>

<p>

(b) Thematic Grants (incl. Special Topics, Community Research Programmes and directed
mode support schemes e.g LOIS; TIGER; BRIDGE)<p>

Time period =  the last full three financial years i.e 1993/94; 1994/95; 1995/96<p>

Award value = as for non-thematic <p>

Person years (RAs) = as for non-thematic<p>

<p>

(c) Core/Strategic (universities research groups and Units only). <p>

Time period =  the last full two financial years i.e  1994/95; 1995/96<p>

Award value = ongoing annual costs on the contract (incl. Research active personnel) <p>

Person years (RAs) = as for non-thematic but for all research active personnel<p>

<p>

(d) Infrastructure<p>

Funds for ship time and capital equipment etc. provided to universities to run services and
facilities have not been included. <p>

<p>

The statements on postgraduate training, supervision, and assessment will be scrutinised by
the Director and Head of Awards and Training and will be used to populate the
Departmental/University database we are compiling (see section on research evaluation
below).   This database will also include the new RAE ratings and information on
Departmental completion rates and reduce the need for such extensive data collection in the
future.   Where there are any substantive problems or queries these will be discussed at the
Training Awards Forum and subsequently transmitted to Departments/Universities.  <p>

<p>

The Training Awards Forum meeting on Thursday 6 February 1997 will examine the
algorithm output(s) and also make decisions on the support for Industrial CASE awards.  
All announcements will be made via letters to Heads of Department as soon as possible after
the Forum meeting (no information will be provided over the telephone).    Award letters
will set out details of the input used, NERC's expectations on how Departments should
make allocations, the timetable for student and topic nomination and subsequent
monitoring arrangements, plus guidance on the way the algorithm based allocation process
will develop for the 1998 exercise.   <p>

<p>

Review of Advanced (MSc) course provision: Research Grant and Training Award
Committee subgroups have been established to take an in depth look, over the period
October 1996 to March 1997, at the courses within their area.   They have been asked to
address a comprehensive set of questions, including those set out in </b><a
href="atnews9">Issue</a><b> 9 of the
Newsletter, and to report to the March meetings of their respective RGTACs.   Final
reports will be considered by the Training Strategy Review Group in April who will make
final recommendations to the June meeting of Council.  Changes to the portfolio of courses
or allocations of studentships to them,  will not take effect until October 1998.<p>

<p>

Science and Technology Boards have been formally invited to provide input to this training
review. <p>

<p>

Fieldwork costs: NERC is concerned about the burgeoning costs of fieldwork for research
students, primarily those associated with overseas projects.  While recognising the
considerable benefits of providing access to overseas training opportunities, in a number of
instances the costs associated with them is becoming excessive.  These and other pressures
on the training awards budget are not compatible with academia's desires to maintain the
total volume of students.  Via the award letters to Heads of Departments, NERC will
therefore be seeking greater justification for overseas projects and will require all
studentships to be fully costed at the outset.  In this latter respect, studentships will
effectively be cash limited.   If fieldwork costs to NERC continue to increase at current
rates, serious consideration will inevitably need to be given to providing fewer studentships. <p>

<p>

RESEARCH EVALUATION<p>

<p>

NERC is continually seeking ways of obtaining increased funds for the research and
training it wishes to support.  However funding for research needs to be won in the face of
fierce competition from all other calls on the public purse.  Even when central government
funding has been allocated, demands on NERC's science budget are many, varied and
growing.  Increasingly stronger arguments therefore need to be advanced in order to justify
support for all the funding modes including the non-thematic(=responsive) element.  This is
where we need your help.  <p>

<p>

Research Grants: Awards and Training already ask research grant award holders to
provide information on publications arising from the research but we need to greatly
increase our efforts to evaluate the impact of these investments.   We are doing this by
taking a more rigorous approach to obtaining information on the output from grants 18
months or so after the final report was submitted.  Information is being sought on
publications in refereed journals, book chapters, patents etc and will also be linked into the
annual returns made to the Research Council's Exploitation Scrutiny Group.    <p>

<p>

Evaluation of output of research grant investments will also play a far more influential role
during consideration of applications for new awards. <p>

<p>

Training Awards: The need to integrate transferable and generic skills training into
postgraduate education programmes is a desire shared by all Research Councils.  The
Departmental statements provided as part of the returns to NERC will be used to compile a
database of information that will be used to track provision of these important training
elements.  Research students are increasingly seeking employment outside academia and
research and it is important that the training provided recognises this and equips students
with the skills to compete in other employment sectors.  Access to such training will
eventually become a pre-requisite for receiving NERC training awards. <p>

<p>

The Training Strategy Review Group also want to reinforce the need for completing
research training and submission of theses within the 3 year funding period.  As such
NERC's expectations of Departmental completion and submission rates will progressively
increase over the coming years.   <p>

<p>

RESEARCH GRANTS<p>

<p>

New Awards: NERC awards made under the </b><a href="jrei96.htm">Joint</a><b> Research
Equipment Initiative are
listed elsewhere.  6 awards were made under Competition A (to the value of c.400k) and
NERC recommended funding of one award under Competition B. <p>

<p>

Resubmission of highly graded proposals: Recent discussion within the RGTACs and
Science and Technology Boards has resulted in a change in policy towards invited
resubmissions.  Decreases in success rates have meant that many highly graded proposals
have just failed to get above the funding cut-off line.  As from the March round of meetings,
RGTACs will have the freedom to recommend that a specified number of highly graded
grants are:<p>

<p>

     reworked by applicants, resubmitted and then subject to peer review and regrading by the
RGTAC,<p>

     reconsidered, without being reworked or further peer review, with the same grading at the
next RGTAC meeting. <p>

<p>

RESEARCH GRANTS AND TRAINING AWARD COMMITTEES (RGTACs)    <p>

<p>

NERC RGTAC membership normally lasts for 3 years.  Replacement members are
identified  primarily by the scientific knowledge/expertise required by the Committee but
are chosen from nominations made by STBs, Council and the academic community.  If you
wish to nominate potential members to one of the 5 RGTAC areas (Earth Sciences, Earth
Observation, Freshwater Sciences, Marine and Atmospheric Sciences, Terrestrial Sciences)
or for Science Based Archaeology, please inform the Director or Head of A&amp;T in writing
before the end of February.   <p>

<p>

NERC SERVICES AND FACILITIES<p>

<p>

NERC Funded Radiocarbon (14C) Analysis<p>

<p>

Permanent members of staff of Higher Education Institutions,  NERC Institutes and any
other persons who are eligible to be awarded NERC Research Grants and/or Training
Awards may apply for NERC funded radiocarbon (14C) analysis via the NERC
Radiocarbon Facilities Steering Committee (RCFSC).  <p>

<p>

Two analytical techniques are available to applicants,  with measurement of 14C in samples
containing  1g carbon by the well established radiometric counting technique which
employs liquid scintillation counting and the radiocarbon measurement of ultra small ( 2mg
carbon) samples by accelerator mass spectrometry (AMS).<p>

<p>

Conditions and procedures to access either or both techniques are identical.  Applications
for projects that are primarily environmental and/or require analysis by the radiometric
counting technique,  should be made directly to the RCFSC or to the RCFSC's
sub-committee,  the NERC Programme Assessment Panel of the Oxford Radiocarbon
Accelerator Dating Service (ORADS),  if the work is primarily archaeological.<p>

<p>

Because a finite resource is being allocated among a large potential user community, all
applications will be  assessed on their scientific quality and graded using the standard
grading criteria.  In any round of applications a grade will be determined below which full
NERC funded support cannot be provided.  For applications at and above that grade the
cost,   including pretreatment of raw sample material,  chemical conversion and the
essential stable isotope ( 13C) determinations,  of samples endorsed by the RCFSC or the
ORADS Programme Assessment Panel,  will be borne in full by NSS.  Samples from
applications below the grade can be analysed if the cost of analysis is met by the applicant.<p>

<p>

Application forms and guidance on the preparation of  an application can be obtained by
contacting the secretary of the RCFSC or of the ORADS Programme Assessment Panel.<p>

<p>

All correspondence to the RCFSC is through its Secretary,  Mr Brian F. Miller,  who is
based at the NERC Radiocarbon Laboratory, Scottish Enterprise Technology Park,
Rankine Avenue, EAST KILBRIDE G75  0QF. Tel: 01355 260037.  Fax:  01355 229829.<p>

e-mail address:  B.Miller@nss.nerc.ac.uk.<p>

<p>

All correspondence to the ORADS Programme Assessment Panel is through its Secretary, 
Mr Paul Pettitt who is based at the Oxford Radiocarbon Accelerator Unit, Research
Laboratory for Archaeology, 6 Keble Road, OXFORD OX1 3QJ, Tel: 01865 273939.  <p>

Fax:.  01865 273932.   e-mail address: orau@vax.ox.ac.uk.<p>

<p>

<p>

MARINE PLANNING AND FUNDING CYCLE<p>

<p>

Some concern has been expressed by the research community about NERC's apparent lack
of support for ship-time.  These concerns are ill-founded and we wish to reinforce NERC's
commitment to funding sea-going research.  The bottom line is that for some reason the
number of research grant proposals seeking ship-time has reduced markedly over the past
2-3 years.   However it should be emphasised that when such proposals are deemed worthy
of support by RGTACs, A&amp;T will continue to meet the superstructure costs.   Dr Caroline
Harper has prepared the following summary on the new cruise planning and funding cycle
for information  <p>

 <p>

NSS has now switched from programming the ships on a financial year basis to
programming by calendar year, to reduce lead times, and to bring us in line with colleagues
in Europe and the USA, so as to facilitate any ship time barters which may be requested. 
The deadline for seatime applications is now 01 April each year, for a 12 month calendar
year programme, commencing the following January.  Two copies of the seatime form
(including scientific case), together with a firm indication of full superstructure funding (in
writing) from the relevant funding source in each case, must reach NSS Marine Planning
by this date, to be considered for the programme.   <p>

<p>

For research grant applicants this means that they must submit their RG forms, together
with the completed seatime application,  to A&amp;T by 01 December the previous year.  These
are peer reviewed and funding decisions made at the March round of RGTAC meetings
before passing on to NSS by 01 April.  For example, the A&amp;T deadline for proposals
involving ship time in calendar year 1998 was 01 December 1996, and funded cruise
proposals must reach NSS Marine Planning by 01 April 1997.  Other funding sources, eg
thematic programmes, EC, Centre/Surveys,  have other deadlines for peer review/funding
decisions, and the relevant Programme Manager/Centre Director should be consulted.  <p>

<p>

After 01 April a draft programme is constructed, in consultation with Principal
Investigators (PIs) and Research Vessel Services (RVS), and considered by the Research
Cruise Steering Group in early June.  Any revisions are incorporated ready for programme
release in early July.  By this stage, precise cruise durations have been calculated, and any
disagreements on service levels etc should have been sorted by the PIs and RVS, so precise
superstructure costs can be quoted to funding sources.  NSS seeks formal confirmation from
the funding sources that funds will be transferred to cover superstructure costs.  A&amp;T
would normally have their decisions to NSS in plenty of time but other funding sources
(including external ones like the EC) can take longer.  Assuming that these confirmations
are received in a timely fashion, NSS aims to release details in early July so that all
concerned are notified well ahead of the next announcement of opportunity in September. 
It also allows RVS 6 months to obtain diplomatic clearances etc.  Delays to confirming
funding can lead to delays in releasing the cruise programme. <p>

<p>

Infrastructure funding is a fixed amount per annum, irrespective of inflation.  It is funded
centrally, and is used to keep the ships operational, but 'tied up alongside'.  Superstructure
funding is required from 'customers' to take the ships to sea to carry out the science and
accounts for less than half of the total cost of the cruise programme each year.  When the
new infrastructure/superstructure arrangements were introduced in 1991, superstructure
funding was allocated to the various Directorates.  It is no longer earmarked, so that
applications for sea time are tensioned against funding requests for other projects.<p>

<p>

For the coming year (1997) A&amp;T has no cruises in the programme, though it has agreed to
fund a seatime barter cruise, which has had to be carried over into 1998 for logistic
reasons.  In the current (FY 1996/97) programme, A&amp;T have funded two sea time
proposals, one of which is a two-leg exercise on RRS Challenger, and the other is a cruise
on RRS Discovery.<p>

<p>

NERC ACCESS TO CLRC FACILITIES<p>

<p>

Changes to the funding mechanism for access to the ISIS neutron source at the Rutherford
Appleton Laboratory and the Synchrotron Radiation Source (SRS), at the Daresbury
Laboratory have now required individual Research Councils to fund their own share of use
of these facilities. The Awards and Training Section has agreed with NSS that current
NERC<p>

grant-holders and PhD students who require beam-time, will be given priority for funding
from the limited existing resources.<p>

<p>

Future usage will require applicants to apply for access costs, at CLRC published rates, on
the research grant application form RG1.  Such applications will be processed as standard
by NERC Awards and Training, including peer review.   If grant funding is approved the
user will be given a "credit balance" in the NSS account with the facilities, a system
analogous to the ticketing system adopted by EPSRC; facility funds will not be transferred
to the user's institution but will actually pass directly between NERC and CLRC.  Funded
users will still have to complete the respective facility application form(s)<p>

<p>

Given the current financial climate it is recommended that in future applications for PhD
studentships involving access to CLRC facilities be submitted as tied-studentships on
standard research grant applications<p>

<p>

ANNOUNCEMENTS<p>

<p>

EARTH </b><a href="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/eos/ao/wwwaq.htm">OBSERVATION</a><b>
SCIENCE INITIATIVE<p>

<p>

The NERC funding routes entry on the NERC Website contains details of this opportunity
which is offering support for sabbaticals and Fellowships in Earth Observation science. 
Alternatively enquiries should be addressed to Dr Sarah Ruth, EO Programme Tel: 01793
411665. FAX 01793 411502. E-mail: saru@wpo.nerc.ac.uk <p>

<p>

IDEAS FOR NEW RESEARCH PROGRAMMES IN TERRESTRIAL AND
FRESHWATER SCIENCES<p>

<p>

To keep at the cutting edge of research, NERC must continue to develop a portfolio of
potential new research programmes i.e. sets of projects linked to a theme or area of
research.  In our jargon these are called thematic programmes and are expected to produce
some results of interest to users within the medium term. (5-10 years).  Ideas for new
thematic programmes of any sort are always welcome, but the purpose of this
announcement is specifically to invite ideas (concept notes) based in the terrestrial and
freshwater areas of NERC's remit.  Other areas of science are not forgotten, but calls have
either already been made in previous years or will be made in the future.<p>

<p>

It is particularly important to note that there is severe pressure on our funds and we are
anxious not to raise false hopes, but if you have a really good idea for a future programme
(not a project!)  in this area please let us know.  Submission should not exceed two sides of
A4 (minimum 12 point typeface) and should be sent before the 14 February 1997 to:   Dr
Anne McFarlane, NERC Polaris House, Swindon.<p>

 Ideas which include, but extend beyond, the terrestrial and freshwater sciences are
particularly welcome and other NERC Science and Technology Boards will be given the
opportunity to support them as appropriate.<p>

<p>

Submission should include a brief statement of the overall aims of the potential programme,
an indication of expected outputs and some information on potential users.  In the first
place, proposals will be assessed by the Research Grants and Training Awards Committees
which may aggregate applications if it seems sensible to do so.  The "winners" of this
competition will be passed to the Terrestrial and Freshwater Science and Technology
Board, but even then the chance of ultimate success is small.  The Board will reduce the
number still further and the remaining proposals will be developed, via for example town
meetings, into full applications which will be rigorously peer reviewed.  It is from these
peer reviewed proposals that NERC will select its new thematic programmes for funding. 
The total preparation time is at least two years and the proposers will have no inside track
for funding.<p>

<p>

If that doesn't put you off let us hear from you!<p>

<p>

COMMUNICATIONS<p>

<p>

COMMUNICATING SCIENCE TO THE PUBLIC<p>

<p>

In line with its mission to promote the public understanding of science, NERC is launching
a communications and media course.  Two are planned for 1997.<p>

<p>

The aim is to equip participants with the skills required to bring their science into the
public arena.  By the end of the course, participants will: <p>

<p>

     understand how the media works<p>

<p>

     know how to write and place a story, including press releases<p>

<p>

     have been introduced to interviewing techniques<p>

<p>

     be able to make a successful presentation to a non-scientific audience<p>

<p>

The course will be run by media experts in conjunction with the NERC Policy and
Communication Division (PCD) and Joint Training Services.  All NERC staff and NERC
grant holders in universities and other institutions are eligible.  The course is free to all
applicants, but participants will be expected to provide their own Travel and Subsistence. 
If applicants have no access to funds, assistance may be available. <p>

<p>

<p>

The course will last for 2 days and will be held at 22, Henrietta Street, London (the
Research Council's, London base).  Hotel accommodation will be booked near Henrietta
Street.   The available dates are:<p>

<p>

                                          24/25 February;   24/25 March<p>

<p>

For more information including nomination procedures, programme etc please contact
Sheila Anderson (PCD).  Tel: 01793 411646.  E-mail: sand@wpo.nerc.ac.uk or Melanie
Slater<p>

Tel: 01793 444332.  E-mail: msl@wpo.nerc.ac.uk<p>

<p>

ELECTRONIC MAIL <p>

<p>

Construction of the NERC directories of e-mail addresses for university Departments,
Registrars etc is nearly complete.  These will be used as a means of drawing attention to
announcements of opportunity, changes to policy and procedures etc detailed elsewhere,
usually the Website.   We have asked each university Department, research institution etc.
to provide us with a single e-mail contact address.   Our assumption is that this single point
will relay the necessary messages and information onward to those who need to know.  It is
therefore important for us to know if there are any changes to this contact point, or if your
Department or institution needs to be added to the directory.   The NERC contact is Mrs
Nicky Stevens:<p>

<p>

                                         e-mail:   nms@wpo.nerc.ac.uk<p>

<p>

Similarly there will also be a growing tendency for us to use e-mail as the mechanism for
responding quickly to general enquiries.  In this regard we urge all people writing to NERC
to quote an e-mail address.  We are also actively promoting the use of e-mail by reviewers. <p>

<p>

USE OF THE WORLD WIDE WEB<p>

<p>

Because of a change of server, the Awards and Training Website address has changed to: <p>

<p>

                         http://www.nerc.ac.uk/awards/index.htm<p>

<p>

Booklets: As mentioned in the previous newsletter, NERC will be greatly reducing the
circulation of printed booklets.  The most up to date versions will be accessible via the
Website.  Distribution of hard copies will be limited to the following with extra (limited)
copies of booklets only being provided on written request.  <p>

<p>

     Research Grants booklet: Hard copy circulation will be to Heads of Department and
University Registries. <p>

     Studentships booklet: Hard copy circulation to all new and current students, Heads of
Department and Registries. <p>

     Fellowships booklet: Hard copy circulation only to prospective applicants.   <p>

<p>

Updating booklets once a year against the background of rapidly changing policy, means
that hard copy is soon out of date.  Use of the World Wide Web allows policy changes and
amendments to be incorporated more regularly and rapidly.  This new practice will also
help to overcome the difficulties of prospective applicants consulting out of date versions of
the booklets.  All changes will be signalled by e-mail message to the single identified
Departmental contact point.       <p>

<p>

Application forms: The A&amp;T entry on the NERC WWW pages also includes application
forms for research grants and fellowship competitions.  These can be down loaded and
represents a further step toward our longer term objectives of full electronic processing of
applications.  Diskettes are also now available in Word and Wordperfect for Apple Mac
users.   Contact <a href="mailto:tim@wpo.nerc.ac.uk">tim@wpo.nerc.ac.uk
</a>for copies. <p>

<p>

<a href="concorda.htm">CONCORDAT</a> ON RESEARCH CAREERS FOR CONTRACT
WORKERS IN
UNIVERSITIES<p>

<p>

A series of regional meetings were held in Birmingham, Cambridge, Cardiff, Glasgow and
Leeds during November and December when Research Councils outlined the objectives and
principles of the Concordat which came into effect on 1 September 1996.  The greatest
interest for Research Councils is in the impact it will have on terms and conditions for
research assistants on grants. <p>

<p>

Research Councils are collectively keen to monitor the impact of the introduction of the
Concordat and all research grant holders who submit final reports after the 1 October
1996, will be asked to pass on questionnaires to all research assistants appointed under the
grant.  The questionnaire seeks information on career management, training etc and can be
returned directly to the Research Council.  Although the first review is not scheduled until
the end of March 1998, collecting information now will provide a dataset which gives better
insights into the impact of its introduction.    <p>

<p>

A+T </b><a href="who">contacts</a><b> list<p>


