<p>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff><p>

<b>NERC INDUSTRIAL CASE STUDENTSHIPS</b><p>

<p>

The NERC Industrial CASE studentship scheme aims to provide UK based industry,
business or commerce (<b>*</b>) with the opportunity to formulate and submit a three year PhD
research studentship application.   Usual NERC rules and regulations governing CASE
research students apply with the expectation that the Industrial partner will contribute at
least 1,000 to the student maintenance grant.<p>

<b><i><p>

(*) NERC uses the Realising Our Potential Awards (ROPA) definition of UK private sector industry,
business or commerce namely:<p>

             -- the company must be UK-owned with government holding no more than a 40% stake;<p>

                or in the case or foreign owned companies or multinational:-<p>

            -- the company must be capable of exploiting research it has funded to the net benefit of <p>

                the UK, for example, through its UK based production or service facilities.<p>

</i></b><p>

Applications to NERC are restricted to one per university/college Department and must be
submitted via the university on an  <a href="studfrm.htm"> IC1</a> application form to Awards and
Training Section
(Mrs L Chapman) <u><b>by 1 November at the latest</b></u>.  Applications received after that date
will
be returned. <p>

<p>

All applications will be assessed in open competition and announcements of successful
awards made by the end of February 1997.    By way of guidance, applicants need to pay
particular attention to the following criteria: <p>

<p>

<u>General</u>: <i>The proposed training must be completed in three years, including writing up and
submission of the thesis.  There must also be additional merits associated with the
proposed external collaboration.</i> <p>

<p>

<u>Research Topic</u>: <i>A strong science case should be made that is well defined with identified
questions or hypotheses, suggested appropriate methodology/approaches and a feasible
plan of action.  The topic should offer genuine scope for doctoral research and innovative
science. <p>

</i><p>

<u>Training</u>: <i> The topic should be embedded within a strong research training environment
that has quality and depth of academic/research staff, good facilities and access and
availability to more formal courses/modules in research methods, transferable skills and
subject specialisms.<p>

</i><p>

<u>Supervision</u>: <i>The supervisor(s) should be appropriate to support candidates in terms of
experience and expertise and be currently active.  Supervisory contact, monitoring and
assessment standards should be evident</i>. <p>

<p>

Copies of the <a href="studfrm.htm"> IC1 </a> form will be sent to heads of department.   Further
copies may be
obtained by contacting the Awards &amp; Training Section either by fax: (01793) 411616  or
<a href="mailto:tawards@wpo.nerc.ac.uk">E-mail: tawards@wpo.nerc.ac.uk. <p>

</a>

</body>
