<body>
<h1><body bgcolor=#ffffff></h1>
<h1>Guidance Notes for final Reports</h1>
MNT 31<center><b>GUIDANCE NOTES FOR THE SUBMISSION </center>
<p>

<center>OF FINAL REPORTS</b></center>
<p>

<p>

NERC maintains close interest in work carried out under its research grants scheme.  A final report
<u>must</u> be submitted within three months of the termination of the award, so that Council, acting
through its Research Grants and Training Awards Committees, can satisfy itself that the work has
been done to acceptable standards.<p>

<p>

All final reports should be planned with as much care as a publishable scientific article. Requirements
for final reporting are detailed in Section 5 of the NERC Research Grants booklet <b>1995/96.  These
specifications must be adhered to.   Any grant holder failing to comply with these
requirements runs the risk of the report being graded unsatisfactory<u></b><p>

</u><p>

<u>Within three months</u> of the termination of the grant, grant holders are expected to submit:-<p>

<p>

4 copies	-	a completed pro-forma (PA1), summarising basic information on original
objectives achievements,  output etc.<p>

<p>

4 copies	-	a detailed report of no <b>more than 8 sides </b>of A4 single spaced typescript of
minimum font size 12 that includes all necessary tables and figures <u>plus</u> a full
list of references (see 5.6 below).  Investigators are expected to provide an
explanation in cases where the use of funds have been significantly different
from that anticipated at the time of award (see para 5.3.3).<p>

<p>

2 copies	-	There should also be an additional one page non-technical summary suitable
for the general public and lay reader describing aims, achievements and
beneficiaries.<p>

<p>

2 copies	-	a final expenditure statement.<p>

<p>

Each report should state clearly the progress and achievements of the project for comparison with
objectives contained in the original application, and any recommendations or amendments made by
the NERC at the time of the award.   If there are exceptional reasons which prevent these being
submitted within three months, NERC must be notified in writing.<p>

<p>

The final report should be well planned and include all necessary tables and figures and should state
clearly the progress or achievements of the project in comparison with objectives contained in the
original application, and any recommendations or amendments made by the NERC at the time of the
award.   It should, also, emphasise general scientific and practical achievements and specify the
beneficiaries (ie other researchers, industry, government etc).<p>

<p>

NERC sees publication in the refereed scientific journals as the proper means of reporting the
findings of the research grant project.  <b>Copies of publications arising directly from the
investigation should be appended, but are not acceptable as a substitute for any part of the
final report details mentioned below.</b>   <u>Details of publications arising for up to 2 years after the
termination of the grant must be submitted to Awards and Training section</u>.<p>

<p>

Referees will be asked to comment on the final report and the Secretariat will feed back to the
investigator as much of their comments as possible (referees may if they wish also make comments
in confidence to the NERC).  The review process will normally be completed within 3 months of
receipt of your final report.
</body>
</html>
