<body>
<body bgcolor=#ffffff><p>

<H1><IMG SRC="/images/nerc.gif" ALT="NERC"></H1>

<h1>Newsletter #9</h1>
<b>Awards and Training<p>

NewsletterDirector: Prof J Bryan Ellis<p>

Head:     Mr David A BrownNumber 9<p>

August 1996Polaris House, North Star Avenue, Swindon, <p>

SN2 1EU, <p>

Tel: 01793 411500, <p>

Fax: 01793 411616</b><p>

<p>

<a href="#strat">NERC</a> Training Strategy<p>

Use of <a href="#www">WWW</a> + E-Mail<p>

<a href="#con">Concordat</a> on Research Careers<p>

<a href="#Survey">A+T </a>Customer Survey<p>

<b>Awards and Training Mission</b><p>

Awards and Training (A&amp;T) section is part of the Science and Technology Directorate and
provides peer
and merit review service for all areas and modes of NERC supported science. In conjunction with the
Science and Technology Boards, A&amp;T has specific responsibility for the management and
allocation of
resources for non-thematic research grants and training awards and for their subsequent monitoring,
evaluation and administration.Special Edition<p>

<p>

Over the next few months, a number of important changes to NERC policy and procedures and our
interface with the academic community will gradually come into effect. Although these have been
signalled
in earlier versions of the newsletter, their importance is such that we urge you to bring them to the
attention of all those who are part of the NERC research community. <p>

<p>

Of the three issues mentioned below, two are unique to NERC and one (the Concordat) draws
attention to
expectations and obligations that are common to all Research Councils. NERC Training Strategy
Review<p>

<b>N<a name="strat"></a>ERC Training Strategy</b><p>

Under the Chairmanship of Professor John Lawton FRS, a member of Council, NERC has established a
Training Strategy Review Group with the following terms of reference: <p>

<p>

"To review the NERC mechanisms for funding and support of postgraduate education and training in
the
context of perceived skills requirements and priorities in the environmental sciences. To examine the
options and approaches necessary to meet future trained manpower  needs and to recommend to
Council
any changes required in policy and procedures".<p>

<p>

Membership includes the Chairmen of all Research Grants and Training Awards Committees
(RGTACs)
and the Director and Head of Awards and Training. There are a range of issues being addressed in the
context of two overriding requirements: <p>

<p>

     it is imperative that any changes to procedures should be defensible from the standpoint of being
simple,
transparent, accountable and ideally robust.<p>

<p>

<p>

     any changes to procedures must recognise the need for them to be accommodated within
NERC's
requirement for efficiency gains that reduce administrative costs to provide more front line funds for
research and training.<p>

<p>

Within this framework the Review Group has agreed the following objectives and timetable:<p>

<p>

1. Development of a methodology for allocation of research (PhD) studentships: The Review Group
are
examining the possibility of developing an algorithm for the allocation of the majority of PhD awards
based
on criteria such as Departmental Research Assessment Exercise (RAE) rating, NERC and other
research
grant income, completion rates, number of research active staff, number of CASE awards etc. The
algorithm is being examined and compared with the more traditional procedures 
and other possibilities with a
view
to presenting final recommendations to the September 1996 meeting of Council. The expectation is that
agreement might be reached to allow the new methodology to be adopted for the 1997 research
studentship allocation exercise. Any agreed changes will be signalled to the community as soon as
possible.<p>

<p>

2. Review of Advanced (MSc) course provision: RGTAC subgroups, yet to be established, will take an
in
depth look, over the period October 1996 to February 1997, at the courses within their RGTAC area
and
asked to address the following questions:<p>

<p>

<p>

     are we training too many MSc students (if so why and in what areas), too few (if so why and in
what areas
are there shortfalls), or are the numbers about right?<p>

<p>

<p>

     how much should the allocation be based on user needs, Foresight areas, strategic Council
objectives and
priorities?<p>

<p>

<p>

     are we currently supporting too many MSc courses?<p>

<p>

     should the term of NERC support be limited e.g. maximum of 5 years to allow flexibility for
turnover and
new course recognition. If no, how is it proposed to create headroom?<p>

<p>

     do we want to identify specific "core" skills and disciplines that NERC should preferentially
fund and
support  e.g. data interpretation, hydrogeology, oceanography,<p>

<p>

     what should be the overall balance between MSc and PhD in your RGTAC area?<p>

<p>

     should there be a specified minimum period for a course to have been operating before an
approach can be
made to NERC for recognition and support?<p>

<p>

     should NERC retain the current policy of recognition with no studentships or only recognise
and support?<p>

<p>

     what is the value of half awards and should this practice be retained?<p>

<p>

The RGTAC subgroups will be able to refer to the most recent reviews of each of the current courses
but
the understanding that the Review Group wish to convey to RGTAC subgroups and the academic
community is that the "status quo" cannot be sustained. The Review Group wish to identify
mechanisms
which facilitate turnover of courses to enable recognition and support of new courses and other training
initiatives including greater opportunity for NERC student involvement in Research Council Graduate
School programmes, specialist module support etc. The Review Group require RGTAC
recommendations
by the end of March 1997 such that they can prepare a paper for submission to Council in June 1997.
Any
recommendations will then be effective from the October 1998 student intake. Implicit in this is that
NERC
will not be seeking applications for recognition of new courses in November 1996<p>

<p>

The Review Group are also aware of wider issues that need to be kept in mind. These include: <p>

<p>

     the balance between MScs and PhDs,<p>

<p>

     the balance between non-thematic and thematic funding modes,<p>

<p>

     the need to promote and reward CASE studentships,<p>

<p>

     the need to retain, and possibly increase, the number of tied studentships on standard research
grants,<p>

<p>

     the need to develop and emphasise the training element in PhD programmes,<p>

<p>

     requirements for all courses and research studentships to include transferable, generic and
interpersonal
skills,<p>

<p>

     the need for short courses,<p>

<p>

     role and integration of MRes,<p>

<p>

     burgeoning fieldwork costs.<p>

<p>

Science and Technology Boards have been formally invited to provide input to this training review. Any
comments or written submissions should be made to the Director or Head of Awards and Training at
NERC. <p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>Use of the <a name="www">World Wide Web </a>and Electronic Mail</b><p>

<p>

Awards and Training already has a discrete section within the NERC pages on the World Wide Web
(http://www.nerc.ac.uk/awards/index.htm.). Over the coming months we will be utilising the WWW
more
and more as the vehicle for providing greater speed and penetration of information, news, policy
updates
and accessibility to booklets, newsletters etc.<p>

<p>

Booklets: One major change is that we will be greatly reducing the circulation of printed booklets.
Annual
targeted circulation of new editions of booklets will be 2according to the practice mentioned below.
Extra
(limited) copies of booklets will only be provided on written request.<p>

<p>

     Research Grants booklet: 1996/97 hard copy version available from 31 July. Circulation will be
to Heads
of Department and University Registries. <p>

<p>

     Studentships booklet: 1996/97 hard copy version to all new and current students, Heads of
Department
and Registries. <p>

<p>

     Fellowships booklet: 1996/97 version, as has been past practice, only to prospective applicants
on request.<p>

<p>

Updating booklets once a year against the background of rapidly changing policy, means that hard copy
is
soon out of date. Use of the World Wide Web allows policy changes and amendments to be
incorporated
more regularly and rapidly. This new practice will also help to overcome the difficulties of prospective
applicants consulting out of date versions of the booklets.<p>

<p>

Application forms: The A&amp;T entry on the NERC WWW pages also includes application forms for
research
grants and fellowship competitions. These can be down loaded and represents a further step toward our
longer term objectives of full electronic processing of applications.<p>

<p>

Use of electronic mail: We are embarking on the construction of a directory of Departmental e-mail
addresses using currently available sources. The intention is to use this directory as a means of flagging
up
changes to policy and procedures which will be detailed elsewhere. There will also be a growing
tendency
for us to use e-mail as the mechanism for responding quickly to general enquiries. In this regard we
urge all
people writing to NERC to quote an e-mail address.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<a name="con"><b>Concordat on Research Careers for Contract Workers in Universities</b></a><p>

<p>

This agreement between various parties comes into effect on 1 September 1996 and there are
expectations
and obligations for everyone involved. The greatest interest for Research Councils is in the impact it
will
have on terms and conditions for research assistants on grants. In respect of maternity leave, long term
sickness, promotion and merit pay, Research Council obligations have been incorporated into the recent
versions of all booklets.NERC wishes to follow this up by obtaining a signed declaration from all
NERC
fellows and current grant holders, on behalf of research assistants, that they have read the Concordat
and
agree the arrangements in respective of their contract or research grant award. The existence of the
Concordat and its integration into research grant assessment processes, will be emphasised at the
October
round of RGTAC meetings in the context of the desire for NERC to meet full necessary and justified
costs
of research grants.<p>

<p>

Research Councils are also keen to initiate the monitoring of the impact of the introduction of the
Concordat. To this end all grant holders who submit final reports after the <p>

1 October 1996, will be asked to include questionnaires completed by all research assistants appointed
under the grant. The questionnaire seeks information on career management, training etc and can be
returned directly to the Research Council. Although the first review is not scheduled until 18 months
after
the introduction, collecting information now will provide a dataset which gives better insights into its
impact.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

<b>A&amp;T Customer <a name="Survey">Survey</b></a><p>

<p>

We are extremely grateful for all the responses to the "customer survey" questionnaire circulated with
the
last issue of the newsletter. Detailed analysis of the returns revealed the following general points:<p>

<p>

     The vast majority of returns emphasised the highly transparent and professional service. It is
clear that the
community has recognised that efficiency gains aimed at releasing more funds for research and training
have inevitably had an impact on the level of service we can provide.<p>

<p>

     The booklets, newsletter, policy updates etc are all viewed as informative.<p>

<p>

     There is an overwhelming desire for much greater use of electronic communication for
transmitting
publications such as booklets, newsletter, applications forms. There is also a groundswell of opinion for
use of e-mail both in response to general queries and for electronic processing of grant applications.<p>

<p>

     Many responses advocated the use of the World Wide Web pages to include details of awards
made,
notification of thematic programme opportunities, announcements of initiatives etc. <p>

<p>

     Indications are that some improvements are necessary to the fielding and handling of telephone
enquiries
especially for those seeking prompt policy advice and guidance.3Awards and Training Section
Administration:<p>

<p>

This section is split into four main areas dealing with pre-administration of thematic (known as
Thematic
Applications) and non-thematic grants (known as Non-Thematic Applications), pre and post award
administration of research grants (known as Maintenance) and the pre and post award administration of
studentships and fellowships (known as Post Graduate Support Sedtion). Listed below are the
personnel
on each section with their phone numbers. The code for Swindon is 01793. Our fax number is 01793
411616.<p>

<p>

<p>

<p>

