<HEADER>
<TITLE>NCS at British Antarctic Survey</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1><P>
<H2>British Antarctic Survey at Cambridge</H2>
<P>
The British Antarctic Survey (BAS) is responsible for all the British Government's scientific
research in the Antarctic, South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands.  Five scientific
research stations in the Antarctic are manned throughout the year.  Halley and Faraday are
used as lower and upper atmospheric physics laboratories, Signy and Bird Island for
biological studies and Rothera as a centre for earth and marine sciences. Two Royal Research
ships, Bransfield and James Clark Ross, supply these stations annually, as well as providing
floating scientific research platforms.  The Air Unit operates four de Havilland wheel-ski Twin
Otter aircraft from Rothera and one Dash-7 type aircraft.  The British Antarctic Survey has
approximately 470 staff, most of which are scientific staff. 
<P>
BAS carries out a wide range of science, as diverse as microbiology and the physics of the
solar system. The scientific research of the Survey is focused on five major and three minor
"themes". These "themes" are the pattern and change in the physical environment of the
Antarctic, both man-made and natural; geological evolution of West Antarctic; dynamics of
Antarctic terrestrial and freshwater ecosystems; structure and dynamics of the Southern
Ocean ecosystem from small phytoplankton to birds, such as albatrosses, and seals;  physics
of solar terrestrial phenomena from Antarctica, looking at the unique magnetic fields;
humans in isolated polar communities and Antarctic geographic information and mapping,
recent work including  a Digital Antarctic Map.  
</P>
<HR>
<H3>Computing in BAS</H3> 
<P>
<A HREF = "/ncs/">NERC Computer Services</A> (NCS) support a wide variety of hardware, software and distributed
computing facilities.  These include a VAXCluster composed of a 600-410 and 7 VAX
workstations, several UNIX workstations from Sun, Silicon Graphics and Digital, and servers
(including a file and software server, and an ORACLE database server).  A range of output
devices is available including a number of  colour PostScript printers.  Around half the 450
PCs are connected to the Ethernet Local Area Network and integrated with the local
computing facilities.  BAS has installed Novell servers, which are run by Institute staff. 
Access to the wider national and international network is via the JANET/UKERNA network. 
BAS staff run satellite communications to the Antarctic, which allows an exchange of
electronic data and messages.  
</P><HR>
<H3>NERC Computer Services staff at Cambridge</H3>
<P>
The NCS Local Support team is comprised of three staff. Computing facilities and support are
provided for the <A HREF = "/ncs/smru.html">Sea Mammal Research Unit (SMRU)</A>, also based in Cambridge. NCS central
support groups provide additional support from <A HREF = "/ncs/keyworth.html">Keyworth</A>, <A HREF = "/ncs/#swindon">Swindon</A> and
<A HREF = "http://www.nwl.ac.uk/ncs/">Wallingford</A>. 
</P><HR>
Contact
<P>
<address>
<P>
Dr Nick Teall<br>
NERC Computer Services<br>
c/o British Antarctic Survey<br>
High Cross <br>
Madingley Road<br>
Cambridge CB3 0ET<br>
