<HTML>
<HEADER>
<TITLE>NCS at Sea Mammal Research Unit, Cambridge</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1>

<H2>Sea Mammal Research Unit, Cambridge</H2>
<P>
The Sea Mammal Research Unit (SMRU) is concerned with all aspects of the ecology of seals
and whales, both in the UK and worldwide.  How many whales are left in the world's oceans?
Are they still under threat from man's activities?  Is the fishing industry really losing huge
sums of money because of the competition from seals? These are the types of question that
SMRU was set up to answer.  Up to 25 staff are based in  Cambridge,  most of whom are
scientific staff. 
 <P>
SMRU's principal responsibility (under the 1970 Conservation of Seals Act) is to provide
scientific advice to UK government departments on the conservation and management of
marine mammals.
<P>
Marine mammals are particularly difficult to study, since they spend large amounts of time
beneath the water's surface.  SMRU has developed novel techniques to address this problem.
An example is the deployment of over one hundred satellite-relayed data loggers, each of
which allows up to 100 days of environmental, movement and behavioural data to be
collected over thousands of miles.  The challenge is to interpret and understand these very
large datasets in relation to the animals' environment and life history. The datasets are
spatially and temporally complex, so relationships can be hard to see and hypotheses
difficult to formulate and test. State-of-the-art workstation-based solutions are used to
visualise such datasets and access underlying data, allowing statistical testing and model
building. This work will help to identify high productivity areas in the oceans and critical
habitats for marine mammals.  
</P><HR>
<H3>Computing in SMRU</H3>
<P>
<A HREF = "/ncs/">NERC Computer Services</A> (NCS) supports a variety of hardware, software and distributed
computing facilities.  These include a VAXCluster, a Sun SPARC 10/40 workstation with an
Evans &amp; Sutherland Freedom Graphics accelerator, an ORACLE database server, a Novell file
server and approximately 20 PCs, running DOS and Windows.  A range of output devices is
available, including colour PostScript printers.  Most PCs are connected to the Ethernet Local
Area Network (LAN) and integrated with the local computing facilities.  Access to the wider
national and international network is via the JANET/UKERNA network. 
</P><HR>
<H3>NERC Computer Services staff at Cambridge</H3>
<P>
The NCS Local Support team is comprised of three staff. The group provides support for the
<A HREF = "/ncs/bas.html">British Antarctic Survey</A>'s computer facilities, also based in Cambridge.  NCS central groups
provide additional support from bases at <A HREF = "/ncs/keyworth.html">Keyworth</A>, <A HREF = "/ncs/#swindon">Swindon</A> and
<A HREF = "http://www.nwl.ac.uk/ncs/">Wallingford</A>.  
</P><HR>
Contact
<P>
<address>
<P>
Dr Nick Teall<br>
NERC Computer Services<br>
c/o British Antarctic Survey<br>
High Cross <br>
Madingley Road<br>
Cambridge CB3 0ET<br>
<P>
Tel +44 1223 251400  (switchboard) or +44 1223 251447 (direct line)<br>
Fax +44 1223 62616<br>
<P>
n.teall@ncs.nerc.ac.uk
</P>
</address>
</P>
<A HREF = "http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC  = "/images/logoicon.gif" align=middle>To the NERC home page</A>
