<HEAD>

<TITLE>Institute of Terrestrial Ecology, Monk's Wood and Bangor</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC = "/images/ncs.gif"></H1>
<HR>

<H2>Institute of Terrestrial Ecology, Monk's Wood and Bangor</H2>
<P>

ITE Monk's Wood and ITE Bangor are stations of the Institute of
Terrestrial Ecology. Following the reorganisation of NERC, ITE (South) and ITE (North) have
been amalgamated as part of the Centre for Ecology and Hydrology. Staff at the institutes
undertake specialist ecological research on subjects ranging from micro-organisms to trees
and mammals, from coastal habitats to uplands, from derelict land to air pollution.
<P><HR>
<H3>Institute of Terrestrial Ecology </H3>
<P>
ITE Monk's Wood is host to the Environmental Information Centre (EIC), which is one of six
designated data centres in the NERC. Its function is to manage corporate data holdings in
the fields of terrestrial ecology and rural land use, and to make these data widely accessible
for applications in science, policy and for wealth creation. The Biological Records Centre
(BRC) is one major component of the Centre. It collates records of species location, habitat
etc., creating a unique resource of  spatially and temporally referenced data. The Centre also
undertakes extensive research into methods of environmental data acquisition and
processing in the fields of remote sensing and Geographical Information Systems (GIS).
<P>
ITE Monk's Wood is also host to the British National Space Centre's
<A HREF = "http://uh.nmt.ac.uk/bnsc/">Remote Sensing Applications
Development Unit (RSADU)</A>
and the Eastern Rivers Group of the Institute of
Freshwater Ecology (IFE).
<P>
<HR>
<H3>Computing facilities at ITE Monk's Wood and Bangor</H3>
<P>
The computer systems at ITE Monk's Wood use a Local Area Network (LAN), which is in turn
connected to the wide area JANET/UKERNA service. The network topology at Monk's Wood is
Ethernet running DECnet, TCP/IP and IPX, providing both Local Area VAX Cluster (LAVC) and
Local Area Network (LAN) functionality.
<P>
The LAVC comprises a VAX 4000/300 boot node with three MicroVAX II machines and 6
VAXstations. Specialised image processing hardware is supported by VAX systems. The
migration to a distributed computing environment has led to the installation of eight Sun
SPARC 10 workstations and a DECstation 5000/240 UNIX system. A Sun SPARCserver 10
M512MP functions as database server.
<P>
PC integration is provided by Novell NetWare, running on a Compaq Prosignia with
approximately 100 client PCs.
<P>
The Bangor systems are again based on an Ethernet LAN and comprise a Sun SPARC 10,
providing both GIS capability and connection to JANET/UKERNA. PC integration is achieved
using Novell NetWare.
<P>
<HR>
<H3>NERC Computer Services staff </H3>
<P>
Three <A HREF = "/ncs/">NCS</A> staff provide computing support at the Monk's Wood site. The Bangor site is
supported remotely from Monk's Wood. NCS central groups provide additional support from bases at
<A HREF = "/ncs/keyworth.html">Keyworth</A>,
<A HREF = "/ncs/#swindon">Swindon</A> and
<A HREF = "http://www.nwl.ac.uk/ncs/">Wallingford</A>.
<P><HR>
Contact for ITE Monk's Wood and ITE Bangor
<P><address><P>
Roger Parsell<br>
