<HEADER>

<TITLE>Institute of Freshwater Ecology, Windermere</TITLE>

</HEADER>

<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC = "/images/ncs.gif"></H1>
<HR>

<H2>Institute of Freshwater Ecology, Windermere</H2>
<P>
The Windermere Laboratory of the <A HREF="http://wiua.nwi.ac.uk/">Institute of Freshwater Ecology</A> (IFE), situated in the Lake
District, undertakes long-term and multi-disciplinary research into freshwater sciences. This
includes:
<UL>
<LI>services to the scientific community (for example, Culture Collection of Algae and Protozoa),
<LI>maintenance of long-term research on fish populations,
<LI>sub-cellular research (ie bacterial endosymbionts of protozoa), 
<LI>whole ecosystem studies (using remote sensing techniques)
<LI>community studies of freshwater invertebrates
<LI>chemical research (for example, detailed study of species interaction)
<LI>production of predictive models of soil/water interactions
</UL>
<P><HR>
<H3>Computing at IFE Windermere</H3>
<P>
Site computing is based on the distributed computing (client/server) model devised by <A HREF = "/ncs/">NCS</A>.
A major component of this model is the Local Area network (LAN), which connects a range
of computer systems on site.  The LAN has a dual File Distributed Data Interface (FDDI)
backbone, running at 100Mbps, connecting the hubs in each of the three buildings.
<P>
A Wide Area Network (WAN) connection is provided, linking the site with JANET/UKERNA and
giving access to other NERC computer systems and to the Internet.
 <P>
Main computing facilities are provided via Novell NetWare, which allows the 70+ PCs on site
to access centrally installed applications software. It additionally provides a central back-up
arrangement to secure disk space. The Novell NetWare runs on a Compaq Proliant, which has
built in resilience and fault tolerance. A second Compaq machine, used for LAN management,
provides a standby facility and can, if necessary, be brought quickly into action as a
replacement system.
<P>
An E-mail server, running WordPerfect Office, is linked to Novell and provides calendar, diary
and scheduling facilities, as well as advanced E-mail functionality.
<P>
The main Unix server consists of a Sun SPARC classic with 40Mb of RAM and 3.5Gb of disk
space. As well as being a UNIX application and file server, this machine provides
communications services to and from the wide-area network. Another UNIX machine acts as
file/compute server and is used primarily for intensive statistical and modelling applications.
<P><HR>
<H3>Software</H3>
<P>
There is a large range of software available on site for both PC and UNIX-based systems. PC
applications are being standardised on Microsoft Windows-based products, including
WordPerfect for Windows, Microsoft Excel, Vista eXceed and Visual Basic. UNIX software
available on site includes SAS, Genstat, Internet News and Fortran.
<P><HR>
<H3>NERC Computer Services (NCS) staff at Windermere</H3>
<P>
<A HREF = "/ncs/">NCS</A> Local Support on site consists of one member of staff, who is responsible for the day to
day running of the computer systems. Activities include local support for Institute staff,
security monitoring, operations, system and consumables procurement, fault-logging and
engineer call-outs. Additional assistance comes from the NCS central groups, who offer
support for more technical problems, carry out installations and interact with suppliers for
centrally-funded hardware and software.
<P>
Contact
<P>
<address><P>
Paul Cullimore<br>
NERC Computer Services<br>
Institute of Freshwater Ecology<br>
Windermere Laboratory<br>
The Ferry House<br>
Far Sawrey<br>
Ambleside<br>
Cumbria LA22 0LP<br>
<P>
Tel +44 15394 42468<br>
Fax +44 15394 46914<br>
<P>
p.cullimore@ncs.nerc.ac.uk
<P>
