<HEADER>

<TITLE>Institute of Terrestrial Ecology, Merlewood</TITLE>

</HEADER>

<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC = "/images/ncs.gif"></H1>
<HR>

<H2>Institute of Terrestrial Ecology, Merlewood</H2>
<P>
Merlewood is one of six research stations belonging to the Institute of  Terrestrial Ecology
(ITE) and is situated in the Lake District in Cumbria. Following the reorganisation of NERC,
ITE (South) and ITE (North) have been amalgamated as part of the Centre for Ecology and
Hydrology. The station undertakes research into various fields including radioactivity, soils
and nutrient cycling, plant ecology and land use, much of which provides important data for
world-wide use.
<P>
An example of the work carried out at Merlewood is research into the distribution and
movement of man-made radionuclides in the environment, more recently concentrating on
the fate of the fall-out from the Chernobyl accident. The main chemical laboratory of the
Institute of Terrestrial Ecology is also based at Merlewood. Here the Analytical Chemistry
Group, with its suite of modern, purpose-built laboratories, provide the necessary support
for the research scientists, as well as for other research institutes, universities, government
organisations and the private sector.
<P>
Constant advances in scientific technology means that Merlewood continues to research into
many areas of great scientific importance and are heavily dependent on an efficient, reliable
and well-equipped computer service.
<P><HR>
<H3>Computing facilities at ITE Merlewood</H3>
<P>
A fully distributed computing environment is operated at Merlewood, based on client/server
technology. The focal point of this is the Local Area Network (LAN) and the following services
are provided by the various servers on the LAN:-
<UL>
<LI>a UNIX file/compute server consisting of a Silicon Graphics R4000 machine with 32Mb
memory and 9Gb disk storage. This provides a general UNIX facility for the site.
<LI>the main database functionality is provided by ORACLE, running on a Sun SPARCserver
10/51 with 64Mb memory and 6Gb disk storage. This machine is accessed using ORACLE
SQL*NET.
<LI>the site communications server consists of a Sun IPC machine with 24Mb memory and 1Gb
disk storage. Among its many tasks, this machine provides the authorization for access to
all UNIX machines on the site and for access to the JANET/UKERNA network.
<LI>a mail server, based on a 486 PC running WordPerfect Office, provides electronic diary
and scheduling facilities to all the networked PCs on site.
<LI>a PC server running Novell NetWare provides PC connectivity. This machine is a Compaq
Prosignia 486DX2-66 with 32Mb memory and 5Gb disk storage. A backup PC server is
maintained for immediate switching in, should the main PC server fail; it is also used for
various tasks such network traffic and NetWare performance monitoring.
</UL>
<P>
A small VAXCluster, consistent of two VAXStation-3100 and two MicroVAX II machines, is
maintained to provide the required VAX-based functionality for activities that have not yet
migrated to the new technology. These include the Terrestrial and Freshwater Sciences
Directorate Management Information System (TFSDIS), an in-house Laboratory Information
Management System used by the Chemistry section, and the Radionuclide Sections SPECTRAN-F system, used to collect data from the counting equipment and analyse the results.
<P>
In addition, several UNIX machines are used in conjunction with geographical information
systems (GIS), mainly by the Land Use research group and the Environmental Change network
(ECN), which is coordinated from Merlewood.
<P>
There are approximately 60 PCs on site and all are networked. The overriding aim is to give
the scientists access to all the site facilities from their desktop, whether they are using a
PC, accessing a UNIX machine, using GIS, sending electronic mail or accessing external
services throughout this country or abroad.
<P>
Merlewood is connected to the wide-area JANET/UKERNA network via a 128 kilostream line
into the University of Manchester Regional Computing Centre (UMRCC), giving staff access to
the facilities available on remote machines both in this country and abroad. A router
provides one means of connectivity between the LAN and WAN.
<P>
There are many software packages available on the site. The main ones used being ARC/Info
(GIS), ORACLE (relational database management system, GENSTAT and Minitab (statistics), SAS
(graphics and statistics), UNIRAS (graphics) and numerous PC packages including WordPerfect,
Systat, Excel, Word, Vista eXceed, Papyrus.
<P><HR>
<H3>NERC Computer Services (NCS) support staff</H3>
<P>
<A HREF = "/ncs/">NCS</A> Local Support at the site consists of two staff, who are responsible for the day to day
running of the computing facilities. They, in turn, have access to central support specialists,
both for backup with the more technically demanding problems and to carry out work, such
as new installations, on behalf of the local team.
<P>
Contact
<P><address><P>
Allan Nelson<br>
NERC Computer Services<br>
Institute of Terrestrial Ecology<br>
Merlewood Research Station<br>
Windermere Road<br>
Grange-over-Sands<br>
Cumbria LA11 6JU<br>
<P>
Tel 05395 32264<br>
Fax 05395 34705<br>
<P>
a.nelson@ncs.nerc.ac.uk<br>
