<html>
<header>
<TITLE>NCS Service Quality</TITLE>                                 
</header>
<body>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1>
<H2>Service Quality</H2>
<P>
The number of computer systems managed by NCS rose in line with expectations to
around 350 by year-end.  System availability was generally good reflecting industry-wide
trends towards improved hardware reliability and greater operating system stability.  The
deployment of distributed computing technology, coupled with reliable system
components led to a re-examination of hardware maintenance requirements.  A new
policy, reducing contracted maintenance on all except shared server systems, was
introduced with the intention of achieving future cost savings.  Paradoxically, air
conditioning failures, lightning strikes and power failures resulted in general loss of
service at a number of sites and steps were taken to limit future problems from these
sources.  Liaison with strategic suppliers was maintained through progress meetings and,
as in past years, these proved a useful forum for progressing technical issues and
exploring mutually acceptable cost-saving opportunities.  Competition in the market
place obliged suppliers to focus resources on opportunities for volume sales.  As a result,
some suppliers were unable to provide the level of support for NERC's business which NCS
had come to expect.  Service Level Agreements were negotiated with the Institute of
Terrestrial Ecology (South), the Plymouth Marine Laboratory, the Institute of
Oceanographic Sciences, Deacon Laboratory and the British Geological Survey and their
effect will become apparent during 93/94.  The most comprehensive of these is a
"Facilities Management Agreement" with the British Geological Survey which sets out all of
the services which NCS will provide in return for an agreed level of funding.  The
agreement includes standards for the quality of service and measures by which this can
be monitored.  This form of agreement is likely to become the norm for all institutes
from 1994/95 onwards and negotiations with other institutes were conducted with this in
mind.  
<P>
As in previous years, computer user group meetings were held on a regular basis at all
major sites and issues of general concern were discussed at two meetings of the NERC
Computer Users Committee.  The role of user groups was examined by the Services and
Facilities Committee as part of a review of its technical sub-committees.  The Committee
concluded that user groups are an important element in the quality management system
for computer services and confirmed its support for their continuance.  
In order to obtain a measure of customer satisfaction, a survey was conducted in which a
sample of registered users, selected at random, were invited to express their views on a
range of quality factors.  The results were encouraging and indicated that the service
provided matched the expectations of its users in most respects.  The survey will be
repeated at regular intervals to monitor progress against this baseline.  The survey also
provided much useful information which will be used in business development.
</P>
<br>
<A HREF = "http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC  = "/images/logoicon.gif" align=middle>To the NERC home page</A>
</body>
</html>



