<HEADER>
<TITLE>NCS at IOS Deacon Laboratory</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1>

<H2>Institute of Oceanographic Sciences, Deacon Laboratory
</H2>
<P>
The
<A HREF = "http://www.nwo.ac.uk/iosdl/">Institute of Oceanographic Sciences</A>,
Deacon Laboratory (IOSDL) is located at Wormley in
Surrey. Scientists there carry out research into many fields of marine science, including
among others:
<DL>
<DT>Physical oceanography<DD>numerical modelling of the oceans, and participation in the major 
  World Ocean Circulation Experiment (WOCE)
<DT>Marine Geology and Geophysics<DD>studies of the mid-ocean ridges and ocean-bottom      
     seismology, wide-area surveys using GLORIA (Geological Long-Range Inclined Asdic)
<DT>Marine Chemistry and Biology<DD>studies of biological and chemical fluxes in the oceans
<DT><A HREF = "http://www.nwo.ac.uk/iosdl/OTech/">Instrument development</A><DD>much of the science is supported by unique instrumentation
developed and built at IOSDL, such as GLORIA and other underwater acoustic imaging
platforms. IOSDL also plays a major part in the NERC Community Research Project developing
the autonomous submersible vehicle
<A HREF = "http://www.nwo.ac.uk/iosdl/OTech/asub/cotdasub.htm">Autosub</A>.
</DL>
<P>
In early 1995, the staff at IOSDL will relocate to the new Southampton Oceanography Centre,
where they will join colleagues from the <A HREF = "/ncs/rennell.html">James Rennell Centre for Ocean Circulation</A>, the NERC
<A HREF = "ftp://ua.nrb.ac.uk/pub/rvshome.html">Research Vessel Services</A>
group at Barry and the University of Southampton.
</P><HR>
<H3>Computing facilities at IOSDL</H3>
<P>
IOSDL has recently migrated from a mainframe-based computing service to a network of
UNIX workstations. This is in keeping with the <A HREF = "/ncs/">NCS</A> Distributed Computing Environment policy.
Currently some 28 UNIX workstations are in use, including a file server and database server.
Most of these are Sun machines, with some Silicon Graphics workstations.
<P>
As well as the workstations, the Institute owns approximately 130 IBM PCs and 60 Apple
Macintosh machines, many of them connected to the site Ethernet Local Area Network (LAN).
An increasing amount of work is done on these 'personal workstations', and a Novell server
has recently been purchased with the intention of improving the sharing of files and
peripherals across UNIX, PC and Macintosh platforms.
<P>
The UNIX machines have a total of approximately 80 Gigabytes of disk space, mainly
distributed among the workstations. This is backed up to professional standards by NCS using
Legato Networker software and a DAT (Digital Audio Tape) drive with a robot stacker
mechanism.
<P>
Some image processing work, for example that for the GLORIA project, is still carried out on
a MicroVAX machine, although moves to UNIX are planned here too.
<P>
Although most of the IOSDL data processing is carried out 'in-house', the major numerical
modelling tasks make use of supercomputers accessible to the academic community, such
as the Cray machine at the Rutherford-Appleton Laboratory.
<P>
High quality hard-copy output is available using both A3 and A0 size colour plotters.
</P><HR>
<H3>Software</H3>
<P>
As with many scientific organisations, much of the programming work is still carried out
using the FORTRAN language. However, NCS has also adopted a successful policy of providing
industry-leading software where appropriate, and much use is made of the UNIRAS graphics
package, NAG subroutine libraries, and the ORACLE database. The latter not only contain data
from several scientific projects, but are also used to run the ORACLE*LIBRARIES package. This
was recently funded by NCS and is used to provide public access by IOSDL users and other
authorised customers to the resources of the National Oceanographic Library, based at
Wormley.
<P>
Geographical Information Systems (GIS) software is starting to be used more, following the
introduction of an NCS-funded system running the LaserScan 'Horizon' package. This
provided valuable initial experience in the benefits of GIS. Major collaborative research
projects now use ARC/Info GIS software.
<P>
Other specialist software tools include the 'Software Through Pictures' package, a CASE
(Computer Aided Software Engineering) tool used by the Autosub team to develop mission
control software for the vehicle. In the future, more use is expected to be made of state-of-
the-art software provided by NCS, for example the ERDAS image processing package and the
AVS graphics and data processing software.
</P><HR>
<H3>NCS staff and services</H3>
<P>
Currently IOSDL has 3 NCS staff supporting around 100 scientific and administrative computer
users. These staff provide the Institute with the local interface to wider NCS services. The
main
<A HREF = "http://www.nwo.ac.uk/ncs/">on-site services</A> include:
<UL>
<LI>operation and back-up of  workstations and Novell server
<LI>installation and configuration of new systems
<LI>front-line support for users' programming queries and problem diagnosis
<LI>monitoring of the site LAN and fault diagnosis and rectification
<LI>planning and project management of future computing provision on-site
</UL>
NCS central support groups provide additional support from <A HREF = "/ncs/keyworth.html">Keyworth</A>, <A HREF = "/ncs/#swindon">Swindon</A> and
<A HREF = "http://www.nwl.ac.uk/ncs/">Wallingford</A>.
</P><HR>
Contact
<P>
<address>
<P>
Dr Phil Stanford<br>
NERC Computer Services<br>
Institute of Oceanographic Sciences, Deacon Laboratory<br>
Brook Road<br>
Wormley<br>
Surrey GU8 5UB<br>
<P>
Tel +44 1428 684141<br>
Fax +44 1428 683066<br>
<P>
p.stanford@ncs.nerc.ac.uk
</P>
</address>
</P>
<A HREF = "http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC  = "/images/logoicon.gif" align=middle>To the NERC home page</A>
