<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>NCS at James Rennell Centre for Ocean Circulation</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY><H1><IMG SRC="/images/ncs.gif"></H1>
<HR>
<H2>James Rennell Centre for Ocean Circulation</H2>
<P><A HREF="http://www.nso.ac.uk/">The James Rennell Centre for Ocean
Circulation</A> (JRC) is situated near Southampton at the Chilworth
Research Centre. James Rennell (1742-1830) was the founder of the
science of oceanography. The Centre forms part of the <A HREF="/ncs/wormley.html"
>Institute of Oceanographic Sciences</A> (IOS), with the role of
providing the focus for the United Kingdom contribution to the <A HREF="http://www.nso.ac.uk/WOCE/woce.html"
>World Ocean Circulation Experiment</A> (WOCE). This work involves
collaboration between scientists from forty nations during the 1990s.
WOCE will use satellites, dozens of ships and thousands of instruments
to take a comprehensive "snapshot" of the physical properties of the
ocean. The goal is to develop a large, high quality data set for use in
developing numerical models of ocean circulation and physical processes.
It is hoped to couple these with atmospheric models to simulate, and
perhaps predict, how the ocean influences the climate over periods of
decades.
</P>
<P>The Centre has about sixty scientific and support staff. The Centre
will join the rest of IOS and
<A HREF="ftp://ua.nrb.ac.uk/pub/rvshome.html">Research Vessel Services</A>
at the new dockside Southampton Oceanography Centre in Spring 1995, and
will work alongside university research teams.
</P>
<HR>
<H3>Computing at the Centre</H3>
<P>The Centre has approximately 60 networked Macintosh machines and 19
UNIX (Silicon Graphics and Sun) workstations. The main file server is an
Epoch optical/magnetic system, which holds 120 Gbytes of data on-line.
Applications software used includes the graphics and visualisation
packages UNIRAS, AVS and PVWAVE. Powerful workstations are used to run
large scale ocean models at medium resolution: additionally, the
research teams make good use of  Cray supercomputers at the
Rutherford-Appleton Laboratory, and elsewhere, to model at high
resolution. Work is underway to program a global model to run on the new
Cray T3D at Edinburgh Parallel Computing Centre, the fastest
supercomputer in Europe.
</P>
<HR>
<H3>NERC Computer Services (NCS) staff at the Centre</H3>
<P>Two NCS staff provide computing support at the site and have
particular skills in network and UNIX systems administration,
programming and graphics applications support. NCS also takes the lead
in data management for the Centre. NCS central support groups provide
additional support from <A HREF="/ncs/keyworth.html">Keyworth</A>, <A HREF="/ncs/#swindon"
>Swindon</A> and <A HREF="http://www.nwl.ac.uk/ncs/">Wallingford</A>.
</P>
<HR> Contact
<P></P>
<ADDRESS><P>Bruce Dupee<BR> NERC Computer Services<BR> James Rennell
Centre for Ocean Circulation<BR> Gamma House<BR> Chilworth Research
Centre<BR> Chilworth<BR> Southampton SO1 7NS<BR>
</P><P>Tel +44 1703 766184<BR> Fax +44 1703 767507<BR>
</P><P>b.dupee@ncs.nerc.ac.uk
</P>
</ADDRESS>
<A HREF="http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC="/images/logoicon.gif" ALIGN="middle"
>To the NERC home page</A></BODY>
