<HEAD>
<TITLE>NCS at Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1><P>
<H2>Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory</H2>
<P>
The
<A HREF = "http://www.nbi.ac.uk/">Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory</A> (POL) is located at Bidston Observatory in
Birkenhead on Merseyside and has 70 scientific staff.  Its mission is:

<blockquote>to undertake world class strategic research in physical oceanography with special focus on
shelf seas processes, global sea level and tides. To develop novel tools for this research
programme and for monitoring sea-levels around the British Isles. To lead the shelf edge and
modelling programmes of the LOIS (Land-Ocean Interaction Study) community research
project and to contribute to the European collaborative project OMEX (Ocean Margin
Exchange). To improve understanding of shelf seas processes, with the help  of observations
and mathematical models, and to develop wave/surge currents, temperature and water quality
models of the seas around Britain. To support the oceanographic community, government and
industry by technology transfer and by managing the British Oceanographic Data Centre, the
IAPSO (International Association for the Physical Sciences of the Ocean) Permanent Service
for Mean Sea Level and the NERC Computer Centre for Shelf Seas Modelling.</blockquote>
</P><HR>
<H3>Computing facilities at POL</H3>
<P>
Site computing is based on a Local Area Network (LAN). The LAN backbone uses fibre optic
cabling to link  three intelligent hubs, one per building. From these hubs network connections
to offices are made using 10 Base T  (IBM Type 1) cabling. A 64 kilobits per second link
is available to the JANET (Joint Academic Network) IP (Internet Protocols) Service known
as JIPS. 
<P>
Computers on site include workstations running the UNIX  operating system and PCs running
DOS and Windows. Also, there is a mass store device using Unitree software, running on a
Convex C220 attached to a Metrum VHS tape robot. Additionally, there is a Cray EL
supercomputer for LOIS modelling work. Network protocols in use are TCP/IP for UNIX
systems and Novell for PCs. All systems are integrated wherever possible.
</P><HR>
<H3>NERC Computer Services (NCS) staff at POL</H3>
<P>
<A HREF = "/ncs/">NCS</A> staff at POL comprise a senior officer and four local support staff, two of whom are
part-time. Duties include running the network, managing site infrastructure equipment,
procurement and disposal of equipment, data management, supporting many software packages 
(for example, ORACLE, UNIRAS, WordPerfect) and running a Help Desk service. Staff are
committed to Total Quality Management and a team approach to their work.  
</P><HR>
Contact
<P>
<address>
<P>
Dr Colin Stephens<br>
NERC Computer Services<br>
Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory<br>
Bidston Observatory<br>
Birkenhead L43 7RA<br>
<P>
Tel +44 151 653 8633<br>
Fax +44 151 653 6269<br>
<P>
c.stephens@ncs.nerc.ac.uk</P>
</address>
