<html>
<header>
<TITLE>NCS Local Support</TITLE>
</header>
<body>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1>
<H2>Local Support</H2>
<P>
The regional management structure, which was introduced in the previous year, was
endorsed by Management Services in a major review of the organisation and structure of
NCS.  The nomination of liaison officers within the infrastructure groups at Keyworth and
Wallingford further improved links with regional teams.
</P>
<HR>
<H3>South West</H3>
<P>
Work began on enhancing communications facilities at the Dorset sites through
investment in the Local Area Network and better access to the Wide Area Network. 
Institute investment in personal computing was supported through improved backup
facilities.  At the Plymouth Marine Laboratory support activity focused on Unix
applications and further integration of the network of personal computers in which the
Institute has made a heavy investment.  The Image Analysis Unit, based at the University
of Plymouth, moved into new accommodation adjacent to a purpose-built student
training facility.  The unit provided support for a number of NERC cruises during the year
by transmitting processed satellite images to research vessels at sea for improved cruise
management.  
</P><HR>
<H3>South East</H3>
<P>
The replacement of the IBM system at Wallingford was a complex task and drew heavily on
the resources of staff in the Southern Area throughout the year.  After extensive
consultation with users, a decision was taken to install a distributed computing system in
accordance with the IT strategy developed by NCS and a series of procurements were
conducted throughout the year to put in place the major system components.  The IBM
system was installed under the earlier "dual architecture" policy and was configured to
provide services to users throughout NERC.  It was therefore particularly important to
ensure that all such users were able to transfer their work to local systems before
closure of the IBM service.  To make this possible, all data accessible only on the IBM
system was copied to new computer media.  As part of the replacement programme, the
Local Area Network at Wallingford was substantially upgraded and an opportunity was
taken to rationalise and extend the cabling system.  New system components were
introduced progressively during the year to allow users to transfer their scientific
applications with minimal disruption.  At the James Rennell Centre, the Epoch file server
was upgraded to improve backup functionality and increase capacity.  This site was the
first to be equipped with a distributed computing system and NCS continued to gain
valuable experience in the management of such systems, encouraged by user pressure for
improved functionality.  Computing facilities on the site were enhanced by further
investment in workstations and upgrades to those already in place.  An opportunity was
taken to reorganise the management of shared files in accordance with the NERC file
structure.  The IBM system at IOSDL, Wormley continued to be heavily used, although the
requirement for user support moved significantly towards Unix and PC-based
applications.  A new library management system was installed, based on ORACLE-
LIBRARIES, to provide improved support for library applications within the Marine and
Atmospheric Sciences Directorate.  This service will also be made available to other
institutes as required and complements the LIBERTAS library management system, which
is based at Keyworth.
</P><HR>
<H3>East Anglia</H3>
<P>
Computing facilities at Monk's Wood were substantially upgraded by extending the VAX
cluster to include a number of additional GIS workstations.  Scientific activities at Monk's
Wood are heavily dependent on the use of GIS technology and NCS staff have become
particularly skilled in supporting such applications.  Institute investment in personal
computing led to a substantial programme of systems integration and commissioning. 
The Local Area Network was extended to improve on-site connectivity and a router was
installed to provide access to JIPS.  Responsibility for providing computer support to ITE
staff based at Bangor was transferred to the East Anglia Region at the request of Institute
management.  The VAX service at the British Antarctic Survey, was heavily used and
functionality was improved by updates to the operating system and applications packages. 
A Unix workstation was purchased for developing image analysis applications and the
Herbarium database was successfully transferred from the IBM system at Wallingford. 
Network connectivity was improved through a programme of work shared between NCS
and BAS.
</P><HR>
<H3>Keyworth</H3>
<P>
The VAX cluster at Keyworth continued to be heavily used with greater emphasis on
servicing the requirements of users based at Keyworth.  Advantage was taken of cost-
savings elsewhere to update the contouring package ISM and thereby provide improved
functionality to BGS users.  Productivity of NCS support staff was improved by the use of
problem management software (CHOPS) and over 2,500 queries were logged and processed
in this way.  The experience gained in using this product was used to advantage in
defining the Operational Requirement for a comprehensive Change Management System. 
The performance of the Local Area Network gave cause for concern and network
management tools were installed to identify and understand network capacity problems. 
These were addressed to some degree by investment in structured  cabling components
which enabled network traffic to be localised.  A working group was established to
examine the issues in greater detail and make recommendations for long-term
improvement.
<P>
A Facilities Management Agreement was negotiated with the British Geological Survey
which will come into force in 93/4.  This agreement defines the services which NCS will
provide in exchange for an agreed level of funding and is likely to become the model for
similar agreements with other institutes in future years.  Under the terms of the
agreement NCS will provide operational support for digital cartographic equipment
purchased by the Survey and steps were taken to prepare staff for this new operational
role.
</P><HR>
<H3>Bidston</H3>
<P>
The programme to update computer facilities at Bidston moved sharply forward following
a decision by the Marine and Atmospheric Sciences Directorate to focus its investment in
computing at the Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory.  A powerful file store system was
purchased to meet the storage requirements of the Laboratory's oceanographic modelling
programmes and to provide a long-term archival storage facility.  Particular care was
taken in developing the specification for this system and in its procurement, as it will be
critical to the successful implementation of Council's Data Policy.  The laboratory
invested heavily in advanced workstation technology and a total of 26 systems were
purchased from institute funds.  NCS provided installation and commissioning support
and upgraded the Local Area Network to provide essential system interconnectivity.  Steps
were taken to assist users in migrating their work from the local IBM system in
anticipation of its withdrawal from service by mid 1993.  Staff productivity was improved 
by the introduction of a Help Desk and over 1100 queries were processed during the year.
</P><HR>
<H3>Lakeside</H3>
<P>
Computer Services at the Merlewood site were badly affected by power supply problems
and a new supply was installed at the end of the year.  ARC/INFO applications were
removed from the VAX 8550 to a cluster of four SUN workstations in an attempt to relieve
pressure on the VAX 8550 which had become seriously overloaded.  By the year-end it
became evident that this system was reaching the end of its economic life and a database
server was installed to support ORACLE applications.  A number of improvements were
made to the MicroVAX configuration at Windermere to reduce costs and improve
reliability.
</P><HR>
<H3>Scotland</H3>
<P>
Computing facilities at Banchory were reinstated in temporary accommodation following
the arson attack at the site and an opportunity was taken to upgrade equipment to
conform with the IT strategy.  For most of the year computer support was provided by
NCS staff based in Edinburgh.  Computing facilities at Bush were comprehensively
modernised and a distributed computing system was installed to meet user requirements
for a substantial improvement in functionality.  Based around a Local Area Network using
structured cabling technology, the system consists of a file server, Unix workstations and
personal computers linked together with Novell Netware.  Computer services at Murchison
House, Edinburgh were badly affected by a lightning strike which resulted in extensive
damage to the communications equipment.  The VAX cluster was enhanced through
institute purchase of a VAX 4000 and several smaller systems.  The site computer room
was refurbished and accommodation rearranged to provide much-needed space for BGS
staff.  Network facilities at Oban were improved and advantage was taken of recently
installed workstations to transfer data from Keyworth.
</P>
<br>
<A HREF = "http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC  = "/images/logoicon.gif" align=middle>To the NERC home page</A>
</body>
</html>





