<HTML>
<header>
<title>NCS Annual Report 1992/1993</title>
</header>
<body>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1>
<H2>Annual Report 1992/1993</H2>

<H3>Introduction</H3>
<P>
For NERC Computer Services (NCS), 1992 marked the start of a new phase in its
development.  New funding arrangements came into operation for the first time giving
science managers greater control over expenditure within the service.  This in turn led to
a new dialogue between NCS and institute colleagues on the way in which their
requirements for computer facilities and support should best be met.  For its part, NCS
put into operation new management methods which aim to ensure future success by
embedding a customer-focused culture within its staff.  The combination of new funding
methods and a new management philosophy is expected to produce a computer service
which is "fit for the purpose" of meeting Council's computing requirements.  It is
gratifying to record that this new approach has been well received by users and staff
alike and is already producing tangible benefits.  
<P>
Computing technology is continuing to develop rapidly as forecast in earlier reports and
the move towards a distributed style of computer provision has accelerated.  The
information technology strategy developed by NCS was accepted by Council and is being
followed by all institutes as equipment falls due for replacement.  Substantial progress
was made in 1992 in modernising Council's computing facilities and the development of
information system strategies within the Science Directorates made it possible to develop
affordable plans for ensuring the continuity of this process in future years.  
<P>
NCS continued to maintain close contact with computing developments in the wider
academic community and benefited from good working relationships with key suppliers. 
These activities enable NCS to identify new opportunities for applying information
technology to NERC's own activities and provide an opportunity to communicate the
experience gained by NCS staff in operating a sophisticated computer service to
colleagues providing similar services in academia.  Through these and other channels, NCS
received advice and information which is greatly valued.  At a more formal level the
Computer Services Advisory Committee met for the last time in October 1992 and was
subsequently stood down.  Its function has been replaced by direct discussions with
institutes and directorates, and on policy matters, by the Services and Facilities
Committee to which it reported.  As in previous years, the views of users were expressed
through numerous computer user group meetings and issues of more general interest
were discussed by the NERC Computer Users Committee.  Computer user groups are an
important part of the quality management system for computer services in that they
provide both a means of drawing attention to problems which have not been fully resolved
and a forum in which to assess the perceived level of satisfaction with service delivery. 
To supplement the latter and to provide a means of measuring and monitoring
improvements, a customer satisfaction survey was conducted and this will become a
routine operation in the future.  The Information Systems Advisory Committee offered
advice on the data services for which NCS has responsibility and the policy and advisory
committees of the Joint Administrative Computer Service provided valuable input on
service provision for business activities.  I would like to thank all committee members for
the interest they have shown in the activities of NCS and for their support and advice.
<P>
As with any service organisation, the quality of the service provided by NCS, seen through
the eyes of its customers, is more dependent on the skills, enthusiasm and attitude of
those delivering the service than the technology and materials of which they are the
custodians.  It was particularly gratifying to see this recognised in the results of the
customer satisfaction survey and in feedback which reached my office directly from
individuals and user group representatives.  I would like to thank my colleagues in NCS
for their support throughout the past year and in particular for their recognition of the
need to move towards a more customer-focused approach to service delivery.  I would
also like to acknowledge the contribution of colleagues in NSS and other parts of NERC on
whom we depend for services and without whose support our task would be made more
difficult.  
<P>
Customers are the mainstay of any successful business and this is fully recognised by NCS
management and staff alike.  We value the working relationship between NCS and institute
colleagues and hope that our actions in providing computer services make a tangible
contribution to the success of their scientific programmes.  Our aim is, and will continue
to be, to provide a computer service which meets or exceeds the reasonable expectations
of our customers and by so doing we hope to retain their business.
<P>
<I>John Down</I>
<P>
<HR>
<H3>Review of Operations</H3>
<P>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF = "/ncs/report2.html">Service Quality</A>
<LI><A HREF = "/ncs/report3.html">Operating Systems</A>
<LI><A HREF = "/ncs/report4.html">Networking</A>
