<HEADER>

<TITLE>Plymouth Marine Laboratory</TITLE>

</HEADER>

<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC = "/images/ncs.gif"></H1>
<HR>

<H2>Plymouth Marine Laboratory</H2>
<P>
The Plymouth Marine Laboratory (PML) was formed when the laboratories of the Institute of
Marine Environmental Research (IMER, West Hoe  building) and the Marine Biological
Association (MBA, Citadel Hill building) merged in 1988. PML comprises around 170 staff,
mostly scientific, and undertakes multi-disciplinary research in estuarine, coastal, shelf and
oceanic waters. Through laboratory experimentation, shipboard and field sampling and
computer modelling, PML scientists investigate the marine ecosystem from the cellular to the
global scale. The MBA continues to exist as a charitable learned society, based within the PML
Citadel Hill building and is responsible for its own research studies, scientific journal, public
aquarium and visiting scientists.
<P>
Scientists from PML are often involved in international scientific cruises through the NERC
ocean-going fleet and the laboratory also operates three research vessels. The R.V. Squilla
is a 20m. stern trawler working mainly offshore in the local sea area. The R.V. Sepia is a 12m.
launch operating in inshore waters and local estuaries, whilst the R.V. Tamaris is 13m., but
shallow-draughted and able to work the upper reaches of local estuaries and rivers.
<P><HR>
<H3>NERC Computer Services (NCS) at PML</H3>
<P>
The <A HREF = "/ncs/">NCS</A> supported computing facilities within the laboratory are currently undergoing many
changes. The backbone of the service is a Local Area Network (LAN) which supports over 100
PCs across the two PML sites and provides access to the wide-area JANET/UKERNA network.
The PML sites are linked by a 2 Mbit link. The IBM LAN server software, which has been in use
for the last three years, is gradually being replaced by Novell NetWare. This changeover will
be complete by the end of November 1994. To serve the more powerful graphics and statistics
packages and modelling programs there is an IBM 9370 mainframe, also being replaced in
1994, and 21 Sun, Silicon Graphics and IBM RS6000 workstations. With the demise of the IBM
9370, PML will see the number of UNIX workstations increase dramatically.
<P>
Basic hardcopy output is provided by a number of high resolution (300 and 600 dpi) A4 laser
printers connected either to individual groups of PCs or to the LAN. Also available from the
LAN is an A4 thermal wax transfer colour PostScript printer, which can provide either paper
hardcopy or transparencies. Image input is provided by an A4 colour scanner.
<P>
The NCS group supporting these facilities consists of six highly skilled staff. Their skills range
from hardware installation through system maintenance, LAN and applications support to
high level programming and training, all on PC, IBM 9370 and UNIX platforms. The group also
provides support for a PC-based microscope image analysis system, complemented by several
UNIX packages.
<P>
Applications packages and software available at PML include:
<UL>
<LI>Operating systems - SunOS, Solaris, irix, AIX, CMS, DOS and OS/2
<LI>LAN and communications software - Novell NetWare, IBM LAN Server and TCP/IP, using Ethernet, Token Ring and X25
<LI>Internet utilities - Mosaic, Gopher, Archie and xrn
<LI>windowing software and environments - Windows, OpenWindows, AIXwindows, SGI windows and Vista eXceed
<LI>word processors and text formatters - Word for Windows, Interleaf and LaTeX
<LI>database, spreadsheet and statistics packages - SAS, Systat, Statgraphics, Excel, S-Plus, Access, Minitab and ORACLE
<LI>graphics, modelling and visualisation packages, languages and subroutines - UNIRAS, UniGKS,
AVS, Explorer, ARC/Info, Oxford Molecular, xv, Havard Graphics, Micrografx Draw, Spy Glass,
Photovision, Hijack, PostScript and GhostScript
<LI>image analysis packages - Erdas Imagine, Visilog, Kontron and Image Space
<LI>programming languages and subroutines - Visual Basic, Turbo Pascal, Fortran, C and Nag
</UL>
<P>
The ability to provide such a highly integrated and coherent distributed computing
configuration, based upon this wide range of hardware and software, is the most notable skill
of the NCS staff.
<P><HR>
Contact
<P>
<address><P>
Sean Nicholson<br>
