<header>
<TITLE>NCS Staff and Finances</TITLE>
</header>
<body>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1>
<H2>Staff and Finances
</H2><HR>
<H3>Staff</H3>
<P>
Low turnover of staff, first seen in the previous year, continued into 1992, reflecting an
employment market offering few opportunities for career advancement.  NERC
Management Services carried out a grading review of all NCS staff; the most
comprehensive review since 1986.  That review resulted in the creation of the specialist
computer grade within NERC.  Discussions were continuing with the staff inspectors on
their latest recommendations at year-end.  Recruiting activity was adversely affected by
unresolved differences of view on the grading of specific posts and their reporting line. 
As a result, posts were not filled in a timely fashion and the service at some sites, notably
Wallingford, was reduced to a lower level than normal.  This was particularly unfortunate
as the system replacement programme increased the requirement for user training and
assistance.
<P>
The creation of the new post of NSS Business Development Manager provided an
opportunity for Mr Darwall to apply his interests in marketing, data policy and quality
programmes to a broader range of problems.  Mr Darwall lead the Technical Liaison &amp;
Consultancy Group from its formation in 1986.  In this capacity he was largely responsible
for developing policy on technical matters.  On his transfer to new duties, the group was
merged with the Resource Management Group to form a new Resource Management &amp;
Consultancy Group under the direction of Dr Farmer.  Following the appointment of a
full-time training coordinator, a comprehensive training programme was implemented
resulting in the delivery of technical training to most members of staff during the course
of the year.  User interest in computing technology was addressed through a series of
seminars and workshops.  These took place at a number of locations and covered
computer modelling, distributed computing and automatic data capture.  NCS staff
attended a number of UK and international conferences presenting papers on parallel
computing and image analysis.  Mr Wiseman and Dr Earnshaw (University of Leeds),
published an introductory guide to Scientific Visualisation which received favourable
reviews.
<P>
Stephen Groom published 3 papers jointly with PML staff.
<P>
At the end of the year there were  114  staff in post.
</P><HR>
<H3>Finances</H3>
<P>
Funds allocated to NCS at the beginning of the financial year were substantially less than
estimates and difficulty was anticipated in balancing the operating budget.  Steps were
taken to contain costs and to increase revenue from external sources.  These measures,
together with savings resulting from delayed recruitment of staff, made it possible to
balance income and expenditure within planned limits and the balance will be carried
forward to 1993/94.  The Capital Investment Programme was completed on schedule with
costs matching estimates closely in most cases.  The level of investment was higher than
expected as a result of decisions taken within science directorates to bring forward funds
from 1993/94.  Discussions on funding for 1993/94 were conducted with a better
understanding of capital requirements and operating costs as a result of the development
of Information Systems Strategies and on Service Level Agreements.<HR>
<H3>Cost Allocation
</H3><P>
NCS is required to identify the costs associated with providing its services and to allocate
these back to institutes in a way which reflects their use.  This is achieved by setting a
unit cost for each of the services provided by NCS and monitoring the way in which they
are used.  Usage is accumulated on a monthly basis by project and transferred to the
NERC project costing system.  Charges for 1992/93 were modified to reflect the increasing
emphasis placed on support for distributed computing and the diminishing requirement
for supporting older systems.  NCS continued to demonstrate its ability to set effective
cost allocation rates by achieving a close match between accumulated cost allocation
charges and the full economic cost as measured at the end of the financial year. 
</P>
<br>
<A HREF = "http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC  = "/images/logoicon.gif" align=middle>To the NERC home page</A>
</body>
</html>



