<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>NCS at British Geological Survey, Edinburgh</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1><P>
<H2><A HREF="http://www.nkw.ac.uk/bgs/">British Geological Survey</A>
(Edinburgh)</H2>
<P>
The British Geological Survey (BGS) is represented in Scotland by its Edinburgh office. From
here survey work is carried out across Scotland and  Northern England, and on the
continental shelf, under the waters around the British Isles. Approximately 250 staff are
based at the  Edinburgh office, most of whom are scientific staff.
<P>
The production of geological maps at various scales is an important part of the Survey's
work. Much of the data is now manipulated in digital form and plotted on devices connected
to computer systems in the office. The mapping of the surface features is supplemented by
borehole information, which is held in a series of computer databases.
<P>
Also located at the Edinburgh office are the Survey's seismology and geomagnetism groups.
The Seismology Group monitors and digitally records earthquakes, both in the United
Kingdom and round the globe. Analysis systems and computerised data handling to monitor
earthquakes and predict the likely earthquake risk  have been developed. The Group also
carries out theoretical and computer modelling work on earthquake generation and seismic
wave propagation.
<P>
The Geomagnetism Group monitors and interprets various changes in the geomagnetic field.
Almost all the recording and analyses are carried out on digital data. From these data the
Group offers a computerised prediction service on geomagnetic activity, since such activity
may affect radio wave propagation and power line distribution systems. Also produced are
numerical models and charts on the secular variation in the Earth's internal magnetic field.
<P>
To facilitate the activities of the Survey, research is carried out to develop efficient data
management systems to allow easy, flexible and rapid retrieval. Work is also carried out on
the handling, analysis and display of spatial data, and the development of digital cartography.
</P><HR>
<H3>Computing at BGS Edinburgh</H3>
<P>
A variety of hardware, software and distributed computing environments are currently
supported by <A HREF = "/ncs/">NERC Computer Services</A> (NCS) for BGS Edinburgh. These include : VMS on a
cluster of 28 VAXes, UNIX on 27 workstations and servers, and approximately 150 PCs, mostly
running DOS and Windows. Almost all the PCs are connected to a Local Area Network (LAN)
and interwork with either the main VAX or, as part of a Novell network, with a Novell network
server. The LAN uses Ethernet protocols and the office is connected to the wide-area
JANET/UKERNA network. A high resolution (400 dpi), large format (44" width roll), colour,
area-fill plotter is available as part of the NCS operated facilities on site.
</P><HR>
<H3>NERC Computer Services staff at Edinburgh</H3>
<P>
The NCS group on site is comprised of 4 staff. The group is also involved with the support of
computer facilities at other NERC sites in the region (including the NERC 
Radiocarbon Laboratory at East Kilbride and the Geological Survey
of Northern Ireland in Belfast).
Background information, advice and support are obtained from NCS central groups 
including at the British Geological Survey headquarters at <A HREF = "/ncs/keyworth.html">Keyworth</A>, Nottinghamshire.
<P><HR>
Click <A HREF="http://www.ncs.nmh.ac.uk/">here</A>
for access to the NCS Edinburgh Information Service, including back numbers of the BGS Computing Newsletter.</P><P></P>
Contact

<address>
<P>
Dr Hugh Gough<br>
NERC Computer Services<br>
British Geological Survey<br>
Murchison House<br>
West Mains Road<br>
Edinburgh, EH9 3LA<br>
<P>
