<header>
<TITLE>NCS Quality Programme</TITLE>
</header>
<body>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1>
<H2>Quality Programme</H2><P>
The decision to adopt Total Quality Management as the business philosophy for NCS was
reported last year.  This initiative was further developed by NCS management and an
implementation programme published in November 1992.  The Quality Programme set out
arrangements for training NCS staff in quality methods and identified ways in which
quality methods were being applied to specific activities.  In particular, the programme
set out a time table of events leading to conformance with requirements for registration
under the BS5750 Quality Standard by December 1994.  The need to train all NCS staff in
basic concepts and methods was identified at an early stage and a decision was taken
that this should be carried out by members of the senior management team to ensure
consistency in presentation and to demonstrate commitment to the Quality Programme. 
By year-end, training had been given to over 50 staff and courses scheduled for the
remainder with completion anticipated by May 1993.  Mission Statements were developed
for each functional unit within NCS and individual members of staff were encouraged to
develop a job plan reflecting their commitment to these team Mission Statements.  As
part of a programme to improve communication within NCS the business planning cycle
was identified and widely circulated.  This sets the activities of NCS into the wider context
of the funding cycle and is intended to assist staff in understanding the need for
timeliness in their planning activities.  Service Level Agreements play an important role in
the Quality Programme in that they define the nature and quality of the services which
NCS commits to provide in exchange for funds allocated centrally and from Directorate
sources.  Substantial progress was made in negotiating Service Level Agreements with
most institutes and by year-end agreements were in force with ITE South, Plymouth
Marine Laboratory, Institute of Oceanographic Sciences, Deacon Laboratory and the British
Geological Survey.  Unfortunately, it proved impossible to make progress in negotiating an
agreement with Headquarters' divisions for services on the Swindon campus due to the
intervention of external factors.  The introduction and operation of a formal change
system integrating problem management, change control and configuration management
was confirmed as a high priority technical requirement.  Progress was made in evaluating
the market for suitable products and funds were allocated for hardware and software to
meet this requirement.  By year-end hardware had been purchased and software
procurement was at an advanced stage.  The overall aim of the Quality Programme is to
ensure that NCS provides a range of services which meet or exceed the needs of users
within a cost which is acceptable to NERC management when compared to other activities. 
Substantial progress was made in introducing Total Quality methods in 1992/93 and the
programme will gain momentum in future years.
</P>
<br>
<A HREF = "http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC  = "/images/logoicon.gif" align=middle>To the NERC home page</A>
</body>
</html>



