<HEADER>
<TITLE>NCS at IFE River Laboratory</TITLE>
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1>

<H2>Institute of Freshwater Ecology, River Laboratory
</H2><P>
River Laboratory, part of the Institute of Freshwater Ecology (IFE), forms a core component
of the Terrestrial and Freshwater Directorate.  River Laboratory is situated near Wareham
in Dorset and carries out research and consultancy studies in freshwater environments on
an independent basis.  The IFE aims to be the UK's principle contractor for the study of the
biology, physics and chemistry of freshwater systems through the expertise of its integrated
teams of problem-solving researchers and its continued investment in equipment and
facilities.
<P>
IFE's River Laboratory areas of expertise include:-
<UL>
<LI>environmental quality &amp; impact assessment methodologies and interpretation
<LI>     nutrient dynamics, growth and control of aquatic plants
<LI>     water quality and environmental assessment
<LI>     pathways and fate pesticides
<LI>     chemical and biological processes in river ecosystems
<LI>     fish stock assessment and fisheries management
<LI>     impact of man on aquatic systems
<LI>     management, conservation and restoration of rivers
</UL>
</P><HR>
<H3>NERC Computer Services (NCS) at IFE River Laboratory</H3>
<P>
Recently there have been great changes in the computing facilities available at River
Laboratory and a program of training is being undertaken to help the staff reap the full
benefits of all the changes.  <A HREF = "/ncs/">NCS</A> supported computer equipment consists of a Local Area
Network (LAN) connecting about 30 PC's to a Novell File server, this provides communal
printing facilities, shared applications and files.  There are two UNIX SUN Workstation for
which the primary use is the development of projects using ARC/INFO, a geographic
information system and one UNIX ORACLE Database Server, which can be accessed from both
the SUN Workstations and PC's.  River Laboratory also has access to a MicroVAX II which is
shared with the Institute of Terrestrial Ecology (ITE) 6 miles away.     The LAN is connected
to the JANET/UKERNA wide area network allowing access to other NERC sites, universities and
computers both nation and world wide.
<P>
The computing facilities, both hardware and software are supported, on site, by one member
of NCS staff, whose time is split between River Laboratory and <A HREF = "/ncs/fz.html">ITE Furzebrook</A>, remotely by
staff based at
<A HREF = "plymouth.html">Plymouth Marine Laboratory</A>
and the NCS centrally based support groups.
</P><HR>
Contact   
<P>
<address>
<P>
Karen Burke<br>
River Laboratory<br>
East Stoke<br>
Wareham<br>
