<html>
<header>
<TITLE>NCS - The Future</TITLE>
</header>
<body>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1>
<H2>The Future</H2>
<P>
Distributed computing is now firmly established within NERC and most sites will be
equipped with systems which conform to Council's IT strategy by the end of 1995.  The
role of institute (and project) funds in meeting computing requirements is better
understood and most workstations and personal computers will be purchased from these
sources in future.  Infrastructure and superstructure funds, as currently defined, will be
used to meet corporate requirements and to provide shared site facilities respectively. 
The number of workstations in operation is expected to continue to grow but at a slower
rate than forecast earlier.  By the end of 1993/94 the number of systems supported by
NCS is expected to reach 430, with a steady rise thereafter to a peak of around 800
systems by 1997.  The power of desktop workstations is continuing to increase rapidly and
the most advanced products will be competitive with present-day supercomputers for
some applications.  1993/94 will see the first purchase of a powerful computer modelling
facility from project funds.  This will demonstrate the importance of project funding
within the capital investment programme for computing and will be a significant
departure from previous practice which limited such investment to desktop equipment. 
Software development will continue to attract attention but the deployment of new
software tools invariably takes longer than expected reflecting the need to reskill
individual members of staff.  Information systems of all kinds are likely to play an
increasingly important role and when combined with better office systems will have a
significant impact on working methods throughout NERC.  At a business level, the
provision of computer services will become more competitive and through implementation
of its Quality Programme, NCS expects to maintain competitive edge.  This will need to be
tested in the market at some future point and, in the meantime, internal pressures
exercised through the funding mechanisms will require NCS to demonstrate its ability to
provide value for money.  Under current arrangements, the service can expect an
external (science management) audit in 1995.  This will provide an opportunity for
Council to reconsider the merits of a corporate computer service and the extent to which
NCS has succeeded in meeting the expectations of its customers.  The management and
staff of NCS are convinced that they have the managerial and technical skills to provide a
computer service which is fit for the purpose of meeting Council's needs and look forward
to demonstrating this through whatever mechanisms are considered appropriate.
</P>
<br>
<A HREF = "http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC  = "/images/logoicon.gif" align=middle>To the NERC home page</A>
</body>
</html>


