<header>
<TITLE>NCS Capital Investment</TITLE>
</header>
<body>
<IMG SRC  = "/images/ncs.gif">
<HR>
<H1></H1>
<H2>Capital Investment</H2>
<P>
Despite continuing financial pressures, capital investment was maintained at a healthy
level and the preparation of information system strategies assisted greatly in the
preparation of affordable capital investment plans.  As a result, the Marine and
Atmospheric Sciences Directorate and the Terrestrial and Freshwater Sciences Directorate
agreed to bring forward funds from 1993/94 to enable major system replacement
programmes to be completed within the financial year.  The capital allocation was set at
1,653K, of which 479K was spent on infrastructure items, 135K on NERC's contribution
to replacement of equipment within the Joint Administrative Computer Service and the
balance on scientific computing equipment.  Most of the infrastructure funds were spent
on communications equipment including switches, routers, structured cabling components
and test equipment.  Software purchases included a new library management system, a
corporate licence for Novell Netware and relicensing the ISM contouring software package
to the latest release level.  A number of workstations were purchased for NCS staff to
enable them to provide effective support to institute colleagues using similar equipment. 
Capital investment from superstructure funds was focused on providing major systems
replacements at the Institute of Hydrology, Institute of Terrestrial Ecology, Bush and the
Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory, and on the provision of new facilities at the
Institute of Virology and Environmental Microbiology.  In each case, a distributed
computing system was installed, taking advantage of existing investment in personal
computers and workstations where appropriate.  At the Institute of Hydrology, a total of
400K was invested in distributed system components including separate file server and
data base server systems, structured cabling, new printing facilities and high performance
workstations.  The IBM service which this system replaced was withdrawn from general use
at the end of the year.  At the Institute of Terrestrial Ecology, Bush a total of 165K was
invested to purchase system components with similar functionality to those at the
Institute of Hydrology but on a scale appropriate to the needs of the site.  Novell Netware
was successfully installed for the first time by NCS in commissioning this installation.  At
the Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory investment focused on improved network
functionality which was achieved by the installation of a new structured cabling system
and on the purchase of a high performance, high capacity file store to meet the long
term storage requirements of the British Oceanographic Data Centre and shorter term
high volume storage requirements for processing the output of oceanographic models
which form an important part of the work of the laboratory.  This item was the highest
value procurement conducted by NCS and resulted in the purchase of a Convex 3200
processor, UNITREE software and a Metrum tape robot system.  Most of the hardware was
delivered at the end of the financial year, with commissioning planned for early 1993/94. 
At the Institute of Virology and Environmental Microbiology a Local Area Network was
installed and a large number of personal computers were purchased for integration into a
distributed computing system using Novell Netware.  Hardware components were delivered
by year end for commissioning at a later date.  The balance of funds were spent on a
range of items reflecting the requirements of individual sites.  As foreseen by the 1990
visiting group, the transfer of funds from NCS to Directorates (superstructure) is leading
to a better understanding of the requirement for capital investment in computing
facilities.  The role of NCS is to advise on technology issues and to assist in the
development of an affordable IT investment plan.  Responsibility for identifying computing
requirements and for determining their relative priority rests with institutes within an
overall funding level agreed within their respective Directorate.  1992/93 saw this system
in operation for the first time and the resulting capital investment programme was a
major step forward in the modernisation of Council's computing facilities.
</P>
<br>
<A HREF = "http://www.nerc.ac.uk/"><IMG SRC  = "/images/logoicon.gif" align=middle>To the NERC home page</A>
</body>
