<Title>Making a Difference</Title>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="teach2.jpg">
<CENTER>
<H1>Making a Difference</H1>
<IMG SRC="excit.gif" HEIGHT=120 WIDTH=160 ALT="Picture of Children Excited!"><P>
</CENTER>
	In May 1996, the fourth grade elementary students of Ohio were required to take a <B><I>proficiency test of skills in ALL subject disciplines</I></B>. The science test required that the students demonstrate understanding and application rather than just knowledge of the facts being taught. The following information, unless noted, is public record.<P>
	<I>Struthers City School District has 4 schools with 6 teachers in the fourth grade. Its demographic makeup is 43% ADC (Aid for Dependent Children), and it places 62 (of 610 districts) from the bottom of the Ohio equity list.</I><P>
	Wealthy districts in the surrounding communities had average scores of 68%, 70%, 76%, and 66%. A <B><I>comparable suburban district scored 40%, and an inner-city one scored 23%</I></B>. Struthers scored a remarkable 56%, but that is not the story. <P>
One day in September 1995, the teachers were trained on the 1995 National Science Education Standards by Mary Linton using the EXPLORING SCIENCE curriculum. <B>The result was an incredible performance correlation of overall student performance vs. teacher use</B> (% supplied by teachers) <B>of the <I>integrated science curriculum</I> provided by the EXPLORING SCIENCE (K-6) program</B>.<P>

<HR><P>
<center>
