<HEAD>
<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>NSTA Review</Title>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="ffffff">
The <I><B>active teachers</B></I> involved with EXPLORING SCIENCE make changes, not excuses!<P>
<HR>
<center>
<B>From the</B>
<H1> National Science Teachers Association </H1>
<B><I>A review of the program</I></B><BR>
<H2>EXPLORING SCIENCE</H2>
(received 11/25/96 - Documentation on file)<P>

</center>
Exploring Science is a series developed to introduce children to the adventure of being the scientist. It provides students with the opportunities to develop the skills of scientific investigation by hand-on oriented lessons, as well as reading that features actual scientists and their discoveries. The basic grade level appropriate content is addressed, yet it envelops development needs of students from all abilities and cultures. The series introduces skills, activities, and open ended questioning models for the teacher. Extensions from each unit reach to integrate with other disciplines.<P>

Students are approached as young scientists using their questioning skills to accept the challenges of each lesson or activity. Science investigative skills are encouraged throughout the series. The language of science is introduced and its use encouraged. They are encouraged to record, graph, and communicate what they have learned as part of their assessment. Many different methods of assessment are proposed by the authors. Further mastery to express their acquired skills is encouraged by such events as invention activities, family science nights, and science fairs. The teacher's guide includes very thorough forms to guide teachers who may not have used these channels before.<P>

One of the strong points of this program is its integration with other subject matter, and its instructions for open ended questions. Teachers are given many models for using a variety of teaching techniques. The use of process skills is apparent in each lesson. There are explicit instructions for using cooperative learning in the classroom. The inclusion of so many excellent suggestions for the teacher can create an overwhelming response when first introduced, but the material is worth the effort of reading and using the suggested techniques.<P>

This material would be very useful to a large district that has a coordinator and standardized curriculum. The series would be effectively used by a system with team teaching. To reap the most from this series, time for team planning would be imperative. The program would also be helpful for teachers in a system that is self contained because of the excellent tips for integration. New teachers would benefit from its modeling of teaching and assessment techniques. The authors have gathered in one book most of the components needed to develop a successful science program. All the process skills are encouraged. Safety concerns are listed in each lesson. Each grade level features a story that expresses a respect for the scientist and their use of the skills of problem solving that develops as they make practical use of basic science process skills.<P>

Activity lessons use easily accessible supplies. Supply lists are extended to provide materials for a number of classes who might be teaching the lessons at the same time. This is a very helpful feature. Model dialog is provided to aid the instructor.<P>

Technology is addressed in each unit. Appropriate software and videos are included with the lesson plans. The series provides content, as well as hands-on activities. Most elementary teachers are not science specialists. The content, activities, and suggestions given in this program are of great value to the average elementary instructor. The same program provides a challenge for the seasoned science teacher who needs a challenge.<P>

<HR>
