<H2>GOING IT ALONE - COSTS!</H2>
<B><I>"The presidential candidates like to say how each community knows what's best for its children. But it took the NAS 4 years of agony to come up with these (science) standards, so it beyond me how they expect local communities to do it on their own."</I><BR>
Bruce Alberts</B>, president of the National Academy of Sciences,<BR>
Addressing the National Science Board on 23 February about the science education standards.<BR>
(reported <B>Science</B>, 8 March 1996<P>

<center>
<B><I>Probably true.</I> (Larry Severson)</B><P>
</center>
<H2>FACTS:</H2>
<UL>
<LI>Educator/Scientists develop National Science Education Standards (4years [1991-1995]- taxpayer $millions).<BR>
<H3>4 years earlier [1991]</H3>
<LI> Teachers develop course outline matching 1995 National Science Education Standards (2 days).<BR>
<LI> Teachers insert previously K-6 classroom tested hands-on lessons to match outline (2 weeks).<BR>
<LI> Teachers spend additional 25,000 hours scripting lessons for general use (self funded!).<P>
</UL>

<HR>
<P>
<I><B>"What does scientific literacy mean in today's world? Scientific literacy is not simply a mastery of facts but a way of thinking - an analytical process through which we reach conclusions. It begins in school where the students should learn to identify their assumptions, think logically, and consider alternative explanations. They should be able to apply the knowledge they acquire, not merely memorize facts long enough to repeat them on the next exam."</B></I><BR>
Robert Peccei, Dean Physical Sciences, UCLA College of Letters and Science<BR>
Fred Eiserling, Dean Life Sciences, UCLA College of Letters and Science<BR>
Quoted in LA Times, Page B9, 2/26/96<P><P>

 
