<Title>Reality</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<BODY BACKGROUND="reality.jpg" >

<H1>REALITY IS ALWAYS UNCOMFORTABLE</H1>

<DT><A HREF="new.htm">Things that I wish I had said, plus ... 11/26/95 .</A><P><P>

<HR>
<P>

<H2>Science Thought:</H2>
A solution to a problem <I>simply works</I>,<BR>
the <B>CORRECT</B> solution <I>works simply</I>.<P><P>

<H2>Elementary Science Thought:</H2>
<I>Evaluating of a Science Program attempting to meet the NSES:<BR></I>
(NSES - National Science Education Standards)<BR>
BAD: Student says, "I can't."<BR>
GOOD: Student says, "I can find out!"<P>
If the new science curriculum takes <I>two years training</I>,<BR>
<B>MOST</B> elementary teachers <I>won't use it!</I>.<P><P>

<H2>Two Types of Bad Science Curriculum</H2>
<OL>
<LI> Numerous errors of fact and omission.<BR>
<LI> Lack of background material related to previous experiences of students AND teachers.<BR>
</OL><P>

If the teachers and students can not understand the information, no learning will take place. It is not enough to present accurate science. It must be understandable by the expected audience. <P>

<B><I>"If you can not explain your job to a five year old, you do not know your job."</I></B><BR>
(Albert Einstein)<P>

A graduate student in Physics can assimilate discussions in science shorthand, but an elementary student, OR teacher, does not have the prerequisite background to fill in the holes. Thus DOES NOT mean "dummy down". It DOES mean relate the information. A sample of related in math would be number line to weeks of allowance.  The students want to understand, so do the teachers.<P>
 
<HR>
<DT><A HREF="buzz.htm">Buzz Words ... 6/10/95 .</A> Buzz words are used as short cut to effective communication, sometimes.<P><P>

<HR>

<P>
<H2>Program Cost</H2>
<b><I>"Money is always there, but the pockets change."</I> Gertrude Stein</B><BR>
Question, "Did you get a GOOD program or a BAD program for your money?"<P>
A BAD Program costs your students - as well as your budget!<P><P>

<HR><P><P><P>

