<HEAD>
<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>FAILURE IS NOT AN OPTION!</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>FAILURE IS NOT AN OPTION!</H1>
<P>

<H2>It is said ...</H2>
<I>"Public education is failing America."</I><P>
<UL>
<LI>We need LOCAL CONTROL!<BR>
<LI>We need FEDERAL FUNDING!<BR>
<LI>Students need basic skills only, don't waste time.<BR>
<LI>Students need problem solving skills only, not facts.<BR>
<LI>We NEED ... !<P>
</UL><P>

Enough of the politicizing! Enough pushing agendas to the exclusion of societies needs. Every source that I have checked has said that within 20 years between 25% and 33% of the jobs available will demand workers who have significant knowledge and problem solving abilities. Only the best of todays' GIFTED programs are providing this background and training. No more than 5% of graduating high schoolers are prepared for these jobs. Given these facts, 5% of future adults will hold 33% of the future jobs. <P>

Our government can not cut spending enough to survive with only 15% of the adult population working. (In fact, the current budget deficiet is related to high paying job losses, not spending. - The president and congress are fighting over which color of garden hose to use while the forest fire rages on.) Starvation will be nearly universal. "<I>Failure is NOT an option!</I>" (<B>Apollo 13</B>). The only solution is to stop discussing what the students can't do, shouldn't do, or who should control the funds. As in the movie, and the real situation, these are:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>The students we have.<BR>
<LI>The teachers we have.<BR>
<LI>The funds we have.<BR>
<LI>The job types we will have.<P>
</UL>
<B>This is what we have, make it work.</B>  "<I>Failure is NOT an option!</I>" <P>

Clearly there have to be changes. We can not continue to throw away the minds of our children/students if there is to be a future for this country. There are many things going right in public education today. In fact, most of the "failures" today are related to short term, limited thinking analysis. However, there are also problems that need addressing. The 1995 National Science Education Standards are an outstanding start towards the future.<P>

The first step is to address the FUNCTION  of education, rather than the PROCESS. Day to day activities, and even the breakdown of subject matter is PROCESS. FUNCTION can be best defined as the ultimate purpose for which education exists. The K-12 schooling, or even college, is not a universal baby-sitting program with a bit of socialization thrown in. Public Education has a purpose, provide future adult citizens who are communicating, cooperating, and contributing. In education, the medium <B>CAN NOT</B> be the message!<P>

<I>To communicate</I>, the citizens must have a common language so that they can understand each other. Since words can have different meanings, the citizens must have a similar background of knowledge that they can agree on. This can be said in spite of our history. New Amsterdam became New York. I question whether there has ever been a time in our history when the percentage of non-English speaking population was lower than it is today! The reality is that our fore fathers dealt with the problem as fact, and went ahead to build a nation.<P>

<I>To cooperate</I>, the citizens must have a respect for all of the different citizens they will be called to interface with. Differences must be understood as simply that. It has been said the, "When two people always agree, one of them is unnecessary." Since the beginning of our history as a country, cultural diversity has not only been a fact, but also our greatest strength. However, there absolutely needs to be an agreement on what are the goals for the future of this nation. A good starting point would be teaching everyone the Constitution. Today we spend far too much time trying to find failures and weaknesses in our founding fathers than we do on what a marvelous document they produced to form the basis of the American dream.<P> 

There are a few things to consider before accepting the statement of public educations "failure" at face value.<P>
1. You are reading this page!<BR>
2. What is the function of public education??<P>

Currently, there is a loud cry to "beat the world in knowledge of facts." Interesting.<P>
<I>"Science is not about facts, but about pushing back the <B>void of ignorance</B>."</I> <BR>
Dr. Eric Molle-Christianson<P>

So, why do we test "facts"? Answer, it is easy!<BR>
So, why do we call for drilling "facts"? Answer, it is easy to look good!<P>

Why don't we emphasize testing (demonstrating) ability to use the information the students have been taught? Answer, that is tough. The whole program of curriculum adoption would be significantly more complex for administrators and curriculum advisors. It would also make it worse for the <I>very few</I> teachers who don't care about the product they produce. The truth is that, in general, good teaching is going on, in spite of poor curriculum materials being supplied to the classroom.<P>

The jobs are not going overseas because the new products and ideas are being created there. No! It is because business leaders have forgotten what Henry Ford knew.  They are destroying their own markets and country for short term gain.<P>

The movie, <B>"Apollo 13"</B>, illustrated very well what the traditional American public school does best. When faced with multiple failures and certain death of the crew, the response was, <I>"I don't care what the book says. This is what we have. Now, find a way to do it!"</I><P>

What do you want:<BR>
Mindless rote memorization? - or<BR>
Make it work!<P>

The first is always easy. That is why so many do it. The second is not. That is why America has led the world in this century!<P>

<H2>Conclusion</H2>
The paradigm of education materials and techniques has to change to prepare for the future. New techniques and materials have to introduced to the classroom. However, that change is not merely adding technology to what we are currently doing. In fact, there are those who are legitimately concerned that technology is both draining the budget and making the problem worse. 

<P>The $13 million Biology classroom at Harvard-Westlake High School was the subject of an LA Times article. While the article enthused over the marvelous things that could be done there, I thought only that the description of the lab approached the ones that existed at the universities that produced "Cold Fusion." It is not the science "toys" that make a great program, but teachers and curriculum that are training the science process and communication. Barbara McClintock did not have an electron microscope when she developed the theories that led to the field of DNA research. Albert Einstein had only pencil and paper when he developed the theory of relativity.<P><P><P>

Larry Severson, Resident Opinionated Person<P>

