<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>The Message</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<I>"The medium is the message."</I><BR>
<B>Marshall McLuan</B><P>


That's acceptable when the only goal is <I>entertainment</I>. Since the book, <B>"Megatrends"</B>, far too many people, in and out of education, have decided that whatever was getting the most hype MUST be the best thing for the classrooms - even when a moments thought would show that the subject was both costly and ineffective in preparing the students for future adult responsibilities.<P><P>

<H1>Education is the medium</H1>
 Macro Press is a company of teachers who worry about the performance of their students, not today, but in the future. It is not enough to "hook" the students with a bit of techie glitz while leaving the future adults without the adult skills so necessary for the survival of this country and the American way of life.<P>

<B><IMG SRC="teaching.gif" ALIGN MIDDLE>     Teachers</B><P>

<DT><A HREF="kathi.gif">Photo of teacher with students - 54K</A> <P>

This Home Page is designed to transmit effective teaching concepts and ideas to those who most need them (everyone). The method is to eschew modem time consuming glitz in favor of written material. Since publishing <B>Exploring Science</B>, we have become quite effective at both graphic layout and multi-media. However, any qualified Value Engineer will always ask, "What is your <I>Function</I>?" The function should always drive the design and methodology of whatever is created. Our <I>function</I> at Macro Press is preparing our students to be <I>Communicating, Cooperating, and Contributing </I>adults, NOT jazzed students! <P>

<IMG SRC="rockstar.gif" ALIGN MIDDLE><B>     NOT Rock Stars!</B><P>


In the material presented here, as in our curriculum, expensive color and imagery will only be used when it is absolutely necessary to present important concepts that justify the cost in time and resources to teachers and parents who spend their own money in an effort to achieve the best education for their charges. <P>

<DT><A HREF="51ex2.pdf" ><B><I>We can do "Pretty" lessons - 136K</I></B></A>
If you look under Samples on the Home Page, the normal way of presenting lessons requires 11-14K, rather than 136K. Communication bandwidth will become an increasing problem as more people join the "NET". This lesson requires the Adobe Acrobat reader. If this is what you want, let us know!<P>


The series, <B>EXPLORING SCIENCE</B>, was produced by these teachers to fit their <I>functional objective</I>. Color is used only in Kindergarten student materials - because the subject of accurate COLOR description is being taught as a science tool. The goal is to provide a generation of students who would never find "Cold Fusion" acceptable. They start effective <B>Communication</B> training in Kindergarten with techniques developed by award winning teachers of non-English speaking students. The students <B>Cooperate</B> in all of their activities, and recognize the advantages of drawing new information and learning from their teammates. Each student, from the beginning, <B>Contributes</B> throughout the year. Tasks are rotated within teams and team members are rotated so that all students see themselves operating in the manner that we define as effective adult citizens.<P>

In one test, a school district in California used the program in a summer school for the "worst half" of their At-Risk students. At the end of the six weeks, the administrators were shocked that kid after kid came up saying, "I'm not stupid like I thought." Unfortunately, the students went back to the old environment for the school year. While both students and parents felt that 85% of the students had shown tremendous growth during the program, only 65% were at or above grade level expectations 8 months later.<P>

Interesting, <B>Exploring Science </B>has no color, not multi-media, unless you count the kids, and no hype to "hook" the kids. Using ONLY good teaching techniques and readily available materials, these students and teachers were enthralled. They did not have to be "hooked". Eight months later, the students were still asking if they were going to "Be Scientist's" again the following summer. <B><I>Education is the message</I></B> of our program and Home Page. We will leave "The medium is the message" to those whose only goal is profit and hype.<P>

<DT><A HREF="failure.htm"><H2>Failure is NOT an option!</H2> ... 12/26/95 .</A><P>
For those who did not look at this file first, consider that history is replete with failed civilizations. The glory of Rome became the Dark Ages. The Mayans builders now live in poverty. Where did Babylon go?<P>
<P>


