<HTML>
<HEAD>
<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>Science Education</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H1>Fundamental, Systemic Change in Science Education</H1>

This phrase is the main subject of conversation in all meetings of the National Science Teachers of America (NSTA) and the National Science Foundation (NSF) when discussing K-12 science education. These discussions have already lead to the 1995 National Science Education Standards (NSES). This paper discusses why the interest exists, what the words mean, and what the final form for K-12 science education should be.<P>

<B>Background:</B><BR>
In 1985, Herb Strongin published a seminal book on hands-on science, "Science On A Shoestring". In the book and other writings, he demonstrated the teaching of the science methodology using simple materials. The thrust of his message was epitomized by the Chinese proverb: <BR>
<B>I hear, and I forget.<BR>
I see, and I remember.<BR>
I do, and I understand.</B><P>

 No longer should we teach only science facts to be memorized, tested, and forgotten. Teaching the facts discovered by previous scientists is vital for the student to understand what we now know, and how we got there, in order to develop new knowledge, but technically that falls under the description of History, not Science.<P>

As we move towards the 21st century, it is becoming obvious to everyone that our technically advanced society could become one of myth and superstition. More and more, jobs are based on the ability to utilize mechanical devices, and design them. Unless the graduating students understand what produced the "miracles", we could lose everything. Societies, like people, either get better, or they get worse. Previous advanced civilizations have failed because the knowledge of their science was not spread widely enough to survive adversity.<P>

<B>Definition:</B><BR>
 Science is the systematic gathering, organizing, and dissemination of new knowledge. Fundamental means the basis of  how things are done. Systemic is defined as the organized grouping of items or ideas to create a whole. Used together in the context of teaching, they mean that the whole method of teaching a subject will be radically and irrevocably changed. <P>

<B>Analogy:</B>
Any horse based transportation society that wishes to go 60 MPH will find out immediately that they can not do it on a horse (falling off a cliff doesn't count!) Switching to a car means two fundamental, systemic changes:<BR>
1.  Pasturing will not fill the gas tank.<BR>
2.  The car will not return home if the driver falls asleep.<P>
<HR>
<H2><B><I>"Houston, we have a problem."</I></B></H2> Apollo 13 mission.<P>
<HR>
<B>Problems:</B><BR>
1.  Perception.<BR>
<I>"We tend to see what we expect to see." </I>Mary Leaky, discussing a delayed discovery.<P>

2.  Materials cost.<BR>
<I>"The school board is not going to approve new materials two years after we bought books, even though no one uses them." </I>Utah Curriculum Director<P>

3.  Training.<BR>
<I>"Reading/Language Arts teachers make up 85% of my elementary staff."</I> California Curriculum Director<P>

4.  Materials sources.<BR>
<I>"We will educate teachers on how to adapt existing materials to create their own curriculum." </I>University educator<P>

<B>An Analogy </B>(From a book on Value Engineering by Antonio Negerete)<BR>
One day, during one of the not so recent product retrenchments, the CEO called his chief engineer into his office. Sam, we have made the "framistan" for some time; however, foreign competition dictates that we reduce its production cost. The washer in the transmission is too expensive. Reduce its cost from $10 to $1, or we close the operation and lay off the people. You have two weeks.<P>

Sam rapidly got together a team. Through extremely diligent research, they found that the washer could actually be replaced with one that cost only $1.80. What a savings!<P> 

Proudly, Sam presented the "new" washer to the CEO, expecting high praise. To his shock, the CEO responded with, "We will start the lay-offs in two weeks. Sam had not met the $1 criteria. Sam immediately asked for another two weeks to restudy the problem. He got the two weeks, but no more.<P>

Sam went back to his team and said, "Our problem was the total cost. Since no cheaper washer can be found, we need to step back and look at what the system using the washer is doing."<P>

To make a long story short, the team discovered that a redesign of the transmission system removed the washer, saving $10, and saved an additional $6. The total saving in production costs was $16. The product was saved and the employees continued working because the engineers looked at what the "system" did, rather than how a part functioned.<P>

It is a fact that people do not like change. Until change becomes unavoidable, changing nothing is both cheaper and easier for all involved. The suggested teacher individualized curriculum is clearly disruptive, not uniform and supportive, in terms of creating a broad based movement towards a "system" of education for all children. <P>

<B>Application:</B><BR>
Currently, a significant portion of our student population is graduating from high school with a lack of understanding of what science is, or even the desire to learn. "Throwing in" some hands-on science on top of existing materials is not the answer. Like finding the cheaper washer, this is not fundamental, systemic change.<P>

To create the level of change necessary to promote the NSES, requires materials that:<BR>
1.  Are hands-on.<BR>
2.  Promote interdisciplinary science understanding.<BR>
3.  Provide the teacher with the necessary science background in the lesson.<BR>
4.  Provide clear guidance in science methodology for the student.<BR>
5.  Encourage the keeping of a scientist journal.<BR>
6.  Treat facts as stepping stones, that may be proven wrong later, to new knowledge.<BR>
7.  Provide a basis for cooperate learning.<BR>
8.  Provide ideas to challenge the student to exhibit science understanding in different formats (synthesis).<BR>
9.  Provide a consistent teaching style and content mix.<P>

<B>Meaning:</B><BR>
<I>Hands-on</I> is obvious, but what about<I> interdisciplinary science understanding?</I> Brain research has shown that humans do not remember facts. They remember linkages between symbol sets that become useable as "facts". Given this data, it becomes clear why the mind tends to compartmentalize information presented in different books, or even different chapters. It is a new subject, it does not LINK.<P>

Providing the <I>necessary background</I> for the teacher is an interesting demand. <B><I>"To learn something new, begin in your own backyard, proceeding from the known to the nearest unknown." </I></B>(George Washington Carver) Students come to the class with a widely disparate knowledge base. ESL students even have a language problem. It becomes important that the lesson series establishes a reference base that is known by all of the students prior to starting. Since 85% of all elementary teachers have little/no science background, they can't help the students achieve this common ground necessary to move forward unless the teacher is first given the background information. Demanding two years of college science classes as an additional requirement is meaningless. That would be 12 units of what? Nuclear Physicists are not prepared to teach high school biology, but we want the elementary teacher to teach and link Physical, Earth, and Life Science information using hands-on science. Background support in the teacher's manual is the only acceptable answer.<P>

Providing the student training in <I>science methodology</I> should be done explicitly. Since science is the method used to discover new knowledge and disseminate it to others, this will help them in all subject areas for the rest of their lives. Actual lessons should be designed where the dominant theme is the exercise of the science methodology.<P>

The use of a <I>"scientist journal"</I> (notebook) is one of the most important parts of being a scientist. Discovery is seldom stumbling over a piece of gold. As is shown by the collection of the notebooks of Leonardo DaVinci at the Elmer Belt Library of Vinciana (UCLA), discovery comes from documenting information over time until the true ramifications become obvious and provable.<P> 

Without <I>"facts"</I> there is no basis for improvement. How do we know the change really was better? On the other hand, treating a "fact" as always true because it was published in a textbook is contrary to the meaning of science. How many books published the hoax, Piltdown Man, or the error of the brontosaurus? "Facts" are what has worked in the past, and need to be used until something better comes along.<P>

Society exists in a <I>cooperative environment</I>, so does science. <B><I>"I stood on the shoulders of giants who preceded me." </I></B>(Newton) All scientists share their work, even when they are working alone. Peer review is the basis of all science. The goal is the accumulation of knowledge, not funny ideas. The cooperative advancement of knowledge makes all of what our civilization has achieved possible. The students need to understand this fact.<P>

Merely being able to parrot "facts" learned from the book is no <I>exhibiting of science understanding</I>, or even the ability to remember and use the information later. The whole concept of the NSES is that the student demonstrate understanding of the material that was covered during the class experiment by applying it in a totally different context. Did you learn how the elbow and muscles of the arm works? Good, design a draw bridge based on what you learned. Find ways to improve on the design using available technology. <I>Synthesize</I> what you know!<P>

<B>Conclusion:</B>
The growth of population, with all of its ramifications, dictates that life will become steadily more automated. This automation requires that the citizens have a strong understanding not only of the underlying principles, but also how the disciplines (Physical, Earth, and Life Science) interrelate for our society to continue. The way we have been addressing the teaching of science in the past has not worked for enough of the society to furnish the increased needs of the 21st century. Fundamental, systemic change has to take place in the classroom, not as buzz words, but as reality. Science is not magic, nor is it for the few.<P>

To achieve these changes, the current abilities and knowledge of both the teachers and students needs to be taken into account. All future science curriculum needs to be rewritten with this in mind. It is not acceptable to blame the problem on bored students and unprepared teachers. Hands-on science excites all students. Elementary teachers have too many other requirements to go off for years studying and writing "science". <B>Make the curriculum fit the need.</B> Don't adjust the requirements to fit current inappropriate curriculum.<P>
<HR>
<H2><B><I>"Failure is not an option."</I></B> </H2> Mission Control, Apollo 13<P>
<HR>
<P>


Larry Severson
Copyright &copy; 1996 <BR>
Macro Press Incorporated<BR>
18242 Peters Court<BR>
Fountain Valley, CA  92708<BR>
Phone/fax   (714) 964-9191<BR>
e-mail:  science@macropress.com<P>

