<HEAD>
<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>Industrial Age</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
I claim this work to be my thoughts!  Larry Severson<P>

<H1>Education in the Industrial Age?</H1>
<B><I>"Why does this magnificent applied science which saves work and makes life easier bring us so little happiness? The answer runs: Because we have not yet learned to make sensible use of it.."</I> Albert Einstein</B><P>

It is interesting to note the current thrust in curriculum development, especially in light of the industrial age that is the basis of our society. Where did we come from? Where are we going? Should we go that way?<P>

Historically, that out of vogue subject, we started out with a few craftsmen and a lot of hackers (the middle ages). There was little education and less reading. Along came the invention of the printing press, now reading material could be reproduced easily and inexpensively. Suddenly, there was more reason to be able to read and learn. Knowledge was readily transferred from the artisan to the student who could read. This led inexorably to the industrial  age of mass production of every day necessities, not just books. The knowledge of those specially gifted was passed on to those with less knowledge or time to discover. All of our lives were made richer by this mass production of products, skills, and understanding.<P>

It is interesting to note the new thrust in education is towards teacher "empowerment". The word empowerment normally means giving greater capability to the user. In this case, one would expect that the teacher, who wants nothing more that to develop knowledge and confidence in her/his students, would become supremely successful in the transfer of knowledge and accomplishment to the students. The artisan produces a new generation of artisans that follow her/him.<P>

We are now in the age of "politically correct", so we need to look at the word "empowerment" closer. As being defined across the educational landscape, does it really empower the teacher? When I get an electric drill to replace the old hand drill, I am empowered in my efforts to drill holes. When I replace the horse with a car to travel between cities, I am also empowered in my ability to travel. When I use a computer to write, and edit, this material, I am also empowered in my ability to communicate by using the efforts of others to make my efforts less, while achieving the desired goal. That is not what "empowerment" means to educators.<P>

In educator speak,  empowerment means that each teacher will achieve buy-in, or acceptance, of the curriculum only by writing her/his own curriculum. What an exciting thought! (I have looked at some of the training courses at UCLA. Their graduates will fully understand what it takes to write a proper science curriculum.) That sounds noble, but does it make sense? Let's ignore for the moment the fact that the highly experienced award-winning teacher/authors of EXPLORING SCIENCE required 3500 hours per grade level to write the curriculum for one subject, science. Let's also ignore the fact that 85% of ALL elementary teachers do not have the science background to write a science curriculum. We need to ignore, additionally, the cost of them trying to get a proper background. The real question is, 
what is the purpose of hiring teachers in the first place -> communicating knowledge?<P>

 In the case of elementary teachers, this means teaching seven different subjects to provide the students with the foundation knowledge. Are they going to write the materials for all seven subject? When will the eat or sleep? MORE IMPORTANT, will their students be prepared for the next (empowered) teacher who wants to do everything differently. It is one thing to adapt consistent materials to meet the different learning styles of the students. It is entirely different when each teacher presents contradictory information. Soon, the student will not know what is correct, or important. 

Society pays for, and expects, the students to leave school prepared to be <B>communicating, cooperating, and contributing adults</B>. Clearly, the thrust towards "empowerment" of the teachers will not contribute towards that goal. Worse, it is the deliberate rejection of all of the lessons of economy of scale and production that we learned during this industrial age. So, why is it being pushed so forcefully?<P>

<B><I>"To define it rudely, but not inaptly, engineering is the art of doing well for one dollar which any bungler can do with two, after a fashion."</I> Arthur M. Wellington</B><P>

The ugly truth is that the education materials, especially science, that are being produced by the major publishers today follow the business dictum, "If you have a bad product, package it pretty, price it high, and market it like ____!" What I have seen at the National Science Teacher Association conventions make me cringe. All of it is pretty, but none of it is what is claimed. The materials violate virtually everything that is known from the fields of brain research and cognitive transfer. In most cases, the materials are also sloppy science, at best. An appropriate analogy would be "Cold Fusion" in fancy packaging. <P>

When teaching thematically linked Physical, Earth, and Life Science, the curriculums use different books BECAUSE they can pull them off the shelf. Ignore the fact that the mind separates material in different books, or even different chapters, into different subjects, I can't!
Ignore the fact that the students are supposed to learn INFORMATION because it is important, but not important enough for the author and publisher to present it in the context of what the student already knows, even though brain research clearly demonstrate that we learn by linking new information to what was previously known.<P>

Because the educational establishment has given up obtaining acceptable materials from the major publishers (who do provide little "grants" here and there), it is now pushing every teacher for herself. <I>The result will be increasing chaos in education.</I> This same establishment closes the door on well written materials from teachers (who do not have the money to provide "grants"). Our authors are well familiar with a number of truly great educational materials produced by teachers that failed to sell. Still real teachers care to leave a legacy to education, in the hopes that some day garbage will stop selling and quality will start.<P>

In the metaphor of art, none of the teachers in America are finger painters. However, few of them are in the category of Renoir, Van Gogh, DaVinci, or Picasso. The lack is not skill, but level of creativity and vision. These teachers can demonstrate and teach the students the how to produce the works of art given the tools, but can not create new ones of that quality. Isn't it time to give these above average intelligence, college trained teachers curriculum materials that actually help them teach. Materials should not leave out critical background information and then treat the teacher as if she were stupid for not knowing it.<P>

It is time to recognize, as did Marva Collins did, that these students want to learn -> and do. Currently, what they are learning is that the materials in class either talk down to them or deliberately, apparently, leave things out to make the student feel stupid. The children want successful accomplishment, not failure. The teachers do also. Both will take success where they can find it, including adverse behavior. BLAME THE TOOLS FURNISHED, NOT THE UNFORTUNATE USERS. Expecting an elementary teacher to operate and teach like a college professor shows a <B>profound</B> lack of understanding of both the elementary environment and good teaching.
<P>
<P>


