<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>Science Context</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H1>Science: Education Context or Core Curriculum?</H1>

<IMG SRC="context.gif" ><P>

<B><I>"Equiped with his five senses, man explores the universe around him, and calls the adventure science."</I><BR>
Edwin Powell Hubble</B>
<P>

<B>Science gives meaning to the necessary basic skills.</B> Without this meaning, the basic skills become tedious and dull to the students. The excitement of hands-on Science is the "spoon-full of sugar" that makes these basic skills meaningful. The children realize that they can not succeed in Science without the requisite skills. Science, properly taught to the new paradigm (<I>National Science Education Standards</I>), is the CONTEXT of education, not a CORE curriculum. It is "learning how to learn", and then <B>communicating what has been learned.</B><P>
Dr. Eric Molle-Christianson has said, <I>"Science is not about facts, but about pushing back the void of ignorance."</I><P>
Science provides a hands-on, rational structure and purpose for all of the "core" curriculum such as Math, Reading/Language Arts, and History. Hands-on Science utilizes what we know about how small children, and adults, learn most effectively by tapping their natural curiosity.<P>
.	Because of the nature of hands-on science, it positively impacts students who are:<BR>
"At Risk".<BR>
Special Needs.<BR>
ESL (Language Development).<BR>
GIFTED.<P>
<B>It can also be low cost</B>, under $3 per student per year on a seven year adoption cycle!<P>

<B><I>"Begin now to study the little things in your own backyard, going from the known to the nearest unknown."</I><BR>
George Washington Carver</B>
<P>
<P>


