<HEAD>
<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>What is SDAIE?</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H1>SDAIE to you California (and the rest of America)!</H1>
<P>
<B><I>"Extensive research has shown that the best academic method of achieving second language acquisition is hands-on science."</I>
 Dr. Anna Chamot, George Washington University (formerly Univ. of Texas)</B><P><P>

<B><I>"Students achieve (second language acquisition) significantly better in programs that teach language through cognitively complex content, taught through problem-solving, discovery learning in highly interactive classroom content. ... In the long term, students do less well in programs that focus on discrete units of language taught in a structured, sequenced curriculum with the learner treated as a passive recipient of knowledge."</I>
Virginia P. Collier (National Clearinghouse for Bilingual Education)</B><P>

<I>It sure sounds as though Exploring Science uses the only acceptable method for ESL training!</I><P>


SDAIE (Specially Designed Academic Instruction in English) REQUIRES good teaching techniques to achieve its goals. The California State Senate has passed a bill (SB1969) that defines SDAIE training requirements as an alternative to the traditional ESL training component to both bilingual and multi-lingual class settings. The research of Dr. Anna Chamot has had its impact on the way that English language training for immigrants is developing. Core subjects can/should be used to enhance language skill development.<P>


<HR>
<H2>NSES (National Science Education Standards) and SDAIE, do they go together?</H2>
A critical reading of the NSES document and SDAIE methodologies shows a tremendous overlap. In fact, if one reads other files on this home page, a PROPER implementation of the NSES is a total SDAIE training program. What does this mean to the evaluator/educator?<P>

<B>National Science Education Standards</B><BR>
<OL>
<LI> In Context, Scientific Process and Problem Solving<BR>
<LI> Thematic Science Relationships (interdisciplinary)<BR>
<LI> Hands-on activities<BR>
<LI> Authentic Assessment<BR>
<LI> Integrated Curriculum<BR>
<LI> Cooperative Learning<BR>
</OL><P>

<B>SDAIE Adds</B><BR>
<OL>
<LI> In Context, language development<BR>
<LI> Scaffolding prior student knowledge<BR>
<LI> Building background information<BR>
<LI> Grade level content <BR>
<LI> Modeling of activities by the teacher<BR>
<LI> Hands-on demonstrations of understanding <BR>
<LI> Interdisciplinary Language (Communication) Authentic Assessment<BR>
<LI> Heterogeneous grouping Cooperative Learning<BR>
</OL><P>
<HR>
SDAIE, to the purists, does not start until the ESL students can handle basic grade level English, normally about third grade. To those more involved in teaching than theory, the above GOOD TEACHING techniques provide the basis for ELD (English Language Development) at an early age. The question really becomes one of function of the education system. Is it merely teaching defined subjects to fill the "squares", or is it to provide "Communicating, Cooperating, and Contributing" adults? Do the students have the skills to work and survive in a society that is becoming steadily more complex and technical?

<HR><P>
<H2>I Don't have ESL (English Second Language) Students</H2>
To Consider:<BR>
<OL>
<LI> The technical language of science is foreign to all students AND most teachers.<BR>
<LI> The program requirements above describe a typical "GIFTED" program.<BR>
<LI> Full Inclusion of Special Needs students require this kind of program according to ASHA. <BR>
<LI> Successful "At Risk" programs have used these methods.<BR>
<LI> With this teaching, ESL third graders beat "GIFTED" fifth graders. <BR>
<LI> Average students fit in this spectrum quite comfortably. <BR>
</OL><P>

<H2>I do Bilingual Teaching!!!</H2>
<DT><A HREF="bilinge2.htm">ESL Optimized Curriculum Approach ... 2/23/96.</A><BR>
The experts have said that it is the best path to success, but how does one implement it?<P>

You also have a requirement for daily ELD (English Language Development). How are you meeting that requirement? There are school districts with an "Exemplary" Bilingual elementary program that have an unacceptable percentage of the students fail in the transition to English in the seventh grade. Perhaps they would find that implementing the research of Dr. Anna Chamot would turn that failure to success.<P>

The purpose of bilingual education is to provide access of core curriculum to the non-English speaking students WHILE they are learning the English skills necessary for adult survival in the American economy. <P>
<P>

<HR>
<H2>CORE Curriculum</H2>
The real problem concerning Science is whether it is a core curriculum or THE core curriculum. As traditionally taught, Science is a core curriculum. It deals with what scientists have discovered and when. However, perhaps that should more properly be called History.<P>

The new way of teaching science, NSES, is to teach how scientists discover and communicate new knowledge. <P>

<B><I>"Science is not about facts, but about pushing back the void of ignorance."</I><BR>
Dr. Erik Molle-Christianson</B><P>

Since this is what we spend so many years trying to teach our children, isn't Science, in fact, THE core curriculum. <BR>
<UL>
<LI> Why do we want the children to read?<BR>
<LI> Why do we want the children to do math?<BR>
<LI> Why do we want the children to draw?<BR>
<LI> Why do we want the children to speak?<BR>
<LI> Why do we want the children to understand our society?<BR>
<LI> Why do we want the children to cooperate?<BR>
<LI> Why do we want the children to achieve?<BR>
</UL><P>

<HR>
The proper implementation of the NSES produces all of those results, especially when the good teaching methods of SDAIE are added. Since Science teaching has evolved from teaching "facts" into teaching how to learn and communicate effectively, Science has become the natural core curriculum around which ALL other subjects are taught. <B>For those struggling to create an integrated curriculum environment, seek no more!</B><P><P>
<HR>
<H2>Studying SCIENCE is "Learning How to Learn"</H2>
The teacher/authors of EXPLORING SCIENCE (Macro Press) have been teaching in and demonstrating SDAIE/ELD methods for years. EXPLORING SCIENCE (K-6) started as a SDAIE/ELD program. (The techniques that "experts" restrict to grade 3 and above work down to kindergarten effectively because the evolving nature of Science education has changed the learning requirement from "facts" to problem solving and communication.) It now does the NSES only because the national standards committee finally realized what GOOD teaching requires!
<HR><P>


