<Title>EXPLORING SCIENCE Sample lessons</title>



<B><I>"A scientist suffers no failures, only unprofitable avenues to pursue." </I></B> <BR>
<B>Dr. Jonas Salk</B><P>

<P>

<DT><A HREF="11goals.htm">Why Don't Most Elementary Teachers Teach Science???</A>
<DD>There must be a reason! Presented here is the response of a Reading/Language Arts mentor teacher, grade 3.
<P>


The following Copyrighted lessons are furnished free for educational purposes, with our copyright. The may not be used for commercial purposes by any person or group except Macro Press, Inc.  Others will be added over time. Asterisked names are in process of preparation for the Web.<P><P>


<DT><A HREF="colors.htm"> Colors All Around Me - K</A>
<DD>Science is discovery. Kindergarten is the ultimate science class.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="11ex3.htm"> What is Liquid? - 1</A>
<DD>Comparing, inferring, and relating of characteristics in the first grade.<BR>
<DT><A HREF="rm1_3.gif"> RM(1)3 (10K gif file)</A><BR>
<DT><A HREF="er1_3.gif"> ER(1)3 (3K gif file)</A><BR>
<P>
<DT><A HREF="rocks.htm"> Rock Hounds - 2</A>
<DD>Develope language first and the second grader can perform sophisticated science.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="energy.htm"> Bread to Toast - 3</A>
<DD>What is energy? Can it be taught thematically?<BR>
<DT><A HREF="gm17.gif"> GM-17 (7K gif file)</A>
<P>
<DT><A HREF="41ex2.htm">Scientists Control Variables - 4</A>
<DD>How are scientists able to test reliably? This is an important concept for ALL students.
<P>
<DT><A HREF="51ex2.pdf">Why Does It Magnify? - 5 (404K pdf file)</A>
<DD>How is it possible to understand and communicate new knowledge graphically?
The normal way of presenting lessons requires 11-14K, rather than 404K (includes 2 student text pages). Communication bandwidth will become an increasing problem as more people join the "NET". <B>This lesson requires the Adobe Acrobat reader.</B> If this is what you want, let us know! The small file format takes us ten times longer to create.<P>

<P>
<DT><A HREF="discovry.htm"> Discovery of New Species - 5</A>
<DD>It is not enough to discover something new. A scientist must be able to communicate the new knowledge by relating it to previously discovered information.<BR>
<DT><A HREF="gm14.gif"> GM-14 (7K gif file)</A>

<P>
<DT><A HREF="51ex5.htm"> Hypothesizing Historians - 5</A>
<DD>Does our present understanding and belief system affect how we view new information? Dr. Betty Meggars said that she liked the lesson!
<P>
<DT><A HREF="62ex2.htm"> Ocean Box - 6</A>
<DD>Just how accurate are the facts presented in science books and papers?
