<Title>Good Teaching - Elementary</Title>
<H1>Good Teaching IS Elementary!</H1>

<B><I>We generally see what we expect to see.</I></B>  Mary Leaky<P><P>

<DT><A HREF="jerry.gif" >The Young Need Good Teaching Too! - 400K</A> <P>

The Goals 2000 program is an effort to address the needs of the American society in the 21st century by educating its children to be first in the world in math and science. Can we teach ALL of the students without good teaching and good teaching materials?<P><P>

Dr. Stephen Krashen has defined good teaching as <B><I>Comprehensible Input</I></B>. But what is that? His definition is, the materials must be presented to the recipient, student, in a manner such that it is both understood and assimilated by the recipient. This sounds simple, it is not. For the student to receive <B><I>Comprehensible Input</I></B>, either the teacher must have a full understanding of both the material to be covered and the student background knowledge, or the teacher resource material presents the information with sufficient clarity and meaning so that the teacher can manipulate the information until the students understand. <I>Materials presently available in the classroom, particularly elementary science, fall significantly short of that goal. </I><P><P>
Much has been made over the concept of <B><I>Comprehensible Output</I></B>. Where the student is concerned, this is testing to validate learning. The concern is whether the student merely knows the facts, or can use them effectively in a variety of different situations. For this reason <I>Authentic Assessment</I> techniques are specifically called for in the new 1995 US Science Standards. Can the student(s) effectively document in a scientist's notebook what has been discovered in  a manner that allows others to find the same results? Can the student(s) discuss these findings at a science conference? Is terminology used appropriately? Can the student(s) design their own tests to extend the nature of the given experiment? The "YES" answer to these questions is Comprehensible Output, Authentic Assessment, and Integrated Curriculum.<P>

Each level of education, from primary to graduate school faces different challenges and requirements. The techniques used to impart the required knowledge and abilities to the students are as different day and night. A good analogy is building a house.<P>

Graduate school could be compared to putting in the finishing touches that turn a building with rooms into a house, hospital, or science laboratory. <I>The primary grades are certainly the foundation upon which the education structure is built.</I> Without the broad spectrum of skills and knowledge that are introduced and built during the elementary years, the specialized science training will result in Cold Fusion.<P>

It has been said that most elementary school districts are made of 85% reading/language arts teachers. Since reading is the first requirement of life long learning, that ratio of teachers is vital. These teachers have are generally specialists in that area, and generalists in all others. These teachers need Comprehensive Input from their teacher resource materials in order to provide Comprehensive Output to their students. <P>

Primary problems that exist for elementary teachers, but should not for college professors are:
<UL>
<LI>Language skills (including ESL).
<LI>Reading and writing skills.
<LI>Basic math skills.
<LI>Discipline and cooperation.
<LI>Learning and Note taking skills.
<LI>Speaking and communication skills.
<LI>Graphic presentation and art skills.
<LI>Problem solving skills.
<LI>History/Social Science perspective.
<LI>Socializing of the students who are new to formal education.
</UL><P>

No college professor ever faces this range of requirements, nor should she/he. If the primary teachers do their job, the task of the college professors will be greatly simplified. However, if the curriculum materials written for the primary and elementary teachers are more appropriate to the specialized (compartmentalized) teaching requirements of high school and college, the task of the primary/elementary teacher becomes difficult/impossible. <I>Based on past performance this is exactly what has been done.</I> Successes have happened, but they are individual achievement rather than general practice.<P><P>

<B>Another educational level analogy:</B><BR><UL>
<LI> Elementary teacher developes the basic skills of running, jumping, and throwing.<BR>
<LI> High school teachers train many sports, e.g. basket ball, baseball, football, and track sports.<BR>
<LI>College hones these skills to a sophisticated level in ONE sport. <BR></UL><P>

<B><I>I have found it impossible to truly understand the findings at archaeological digs without consulting with experts in a wide range of disciplines, such as climatologists, oceanographers, geologists, etc.</I></B>  <BR>
Dr. Betty Meggars<BR>
Museum of Natural History, Smithsonian<P>

<B><I>In my work researching radioactive materials disposal, I have to use Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Geology, and Mathematics daily.</I></B><BR>
Dr. Leo S. Gomez<BR>
Sandia National Laboratory<P>

As the 1995 National Science Education Standards state, the seminal work done by Project 2061 provides insight into solving the teaching of relationships between science disciplines. <I>(See report on Meeting the Project 2061 Benchmarks.)</I>  However, within the field of science education, it has fallen on the 1995 Standards to document the requirement for an integrated curriculum. <B>These new standards actually reflect what the best elementary teachers have been doing out of necessity.</B> <P>

While, presently, each curriculum area has been text and training materials written as separate academic entities, all of the best teachers have been integrating the materials for years. A reading lesson covering getting water from a well in the book <B>Little House on the Prairie</B> leads to a science lesson on pulleys, which leads to a history/Social Science lesson on the westward movement, which in turn leads to a discussion on how science and technology improve life. This approach produces a gain in time for the teacher and an expanded understanding and appreciation by the student for all three subjects. This lesson, done cooperatively, provides for all different learning styles and skill levels. <BR>
Related reports:
<DT><A HREF="1bsintro.htm"> How Can We Create the Scientific Attitude</A>
<DT><A HREF="1scithnk.htm"> What are the Scientific Thinking Processes?</A>
<DT><A HREF="1handmnd.htm"> Is There More Than One Kind of Hands-on?</A>
<DT><A HREF="1scinbk.htm"> Documenting Scientific Studies</A>
<DT><A HREF="1cooplrn.htm"> Get Your Students Cooperating - How?</A>
<DT><A HREF="1curconn.htm"> Integrating the Curriculum</A><BR>
<DT><A HREF="1grorg.htm"> The How and When of Graphic Organizers</A><BR>
<DT><A HREF="1lep.htm"> Meeting the Needs of the Multi-Language Classroom </A>
<DT><A HREF="1sneeds.htm"> Meeting the Needs of the Full Inclusion Classroom</A>
<DT><A HREF="1ch1.htm"> Meeting the Needs of the "At Risk" student</A>
<DT><A HREF="1vcis.htm"> Values, Current Issues, and Society</A><BR>
<DT><A HREF="1hsconn.htm"> Implementing the Home-School Connection</A><BR>
<DT><A HREF="1authass.htm"> Assessing the Curriculum Product</A><BR>
Authentic Assessment is not a "good teaching" technique. It will, however, provide you with the ability to evaluate whether your students actually understand what they are being taught. This will be true even for those students who are not able to express their understanding by traditional means. <DT><A HREF="1authass.htm">Authentic Assessment Made Easy</A>

<P>
 EXPLORING SCIENCE was written by teachers to address these needs.<P>

One aspect, that should be obvious, is that to study how scientists learn is to study how to learn effectively. A curriculum based on the new 1995 Science Standards should naturally improve the learning techniques of ALL students. This in turn should improve the student performance in every other subject. This could lead one to the conclusion the teaching science to the new 1995 standards should make science the curriculum about which ALL other subjects flow. This is exactly the approach used by the teacher/authors of EXPLORING SCIENCE.<P>

This learning should also include the teachers. While a specialist, Physics, Chemistry, etc., can spend significant periods of time learning the new knowledge in that discipline, the generalist has no more time to spread over all of the disciplines being taught.
One final requirement then follows, for the primary and elementary generalist (Standards 3-9 para 2), the teaching materials should be self-mentoring. No reading/language arts teacher can afford two years of intensive in-servicing to teach the materials for any one curriculum, especially since she/he is required to teach seven different subjects AND may be teaching a different grade level next year. ALL of the in-service materials HAVE to be built into the teacher materials if there is ever going to be the successful science teaching desired for ALL students.
<P><P><P>

