<TITLE>The Future of Science Education</TITLE>


<DT><A HREF="meetus.htm">How to meet the new US Science Standards for elementary students</A>
<DD>The NEW US Science Education Standards do not stop at knowledge of accepted science facts, nor at "Hands-on". It even goes beyond the Thematic approach of Project 2061, American Association for the Advancement of Science. It REQUIRES a full level of curriculum integration.
<P>

<DT><A HREF="do2061.htm">Meeting the Project 2061 Benchmarks</A>
<DD>Thematic Science may be new to science teaching and materials. It is, however, based on the realization of scientists in many fields that they need information from other disciplines to solve their problems. Elementary teachers have been doing thematic integration of reading, art, and math subjects for more than 20 years to provide better understanding for their students.
<P>

<DT><A HREF="tenplus.htm">10 Critical Science Instruction Needs +2</A>
<DD>Science Education has entered a new age. It is now recognized that telling the students what has been discovered in the past is not enough.
<P>

<DT><A HREF="1themes.htm">What Do the Science Thematic Names Mean</A>
<DD>A teacher needs to know what the words mean. The Curriculum Director needs to know where they appear across the grade levels. Both questions are answered in this brief.
<P>


