<Title>Our Experts</Title>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1>The Expert Basis For Exploring Science</H1>
<B>expertise [French, from expert, experience] Skill or knowledge in an area.</B><P>

The expertise of the authors is clearly in the elementary and primary classroom and teacher training environment. They achieved this expertise the way that quality teachers have always done it. They worked and studied. By listening to and reading from the top field research being done in the universities across the nation, they have picked out the best work and adapted it to the environments of their classrooms. <P>

By its nature, research is always a special case situation that needs to be adapted by field practitioners. The following is a partial list of researchers whose works have been utilized heavily by the teacher/authors  in the classroom and the writing of Exploring Science.<P>
<UL>
<LI>Gardner's Multiple Intelligences<BR>
	<LI>Johnson, Slavin, and Kagan's Cooperative Learning<BR>
	<LI>Chamot's Language Acquisition through Science<BR>
	<LI>Montgomery's Full Inclusion of Special Needs<BR>
	<LI>Krashen's Comprehensible Input<BR>
<LI>Jim Cummins' Comprehensible Output<BR>
<LI>UCI brain research on Patterning and Recognition <BR>
	<LI>Long's Negotiating for meaning<BR>
	<LI>Leanna Traill's building on prior knowledge<BR>
<LI>Virginia Collier's Successful English Language Acquisition<BR>
	<LI>Gabriel Rico and Susan Kavolich's use of Graphic Organizers<BR>
	<LI>Marcia Brechtal for Project G.L.A.D, Title VII National Academic Excellence. <BR>
	<LI>Grant Wiggins and Leanna Traill - Authentic Assessment/Portfolio Analysis </UL>

</BODY></HTML>

