<Title>NSES NOW!</Title>
</HEAD

<BODY>
<H1>The U.S. 
National Science Education Standards: 
Hogwash OR Hooray! 1/03/96</H1>
Leigh Hoven-Severson, Teacher<BR>
Penelope Walters Swenson, Assistant Superintendent, Curriculum<P>
<B>The new National Science Education Standards have been adopted.</B> These standard arose out of a clearly identified educational need. Dean-Witter estimates that within 20 years 50% of all stocks publicly traded will be technology based, up from 18% today. What does that mean for the product of our educational system, America's future work force?<P>

<H2>Citizens of the 21st Century Will Need to be:</H2>
<UL>
<LI>	Problem Solvers<BR>
<LI>	Cooperative Workers<BR>
<LI>	Self-starters<BR>
<LI>	Scientifically Literate<BR>
<LI>	Flexible Thinkers<BR>
<LI>	Critical Evaluators<BR>
<LI>	Effective Questioners
</UL><P>
This is not just the top 5% of the students. It is all of those students who expect to hold a job in the 21st Century! <B>Objective: <I>America's students must become first in the world in science and math by demonstrating competency over challenging subject matter.</I></B><P>
The National Science Education Standards is a large document; however, its content requirement is general and not great. The real requirements are in the approach to education. These requirements are basically six items that many elementary teachers now do in other subjects.<P>
<H2>Standards</H2>
<OL>
<LI><DT><A HREF="1scithnk.htm"> Scientific Process and Problem Solving?</A><BR>
<LI><DT><A HREF="1themes.htm"> Thematic Science Relationships</A><BR>
<LI><DT><A HREF="1handmnd.htm"> Hands-on activities</A><BR>
<LI><DT><A HREF="1authass.htm"> Authentic Assessment</A><BR>
<LI><DT><A HREF="1curconn.htm"> Integrated (Interdisciplinary) Curriculum</A><BR> 
<LI><DT><A HREF="1cooplrn.htm"> Collaborative  (Cooperative) Learning</A>
</OL>
<P>
<HR>
<DT><A HREF="tenplus.htm"> The most critical needs of science education are:</A><P>
<HR>
<P>
The NSES is the product of a prolonged effort by some of the nations top science educators. Like all efforts of a large committee with lots of feed back from educators and teachers around the country, the NSES is the definition of THE GOOD, THE BAD, AND THE UGLY! <P>
<H2>THE GOOD</H2>
The standard calls for a program incorporating outstanding teaching techniques in an integrated teaching environment using cooperative learning. In the optimal setting, a good analogy would be the Rutan team of engineers who produced the Voyager. They set out to produce a plane that could fly around the world on one tank of gas, and succeeded. They developed a complete airplane to meet the goal, "Fly around the world on a single tank of gas".<P>

<IMG SRC="voyager.gif" ALIGN MIDDLE><B>     Voyager</B><P>

Isn't the voyager teams goal comparable to education's goal of making America's students first in the world in science and math as demonstrated by the ability to solve complex and challenging problems? A curriculum produced by the same methodology would be one that is a fully developed curriculum concept designed to meet the goals of the NSES <B>before</B> the activities are added. And, the activities selected would match the projected learning requirements. Active mentor teachers used this method to develop EXPLORING SCIENCE.<P>
<P>

<H2>THE BAD</H2>
In all committee efforts, significant compromises are made to accomodate various groups. By making the study and knowledge requirements K-4, 5-8, 9-12, to allow local districts to do their own thing, the NSES made it possible for the children of our mobile society to slip through the cracks. For a family that moves a lot, EVEN IF EVERY SCHOOL DISTRICT THEIR CHILD ATTENDS COMPLIES FULLY WITH THE NSES, it is possible that the child will NEVER study the solar system, the human body, or (your choice of required subject matter). Each school district is allowed to teach a subject in the grade level of their choice.<P><P>

<H2>THE UGLY</H2>
The NSES is full of examples of "perfect" activities. One can count on the various publishers going out and building modules of "perfect" activities and calling the program NSES compliant. Each team is called on to design a "perfect" component The teams then present their "perfect" components:<P>


<IMG SRC="lwing.gif" ALIGN MIDDLE><B>Left wing </B><P>
<IMG SRC="rwing.gif" ALIGN MIDDLE><B>Right wing </B><P>
<IMG SRC="power.gif" ALIGN MIDDLE><B>Power Plant </B><P>
<IMG SRC="fuselage.gif" ALIGN MIDDLE><B>Fuselage </B><P>
<IMG SRC="tail.gif" ALIGN MIDDLE><B>Tail </B><P>

<BR>
These are packaged brightly as modules of the "perfect" airplane kit. Of course, you can count on the failure "to fly" being placed on "incompetent" teachers and "lazy" students! <P>

Is it possible to easily identify the "UGLY"? Most of those programs will be sublimely easy to identify! <P>
<I>Are the student materials packaged into separate Physical, Earth, and Life Science books?<P>
 Does the student get referred to multiple little books/pamphlets during the course of a lesson or series of supposedly interrelated lessons? </I><P>
Those are definite clues that the publisher grabbed materials off the shelf to "look like" an integrated curriculum rather than producing a real one. Both children AND adults tend to separate study into blocks. What is in a different book, or even a different chapter, is a different subject of study. It is NOT linked in our minds!<P>

<HR>
<P>

The GOOD, the BAD, and the UGLY should be obvious to all concerned. Is there any evidence that the GOOD really works? How about a case study?<P>

<HR>
<H2>Happiness is...</H2>
In 1991, a group of nine elementary teachers got together to address the deficiencies that existed in curriculum materials supplied for their classrooms. They produced a K-6 <I>integrated curriculum, hands-on</I> science program called <B>EXPLORING SCIENCE</B>. It is rewarding to note that four years later the national standards committee has decided that all science curriculum materials used in America's classrooms should be written to resemble the program written by these teachers. The National Science Education Standards (NSES) is available by calling 1-800-624-6242. <I>(See greater review below)</I><P><P>

For training on how to meet the NSES in your classrooms, look to Macro Press - those nine teachers - and other carefully chosen qualified presenters. <A HREF="nsestran.htm">Trainers and phone numbers</A>
<P>
<HR>


 The case study consists with a group of third graders entering the NASA/NSTA SSIP (Space Science Involvement Program) competing against fifth graders. O.K., so the fifth graders had 80% more schooling time, so what? The what is interesting. The third graders were not only not gifted, they were also educated in large (29-33 student) suburban classrooms with other students who not did not speak their language, nor did their teacher. <P>
<HR>
<H2>Chronology of Educational Success:</H2>
(<U>Formulation</U>)  September 1990, three non-English speaking students (Chinese, Hindi, and Farsi) joined other non-English speakers (29 students with 11 different languages) in the Kindergarten classroom of Jerry Bolliger (K + 1 Author).<P>

<DT><A HREF="colors.htm"> Building language using Kindergarten science is not only possible, but desireable.</A><P>

(<U>Gestation</U>)  September 1992, this class of 29 LEP students entered the classroom of Kathy Manual (Grade 2 author).<P>

<DT><A HREF="rocks.htm"> The results of language building is the ability to do sophisticated (for second graders) science.</A><P>

(<U>Fruition</U>)  September 1993, these three students joined 30 other students (40% ESL - 7 languages) entered the classroom of Leigh Hoven-Severson (Chief Editor).
January 1994, these three 3rd grade students competed against gifted 5th grade students trained by in GIFTED magnet programs. Steven Chen, Himani Amoli, and Laith Oweini took first in California and second in the nation. Another team of their classmates took second in California. The classroom itself was a near worst case scenario  (33 students, 40% ESL, 3 full inclusion students, 3 "at risk" students, and one gifted student).<P>


January 1995, Leigh's students entered again. They took 1st and 3rd in California.
Look at the NASA/NSTA SSIP contest. It tests whether students are achieving your education goals!<P>
<HR>

The development of language and communication skills, particularly for elementary students, is simplified when it is integrated with the modeling of successful hands-on science. The interdisciplinary teaching requirement of the NSES optimizes teaching for all levels. Teaching with materials that match in every requirement the NSES, these students learned reading, writing, arithmetic, and speaking in English. <P>

<HR>
How was the NASA/NSTA SSIP contest won by the worst case scenario classroom?<P>

<DT><A HREF="1winning.htm"> Winning the SSIP</A><P>
<HR>


Science is also descriptive vocabulary. The method and associations used to teach the vocabulary is less important than the understanding and application gained.<P>



<H2>ENERGY RAP</H2>

(do motions called for)<BR>
<B>That's heat energy I'm here to say.<BR> 
It works in a most peculiar way. <BR>
Rub your hands together,<BR>
Hot, hot, hot,<BR>
But unburned wood is</B>
(wiggle index finger showing NO!)<BR>
<B>Not, not, not.</B><BR>
(simulate placing pennies in a piggy bank)<BR>
<B>"Potential" means stored<BR>
Like savings in the bank.<BR>
"Kinetic" means moving</B><BR>
(simulate turning the crank on a fishing reel)<BR>
<B>Like motion of a crank.<BR>

Heat, light, nuclear too,</B>
(point to yourself, then to the people addressed.)</B>
<B>Energy works for me and you.</B>
<P><P>

<HR>

Language can be built by teaching how to keep a Scientist's notebook!<P>
<H2>Going On a Bug Hunt!</H2>

Teacher leads --  students echo.)<P>
<B>Going on a bug hunt!<BR>
Going to spot a lot of them<BR>
Big bugs, little bugs<BR>
Maybe just a few slugs<BR>
Going on a bug hunt!</B><BR>
(shade eyes with hand - look around ground)<BR>
<B>Looking under rocks and leaves</B><BR>
(look around upward)<BR>
<B>Looking up in the trees<BR>
Searching over the school ground</B><BR>
(simulate writing in notebook)<BR>
<B>Charting all the bugs I found</B><BR>
(simulate drawing bug)<BR>
<B>Drawing pictures in my book<BR>
To remember just the way they look<BR>
Keeping detailed info-<BR>
So I'll stay in the know<BR>
Going on a bug hunt<BR>
Quietly, set, off I go . . . . . . . </B><P>

Science is documentation and communication, as well as hands-on activities and learning "facts".<P>
<HR>
 The NASA/NSTA SSIP contest is an accurate Authentic Assessment of your students progress towards meeting the NSES requirements. The 1995 National Science Education Standards are designed to make America's students first in the world in Science and Math. The teaching methods needed are very clear in the standards. Appropriate materials exist AND work!<P>
<HR>
<DT><A HREF="nsestran.htm"> Be the Best, train on the NSES!</A><P>
<P>


