<Title>WHAT'S NEW</Title>

<H1>Today, Tommorow, and Maybe the Next Day</H1>

We are starting, 11/26/95, to add scientist biographies to the information on our page.
<A HREF="1feasci.htm">Featured Scientists</A><P><P>

Much has been said in the last 10 years about the failure of education and teachers, and about the students! Most of it, I believe, is short-sighted and does not address the real causes of failure (last in the industrialized world in science and math).<P>

The classroom teachers are working as hard as they ever have and the children enter kindergarten as eager as ever. So what is the problem? As I see it, the problem is:
"When you are up to your elbows in alligators, it is difficult to remember that your job is to drain the swamp." So much emphasis has been placed on short term activities, lacking any long term goal, that we have lost sight of the fact that education's function is to produce adults who are communicative, cooperative, and contributing. I have been looking at the "guilty", and they are not. Education is being asked to do so many contradictory things that the people involved are too deeply involved with the process to remember the function.<P>

It is my <B>biased opinion</B> that curriculum needs to meet the needs of both teachers and students. I have yet to run into really bad science activities, as an example. However, I have looked in vain to find any other integrated curriculum program besides EXPLORING SCIENCE. Demanding elementary teachers to take at least two years of training so that they can "integrate" the lessons for their classrooms is unacceptable in my opinion. To be considered a hands-on, integrated curriculum each program, and section within the program, should have clearly defined objectives with the paths to obtain those objectives spelled out. Additionally, the teacher advise and training should be incorporated in the teacher manual in such a way that ANY qualified teacher can teach the lesson properly. The National Science Education Standards can only be achieved if the curriculum used is written in this manner. I have never met a scientist who could teach every discipline. Asking a elementary reading-language arts teacher to perform this task without built-in science support is ludicrous. <BR>
Larry L. Severson (speaking for myself).<P>

<HR>

<I>"Education is not a pendulum; it is a spiral. Each correction takes into account the failings of the past and moves inward towards better teaching. Those pushing "back-to-basics" forget the problems that lead to the "higher-thinking" style of teaching used the last 30 years. We need to keep the good of the currently condemmed teaching style while incorporating more basic skill work. WE NEED BALANCE, not retreat."</I><BR>
Marcia Brechtal<BR>
Coordinator/Disseminator, Project G.L.A.D<BR>
Title VII, National Academic Excellence<P>
<HR>
<P>

<I>"... Sure its nice to have Internet access in the classroom -- just like it's nice to have outlets in the classroom where you can plug in projectors and other educational appliances. But just as quality of education in the past wasn't dependent on electrical wall sockets, the quality of the educational future won't be dependent on digital Internet sockets. To argue that it should displays both an ignorance of history and a dishonesty about the real challenges facing the schools. The Internet isn't a part of the solution; it's part of the problem."</I><BR>
Michael Schrage
LA Times<BR>
October 9, Page D-2<P>
<HR>
<P>

<I>"The coming of the information age is forcing schools to rethink curricula, which they probably should do anyway. Unfortunately, some schools insist on using computers as glorified flash cards, transferring boring rote learning from paper to software. And some of the glitzy multimedia education tools go too far the other way, making education into a game. Somewhere in between are schools using computers to let the kids run experiments, analyze data, and write papers in ways that could not have been imagined 20 years ago."</I><BR>
Byte Magazine<BR>
September 1995, Page 131<P>
<HR>
<P>

<I>"It's clear that learning facts without understanding isn't much of an education, and students are highly motivated to play games rather than study facts. But the weakness of the problem-solving approach to education is that it's no use solving problems unless they are related to the real world: while the ability to think is valuable, sometimes what you need is to be told how someone else did it.<P>
We tend to learn to do what we've already done. Every sports coach understands this. Left to themselves, students generally won't stumble onto the proper technique. Take fencing as an example. Hand a class of beginners weapons and protective equipment, and in a week, they'll have "problem-solved" their way to so many bad habits they may never be any good."</I><BR>
Dr. Jerry Pournelle<BR>
Byte Magazine<BR>
September, 1995, Page 283<P>
<HR>
<P>

<I>"Science education requires a balance of facts, thinking processes, and skills."</I><BR>
Bobbie Mahler<BR>
Assistant Superintendent<BR>
Centralia ESD, California<P>
<HR>
<P>


<DT><A HREF="computer.htm">PROPER Use of Computers in Schools</A>
<DT><A HREF="writing.htm">PROPER Scientific Writing</A>
<DT><A HREF="material.htm">PROPER Testing of Teacher Resource Materials</A>
<DT><A HREF="educate.htm">PROPER Educational Theories</A>
<DT><A HREF="standard.htm">Becoming First in the World</A>

<HR>
<DT><A HREF="11goals.htm">Science education thoughts</A>
<DD>It is estimated that 95% of primary and elementary teachers do not teach science. Is there a reason why science gets only lip-service in K-6 grades?
<P>

<DT><A HREF="meonly.htm">In my opinion</A>
<DD>Some thoughts based on discussions at the NSTA National Convention in Philadelphia are presented here.
<P><P>

Starting 1 June, 1995, we will attempt to add new K-6 hands-on science lessons as time permits. These samples are from our science series, EXPLORING SCIENCE. Because EXPLORING SCIENCE was written by active classroom teachers who understand the problems, it actually goes beyond the requirements of the 1995 National Science Education Standards, November 1994.<P>

Clearly, the lessons would be better supported in the total context of the EXPLORING SCIENCE curriculum. However, expect to be amazed how well they will work in your classroom with what is on Internet.
