<HTML>
<HEAD>
<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>Buzz Words</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>BUZZ WORDS MAY NOT BE APPROPRIATE</H1>

<B><I>"The English and the Americans, two people separated by a common language."</I> Winston Churchill</B><P>

On this page we will be developing a glossary of education Buzz Words, and their appropriate usage. A significant part of what is wrong today in education is application of the wrong tool for the job. The failure to communicate because of the use of buzz words is of great importance.<P>
<HR>
<H2>Less is More!</H2>
What a beautiful, expressive phrase. We all immediately identify with its meaning, don't we? Rather than scattering our teaching efforts, we can get right to the heart of the matter, concentrate on what is important. There will be no more time wasted on confusing, extraneous facts.<P>

Wait a minute, are we forgetting something? Every accident investigator is familiar with the fact that no two witnesses will describe the accident exactly the same. <P>

To a college professor, <B>"Less is More"</B> clearly means "fewer areas of study, but in greater detail." After all, that is what a college develops, experts.<P>

To an elementary teacher, <B>"Less is More"</B> means something quite different. The children come to the teacher with no foundation on which to build the new knowledge. The teacher attempts to lay this foundation by relating all of the facts together, link the cement that binds aggregate into concrete. This can only be achieved by using lots of little facts, aggregate, that can be related. Energy is "change of state":<P>

<UL>
<LI>A child running.<BR>
<LI>A plant growing.<BR>
<LI>A rock rolling.<BR>
<LI>Lightning flashing.<P>
</UL>

This is depth in concept, not a given fact. This is not expertise! The facts are presented in very shallow depth. Try building a house on sand, or gravel, it will not stand. The glue of "science themes" binds the bits together so that the student develops an understanding on how things relate. When the college teaching style is moved to elementary classrooms, two things happen:<P>

<OL>
<LI>The information is difficult to assimilate.<BR>
<LI>No foundation upon which education can be furthered is laid.<P>
</OL>
<HR>

When you hear any "Buzz", question the person about its meaning and appropriateness to the task at hand. In most cases, it won't be.<P>
<HR><P><P><P>

Copyright &copy; 1996 <BR>
Macro Press Incorporated<BR>
18242 Peters Court<BR>
Fountain Valley, CA  92708<BR>
Phone/fax   (714) 964-9191<BR>
e-mail:  science@macropress.com<P>

</BODY></HTML>
