Content-length: 7998
Last-modified: Tue, 17 Sep 1996 21:27:58 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>NUMBERS</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="numbers.jpg" >
<CENTER>
<H1>THE LITERACY OF NUMBERS</H1>
</CENTER>
A successful society can only exist where all/most adults are communicating, cooperating, and contributing. To achieve that goal, the education of the students must prepare them to function in that manner. Obviously, the education of children to function as integrated/useful adults in America needs to be significantly different than for children of the Kalahari Bushmen.<P>

Since the invention of the printing press, the ability to read has been the avenue to self-learning. For this reason, 85% of all elementary teachers are Reading/Language Arts specialists. Those who want to teach, and the districts that hire them, know where the most emphasis needs to be placed in the early years -> reading, then writing. Once a child can "read to learn", their future ability to communicate, cooperate, and contribute is simplified.<P>

Every day we hear about the need for "literacy" in different subject areas: <BR>
<UL>
<LI> Language, <BR>
<LI> Science, <BR> 
<LI> Technology, <BR>
<LI> Math, <BR>
<LI> Geography, <BR>
<LI> etc.<P></UL>
Sounds good, but what does it mean for the schools, teachers, and students?<P>

<HR>
<CENTER>
<H2>10-80-10</H2>
</CENTER>
While I was in the military (30 years ago), we frequently heard that:<BR>
<I>10% succeeded, no matter what.<BR>
10% failed, no matter what.<BR>
<B>80% achieved based on one's leadership - or teachership.</B></I><P>

In other words, high achievement by a class of the top 10% is nothing to brag about. Failure with the bottom 10% is expected, BUT, how does one recognize the bottom 10%. Starting with only those students who had already failed, and dropped out of school, Marva Collins had 85% of her students graduate from college. All of her students were supposedly bottom 10%!<P>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H2>75-15-10</H2>
</CENTER>
Because of what I feel is an inappropriate use of the term literacy, I went to
a reading/language arts specialist and asked her to define what she considered
a literate person in her specialty. She said, "A <I>literate</I> person is one who can
understand what is read, can write, speak, and communicate <B>effectively</B>, but most 
importantly, reads and writes for <B>pleasure</B>."<P>

If 75% of the people read, one in four do not. That is not a literate society. However, is 75% read for pleasure and 15% can read, only the 10% don't read. That is a <B>literate society</B>. This same reading expert, who has taught 30 years with learning to disabled to gifted classes, stated that only about 3% were incapable of being taught to read well enough to "read to learn". The other 7% have problems unrelated to ability.<P>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H2>PROBLEM</H2>
</CENTER>

However, we are not calling for just reading. We also want literacy in:<BR>
<UL>
<LI> Language, <BR>
<LI> Science, <BR> 
<LI> Technology, <BR>
<LI> Math, <BR>
<LI> Geography, <BR>
<LI> etc.<P></UL>

There is a basic problem here. There is a significant difference between a generalist and a specialist. If America's reading specialist elementary teachers can not be considered "literate" in all of the disciplines above by the definition above, how is America to achieve literacy in these areas? Many authoritative sources (including Project SEED (CalTech), NSF, etc.) are calling for two years specialized science training for every elementary teacher. How about adding two years advanced Math and two years in computers and two years in Geography? Good Luck! The teachers, districts, and other funding agencies can/will not fund such an exercise.<P>

<CENTER>
<H3>WHY?</H3>
</CENTER>

Why do we have these problems? There was a time when virtually every child completing third grade could read well enough to "read to learn". Will Rodgers once said, "The average American graduates from high school ready to take on the world knowing that he will succeed." Perhaps curriculum and expectations have changed. <P>

Everyone involved in elementary education knows well the continuous change in ideas and frameworks that they are supposed to teach. We no longer know, as a society, what is important for the student to learn, or the teacher to teach. <P>

A good example is technology. Being comfortable with one's ability to solve problems and use whatever tools are available to make the job easier is definitely an asset. The question is not whether one should introduce technology into the classroom or not. Instead, the question is how to use it appropriately. The answer is not whether the student was "hooked" by the technology (tool), but rather if the student learned to comfortably solve the problem at hand in an expeditious manner USING THE BEST TOOL AVAILABLE. There are arenas in which technology usage is called for, and those where it hinders. <P>

Given these real unsolved problems, the new answer is to have each teacher grab the available materials from the universities and major publishers (that require two years training to use effectively) and make it hers/his by writing all of the supporting information needed. Talk about "finger painters" posing as artists! These educated reading/language arts teachers, 85%, do not have the background or TIME, but they are going to write the science program that they teach in their classrooms. RIGHT!<P>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<H2>SOLUTION</H2>
</CENTER>
What elementary students need is a strong "general" background, a foundation for the future building of expertise. This general background is what allows the future adults to communicate with each other meaningfully with cooperation, each contributing from his/her background. This learning has to be presented in the context of what the child already knows.<P>

How about a novel thought? Elementary teachers have to teach all of the subjects that we desire "literacy" in every day. But they need none of the depth of detail or knowledge that a graduate student in those disciplines would need. What the teacher is building is a foundation of bits of knowledge cemented together with linkages to other disciplines so that the student can erect a structure of understanding that will effectively contain and support all future learning. Since these teachers are primarily Reading/Language Arts professionals, why not give them the support that they need in the teacher materials? <P>

<B><I>"If a person can not explain his job to a five year old, he doesn't know his job."</I> Albert Einstein.</B><P>

If the materials produced by the various educational publishing sources have to be "dummied down" to uselessness, or require two years training for the teachers (college graduates), clearly, they do not "know their jobs".<P>

<I>Every child enters Kindergarten eager to learn. By the fifth grade, only 10% are still eager. Why are we throwing away the 80%?</I><P>

<B>Marva Collins didn't. Jaime Escalante didn't.</B> They took "failures" and created success; THEY PROVED THAT 75-15-10 IS POSSIBLE. There are other teachers who are doing similar things in their classrooms across America. But, we need this achievement in every classroom, not just some! That is what this whole home page is about. <P>

<HR>
<P>
You do not have to buy <B>Exploring Science</B>, <I>we will tell you how to write your own version</I>. We have even given samples and training materials referenced on this Home Page. If you expect anyone else to use the materials, it will only take 3500 hours per grade level (if you have the background). Of course, if it is for your personal class use only, you can cut the time significantly by taking shortcuts. In any case, we are here to help BECAUSE educating children is more than our job, <I>it is our future</I>.<P>

<HR>
Larry Severson<BR>
Home Page editor<P>
<HR>
<P>


