Last-modified: Wed, 29 May 1996 04:30:32 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>Scientific Literacy</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H1>SCIENTIFIC LITERACY</H1>
</CENTER>

A questioning mind is wonderful. A teacher who fosters questioning minds is a gift. The following is an e-mail question/response.<P>

<HR>
<B><I>"The world is a laboratory to the inquiring mind."</I> (Martin H. Fischer)</B><P>

At 06:45 PM 5/24/96 -0400, you wrote:<BR>
>I'm not sure if this question is appropriate, but your www pages seem 
to suggest that it is ...<P>
>
>I have an instructor who believes that there are only four major
scientific disciplines:  physics, biology, chemistry and mathematics. 
Additionally, he believes that there are approximately 20 questions in
each of those fields that, together, determine a person's "scientific
literacy."  In other words, if a person understands these 20
questions/answers (i.e. concepts) then they would be considered as
"scientifically literate." <P>
>
>I've been asked by this instructor to ask authorities in education what 
their views on this are.  Do you agree, do you disagree?  If you agree, 
or agree in part, what would you consider those facts/concepts to be? (or 
at least, what would SOME of them be?)<P>
>
>Thank you in advance for any help, suggestions, and comments you can provide<P>
><P><P>
Hi Ken:<P>

Before you use my answers, consider who will be giving you the passing grade 
you seek. Einstein was kicked out of college for refusing to admit that the
professors knew everything. All knowledge is good, but some should be voiced
judiciously. That said, my fondest memories were of professors who demanded
that their students tackle an "impossible" task. They were well aware of what
I write below.<P>
<HR>
You have raised two separate issues that I feel strongly about:<BR>
Literacy and science disciplines.<P>

<H2>LITERACY:</H2>
Because of what I feel is an inappropriate use of the term literacy, I went to
a reading/language arts specialist and asked her to define what she considered
a literate person in her specialty. She said, "A <I>literate</I> person is one who can
understand what is read, can write, speak, and communicate <B>effectively</B>, but most 
importantly, reads and writes for <B>pleasure</B>."<P>

On that basis, being able to answer only 20 questions on any subject would never
be considered literate. On the other hand, it could be considered an acceptable
level of knowledge for the average citizen -> providing the questions are framed
in such a way that the knowledge demonstrated impacts the person's ability to
function as a communicating, cooperating, and contributing adult. It is unlikely
that a person who could answer only 20 questions about science has ever read science
material for pleasure.<P>

<B><I>"If you can't explain your job to a five year old, you don't know your job."</I> (Albert Einstein)</B><P>

From their writing, I find little evidence that the knowledgeable writers of the scientific papers in "Science", the journal for the American Association for the Advancement of Science, are literate. If only those initiates in a given arcane discipline can understand what is presented, that material is NOT the result of a person exhibiting LITERACY. The rationale for this problem is presented in the following discussion.<P><P>

<H2>SCIENCE DISCIPLINES:</H2>
In response to your instructor's beliefs about the major disciplines of science, 
I say, "Yes, but ..."<P>

<B> SCIENCE has been defined as the systematic accumulation, organization, and dissemination of knowledge. There is no mention in this definition of artificial disciplines.</B><P>

While I was at the USAF Academy, I had a Physics professor who started every
speculation with the comment, "ALL generalizations are wrong." At the beginning
of every semester he told the students of the time he made the statement, "You can't
push on a rope." -> to which a student reacted with, "What if it's frozen?" So he always added, 
"For very long."<P>

In the middle ages, we had the alchemists who believed in "earth, air, fire, and water".
They thought that transforming lead to gold was simply going from one form to another
with "earth". We know a bit more today. We know so much that we have developed artificial
disciplines to provide a framework for the controlled research so necessary to obtain reliable data. This has led to a number of different units for such unifying themes as energy because the early scientists did not realize the simple fact that is something changed state, energy was involved. The scientists, during their research, found that some things worked time after time, reliably. They then went on to create terms and mathematics to explain what they observed so that  others could duplicate what they found. So, now we have electrical, mechanical, chemical, 
nuclear, and biological energy units. Hogwash!<P>

<B><I>"What we know is of small amount, what we don't know is enormous."</I></B> Marquis de LaPlace<P>

While I was working in a research lab a few years back, there was a laser project at
the point of failure. Two years down the drain because the laser beam that the two Chief
Scientists were directing towards a highly polished curved aluminum mirror was not 
producing the expected spread spectrum. They could not understand why they weren't even 
getting a laser beam out of the system. After repeated fine polishing of the mirror, they still got white light.<P>

When questioned (by a junior scientist with a bare BS, General Science, who was passing by)
about the wave length of the laser beam, they admitted that it was "very short". They still did 
not consider the molecular size of the aluminum mirror until asked point blank. Lasers and 
molecular size are both Physics! A light coat of machine oil turned the "failure" into 
immediate "success". These Chief Scientists were experts, but were they scientifically literate?<P>

A pundit once said, <B><I>"An expert is one who has learned more and more about less and
less, until they know everything about nothing."</I></B>

This is actually why the new push towards thematically integrated science. In my opinion,
there are not four major areas of science, but one. The elbow/arm and the draw bridge
exhibit similar behavior.<P><P>

<H3>WHY?</H3>
Why did the answer come from a young junior scientist? Why are most significant science
breakthroughs created by young males? <P>

<B><I>"If a distinguished, but elderly scientist says something is possible, he is almost certainly
correct. But if he says something is impossible, he is probably wrong."</I> (Arthur C. Clarke)</B><P>

Science, and life, is a balancing act. Major advances require "standing on the shoulders of
giants who preceded me." (Newton) However, increasing book learning and "facts" create
the inhibitions of "can't" in the researcher. <P>

<B><I>"We tend to see what we expect to see."</I> (Mary Leaky, Anthropologist)</B><P>

Two things impact the ability to make a breakthrough:<BR>
1.  A basic understanding of what is happening.<BR>
2.  A willingness to risk failure.<P>

<B><I>"Every grand advance in science has issued from a new audacity of imagination."</I> (John Dewey)</B> Is there a better description of youthful exuberance, as shown by the young Einstein and Darwin?<P>

Young males, like those who "shoot the pier" on their surf boards, are more excited by the
challenge than worried about the risks of failure. They see only the thrill of success. 
Older males, and the more socially adept females, tend to consider the loss of reputation that could result from "blowing" such an attempt. They are considerably more cautious in their rush to publish results that can not be readily duplicated. Looking foolish in the eyes of their peers is equivalent to "hitting the pilings" - reputation death. They make significantly fewer mistakes, or major breakthroughs.<P>

While there is no evidence to support a real quality difference over the careers of male and female scientists, the females, like the more mature males tend to be cautious and exacting in their research. "Cold Fusion" is not the expected result. This caution has significant benefits to science. The "Science" journal writing reflects this tendency. Unless one exhibits circumspection and a knowledge of the obscure insider terminology, one is not considered an expert by the peer review committee. A major new discovery simply explained may sound trivial to one who does not understand how difficult the research and thought that went into the discovery. The tremendous loss of cross discipline knowledge utilization is a natural and expected consequence. (Personally, I find this as totally unacceptable as it is understandable. I am sure that I am wrong, but sometimes I feel that the approach is, <B><I>"Verisimilitude is our goal. Obsfucation is our methodology."</I></B>)<P>

The older scientists also tend to be restricted because they "know something won't work." 
Senior scientists act more as engineers, refining what is already known, minimizing risk, but producing stability. The younger male scientist, however, is prone to "hitting the pilings" because they don't acknowledge the consequences of their acts, or fail to understand why their idea is faulty. They are ever willing to fearlessly take the Einsteinian leap.<P>

It is said, <B><I>"There are old pilots and there are bold pilots, but there are no old, bold pilots."</I></B><P>
<HR>
<B>NOTE:</B> Barbara McClintock, among many other great female scientists, proves the truth in what my Physics professor said about generalizations. Her research on "jumping genes" was as exciting and risky politically as any done by young males, especially since 20 years passed before the electron microscope was developed and her theories could be proved.
<HR>
Math is the way we measure and quantify what we see and test. It provides a rational method
for describing what can or will happen under specific circumstances. Math is the description
of the possible. Without math, we can't quantify (explain) what we discover, nor can 
anyone be sure that they have truly replicated the previous work. <P>

Put another way, "science" has developed the way any device, including computers, has. We
apply a bit of this and a bit of that to see if it works. When it does, everyone rushes out to
duplicate it. Eventually, we have a "Rube Goldberg" monstrosity  that works after a fashion. Then some really sharp Value Engineer looks at the product and asks, "What is its function?"
From that question comes a unifying theory (design) that is simple and reliable.<P>

When I was in graduate school in "confuser" science, we were given an "impossible" task to 
see what we could do. As a team, we simply studied the experts to find out why it was
impossible, then found a different way. No sense in repeating what didn't work for others.
It took five weeks to do the "impossible". Now, 10 years later, everyone does it.<P><P>

<H2>ON SCIENCE EDUCATION:</H2>
Mankind is different because the "stars" are there to be climbed. Every child wants to know and
do it all. As they grow up, the children find out that the can't "walk to the moon". With the 
passing years, the "can'ts" increase until the adults stop trying. True science education
consists of teaching the children two things:<BR>
1.  We don't know how to do that.<BR>
2.  We can teach you how to discover a way to do it.<P>

In the new scheme of science education:<BR>
Children are born with "Why?" in their every thought. True scientists never stop. The science methodology should be the context about which all curriculum is taught.<P>
The primary children are taught to work together to explore the world around them and 
explain what they find. <BR>
Cooperation<BR>
Documentation<BR>
Communication<P>

The elementary student is taught the unifying themes that provide the basis for understanding 
how all science is related AND how previous generations of scientists discovered what they did.<BR>
Facts (History)<BR>
Scientific Thinking Processes<P>

In high school, the students begin learning how to go into greater depth in specific areas. 
They also expand on the idea of controlling variables to isolate what they observe from
miscellaneous external forces.<BR>
Problem Solving<BR>
Study in more depth, by subject<P>

College continues narrowing the focus until the Ph.D. doesn't always see the forest. The 
trees get in the way.<BR>
Undergraduate: prove you can learn<BR>
Masters: apply what you have learned<BR>
Doctorate: explain some new knowledge that you have created.<P>

At some point in the education, hopefully, every student will realize that all actions have
consequences, not all of them good. Most of the significant problems in science education today are the result of ignoring the intellectual base possessed by the student (ignoring Einstein's comment). "Dummy down" is not necessary, establishing a common reference point for understanding is!<P><P>

<H2>CONCLUSION:</H2>
Every adult is impacted by scientific knowledge. Consider how life would be without fire, or 
the wheel. <B><I>"Standing on the shoulders of the giants who preceded me"</I></B> is vital. Being limited 
by their brilliance is ludicrous. Leonardo daVinci simply didn't know everything and Einstein's professor knew less.<B><I> "Discovery consists of seeing what everyone has seen
and thinking what nobody has thought."</I> (Albert Szent-Gyorgi)</B><P>

Scientific is less about answering any 20 questions in any so called discipline and more about
learning how to:<BR>
1.  Observe in detail.<BR>
2.  Discover new information<BR>
3.  Complete the discovery by communicating the knowledge to someone else.<P>

<B>"Being scientific"</B> is what being human is all about. There is no job so menial that it doesn't involve problem solving.<P>

<B><I>"Equipped with his five senses, man explores the universe around him, and calls the adventure
science."</I> (Edwin Powell Hubble)</B><P>

The scientifically literate adult of tomorrow will fully understand that there are consequences
to all actions. The person will be able to identify public policies that are not in the best
interest of future generations. This person will enjoy reading about and discussing new
ideas and possibilities. Of course, this requires a realization that the compartmentalization
of science into Physics, Chemistry, and Biology, while useful for research, is inherently 
artificial and limiting.<P>

What is not understood is MAGIC.<P>

<P>
<HR>
You can tell your professor that I am sure that I would enjoy his class.<P>

<HR>


Larry Severson<BR>
Home Page editor<P>
<HR>
