</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<!-- SS~~0001 -->
<Title>Why</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR=#AAFFFF>
<CENTER><H1>WHY?</H1>
</CENTER>
<B><I>"Why?" is a wonderful question.</I></B> Every child, and every scientist, spends most of his/her day asking why. The question is pertinent to every decision we make. Why are we doing what we do? Why are we doing it in the manner that we are doing it? Why are we using the specific tools? Why are we using the specific resources? <P>

The presentation of known facts, for a teacher, is vital to the process of developing knowledge and understanding. However, in an era of rapid scientific discovery, teaching science must be more than mere "facts", even when presented "hands-on". The better way is to concentrate on the scientific process, and teach the students to question, in the manner of Einstein, Darwin, and Leonardo daVinci. Logical, organized problem solving, especially in groups and teams, is valuable to every person, not just those entering scientific fields.<P>

<CENTER><H1>WHY SSIP?</H1>
</CENTER>
<B>SSIP</B> is short for the <I>National Aeronautics and Space Administration/ National Science Teachers Association</I> <B>"Space Science Involvement Program"</B>. Leigh Hoven-Severson answers the "Why?" question quite well.<P>

"I was attracted to the competition because the rules required a team approach. It stipulated a mission statement explaining how their project would benefit mankind. I believe strongly that children need to learn to work together cooperatively and collaboratively. Secondly, they need to respect and care for our planet. Therefore, I knew that this project was something that both my students and I would benefit from - and we did.<P>

But then I was worried - no, I was scared! Did I have the science background to lead my students in this endeavor? I was a social science major, an English/Language Arts mentor.  My 3rd grade students would be competing against 4th and 5th grade students with teachers with strong science backgrounds.  How could we expect to do well?<P>

Then I had a serious talk with myself. What was important -  learning or winning? <I>The answer was easy - learning, of course!</I> This was an opportunity for me to learn along with my students. It was an opportunity to challenge my students on a level that they had never been challenged before."<P>

<CENTER><H1>The Winning WHY</H1>
</CENTER>

Every child drives his/her parents to distraction with <B>"Why?"</B> Now its pay-back time. Why:<P>
<UL>
<LI> did you chose that problem to solve? <BR>
<LI> did you pick that method? <BR>
<LI> does your vehicle look like that?<BR>
<LI> is there an antenna there?<BR>
<LI> are you using robots?<BR>
<LI> and so on...
</UL><P>

Over the last three years, I have consistently watched grade 3-5 students push the envelope of science. Every winning entry has matched (or exceeded) science journal articles that appeared over the following year. Over the summer, we will be reducing various winners to Adobe Acrobat format, so that you can view their work. One team, Jan. 1995, of 3rd and 4th graders did better work than MIT scientists. (See MIT Technology Review, Feb-Mar 1995, "Comet Busters".) The students wrote, "We wanted to get the nuclear weapons off the Earth. First, we were going to shoot them into the Sun. Then we decided that it would do more good to use them to protect the Earth. ... We will use the nuclear weapons to destroy or divert the meteors, asteroids, or comets that come near Earth."<P>

<HR>
<B>[Note: all samples, as added, will be about 80K and require Adobe Acrobat.]</B><P>

The James H. Cox Elementary School staff and parents are proud of what their (large class, multi-language public school) students have achieved over the last three years (3 years competing only):<BR>
<B><I>1994 	1st and 2nd in California, 2nd in the nation. (all grade 3 students)<BR>
1995 	1st and 3rd in California.<BR>
1996	<A HREF="ozonemdr.pdf">1st </A >  , 2nd, and <A HREF="moonmine.pdf">3rd </A > in California, 3rd in the nation.</I>  (A CLEAN SWEEP!)</B><P>

<HR>
<I>The children answered the "Why?" to their satisfaction.</I> They clearly did the same for the judges. But more important is the fact that every child, even the non-winners in the competition, WON. Every child learned that their ideas had value, once they could answer "Why?" The "losing" students, when questioned, knew why they lost, and why they had actually won.<P>

<I>This is what we wish to see from and for all of our students.</I> Then America's students will truly be ready for the 21st century. No computer, or other piece of technology, can replace the power of the brain in full function. <P>

<B><I>Unbeatable Excitement!</I> Watch the children creating!</B><P>
<HR>
The SSIP contest is an annual event that covers multiple grade level contests both science problem solving and art. <BR>
Grade 3-5 "Future Aircraft/Spacecraft Design"  - Mrs. Severson's students.<BR>
Grade 6-8 "Mission To Planet Earth"<BR>
Grade 9-12 "Aerospace Internships"<P>

All grades, matching groupings for Space Art.<P>

Entries: National Science Teachers Association<BR>
Attention: SSIP Competition<BR>
1840 Wilson Blvd.<BR>
Arlington, VA  22201-3000<P>

Final submittal date each year is Jan. 10th. Results are published May 10th.<P>
<HR>
Larry Severson<BR>
Home Page editor<P>
