<Title>Winners All!</title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<H1>3Peat For Cox Elementary School</H1>
<H2>3 Girls Beat the Bias</H2>

<B><I>"Science is a little bit like the air you breathe - it is everywhere."</I></B> (Dwight D. Eisenhower)<P>

James H. Cox Elementary School, 17615 Los Jardines East, Fountain Valley, CA [phone (714) 378-4241)] is proud to announce that for the third straight year the students of Mrs. Leigh Hoven-Severson have won the <B>NASA/NSTA SSIP (Space Science Involvement Program) </B>contest [grades 3-5]. Her students have taken first in state 3 consecutive years. <P>

<I>"Our mission is to take the ozone from the Troposphere, where is harmful, and put it in the Stratosphere, where it is needed. That way the people of Earth will be protected from the Sun's harmful ultraviolet rays, and people will be able to breathe cleaner and healthier air." </I>With this opening paragraph, a team made up of fifth grade girls (Kay Lee, Laura Duquette, and Jana Aoki) produced the third place national winning design, "The Ozone Mender". <P>

The team, working together after school and on weekends, created a complete design consisting of exterior, interior, and special features of the space vessel that would carry the crew through mission completion. They then wrote a 1000 word essay explaining how each part of the design contributes in the mission success.<P>

<B><I>"Every grand advance in science has issued from a new audacity of imagination." </I></B>
(John Dewey) These three girls have dared to go on the "joyous adventure" of science.<P>

The Cox staff and parents are proud of what their students have achieved over the last three years:<BR>
1994 	1st and 2nd in California, 2nd in the nation.<BR>
1995 	1st and 3rd in California.<BR>
1996	1st, 2nd, and 3rd in California, 3rd in the nation.<P>

<HR>
For too many years science has been taught as a subject with a capital "S", as something mysterious, as something for the "nerd" boys. As America has lost its technology edge to other countries, it has become clear how wrong this method of teaching is. Science is not "facts", it is the process of gaining new knowledge and passing on this knowledge to others. Facts discovered previously are important for the gaining of new knowledge and understanding, but they are more appropriate to the subject of History.<P>

A change is in the air. The <B>National Science Education Standards (December 1995)</B> demand an integrated, hands-on approach to the teaching of science methodology to all students. Scientific problem solving, documentation, and communication is not for the "nerdy" boys, or the brilliant few; it crosses all race, ethnicity, and sex boundaries. It impacts the ability to learn effectively by everyone from the "GIFTED" to the "Educationally Handicapped". It works!<P>
<P>

<HR>
Copyright &copy; 1996<BR>
Macro Press Incorporated<BR>
18242 Peters Court<BR>
Fountain Valley, CA  92708<BR>
Phone/fax   (714) 964-9191<BR>
e-mail:  science@macropress.com<P>

