<Title>Winning The NASA/NSTA Space Science Involvement Program</Title>
<H1>Third Grade Success</H1>
<I>[NOTE: This teacher's students repeated in 1995, taking 1st and 3rd in California.]</I><P>
At 10:15 A.M. on Wednesday, May 25, 1994, I received a phone call in my third grade classroom. It was from the NASA California state representative for the NASA/NSTA Space Science Involvement Program. To my shock, Rick Valencia said, <B><I>"Your students took First and Second place in California and Second in the Nation."</I></B> He then went on to say that the third entry, which did not place, was also outstanding.<P>

<IMG SRC="teamkrup.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=300> 
<I>Team 1 and 2 with Dr. Krupp</I><P>

At this announcement, pandemonium broke out. No one could believe it. Surely, the call was a joke! The kids were excited. Everyone was floating, but not believing. Then the award certificates, ribbons, and medals arrived. It became very real to the class. Those who had decided not to take part wished that they had. <B>"Next year!"</B> became the rallying cry. <P>

How did this all start? In November 1993, news of the NASA Space Science Competition arrived at James H. Cox Elementary School in Fountain Valley. There were several competitions for various age groups. The one that immediately caught my attention was Design a Future Spacecraft for grades 3-5. A team or 3 or 4 students were to design a future spacecraft that would in some way benefit mankind. The competition requirements were draw the interior, exterior, and special features views and write no more than 1000 words explaining their spacecraft, its mission, and the contributions of each team member. <P>

<IMG SRC="team1.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=300> 
<I>ESL Team 1 (one member returned to India)</I><P>

At first I was excited. Space exploration fascinates me and I want to impart that fascination to my students. The idea of a mission that benefited Earth, fit with my own idea that it is important to teach children that they can make a difference. In addition, the requirement that students had to work as a team,  reinforced my goals of cooperation, communication, and enhanced academic achievement.<P> 

<B>It's Elementary's</B> (a California program) first recommendation is <I>"make a rich, meaning-centered curriculum the centerpiece of instruction ..."</I> Here was an opportunity staring me in the face so to speak.<P>

But then I was worried - no, I was scared! Did I have the science background to lead my students in this endeavor? I was a social science major, an English/Language Arts mentor.  My students would be competing against 4th and 5th grade students with teachers with strong science backgrounds.  How could we expect to do well?<P>

Then I had a serious talk with myself. What was important -  learning or winning? The answer was easy - learning, of course! This was an opportunity for me to learn along with my students. It was an opportunity to challenge my students on a level that they had never been challenged before.<P>

Fortunately, I had a lot to back me up. I had NASA, Odyssey Magazine, and dedicated public and school librarians who would take the time to insure that children found appropriate materials. More importantly, I knew my students had a strong science background. My school had science as its focus for the last two years. Three of the teachers, plus myself as editor, had worked with other teachers to write a science series that emphasized scientific process skills, cooperative/ collaborative learning, oral and written communication, and problem solving. This was the third year of using that program.<P>

Here was a chance to find out how much science I had gained in the three years of editing science materials. My decision was made.<P>

I know many teachers shy away from entering competitions. They are a lot of work and take a lot of time - and that's true! Looking back, I know the time and work was worth it. I hope by sharing my experience with you, it will encourage you to give this competition a try. <B><I>It will be a winning situation for you and your students regardless of the outcome.</I></B><P><P>

<H2>Getting Started _ The Steps I Took</H2>

<H3>1. PERSONAL DECISION TO COMMIT THE TIME</H3>
	Realize that you don't have to be an expert. The U.S. Department of Education says, "Elementary school teachers do not need to be experts in every aspect of science; in fact, most scientists are experts in only a narrow specialty." You can have fun learning along with your students.<P><P>

<H3>2. WHO? </H3>
	Ask yourself, is this something I want my entire class to do?  Would I rather do this with interested students only?<P>
	Believing that every child should be given the opportunity to achieve, I decided to do the project with all interested students.  I told my class, if they were interested in working in teams, learning a lot, and having fun designing a future spacecraft, this was the perfect opportunity. Since we were competing against 5th graders, expecting to win would be unrealistic.<P><P> 

<H3>3. WHEN? </H3> 
	How do you find the time when you already have more to teach than can be covered in regular school hours? Your WHO answer will help determine this. If you are having the entire class participate, this can become your science, art, and language arts class time.<P>
	Since I had decided to have volunteers only, I scheduled meetings after school. That way I would have the positive teaching experience of working with committed students without worrying about what the rest of my class was learning and doing. It was extra time, but it was also a rare treat!<P><P>
	
<H3>4. RESEARCH</H3>
	I began with the NASA video tape, Living and Working in Space. It is free. To get one send a new unopened video tape to your NASA center. They will record the tape and send it back with no charge. This takes about two to three weeks. If that is too long, you can often check out a similar tape from your public library or rent one from the nearest large video store. <P>

NASA also has two sets of activity cards on all aspects of living in space. I assigned cards to students for homework. They read the material and did the activities. At the next meeting each student reported to the group. For example, one activity card discussed eating in space. The students ate pudding with baby sized spoons because food in space will stick to both the top and the bottom of the spoon. A regular sized spoon would give you a Paul Bunyan sized bite!<P>
	We also used Odyssey Magazines, local and school libraries for research and ideas. Lastly, we used 50 Simple Things Kids Can Do to Save the Earth by Earth Works Group. The first few pages give an excellent overview of the major problems facing our planet.<P><P>

<H3>5. FORMING TEAMS</H3>
	Teamwork is a strong requirement of the design a future space spacecraft project. Each student must document their contributions in the written portion. My students made their own team selection. That worked quite well. <P>
<IMG SRC="team2.gif" WIDTH=500 HEIGHT=300> 
<I>Team 2</I><P>
<P>

<H3>6. BRAINSTORMING</H3>
	After much research and discussion, the students listed reasons why a spacecraft of the future would go into space: colonization, exploration, mining, search for fuel alternate fuel sources, etc.<P><P>

<H3>7. HANDS-ON, HANDS-ON, HANDS-ON!!! </H3>
	I told the teams to go directly from brainstorming to writing about their mission. This didn't work. While I was telling them to go home and write down their ideas, they were going home and creating models from whatever they had: legos, plastic liter bottles, soda cans, coffee filters, straws, foil, etc. <P>
	It was when they brought these in to share with their groups that ideas really began to flow. Modifications were made. New spacecraft were constructed. Throughout there was animated discussion and revision.<P><P>

<H3>8. DECISION TIME</H3>
	Each group had to answer the five W's (Who, What, When, Where, Why) regarding their spacecraft and mission. For example: The Mars Express team wrote:<BR>
<UL>
<LI> Who: robots for the first missions/ colonists for later missions<BR>
<LI> What: to set up a colony that would manufacture its own air and grow its own plants & food<BR>
<LI> When: 50 - 100 years in the future<BR>
<LI> Where: Mars<BR>
<LI> Why: because there is a population problem on Earth and future generations will need another place to live<P>
</UL><P>

<H3>9. INTERIOR, EXTERIOR & SPECIAL FEATURE DIAGRAMS</H3>
	This is a very important part of the competition. It is weighted heavily. I asked an architect to come in and give the students some suggestions on scale drawing and composition. I was glad I did because I learned along with my students. We ended up using a combination of photos and scale drawings.<P><P> 

<H3>10. THE WRITING</H3>
	For third graders, especially my ESL/LEP students, this was the most difficult part. They could write up to 1000 words to describe their spacecraft, its mission, and their individual contributions. We divided the writing responsibilities into five parts:<P>
 
	1. The goal (which included the 5 W's)<BR>
	2,3,&4.  Detailed descriptions of the interior, exterior, and special features<BR>
	5. Team members' contributions and conclusion<P>

 Each team member took a section, did it as homework, brought it back for discussion and revision by the team. When this was complete, I typed the composition using a word processor with a spell and grammar checker. Together we did the final editing.<P><P>

<H3>11. CREATE A DISPLAY AND HONOR STUDENTS </H3>
	Finishing this task is an achievement! Make copies of the final submittal for display. Have the teams create a display board and put them in a central place at your school. Take photos of the teams with their display. Mention the teams in school communication. Invite parents and district personnel to see the display and talk to the designers. Have local scientists meet with your design teams.<P><P>

<H3>12. CONGRATULATE YOURSELF</H3>
You are preparing your students for the 21st century. Constructing a Thinking and Meaning-Centered Curriculum Module, California School Leadership Academy, 1990, lists seven qualities for "citizens of the 21st century: problem solvers, cooperative workers, self-starters, information managers, flexible thinkers, effective questioners, and multi-lingual." Participation in the NASA Spacecraft Design Team Competition does six of the seven! (It doesn't make students multi-lingual.)<P><P>

The due date for the next competition is Jan. 10, 1996. Look for the flyer at your school. May you take your students on a mission where no one has been before!<P><P>

Resources:<BR>
NASA Teacher Resource Centers in YOUR STATE<BR>
(write for catalogue)<P>

Ames Research Center<BR>
Mail Stop 204-7<BR>
Moffett Field, CA 94035<P>

NASA Edwards Air Force Base<BR>
ATTN.: Don Haley<BR><P>

