<BODY BACKGROUND=" teach2.jpg" >

<H1>Open challenge to NSF (National Science Foundation)</H1>
 

Macro Press (a company of elementary mentor/master teachers) challenges NSF to an "educate off", based on the requirements of the 1995 National Science Education Standards. NSF has spent $350 million. The Macro Press teachers used their own money.<P>

<TABLE border=6>
<TR>
<TD><FONT SIZE=4 STYLE=BOLD FACE="Arial, Helv"> 
<UL>
<LI>Pick any of the K-6 curriculums developed under NSF funding, <BR>
<LI>create a level playing field, <BR>
<LI>use six days maximum teacher training time for the curriculum, <BR>
<LI>test student performance in real classrooms,<BR>
<LI>and compare NSF curriculum Vs EXPLORING SCIENCE results.<BR>
</UL>
</TR>
</TD>
</TABLE>

The teachers at Macro Press prefer testing in those classrooms that are currently not performing to an acceptable level. EXPLORING SCIENCE by Macro Press will win in SCIENCE because classroom teachers wrote it. While NSF is being challenged to produce in science education only, Macro Press students will show significantly greater gains in all other subject areas as well.<P>

<HR>
