<HEAD>
<Title>ESL Strategies for Bilingual Education</Title>
</HEAD>

<BODY>
<CTR><H1><I>GLAD</I> STRATEGIES WITH <I>EXPLORING SCIENCE</I> USING PRIMARY LANGUAGE</H1></CTR>

Review the <A HREF="1lep.htm">ESL introduction</A> on the use of <I>Exploring Science</I> on pages P46-P47 written by Marcia Brechtel, Project GLAD Coordinator/Trainer. Here are four important considerations:<P>

<UL>
<LI>Both classroom teachers and bilingual paraprofessionals need formal training in the GLAD model in order to ensure successful implementation. <BR>

<LI> Bilingual paraprofessionals need <B>adequate time and resources</B> to develop high level, scientific academic concepts, vocabulary and materials in primary language.<BR>

<LI> Since bilingual paraprofessionals are our only resource for primary language, their entire program should reflect the development of primary language. (No grading math papers, giving spelling tests, or running off student materials for the teacher.)<BR>

<LI> Concurrent translation is the least effective use of primary language and is not used in the GLAD model nor with <I>Exploring Science</I>.<BR>

<LI> Student achievement and student empowerment will not occur unless the culture, personal experiences, and primary language of each student are truly valued by everyone in the learning community.<P>
</UL>
GLAD Strategies to be used by the <B>Bilingual Paraprofessional</B> in primary language with a focus on heritage and culture.<P>

<H2>FOCUS/MOTIVATION</H2>
<UL>
<LI> Read aloud from magazines, newspaper articles, primary language texts<BR> 
	Read about historical contributions<BR>
	Read about key figures in the scientific community<BR>
	Read about past and current conditions in the scientific community<P>

<LI> Access background information of students and prior experience<P>

<LI>Best done in cooperative learning groups with a focus on authentic dialogue, discussions centered on realia, manipulatives, science materials, picture file cards, visuals, diagrams, models<P>

<LI>Use of the <B>FREE EXPLORATION</B> in the <I>Exploring Science</I> model reinforces this unstructured time where students construct their own meaning and begin to formulate generalizations, pose questions and make predictions.<P>

<LI> Student oral language and feedback is recorded by dictation in various forms such as the inquiry chart, KWL charts, clustering, mind mapping etc.<P>

<LI> The bilingual paraprofessional is modeling the written form of primary language thus reinforcing reading and writing development.<P>

<LI> Students write in primary language in their Scientist's Notebook and Glossary pages.<P>

<LI> Laboratory and safety rules are reinforced in primary language<P>

<LI> Role of the bilingual paraprofessional is to reinforce, validate, clarify and extend concepts and vocabulary in primary language, providing high levels of cognitive and academic scientific language.<P>
</UL>

<H2>INPUT, DIRECT AND STUDENT EXPLORATIONS</H2>
<UL>
<LI> Done in primary language first if trained, certificated bilingual teachers are
	available.<P>

<LI> Use the 10-2 lecture method along with any input charts for primary language processing of new information<P>

<LI>Preview/Review in primary language, reinforce Exploring Science key questions, key concepts and vocabulary, use class discussion questions for reviewing<P>

<LI>Don't use two languages on one chart, develop primary language charts in small reinforcement groups. For example, if students are reviewing an inquiry chart in English, several primary language groups can also be doing it with the bilingual paraprofessional.<P>

<LI> Bilingual paraprofessionals assist students by developing banks of primary language word cards for each chart being used in the Language Functional Environment.<P>
</UL>

<H2>GUIDED ORAL PRACTICE</H2>
<UL>
<LI> Students develop habits of interaction and communication<P>

<LI>Use the 10-2 lecture method with primary language processing first, then processing in English second. Students should be in the habit of discussing in primary language first, then in English second in a natural flow from one language to another.<P>

<LI> Cooperative learning structures should be done in primary language first, followed by heterogeneous language groups second, processing in English.<P>

<LI> The bilingual paraprofessional is circulating around the classroom clarifying, reinforcing concepts and validating generalizations, providing high level primary language when needed.<P>

<LI> Classroom teacher plans for flexible groupings that will meet the primary language needs as well as providing ESL reinforcement in English done by good English-speaking models<P>
</UL>

<H2>READING/WRITING</H2>
<UL>
<LI> Use the Process Grid to record student feedback in primary language, then later to be used for oral discussions, reading and writing development and extension.<P>

<LI> Bilingual paraprofessionals take student dictation of everything they know about a topic or science exploration. This GROUP FRAME becomes the summary and focus for reading and writing fluency and skills. The bilingual paraprofessional models for students how to formulate ideas in various forms such as a paragraph, a list, an outline, using bullets etc.<P>

<LI> Note: This kind of primary language reinforcement cannot take the place of certificated, bilingual teachers, but it is valuing primary language in a positive, educational way, moving students toward primary language literacy.<P>

<LI> Access to the Exploring Science student text is made possible by the
	extensive development of English oral language fluency leading to reading
	and writing<P>
</UL>


<H2>CLOSURE</H2>
<LI> Give students a choice of which language is to be used for their closure activities. All options are possible.<P>

<LI> The Home/School Connections should be translated into primary language whenever possible. The focus of this kind of homework is communication, not paper and pencil drill and practice, <I><B>It is the parent/child interaction that is most important.</B> Don't ask a parent to read or write if they are not literate themselves.</I><P><P>
</UL>

Linnea Haley, Project GLAD Disseminator/Trainer <I>Exploring Science</I> Author<P>

February, 1996<P>
</BODY></HTML>

</DOC>
