</DOCHDR>
<Title>America's Goals</Title>

The new 1995 <B>National Science Education Standards</B> and <B>Goals 2000</B> have asked elementary teachers to help their students become science literate. Various reasons have been given for past failures:<BR>
<OL>
<LI> The teachers do not have an adequate science background.<BR>
<LI> Proper facilities and equipment are not available to these teachers.<BR>
<LI> Curriculum materials are not sufficiently "scientific".<BR>
</OL><P>

All of these reasons have some merit, but not much. The truth is simple. These very capable elementary teachers are all aware that:<BR>
<UL>
<LI> Children who do not read by the third grade seldom achieve academic success.<BR> 
<LI> Children who do not develop cooperative social skills are not good citizens.<BR>
<LI> Children who do not have basic math skills can't perform as adults.<BR>
<LI> Children who do not communicate effectively lose.<P><P>
</UL>
When approached as separate disciplines, these needs require all of the teacher's time and resources. There is no time for "nice" things, such as science literacy. However, the teaching of <I>integrated curriculum</I>, cooperative, hands-on science "creates" instruction time by providing meaning to, and practice in, the other subject disciplines while providing the skills essential for students and scientists. <P>

Science can, and should, become the "core" subject around which all other subjects are taught. New knowledge is exciting to the children. Teaching the scientific process through hands-on science is essentially teaching the children how to learn more effectively. When done in cooperative settings, the children also learn effective communication by sharing information with their peers.<P>

<B>EXPLORING SCIENCE</B> was written by active elementary grade mentor teachers with these realities in mind. Because of that, the program addresses many of the stated objectives of <B>GOALS 2000</B>:<BR>
<UL>
3. All students will leave grades 4, 8, and 12 demonstrating competency over challenging subject matter.<BR>
4. The teaching force will have access to programs for the continued improvement of their professional skills.<BR>
5. American students will be first among the world's children in mathematics and science achievement.<BR>
6. Our adults will be literate, and possess the knowledge and skills necessary to compete in a global economy and exercise the rights and responsibilities of citizenship.<BR>
8. Every school will promote partnerships that will increase parental involvement and participation in promoting the social, emotional, and academic growth of children.<P>
</UL>

</DOC>
