<Title>Colors - Kindergarten</Title>
<H1>Colors All Around Me</H1>

<H2>Thematic Emphasis:</H2>
SCALE AND STRUCTURE<BR>
	Sub Theme:  Stability<P><P>


<H2>Science Concepts:</H2>
<OL>
<LI>  All matter has properties that can be observed,defined and recorded.<BR>
<LI>  We give names to different colors.<BR>
<LI>  Color serves as a form of protection for animals.<BR>
<LI>  Our eyes gather information about the color of objects.<BR>
<LI>  Our brain stores and uses the information it receives from all our senses.
</OL><P><P>


<H2>Scientific Thinking Processes:</H2>
Observing   Comparing   Ordering   Communicating<P><P>


<H2>Vocabulary: </H2>
  color   chameleon   red   yellow   green   blue   
		     orange   purple   brown<P><P>

<H2>Materials:</H2>
<B>Per Student</B><BR>
HAND LENS<BR>
SCIENTIST'S NOTEBOOK<BR>
PARENT NOTE #11<BR>
EXPLORATION REPORT #7<P>

<B>Per Pair</B> (two children)<BR>
Red, yellow, green, blue self-stick notes, 
    each with the name of both partners 
    written on it.  (Only the red self-stick 
    notes will be used on the first day of 
    this exploration.  The other colors will 
    be used on subsequent days.)<P>

<B>Per Group</B> (8-10 children)<BR>
Large chart paper for recording 
    observations<BR>
Marking pen<P>

<B>Per Class</B>
Picture book, <B>The Mixed-Up Chameleon</B>, 
    by Eric Carle<BR>
One copy each of 
    RESOURCE MASTERS K7-20<BR>
    (These are pictures of all the objects
    mentioned in the "Colors All Around Me" 
    song.  You may wish to color them in
    the same manner as the illustrations in 
    the student text and then laminate them,
    since the children will be handling them 
    often.)<P>


Pocket chart with sentence strips on which 
    are printed the words to the
   <B> "Colors All Around Me" song:<P>

	Stop signs, valentines,<BR>
	The hair on my friend's head,<BR>
Chimneys, and rubies and strawberries too-<BR>
	Lots of things are red!<P>

	Bright moon in the sky,<BR>
	Jiggly lemon jello,<BR>
Daisies and grapefruit and pineapple too-<BR>
	Lots of things are yellow!<P>

	Fresh grass, lettuce leaves,<BR>
	Jumping frogs I've seen,<BR>
Emeralds and spinach and broccoli too-<BR>
	Lots of things are green!<P>

	Clear sky, swimming pools,<BR>
	The jeans that I outgrew,<BR>
Sapphires and lupine and blueberries too-<BR>
	Lots of things are blue!<P>

	Orange orange, purple plum,<BR>
	The brown eyes on my face,<BR>
	All of the colors around me 
		help make <BR>
	The world a brighter place!</B><P><P>


<I>NOTE:<BR>
This exploration works best with the class divided into three or four groups (depending on the size of your class) of 10 to 12 children who will work in pairs over a period of four days.  Each group will work under the direct supervision of the teacher while the other children are involved in other activities.  The exploration time for each group is short, so the exploration each day could be carried out within a single rotation.<P>

The explorations will be carried out over the entire week, with the children focusing on one color each day for the first four days.  You will want to keep the same groups during the entire week because each group will keep adding information to its own data chart as the exploration continues.<P></I><P>


<H2>Key Question:</H2>
HOW CAN WE USE COLOR TO OBSERVE AND DESCRIBE OBJECTS IN OUR ENVIRONMENT?<P><P>


<H2>Time Allotment:</H2>
Read aloud and discussion:  
    15 minutes (first day only)<BR>
Matching colors and communicating 
    with group: 15 minutes per group 
    each day for the first four days<BR>
Song and daily closure:  
    15 minutes each day<BR>
Recording data in 
    SCIENTIST'S NOTEBOOK (fifth day only): 
    15 minutes<BR>
Reading STUDENT TEXT:  
    10 minutes (fifth day only)<P><P>


<H2>Management Suggestion:</H2>
Review the "STOP" signal, and set standards for groups who will move from working with the teacher to an activity as well as for those who will clean up and leave their activities to come and work with the teacher.  Before the first group begins its exploration, make sure that all the children understand that everyone will have a turn.<P><P>
  
 
 
<H2>Procedure:</H2>
<H3>1.  READ ALOUD AND DISCUSSION</H3>
Set the stage for reading aloud Eric Carle's <B>Mixed-Up Chameleon</B> by explaining that a chameleon is a real animal, and that it really does change color to blend into its surroundings.  If possible, show a picture of a real chameleon.  Read the story aloud, taking time to discuss the wonderful illustrations.  At the end of the story, ask the children to imagine what it would be like to be a chameleon and change colors to match the environment.  Would they like it?  Why, or why not?  Discuss why it is helpful for chameleons to be able to change their colors.  Ask if the children know of other animals whose color keeps them safe.<P><P>

<H3>2.  MATCHING COLORS AND COMMUNICATING WITH GROUP</H3>
Have the small group (10-12 children) seated on the rug near the large chart wearing their HAND LENSES.  Explain that they are going to work with partners and pretend that they have a pet chameleon.  Hold up the red self-stick notes, and say,  <B><I>"Pretend that this is your chameleon, and you want it to hide it somewhere red where nobody will notice it.  Where could you put it?" </I></B> Pass out a note to each pair and tell them to find something red in the room, put the "chameleon" on it, and return to the rug.  Explain that if another chameleon is already there, they'll have to find another spot.  When the pairs return, have each pair in turn lead the group to the part of the room where their chameleon is hiding and see if the rest of the group can see it.  When the chameleon has been seen by the other children, the children who hid the chameleon collect their "pet" and the search continues.  When all have been found,  have them placed on the chart in the appropriate place.  Ask the children to recall where each chameleon was in the classroom, and write the location on the chart.  Dismiss the group to another activity and work with the other groups in turn until all children have participated in the exploration.<P>
    Repeat the activity on subsequent days with yellow, green and blue self-stick "chameleons."<P><P>



<H3>3.  SONG AND DAILY CLOSURE</H3>
Show the pictures of the stop sign, valentine, red-haired child, ruby, chimney and strawberry to the class, identifying each by name and giving the children a chance to talk about where they have seen each of these things.  Introduce the first verse of the "Colors All Around Me" song, which is sung to the tune of "Row, Row, Row Your Boat", while pointing to the words in the pocket chart:<P>

		<B>Stop signs, valentines,<BR>
		The hair on my friend's head,<BR>
		Chimneys, and rubies and strawberries too -<BR>
		Lots of things are red!</B><P>

     Ask the children to listen again to see if each of the pictured items is mentioned in the song.  Ask which item is mentioned first in the song, and select a child to stand by the pocket chart and hold the picture.  Repeat with other pictures until six children are standing holding the pictures in the correct order.  (Whenever they aren't sure which object comes next, sing the song again.)  Sing the song together, having each child hold his picture up high when the object is mentioned.  Repeat several times with different children arranging themselves in sequential order and displaying the pictures.<P>
    Repeat this verse of the song on subsequent days, and on each day add new pictures and a new verse.  By the end of the fifth day the line of pictures will be a circle with everyone holding a picture.<P>
    Allow time for discussion.<P><P>

	<B>Discussion Questions:</B><BR>
Some possible content questions might be:<BR>
	<B><I>What senses were you using when you observed colors today?
	What red (yellow, green, blue) things did we see and talk about
	today?<BR>
	Are these things always that color, or are they are sometimes
	other colors?<BR>
	What other things can you think of that are usually red (yellow,
	green, blue)?<BR>
	If you were a real chameleon, what red (yellow, green blue) place
	 would you choose to hide?  Why?<P></I></B>

Some questions to help children assess how they worked together
might be:<BR>
	<B><I>How did you and your partner decide where to put your
	chameleon?<BR>
	How did you help others clean up when it was your turn to leave
	your activity and work with the teacher?</I></B><P><P>

<H3>4.  RECORDING IN SCIENTIST'S NOTEBOOK</H3>
On the final day of the exploration read and discuss EXPLORATION REPORT #7, naming the objects and talking about the real color of those objects.  Tell the children to color each object its real color.   Have a variety of writing and drawing materials available, i.e., pencils, colored pencils, marking pens, crayons, and let the children choose.  Dismiss children to the work area, and pass papers.  Encourage the children to discuss the activity with their neighbors while they are working.  (This is not a test!)  When someone is finished, give the "STOP" signal and help that child model getting his/her SCIENTIST'S NOTEBOOK, putting in the new paper and putting away the HAND LENS.  Explain that when they are finished they may read their SCIENTIST'S NOTEBOOK or look at another book from the science lab until everyone is finished.<P><P>

<H3>5.  READING STUDENT TEXT</H3>
  Signal the class to put away everything except their SCIENTIST'S NOTEBOOKS and to bring their SCIENTIST'S NOTEBOOKS to the rug.  Review the song.  Present the final verse in the manner described under Procedure #3.  Sing the whole song several times, having the children trade pictures with their neighbors after each rendition.  Have the children open their SCIENTIST'S NOTEBOOKS and find the "Colors All Around Me" song in the Student Text section.  Remind them that this part of the book has special pages that can help them remember what they have learned.  Read the title, "Colors All Around Me", and tell them that the whole song about colors is there.  Tell them that you will read the words from the book as you sing the song to them, but that they already know how to sing it, so they can read along with you!  Sing the entire song together with the children, and tell them how clever they are to have learned how to read so well all by themselves!<P><P>

 
<H2>Further Exploration:</H2>
Point out things in the classroom that are sorted by color, i.e., bottles of tempera, colored construction paper, unifix cubes.  Discuss why those things are sorted by color, i.e., to make it easier for people to find the things they need.  Discuss whether sorting other things, such as books, by color would be a good idea or not.<P>
Provide opportunities for sorting a variety of objects by color.  Make large rings of colored yarn on the rug and have objects sorted by placing them inside.<P>
Provide an opportunity to make and observe the color in bubbles outdoors on a sunny day.  Make blowers of different sizes and shapes by bending wire or cutting the center out of plastic container lids.  Use commercial bubble liquid or make your own  A quart of water, 1/2 cup of liquid detergent, 1/4 cup of glycerine and a tablespoon of sugar makes enough for the whole class to blow a lot of bubbles.<P>
Hang a prism near a sunny window.  Put a large piece of white paper and some crayons nearby so the children can duplicate the colors they see.<P>
Sort the objects in the "Things to Look At" box by color.<P>
Sort children's belongings such as coats, jackets, backpacks by color.<P>
Take a color walk around the school.  Record observations.  Count and see which color had the most entries.  Discuss whether the result would have been the same if we had walked another place such as inside a supermarket or at the beach.<P><P>


<H2>Evaluation:</H2>
<UL>
<LI> Did all the children participate in the activities?<BR>
<LI> Can most of the children describe common objects by naming their color?<BR>
<LI> While they were working in pairs, did they talk with their partner about 
	the activity?<BR>
<LI> Did each pair hide their chameleon appropriately?<P>
</UL><P>


<H2>Variations/Extensions:</H2>
Dismiss children to recess or other activities by naming a color, i.e.," If you're wearing red, stand up and point to what you're wearing that's red."<P>
Read aloud from the books suggested in the "Curriculum Connection" section of this unit.<P>
Have all the groups share their chameleon charts with the entire class.<P>
Repeat the chameleon activity with other colors, i.e., orange, purple, pink, white, brown, black.<P>
Have children choose their favorite colored unifix cube.  (Do this by having the children choose their cube one at a time and hide it in their hand so nobody sees their choice.) Seat the children in a large circle on the rug and have them put their cube in the center of the circle, attaching it to any other cubes that are the same color.  When all cubes are in the center of the circle, create a real graph by lining up the sets of different colored cubes.  Compare, count and discuss.<P><P>


<H2>Home-School Activity:</H2>
Invite children to take color walks inside their house, each day looking for a different color.  Have them report what they found and record in on a "Color in Our Homes" chart.  PARENT NOTE #11 explains this activity and suggests read-aloud books that will reinforce and extend the child's understanding of concepts related to color.  Read and discuss the note with the children, and then have them tape or clip it to the cover of the SCIENTIST'S NOTEBOOK.<P>

Encourage the children to take their SCIENTIST'S NOTEBOOK home after EXPLORATION REPORT #7 has been completed.  Remind them to return it to school the next day.<P>


